r a BC-POOL-SHOCK-2NDTAKE-KA     07-22 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POOL-SHOCK-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ... the water.
</P>
<P>
   The grid also protects swimmers by keeping all metal at the same
voltage potential. This way, if stray volts enter the grid, the
voltage passing through all the metal is the same. If someone
touched the metal, there would be no shock.
</P>
<P>
   That's the same reason a squirrel can sit on a power line
without getting hurt.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is a difference in voltage _ as when the squirrel
touches another power line or a pole _ the result could be a shock
or death.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing you have to remember is that the grid is not 100
percent effective,'' said Rick Park, a service coordinator for SKC
Electric. ``It is not a sure thing. It is there for safety, and it
is the best humans can come up with. But you have to remember there
are a lot of variables that can defeat these systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Herzig's inspection of the Tomahawk Ridge pool found that
several structures were added to the complex without being properly
connected to the grid. Also, several other items were initially
connected but were altered sometime after installation.
</P>
<P>
   A third group of items were never properly bonded during the
original installation, Herzig said. Overland Park officials denied
that.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the items were ladders, lifeguard stands, canopies and
diving board rails.
</P>
<P>
   City officials found similar problems at the city's other five
pools.
</P>
<P>
   After area cities heard about Overland Park's pool closings,
some decided to make sure their pools were safe.
</P>
<P>
   Olathe, Kan., for example, was advised that because the city had
not added features or modified its pools, the original design and
construction would ensure people's safety.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as a precaution, the city had an electrician inspect its
pools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pools were fine,'' said Marlene Natoli, assistant director
of community services. ``We did some minor modifications following
the test, but there were no problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Other cities conducted tests before the pools opened for the
season. Overland Park, which did not test the grid system before
the season began, will now require such tests every year, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cities with older pools, such as Kansas City, do not have the
protective grids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the grid systems, because our pools were built
back in the 1940s and 1950s,'' said Chuck Moore, communications
officer for the Kansas City Parks and Recreation Department.
</P>
<P>
   The city checks the pools at the beginning of the season to make
sure everything is safe, Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Banks, president and owner of Banks Pool &AMP; Spa Designs
Inc. in Kansas City, said it was important for homeowners and
apartment complexes with pools to periodically check them to make
sure that their safety measures are working properly, including
checking the grid system.
</P>
<P>
   Pools are designed to withstand incidents such as the one in
Overland Park, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been a lot worse,'' Banks said. ``Fortunately,
Overland Park found out about its problems with the pools without
anybody getting injured.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
