<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS AMD LEITER CAN'T SHAKE TURNER FIELD CURSE, LOSING 6-3 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Melvin Mora stood in the Mets dugout at Turner Field
before Friday night's game and said he was not concerned with
rumors that he might soon be replaced as the Mets' starting
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I know,'' he said, ``is they need me out there
at shortstop, and I'm going to try to do my best, and I will do my
best.''
</P>
<P>
   With two out in the ninth inning Friday night, Mora gave the
Mets his best, surprising the Atlanta Braves with a bunt and
reaching safely on a single. But Mora's best has not been good
enough, and Mora could not have known then that the Mets already
had worked out a deal in principle with the Cincinnati Reds that
would bring Barry Larkin, a potential Hall of Fame shortstop, to
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Mora has filled in capably for the injured Rey Ordonez, but if
Larkin approves the deal, he will lift a team that needs the help.
The short-handed Mets fell to the Braves, 6-3, as Al Leiter
faltered again in a ballpark that bedevils him and the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Field has been a house of horrors for the Mets, whose
playoff hopes died here in 1998 and whose World Series dreams were
dashed here last October.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine conceded before Friday
night's game, ``is a ballpark that hasn't been a friendly place to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   In their last 16 games at Turner Field, the Mets are 1-15. That
record includes the Mets' three losses here in the National League
Championship Series last year.
</P>
<P>
   The four-year-old park has been most inhospitable to Leiter.
Counting his start in the decisive sixth game of last year's NLCS,
when he allowed five earned runs and did not retire a batter,
Leiter has given up 16 earned runs in 161/3 innings at Turner
Field, for an 8.82 earned run average. He was even the losing
pitcher in the All-Star Game here 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter worked six innings Friday night, allowing five runs (four
earned) and six hits. He dropped his third decision in a row since
beating the Braves at Shea Stadium on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter allowed singles to the first two hitters he faced, Rafael
Furcal and Andruw Jones, and they executed a double steal as
Chipper Jones struck out. Brian Jordan followed with a single to
center, scoring two runs, including one by Jones, who overslid the
lunging catcher Mike Piazza, then scrambled back to touch the plate
with his foot.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets used four singles and a walk by Braves starter Terry
Mulholland to take a 3-2 lead in the third. Joe McEwing, Piazza and
Jay Payton all had run-scoring singles, and when Mulholland, a
control pitcher, walked Benny Agbayani to load the bases with two
out, Braves manager Bobby Cox called for John Burkett.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett, who defeated the Mets at Shea Stadium in the opener of
the clubs' four-game series on June 29, was bumped from the
rotation when the Braves acquired Andy Ashby in a trade over the
All-Star Game break. But he was stingy Friday night, retiring Mora
on a flyout to center to end the third and then cruising.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves gave Burkett a lead in the bottom of the third, when
a decision by third baseman Lenny Harris proved costly.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on second and third, Harris fielded Jordan's
grounder and threw to Piazza at the plate. The throw pulled Piazza
into the path of the base runner, Andruw Jones, who scored as the
ball got away. Harris was charged with a throwing error, which
allowed the runners to advance a base.
</P>
<P>
   The score was 3-3 and Andres Galarraga grounded to shortstop,
bringing in Chipper Jones to give Atlanta the lead. The Braves
added another run on a homer by Javy Lopez in the sixth, and
Chipper Jones added a run-scoring single in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were playing without second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo,
who received an anti-inflammatory injection in his sore right hip
before the game, which should make him available for the final game
of this series on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give guys motivation to keep playing,'' Alfonzo
said. ``The last thing we need right now is me going on the
disabled list. We win with all 25 guys. It's kind of a little hard,
but it's something you're going to have to deal with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
