u a BC-NY-MOSQUITO-SPRAYING-     07-22 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MOSQUITO-SPRAYING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE AND FEDERAL OFFICIALS MAY OK PESTICIDES AFTER MAYOR'S
COMMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Arguing that humans are more important than a few
fish, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani sharply criticized state and federal
environmental officials Friday for blocking the city from spraying
pesticides in wetlands and other marsh areas in its battle against
the West Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor attacked the government policies _ which prohibit
spraying many pesticides over water, to protect fish and other
aquatic life _ as he announced that spraying to eradicate
mosquitoes that carry the virus would be extended to nearly all of
Staten Island and northern Queens on Monday night because three
more infected birds had been found in those areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that danger to human life is more important
than birds, fish and insects,'' said Giuliani. He condemned
policies of the National Parks Service, which had prevented
spraying pesticides inside the Gateway National Recreation Area,
and the state's Department of Environmental Conservation, which has
strictly enforced a federal prohibition on the use of pesticides in
ponds and wetlands elsewhere in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's protests, at a news conference on Staten Island,
provoked immediate offers of compromise by state and federal
officials. The Parks Service said it would allow the city to spray
in the Staten Island section of Gateway at the same time it sprays
elsewhere in the city on Monday. A senior official of the
Environmental Protection Agency in Washington said the agency would
consider granting the city an emergency waiver to allow spraying
over water, perhaps at the same time on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal and our desire is to make sure we are providing
complete health protection,'' said Stephen Johnson, the deputy
assistant administrator for the EPA's office of prevention,
pesticides and toxic substances. He said the waiver would allow the
city to spray its pesticide, Anvil, over water despite federal
rules that prohibit its use in areas ``where surface water is
present.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the state Department of Environmental
Conservation, Jennifer Post, said last night that her department
would request the waiver ``if that is the route the city wants to
take.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the apparent concurrence of state and federal officials,
the city's plan to spray Anvil over water was greeted with
skepticism by environmentalists, who fought fiercely last year
against the city's use of malathion, a more toxic pesticide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor's constant drumbeat about the safety of this product
or any of these products could make people cavalier about
exposure,'' said Jay Feldman, executive director of the National
Coalition Against the Misuse of Pesticides, a Washington-based
environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who acknowledged that spraying Anvil over water would
kill fish, dismissed environmental protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We catch fish to eat them, so if we lose a few fish to save
human lives, I don't understand'' the confusion going on, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's announcement of expanded spraying came after health
officials concluded that the West Nile virus had killed a blue jay
in Douglaston, Queens, and a crow and a sparrow in the Great Kills
and Bay Terrace sections of Staten Island during the first week of
July. The dead birds are among five identified in the city this
year that were infected by the virus, which was responsible for 62
confirmed cases in people last fall, including seven deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is most problematic for children under 5, the elderly
and people with weakened immune systems. Otherwise, it causes
flulike symptoms in healthy adults.
</P>
<P>
   The city's health commissioner, Dr. Neal Cohen, while clearly
concerned about the fresh evidence of disease-carrying mosquitoes,
said the threat to the city was complicated by the wide swath in
which infected birds had been identified _ from the city to the
suburbs. He said that posed a threat that the mosquitoes were
migrating to unpredictable locations.
</P>
<P>
   State health officials said Friday that 29 birds had been killed
by the virus this year, including five crows in Rockland County and
a blue jay in Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   But since there have been no cases of West Nile infection in
humans in the city this year, Cohen said ``there is no reason to
reach the conclusion that the virus is more prevalent or has more
traction'' than last year. He added that medical analysis of those
who became ill or died last year indicated that the first case had
been in early August, suggesting that an outbreak in humans this
year, if it occurred, could not emerge much earlier than last year.
</P>
<P>
   Spraying has also begun in Rockland, Westchester and Suffolk
counties, and Giuliani said Friday that the findings in Douglaston
prompted health officials to ask Nassau County to begin an
eradication campaign along its western borders.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Katherine Gaffney, the Nassau County health commissioner,
said Friday that she had no intention of ordering pesticide
spraying unless infected birds or mosquitoes were found in the
county.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to begin adding chemicals to the ecosystem if
simple, preventative measures can be used instead,'' she said,
adding that the county had tested 189 dead birds and more than
25,000 mosquitoes this year, without finding any West Nile
infections.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Friday that the city might also ask Union County
in New Jersey to spray pesticides because of its proximity to the
section of Staten Island where infected birds were identified this
week. Tom Plant, a Union County spokesman, said the county had
already engaged in extensive testing of chickens and other birds
this year and had found no evidence of infection.
</P>
<P>
   The city's spraying could be completed on Monday night, health
officials said, when trucks are deployed in the area around
Douglaston and across Staten Island. Delays caused by weather or
other problems could require additional spraying on Tuesday night,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Friday when the city could complete spraying in
the Staten Island part of Gateway National Recreation Area, and
city health officials said some details of the operation _
including who would pay to spray the park _ remained to be
negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   But they said the agreement of the Park Service to allow any
spraying inside Gateway was welcome, particularly because one of
the infected birds identified on Staten Island this week had been
found close to the park's boundary, and could have been infected
from there.
</P>
</TEXT>
