<HEADLINE>
BILLBOARDS URGE MOTORISTS ON I-70 TO OFFER IDEAS TO IMPROVE
HIGHWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATIE HOLLAR and KYLE S. THOMAS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Big and bright, the billboards beckon to
drivers on Interstate 70: ``70 needs help! Got ideas?''
</P>
<P>
   Boy, do they. At least 6,000 motorists, at last count, have
contacted the Missouri Department of Transportation through its Web
site. Officials say they can't count the number of people who have
called or written.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to I-70, it seems, everyone has a horror story.
From Kansas City to St. Louis and stops in between, drivers gripe
and grumble about the highway's potholes, traffic jams and constant
construction.
</P>
<P>
   If the billboards work, I-70 cynics may be the highway's
salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Springs, Break Time.
</P>
<P>
   A taxicab-yellow pickup pulls into the parking lot of the Break
Time gas station. Out step Travis Young, of Higginsville, and
Bradley Maberry, of Sweet Springs.
</P>
<P>
   The two of them drive I-70 every day. They see the potholes,
they feel the bumps through the seat of the old truck, and they see
the construction crews trying to fix those problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do work every month, and it doesn't help it,'' says
Young, 20. ``There are good spots, there are bad spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Maberry, 17, says the crumbling condition of I-70 has lured some
truckers to take U.S. 40, thus ``another highway gets messed up.''
</P>
<P>
   The two don't have high hopes for I-70.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may get it fixed,'' Young says, ``about when I turn 80.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be in the year 2060.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri highway officials, now studying alternatives for fixing
the road, insist it won't take that long.
</P>
<P>
   Stretching from Baltimore to Cove Fort, Utah, I-70 is the oldest
interstate highway route in the United States. And the 251-mile
portion of the road that stretches across Missouri has taken a
beating since construction was completed in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   The highway was designed to last about 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the road begins to show its age, motorists and state
officials are wondering what should be done about it.
</P>
<P>
   Significant changes certainly are called for, said Linda Ell
Clark, a planner for the Missouri Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Clark cited the ``present serviceability rating,'' which is
compiled by a team of surveyors who examine the nation's roadways.
The rating crew found that 24 percent of Missouri's I-70 was in
poor condition. Forty percent is ``very poor.''
</P>
<P>
   In its early years, the interstate would average 15,000 to
20,000 cars daily, traffic officials say. Today, the highway sees
about two times as many _ 35,000 vehicles a day in rural areas and
45,000 near St. Louis, Columbia and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I-70 was designed, it wasn't designed to hold as much
traffic as it does today,'' said Jim Coleman, of the Missouri
Department of Transportation. ``Especially not truck traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen construction projects are set up between Kansas City
and St. Louis this summer, as the department tries to fix some of
the road's worst spots.
</P>
<P>
   Caution signs, orange and white barrels occupy the shoulder.
Workers use heavy machinery to resurface lanes. Others insert guard
rails, restore bridges and patch the road's median.
</P>
<P>
   Danville, Phillips 66.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Key pulls his champagne-colored Cadillac into the shade.
He's driving home from St. Louis to Jefferson City. But the
formidable summer heat and the dozens of orange barrels on the road
make for a long drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just getting some rest,'' he says, turning the Cadillac's
air-conditioner on high.
</P>
<P>
   Key hates driving in the construction zones, but he understands
the need for the I-70 projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're trying to fix it for good,'' he says. ``It's
just a big job. They're doing what they can.''
</P>
<P>
   Solution or not, motorists complain that construction is a major
hassle.
</P>
<P>
   Construction at night would make it easier for drivers during
rush hour, says Michelle Ifill, of Junction City, Kan., sitting in
the back seat of the family station wagon while her husband refills
a cooler with ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is too much traffic because of road work,'' she says.
``And the people drive crazy in Missouri.''
</P>
<P>
   Six road crews worked between Kansas City and St. Louis on a
recent weekday. The orange cones, yellow dump trucks and steaming
asphalt have become a common sight along the highway.
</P>
<P>
   More troubling are the 14 crosses along the road, marking the
locations of fatal accidents.
</P>
<P>
   There could be more crosses to come. If projected traffic
increases hold true, the Transportation Department expects
accidents to double in the next 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason for the construction, said department
spokesman Mark Kross.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, about 6,000 trips are made between Kansas City and
St. Louis. That number could double by 2030, according to
transportation statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make it a safer road for drivers that travel between the
state's largest two cities, we have to stick by our current
construction schedule,'' Kross said. ``During this time, we have to
come up with a strategic plan to reduce congestion and collisions
on this statewide road.''
</P>
<P>
   By 2030, estimated volumes are expected to reach 80,000 to
90,000 vehicles a day in urban areas. The rural spaces could see
50,000 to 60,000 daily.
</P>
<P>
   Seven I-70 help billboards already dot the roadside. Seven more
will be put up soon.
</P>
<P>
   The responses to the phone line and the Web site will be
considered in MoDOT's I-70 improvement study.
</P>
<P>
   The agency hopes the plan will revamp I-70 in Missouri.
Conducted by a team of engineers, the study aims to solve the
ongoing problem of roughness, congestion and accidents.
</P>
<P>
   MoDOT hopes to have the first part of its plan completed by the
spring of 2001. The plan focuses on the 200 miles that stretch from
Kansas City's Interstate 470 to Lake St. Louis just outside St.
Louis. Besides the road, the study will examine five miles on
either side of the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Within that area, there are 53 interchanges and 130 bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Already, public meetings and engineers' suggestions are sparking
ideas to revamp the road, said Jerry Mugg of HNTB Corp., the
consultant that is heading the study.
</P>
<P>
   The study already has sparked some ideas:
</P>
<P>
   - A four-lane road could be constructed five miles to the north
or south of I-70. Building a new four-lane expressway or toll road
is estimated to cost about $2.5 billion _ the same as
reconstructing and widening the existing one.
</P>
<P>
   - Special lanes could be designated for buses and carpools.
</P>
<P>
   - Around the cities, park-and-ride programs could be
implemented, cutting down on commuter traffic.
</P>
<P>
   - A high-speed rail could be installed, running down the median
or alongside the road.
</P>
<P>
   On the Kansas side, highway officials also are looking at the
future of I-70 from Kansas City, Kan., to Topeka, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Adding lanes and energy-efficient transportation methods could
be some strategies they consider, said Kim Stich, a spokeswoman for
the Kansas Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Past Topeka, there is not a need for improvement,'' she said.
``If we have to concentrate on improving the road statewide in the
future, we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Just outside Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   At a rest stop at mile 125, Frank Walsh sits in the grass,
trying to repair his Harley-Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh and his two buddies in bandannas are riding to St. Louis.
From there, they'll head north to Sturgis, S.D., for the annual
Harley convention _ if they can get this motorcycle to start.
</P>
<P>
   I-70 is especially vicious to bikers, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a bump off a bridge that almost made me come off my
bike,'' Walsh says. ``I've almost scratched out I don't know how
many times. The road's terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Hossfeld relaxes near his UPS truck. Hossfeld's been
driving I-70 for 26 years. He travels five days a week on the road,
and he's seen his share of bad accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``From St. Louis to Kansas City should be six lanes, to reduce
accidents,'' Hossfeld says. ``Also, a bypass around Columbia.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbia's Exit 128 is the worst part of the road, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sharp curve needs to be taken out, fill the median with
concrete and put up barriers to reduce head-on crashes,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Hossfeld has seen the big billboards that ask drivers for
suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent my two cents in,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
