<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9681 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-SALMON-AZR &LR;      07-22 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMON-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-SALMON-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    SALMON HAS PLANS FOR AFTER OFFICE(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By CHRIS MOESER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. Matt Salmon will be gone from Congress in January, but he's
making sure he won't be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   The Mesa Republican says he plans to play a major role in state
politics once he leaves office by forming a non-profit foundation
to advocate and lobby for education and children's issue. What he
won't say is whether his new focus is a prelude to a bid for the
governor's office in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is aside from whether or not I'm running for governor.
This is not the `Matt Salmon for governor' exploratory committee,''
Salmon said in a telephone interview this week from Washington,
D.C. ``This is a foundation to try to address Arizona's problems,
which I will do whether I run for governor or whether I don't. I
don't know that I'm going to run for governor or that I won't.
There's a lot of thought that has to go into that. But along the
way if you have a chance to do some good, you ought to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   But some political analysts say Salmon's creation of the
Foundation for Arizona's Future has everything to do with
(beginitalic)his (enditalic)political future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about running for governor,'' said Bruce Merrill,
an ASU journalism professor and pollster. ``This is about keeping
access to the media once he leaves office. It's very smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon launched the foundation as chairman of a 19-member board
that includes Republicans and Democrats, including former Assistant
Attorney General Steve Twist, former Mesa City Councilman John
Giles, Tucson trial lawyer Gary Bryant and Phoenix lobbyist Kevin
DeMenna.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon and the other board members will not be paid, although he
hopes to raise $150,000 over the next year to hire staff. The goal
is to research issues like a think tank, but also to lobby at the
state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a think tank. This is an action tank,'' Salmon
said. ``We intend to look at issues and come up with solutions, and
we intend to advocate for those solutions. This is not some kind of
passive board. We are going to try to make change.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon cited examples of what he'd like to work on: education,
child abuse, child support enforcement and divorce laws. And he
said the focus in education should be on improving science and math
performance by attracting better teachers - with more money, if
necessary - and by creating a science and math charter school.
</P>
<P>
   He's been harshly critical of Gov. Jane Hull's plan for a
six-tenths-of-a-cent sales tax increase to raise teacher salaries
and reduce class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a propensity in government to always believe that the
answer is just to throw money at a problem without any kind of a
well thought out plan,'' he said. ``There is no game plan right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that he will defer to his board to decide exactly
what to pursue, pointing out that he has picked a diverse group
that won't rubber-stamp his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those board members agreed. Bryant, who calls himself
a liberal Democrat, has known Salmon for 20 years. He said he
expects to frequently disagree with Salmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's someone who believes in things. I like that,'' Bryant
said. ``If he asked me to help, there's clearly no agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon has long been something of a political enigma. He was
first elected to Congress in 1994 when Republicans swept to power.
But he was quickly at odds with GOP leaders, including then-House
Speaker Newt Gingrich. Salmon criticized Gingrich for abandoning
core principles of the ``Contract with America,'' such as tax and
spending cuts. He supported the coup against Gingrich that
eventually led to the speaker's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   And although Salmon is staunchly conservative, he has earned a
maverick reputation. He is one of the few members of the 1994
freshman class who stuck to a pledge to leave office after three
terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be an effort to soften his rightist image,'' Phoenix
pollster Earl de Berge said.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon's announcement of the foundation even drew guarded praise
from a potential rival.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Goddard, a former Phoenix mayor and two-time Democratic
gubernatorial candidate who is weighing a third race for the post,
noted that Bryant's inclusion on the board as evidence that
Salmon's intentions may be altruistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, any time you have to look suspiciously at something
that has a potential candidate as a chairman,'' Goddard said. ``But
I wish him well. Any responsible voice for kids and families in
this state is desperately needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon could face a crowded field in the Republican primary for
governor. Former Attorney General Grant Woods, Secretary of State
Betsey Bayless and Senate President Brenda Burns are all potential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon said he has not decided whether he will run, saying
instead that he will take a job in the private sector when he
leaves office to capitalize on his expertise on China. He is fluent
in Mandarin Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expect that there will be cynics galore,'' he said.
``But you weigh on one hand the potential of criticisms from cynics
or the potential of continuing to do good. I'm 42 years old. I'm
not going to wither up and go away. I will be a force to be dealt
with in Arizona, whether it's on the sidelines helping other people
or in elective office myself. I will be involved in Arizona's
future one way or another.''
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporter at Chris.Moeser(a)Arizona
</P>
<P>
   Republic.com or (602) 444-8069.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
