</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: METS, BRAVES REINTRODUCE THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This should have happened a few months ago. The Braves
and the Mets should have been getting it on in April or May,
reviving their rivalry early and often.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, baseball has been operating with a mentality of
painting itself into isolated corners, like Dagwood Bumstead in the
Sunday comics.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night the Mets were visiting the Braves for the first
time this season, with the same dismal result, a 6-3 loss. They
have won only 12 of 41 regular-season games in Atlanta since 1992
and were 0-3 in last year's playoffs, which constitutes a weird
kind of rivalry, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had not been here since Kenny Rogers, with a tepid air
of inevitability, walked home the winning run in the 11th inning of
the sixth game of the National League Championship Series late on
the night of Oct. 19
</P>
<P>
   Through the marvel of Major League Baseball planning, the two
teams did not meet again until June 29, the night 600 New York City
police officers were needed to usher John Rocker into Shea Stadium.
Now that Rocker has settled into being just another knucklehead,
the teams can go about their business of competing for the division
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is awfully late to be here for the first time,''
Bobby Valentine said Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   This gaping void between engagements allowed Braves fans to
smirk that the Braves have dominated the Mets for the past decade.
Mets fans could reply with some veracity that they would have stood
up to the Yankees better than the weary Braves did in the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what miracles Melvin Mora might have wrought? Now the
Mets are trying to get Barry Larkin to supplant Mora as shortstop
pro tem; things happen fast.
</P>
<P>
   There is a history to these two teams, but baseball has done its
best to suppress rivalries in recent years, playing a so-called
balanced schedule with a gooey dollop of empty-calorie interleague
games. Through this gimmick, the Mets have been playing before
empty club boxes in Toronto while the Braves have been trying to
bring major league baseball to the grim dome in Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The people who run baseball are nothing if not astute. Just the
other day they announced plans for an unbalanced schedule in 2001,
meaning teams will play up to 19 games against division rivals.
</P>
<P>
   There is some fear that baseball will realign what is left of
the two-league rivalry in the near future, perhaps separating the
Mets and Braves. ``I don't want 'em to go away; I want to beat
'em,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, at least, there will probably be three trips by the
Mets to Atlanta and three by the Braves to New York. This means
teams can take more responsibility for their own fate, can give
themselves a boost in the damp of springtime, turn on the burners
in the heat of summer and protect their turf in the chill of
autumn.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing like two teams starting to develop warm and
fuzzy feelings toward each other: Those lucky dogs! Those impudent
pretenders! Those cowardly weasels!
</P>
<P>
   This is what pennant races used to be like. The classic subway
rivalry between the Brooklyn Dodgers and the New York Giants was
exacerbated by its frequency _ 22 games a year. If Sal Maglie, the
Barber, shaved the swarthy jowls of Carl Furillo, the man known as
Skoonj would not have to wait interminably for his chance to bunt
down the first-base line and see if he could leave cleat marks up
and down Maglie's flannels.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there was no designated-hitter rule to encourage a
Roger Clemens to become the classic American League bully, throwing
inside against great hitters like Mike Piazza, knowing he would
never have to stand in the general vicinity of home plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets now have a healthy little rivalry against Clemens, but
they will have to wait a very long time to see him again. Late
October would work.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball needs its rivalries, but interleague schedules and
expansion have diluted the product, creating a schedule of
one-night stands and creating makeshift return excursions to make
up inconvenient rainouts.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Mets and Braves play home-and-home series in
September, when division rivals should meet. ``If you play enough
games, they usually even out,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't evened out for the Mets here, but they keep
hustling. Friday night, with Larkin rumors infiltrating the dugout
at game time, the Mets fell behind by 2-0, ``but I didn't see us
give up,'' Valentine said, hopefully. The team's collective
memories of Atlanta are not good, but at least they are memories,
and baseball should do more to stimulate them. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
