<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TORRICELLI-SUPPORTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
50 SOUTH NEW JERSEY DEMOCRATS ENDORSE TORRICELLI'S BID FOR
GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON _ More than 50 South Jersey Democrats announced their
support for Sen. Robert Torricelli Friday in his bid to supplant
James McGreevey as the party's presumptive nominee for governor.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's backers claimed that the show of support, which
included top officials in three counties and two county Democratic
Party chairmen, would be the first in a series of endorsements as
unstoppable as toppling dominoes.
</P>
<P>
   But McGreevey's loyalists dismissed the endorsements as a weak
showing, and said that they would announce their own South Jersey
supporters on Saturday, arguing that the region's Democrats
remained divided, at best, in the governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   While such endorsements are unlikely to influence many voters,
they are considered critical at this stage in the
McGreevey-Torricelli showdown. The senator is seeking to prove he
would be the choice of an overwhelming majority of Democrats, and
needs to show he has the support of the most influential party
leaders. McGreevey, the mayor of Woodbridge, is striving to prove
he can withstand Torricelli's challenge, and must prevent
defections from his ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Those endorsing Torricelli Friday included the Democratic
chairmen in Camden and Burlington counties; the freeholder
directors _ the top elected officials _ in Camden, Cumberland and
Gloucester counties; the mayors of Atlantic City and Cherry Hill;
former Rep. William Hughes; seven assemblymen; and two state
senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an endorsement by the Who's Who of Democratic
leadership in southern New Jersey,'' said George E. Norcross III,
the Camden County power broker.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the officials listed as favoring Torricelli withdrew
his endorsement Friday night, saying he had been bamboozled. Tom
Pankok, the Salem County Democratic chairman, said he had agreed to
add his name to the list only because he had been told that
counterparts in Cumberland and Gloucester counties had already done
so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to remain neutral,'' Pankok said. ``I'm so sick and
tired of hearing so much misinformation. I don't want to talk about
endorsements or anything till after the November election.''
</P>
<P>
   McGreevey refused to discuss the list of Torricelli supporters,
except to say he remained confident he would survive the senator's
challenge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 0026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
