<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9687 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLA     07-22 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN HAS NO TIME TO TALK _ JUST PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Mo Vaughn is the only Anaheim Angel to play in all 97
games this season and he's started all 97. But if ever there was a
time he might have been given a day off, it was Friday against the
A's.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was hit in the helmet by a pitch thrown by Texas' Darren
Oliver Thursday in the first inning. He stayed in the game and
batted four more times, drawing four walks. He showed up at the
Oakland Coliseum Friday afternoon with some swelling on the right
side of his face but said he was able to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel beautiful,'' Vaughn said as he dumped a couple of
aspirin tablets from a bottle into his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the normally talkative Vaughn didn't feel much like
talking about the beaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he wants to make a big deal out of it,'' manager
Mike Scioscia said. ``He doesn't want people to focus on what he's
doing. He truly encompasses a team ideology. It's like, 'I got hit,
let's play.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was checked out by doctors Thursday, who cleared him to
play.
</P>
<P>
   !Superstitious: Darin Erstad said he doesn't have any pregame
superstitions, nothing like Wade Boggs' insistence on eating
chicken before every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing that I say I have to do,'' he said. ``Everybody has
some kind of routine that makes them feel comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, however, does wear the same grungy T-shirt with cutoff
sleeves every game. The shirt _ which carries the phrase, ``Eat
right, drink lots of fluids, get plenty of rest'' on the front _ is
starting to get a little yellow. On the back is the phrase, ``Go
like hell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the shirt disappeared, I wouldn't commit suicide,'' Erstad
said. ``It's just a shirt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 0035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
