A9688 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-MINETA-COMMERCE-SFCHR     07-22 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINETA-COMMERCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINETA SWORN IN AT COMMERCE IN QUICK CEREMONY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ Norm Mineta, who spent three years imprisoned at a
Japanese American internment camp and 20 years representing the
South Bay in Congress, was sworn in Friday as the 33rd secretary of
commerce.
<P>
   Mineta is the first American of Asian descent to serve in a
president's Cabinet. He was sworn in at a hastily arranged private
ceremony after a speedy and controversy-free confirmation by the
Senate late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 68-year-old former San Jose mayor will serve for six months
until President Clinton's term comes to an end. Mineta replaces
William Daley, who resigned from the Commerce Department last month
to manage Vice President Al Gore's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six months is a virtual eternity in the new economy,'' Mineta
said at a confirmation hearing before the Senate Commerce Committee
on Wednesday. Mineta said his top priorities will include promoting
free trade, expanding e-commerce and pursuing a policy of ``digital
inclusion to bridge the digital divide.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Six months of opportunity and responsibility will demand a
greater focus to make a greater difference in that time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; China Trade a Top Priority
</P>
<P>
   Among his first likely tasks will be to secure Senate passage of
permanent trade relations with China, a top goal of the Clinton
administration and the business community.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta will oversee a department of 40,000 employees with a $5
billion annual budget; his responsibilities range from promoting
American business and issuing patents and trademarks to conducting
the census and running the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   His appointment was hailed by Asian American groups as a
significant step toward ending discrimination and opening avenues
that have long been viewed as off-limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at our history in this country, with a lot of
discrimination, epitomized by the internment camps during WWII, and
then to the year 2000, with Mineta becoming an appointee in the
president's Cabinet _ it's been a long distance we have traveled,''
said John Tateishi, executive director of the Japanese American
Citizens League.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a signal to the rest of the country that Asian Americans
have arrived, and that we are now part of the fabric that makes up
the leadership of America,'' Tateishi said.
</P>
<P>
   As a 10-year-old boy in 1942, Mineta and his family were forced
from their San Jose home and sent to an internment camp in Wyoming
along with other Japanese Americans who were deemed a risk to the
national security.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta recalled his father bringing the family together, and
saying, ``He did not know what the war would bring to my mother and
to him, since they were resident aliens. ... However, he was
confident that his beloved country would guarantee and protect the
right of his children _ American citizens, all. But his confidence,
as it turned out, was misplaced.''
</P>
<P>
   Mineta led the fight in Congress to secure reparation payments
for the tens of thousands of Japanese Americans forced into the
camps. He rose to the rank of chairman of the Transportation and
Public Works Committee before leaving the House in the middle of
his 11th term to accept a senior executive position at Lockheed
Martin Corp., the world's largest defense contractor, which at one
time was the largest private employer in his district. At Lockheed,
Mineta worked on public transportation issues.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tried unsuccessfully in 1992 to tap Mineta to be
secretary of transportation, and he is regarded as a likely
candidate for a Cabinet post if Gore wins the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Mineta) brings an in-depth understanding of American business
and a strong sense of the needs of our high-tech economy,'' Clinton
said in a statement released by the Commerce Department. ``But he
also has a deep concern for people, for the people in places who
are not yet fully participating in the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mineta's strong relations with Republicans as well as Democrats
was evident at his hearing before the Senate Commerce Committee
this week where Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the committee chair,
praised him as a ``great American.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Norm Mineta's life story is, in a real sense, a celebration of
America,'' said Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   McCain expressed concerns about the ``alleged political nature''
of the Commerce Department's trade missions, but no objections were
raised to Mineta's confirmation. Members of the audience, including
Capitol Hill staffers, friends and members of Washington's Asian
American Committee burst into applause when the 90-minute hearing
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta was unanimously approved by a voice vote late Thursday
night. Mineta, who said at his hearing that ``accountability and
accessibility are among the greatest responsibilities that every
public servant owes,'' declined requests for interviews Friday. A
public swearing-in ceremony is expected in the next couple of
weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
