<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROCKOVICH-ABCTV </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROCKOVICH CLAIMS MEDIA INACCURACIES
</HEADLINE>
 - LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DANA BARTHOLOMEW 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTLAKE VILLAGE, Calif. _ Movie heroine Erin Brockovich issued
a challenge Friday to the TV news reporter who claimed her landmark
legal victory was based on a false assumption: Drink the water.
</P>
<P>
   Brockovich, the Agoura Hills, Calif., legal aide whose fight
against a utility company for poisoning well water won a $333
million settlement and a movie in her name, dared the anchor to put
his mouth where his mouth is.
</P>
<P>
   Her target: John Stossel, whose ``Give me a break'' segment on
ABC-TV's ``20/20'' last week called into question the harmful
effects of chromium 6 on the residents of the desert town of
Hinkley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found the piece appalling,'' said Brockovich, 40, visibly
upset during a news conference in Westlake Village on Friday.
``Chromium 6 is toxic; chromium 6 is poison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Mr. Stossel, and his family, to come out here. I want
you to start drinking chromium 6-laced water, day in and day out,
just like the people in Hinkley did everyday.''
</P>
<P>
   A statement from ABC News on Friday defended the Stossel
broadcast by saying it never claimed drinking chromium 6 is safe,
but that ``drinking, breathing, or touching large amounts of
chromium 6 can cause lots of diseases - including lung and sinus
cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Brockovich and her boss, Thousand Oaks attorney Ed Masry,
called for Stossel and his producer to apologize to them and to the
650 plaintiffs of Hinkley for what they say was a dangerous and
misleading broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   They also called for the media members' jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Masry, 67, whose Westlake Village practice forced PG&AMP;E into
paying millions after dumping chromium-laced water near its pumping
plant north of Barstow, called Stossel ``a plain-out fool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To permit a brainless news report to be aired without
verification of certain facts is absolutely ludicrous,'' he said.
``I would check the facts before encouraging children to drink
toxic poison - you might as well tell them to play with a loaded
gun.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a transcript of his July 14 broadcast, Stossel
questioned whether chromium made Hinkley residents and PG&AMP;E
employees sick.
</P>
<P>
   There's no proof, he said, that chromium-laced drinking water
causes cancer. He cited the Environmental Protection Agency, which
sets drinking water standards, and the state Cancer Registry, which
he said found no excess cancer around Hinkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a known carcinogen if inhaled at high levels,'' said
Stossel, ``but there is no proof that the exposure in Hinkley made
people sick, or even that above-average numbers of people were
sick.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``20/20'' broadcast cited a PG&AMP;E study of 50,000 suspect
power plant workers who turned out healthier than average, a study
Masry said was impossibly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   A summary of the corrosive effects of chromium 6 by the National
Safety Council division says it can damage tissue through exposure
via air, water, soil and food.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Dahlgren, the toxicology expert whose examination of
50 Hinkley residents influenced the 1993 settlement, said they
showed classic symptoms of chromium poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't subtle stuff,'' he said. ``They had very, very
severe upper respiratory problems, nosebleeds, cancers - things
known from people who have a history of chromium exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to calling for his job, Masry challenged Stossel to
debate Brockovich on the facts about chromium 6.
</P>
<P>
   Asked on television whether he'd let his family drink the water
in Hinkley, Stossel stalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, none of us like pollution,'' he said. ``I wouldn't like
them to drink the water, but let's not terrify people unless we
know it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
