r a BC-POLITICS-COLUMN-SFCHR     07-22 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EVEN DEMOCRATS ARE DEFENDING BUSH AIDE ON CONFLICT CHARGE  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Timing is everything in politics.
</P>
<P>
   And with a week to go before the Republican National Convention,
the state Democratic Party tried to rev up accusations that Texas
Gov. George W. Bush's state campaign chair, Gerald Parsky, was
guilty of conflict of interest when he served as a University of
California regent and head of a UC investment committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looks like another Quackenbush problem for the Republicans _
using inside government pressure to direct funds,'' said Bob
Mulholland, campaign adviser to the state Democratic Party in a fax
sent to national political reporters this week.
</P>
<P>
   The problem: leading state Democratic pols, some of them Vice
President Al Gore's biggest supporters, have repeatedly said they
have no reason to believe there are any problems with Parsky _ or
his fellow UC regents _ in the award of a $350,000 contract to
Wilshire Associates, a well-known investment firm. The company is
headed by Dennis Tito, who has donated to Republican causes.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Gov. Gray Davis' office, contacted more than a month
ago about questions on Parsky, said he had ``no reason for
concern'' on the regent's actions. His views haven't changed, his
spokeswoman confirmed this week.
</P>
<P>
   The office of Democratic Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamante, another UC
regent, said likewise last month. This week, he told us he still
has no reason to believe Parsky had done anything wrong _ though he
would have preferred that a contract for the second portion of a
plan had been bidded out.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Hopkinson, a Democratic insider and Davis appointee who
now heads the UC investment committee, defended Wilshire as ``a
firm of international repute'' and came to the defense of Parsky as
well.
</P>
<P>
   And State Controller Kathleen Connell _ a major Democratic Gore
supporter _ said of Parsky's accusers: ``I don't see any conflict.
... I don't understand how they came to that conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Connell sits on the board of CalPERS, the state's $180 billion
pension fund, which she said also chose Wilshire as its investment
adviser because ``they're eminently qualified. ... They're not a
second-tier firm. They're the premiere firm _ I can vouch for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tito, Wilshire's executive, may be a Republican, but he's also
``one of the smartest (investment managers) in the country,''
Connell said. ``He developed the Wilshire (stock) Index, which
everyone in the country is using.''
</P>
<P>
   The only proven problem Bustamante had with Parsky? ``He's
backing the wrong candidate for president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Pete Wilson was not chosen as a delegate to the
Republican National Convention. But sources tell The Chronicle that
he will attend the confab in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Parsky, Bush's state chair, confirmed this week that Wilson
would not be a delegate. ``He has not been part of the Bush
campaign,'' Parsky said, adding that Wilson has devoted his time to
the ``Shape the Debate'' campaign instead.
</P>
<P>
   Bush appeared to forcefully distance himself from Wilson last
April when he said Republicans will reject ``the politics of
pitting one group against another.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's presence at the GOP convention could create waves _ and
pose some problems for Bush. Wilson is most closely associated with
his support of Proposition 187, the anti-illegal immigration
measure Bush has sought to put at arm's length.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilson was also a champion of GOP pro-choice delegates the
last time around, waging a battle for them to be heard _ even
though he was eventually drowned out.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush said he would welcome Wilson's support, the ex-gov
has been MIA in the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And don't look for any photo ops of Wilson and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   That would make Democratic campaign consultant Mulholland too
happy _ and faster than you can say ``Al Gore,'' he'd put it to use
at those Democratic Latino Unity rallies.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle reporter Tanya Schevitz contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
