<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GUZE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTED PSYCHIATRIST SAMUEL GUZE, 76, DIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Samuel Barry Guze, an influential psychiatrist who worked to wed
his discipline to medical science and its diagnostic techniques,
died on Wednesday at Barnes-Jewish Hospital in St. Louis. He was 76
and lived in Clayton, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was bone marrow disease, said a spokesman for the
Washington University School of Medicine, where he was the Olin
Professor of Psychiatry.
</P>
<P>
   Guze (pronounced goo-ZAY), was among the first psychiatrists to
use the study of twins as a way to investigate the role of heredity
in mental illness. He and his researchers contributed significantly
to the knowledge of genetic vulnerability to alcoholism and
schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   Guze trained as an internist before turning to psychiatry. In
the 1950s, he propagated the view that psychiatric trouble should
be diagnosed through the use of a scientific model and a biological
approach.
</P>
<P>
   As Guze, who also was an associate professor of medicine, once
put it: ``I couldn't ignore my training in internal medicine. I
suggested we approach psychiatric patients the way general
physicians approach all patients.''
</P>
<P>
   His views found general acceptance in 1980, when he helped to
compile the American Psychiatric Association's standard DSM-III,
the ``Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders.'' He
and Donald Goodwin also published a textbook for adherents of the
medical approach, ``Psychiatric Diagnosis'' (1974), whose fifth
edition of 1996 remains in print at Oxford University Press.
</P>
<P>
   Also in print are ``Why Psychiatry Is a Branch of Medicine''
(Oxford, 1992), and two books of which Guze was editor or
co-editor, ``Adult Psychiatry'' (Mosby, 1996) and ``Childhood
Psychopathology and Development'' (Books on Demand).
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Guze, a native New Yorker, attended City College before
receiving his medical degree from Washington University in St.
Louis in 1945. He trained in internal medicine at Barnes Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Washington faculty in 1951, served as vice
chancellor and president of the medical center from 1971 to 1989,
and headed the department of psychiatry from 1975 to 1989 and again
from 1993 to 1997. He also was psychiatrist in chief of the
university-affiliated Barnes-Jewish and St. Louis Children's
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Guze is survived by his wife of 54 years, Joy Campbell Guze; a
son, Jonathan D., of Durham, N.C.; a daughter, Jeremy Ann Guze
Opitz of Danbury, N.H., and five grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 0043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9696 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-UNITED-AIRLINES-SFCHR     07-22 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITED-AIRLINES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SUMMERTIME BLUES FOR UNITED AT SFO  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At the height of the summer travel season,
United Airlines is scrambling to cope with major flight delays and
cancellations, leaving angry passengers waiting for hours in
airports across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Union troubles, crowded runways and bad weather share the blame,
according to United, the Bay Area's dominant airline.
</P>
<P>
   In May, United led all other airlines in flight delays with only
57 percent of its planes arriving on time, according to the latest
available figures from the Department of Transportation. It also
led in flight cancellations, with 9 percent of flights never taking
off.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is especially acute at the San Francisco Airport,
the nation's worst in terms of delays, caused in most cases by fog.
United accounts for more than half of the airport's flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing everything we can, everything in our power,''
said Chris Brathwaite, a spokesman for United. ``It's been pretty
well documented that we've had some operations difficulties. But
the delays and cancellations are not because of one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   United's troubles began April 12, when its pilots contract
expired without an agreement. Many pilots reacted by refusing to
work overtime, leaving the airline scrambling because its schedule
is created taking overtime into account.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, many of United's maintenance crews have refused
to work overtime until their contract, which expired July 12, is
renewed. That has created a backlog of minor maintenance problems
that has doubled the number of grounded planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not paid near what all the other major airlines pay,''
said Herb Hunter, a spokesman for the United Airlines pilots union.
``I feel really bad for our customers. I hope they will be
patient.''
</P>
<P>
   The effect of these union disputes on flight schedules have been
compounded by the busy summer travel season, air traffic control
problems and unseasonable weather. For example, 13 United flights
in San Francisco were eliminated Friday because of fog.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of crew troubles, United has canceled at least
4,800 flights between May and September, or about 2 percent of the
airline's entire schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Lost business amounts to at least $50 million from April to
June, according to United's parent company, UAL, based in Chicago.
How much more the labor disputes, which have gone on four months so
far, cost the airline depends on how long they last.
</P>
<P>
   Many passengers are encountering an array of difficulties after
they arrive at the airport. For instance, a Chronicle reporter, who
was flying from Newark to Oakland Friday, was asked at the ticket
counter to take another flight in exchange for a $100 coupon
because his original flight was overbooked.
</P>
<P>
   The first leg of his flight was canceled because there was no
replacement for a defective part in the plane's navigation system.
He arrived in Denver late on a different plane, only to be told
that the final leg of the flight was delayed because the pilots
were in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wilson, a spokesman for San Francisco Airport, said that up
to four or five United flights have been canceled per day this
month because of crew shortages. But he said that many of those
were short distance shuttles that depart frequently so passengers
could simply take a later flight, and in some cases, be put on
another airline.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, some United passengers with canceled flights had
to sleep in the airport overnight, Wilson said. Because of these
inconveniences, the airport is receiving more passenger complaints
about United than normal.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers can take several steps to reduce the chances of a
long wait because of a delayed flight. Brathwaite, the United
spokesman, suggested that passengers call or check the airline's
Web site for flight delays before going to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Airport officials have been bothered by United's
tardy flights even prior to this summer, and they have asked the
airline to improve timeliness by at least 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   United has agreed but has not said specifically how it will be
accomplished. Possibilities include adding a few minutes to flight
itineraries and reducing the number of flights.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Kuhlmann, vice president of Roberts, Roach &AMP; Associates, an
aviation and transportation consulting firm in San Francisco, said
United is caught in a tough situation. ``United has had the
especially unfortunate situation of having labor trouble when they
are compounded by all sorts of other stuff,'' Kuhlmann said.
``They're stuck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
