<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9699 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     07-22 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPORTING MUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's news-and-views edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   News item: Davey Johnson returns from the hospital to manage the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Views: It wasn't the least bit surprising that the 2000 Dodgers
made their manager sick. Since he arrived, he's been tearing
himself up internally about all of the personnel shortcomings that
G.M. Kevin Malone handed him.
</P>
<P>
   But Malone is clearly winning the internal battle for control.
All of the key people in the front office are Malone hires, and he
has the support of CEO Bob Daly. Johnson didn't even have final say
on all of his coaches. That might make my heart beat faster, too.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Olbermann of Fox Sports Net reported this week that Dodger
officials were preparing to fire him just before he checked into a
hospital. But at this point, what's the use of letting him go? A
firing now would make the organization look sour and mean-spirited.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Johnson is fire, baseball sources say Malone will make
another run at Montreal's Felipe Alou, too, before settling for
someone like Kevin Kennedy. Alou chose to stay in Montreal two
years ago after the Expos stepped up with a new contract, but the
franchise remains an endangered species. Maybe this time Alou
doesn't get sentimental.
</P>
<P>
   After completing the current homestand, the Dodgers play 23 of
their next 36 games on the road, a run that will take them to
September. If that's bad news, here's the good: Only six games of
the next 36 are against division leaders or serious wild card
contenders, three each against the Braves and the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Friday, the N.L. West-leading Diamondbacks have 39 of
their 66 remaining games on the road, too, where they're under
.500.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the Dodgers play 19 of 28 games at home.
Twenty-two of those 28 games will be against N.L. West foes,
including six with Arizona, three with the Giants and six with the
let's-ruin-the-Dodgers-season Padres.
</P>
<P>
   News: Angel pennant hopes are closing in on August.
</P>
<P>
   Views: September is what we remember, but races are often lost
in August.
</P>
<P>
   After the Angels short road trip is concluded, they will play 13
of their next 16 at home. But 10 of those home games are against
the White Sox, Red Sox and Yankees, and thereafter, the Angels 29
of their last 44 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage the Angels do have is more games under their belt.
Thanks to early season rainouts, the Yankees (six) and red Sox
(four) have quite a few more games to play than the Angels.
Doubleheaders and a lack of off days equals losses.
</P>
<P>
   News: Wild card races are hotter than Carl Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Views: As much as one might disdain the wild card, the 2000 race
has pennant-race atmosphere. The only A.L. division that's
essentially cinched is the Central (White Sox), leaving six teams
playing for three playoff spots, and through Thursday, all six were
separated by less than two games.
</P>
<P>
   In the N.L., the Braves and Cardinals look safe. The Braves have
a schedule edge on the Mets and the Reds do not seem capable of
making a run, especially after trading Denny Neagle. But just five
games separate six contenders for two playoff spots (N.L. West,
wild card), if one believes Colorado, Cincinnati and Florida, all
just a game over .500, are contenders.
</P>
<P>
   News: Kevin Brown goes on a rant over a newspaper column.
</P>
<P>
   Views: I like to believe that athletes are bright enough to know
when they're being worked, but Brown obviously didn't. He did
exactly what the author wanted him to do, make a big fuss over
nothing and draw attention to a brief episode that was of no news
value or use to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   News: Shawn Green starts to shake his slump.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Green didn't make any excuses for his slump. But the
truth is that his homecoming has kept him extremely busy. He's very
generous with his time and money, and his first year playing at
home has definitely added a dynamic he didn't need.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he became the official spokesman for the Jewish Big
Brothers program. He filmed several public service announcements
that urge men to volunteer for the organization's mentoring
program, which has suffered a steep decline the last few years. He
will also participate in select Big Brother functions.
</P>
<P>
   Green has thrived as a person and ballplayer through his
relationship with his father, Ira, but Ira's father died young.
This is Green's way of giving back to his community while also
extending a bridge to his dad's past.
</P>
<P>
   News: Baseball's blue ribbon panel on its economics says 27 of
30 teams lost money, and it alludes to folding weaker franchises as
a way to stem the game's financial divide.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Sorry, I don't buy the idea of 27 losers in baseball,
especially when four of them are owned by media conglomerates _ the
Dodgers, Cubs, Braves and Angels. You know management at those
companies can shift money around to show a profit or loss on
whatever it wants.
</P>
<P>
   But I heartily agree with the idea of folding at least two
franchises. (I'd vote for Montreal and Tampa Bay.) The best way to
get the attention of the player's union is to threaten eliminating
100 major league jobs (40 man rosters plus coaches), another
250-plus minor league jobs, plus another 300-plus white collar jobs
(front office, scouting).
</P>
<P>
   Montreal is a great city, but the most memorable moments there
hardly involved the Expos _ Rick Monday's 1981 playoff home run and
Tony Gwynn's 3,000th hit _ and there was already proof that Florida
is a soft market before Tampa Bay was given a franchise.
</P>
<P>
   News: Isiah Thomas named Indiana Pacers coach.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Scratch one contender from the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   News: The 2000 NFL season nears with L.A. still without a
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Here's a viable quote from a U.S. Senator on the NFL:
``Fans want to watch footbvall, but a majority of owners would
rather play Monopoly ... So many cities are hungry for pro football
that they have launched a bidding war to lure away established
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   That comes from Tennessee Senator Al Gore, Jr. No, not the
current Democratic party candidate, Al Gore, but his dad, circa
1986, when the NFL was lobbying for congressional perks.
</P>
<P>
   More proof that things don't change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
