<HEADLINE>
STEPHEN GENDIN, 34, ADVOCATE AND WRITER FOR AIDS CAUSES; THOMAS
SARDINO, 72, SYRACUSE POLICE CHIEF; VIRGINIA SAURWEIN, 71, U.N.
OFFICIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: No byline) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stephen Gendin, an activist and writer who founded a nationally
known mail-order prescription service for people infected with HIV,
died Wednesday in New York. He was 34.
</P>
<P>
   Gendin died of cardiac arrest while undergoing chemotherapy for
AIDS-related lymphoma, said Sean Strubb, founder of Poz, a national
magazine about life with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Gendin spent the last 15 years working to help people who had
AIDS or who were infected with HIV, the virus that causes it. He
was a founder and the chief executive of the Community Prescription
Service, a mail-order pharmacy service that also distributes
information to people with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Gendin also became known through a regular column he wrote for
Poz. In the column, he discussed in graphic detail the toll AIDS
took on his body, his fantasies of political assassination and, in
an article that incited outrage among many gay men, the guilt and
the pleasure he felt from having unprotected sex.
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman at Brown University, Gendin learned he was
infected with HIV. He founded the Rhode Island Chapter of Act Up,
the AIDS protest group, and was active in fund-raising for the
organization's New York chapter. He regularly took part in
protests, rallies and mass acts of civil disobedience, for which he
had a long arrest record. He was a director of AID for AIDS, which
distributes medications to patients in Latin America. He was also a
founder of Sex Panic, a group that contends it is preserving New
York's untrammeled ``sexual culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Gendin is survived by his partner, Kyle MacDowell; his father,
Sidney Gendin of Ypsilanti, Mich.; and his sister, Margo Hart of
Ionia, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   THOMAS SARDINO, 72, SYRACUSE POLICE CHIEF &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas J. Sardino, who as Syracuse's police chief strove to
defuse demonstrations, disorders and racial tension in the early
1970s, died July 14 in Syracuse. He was 72 and lived in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was heart failure, The Associated Press said.
</P>
<P>
   Sardino headed his city's police from 1970 to 1985. In
mid-August 1971, when Syracuse youth gangs were involved in a
series of racial clashes, window breakings and fire-bombings, he
sent police community relations teams and human relations experts
to try to bring peace between the gangs, and the violence subsided.
</P>
<P>
   Early that month, after three nights of fire-bombing, Sardino
declared that ``citizens who feel their life and property are
threatened by arsonists may use deadly force.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, when Vietnam War opponents, after protesting at
Syracuse University, wanted to march through the city's streets,
Sardino gave his approval. But he stipulated that the march had to
be well behaved _ and be led by him.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1990 interview, David Ifshin, who had been a Syracuse
student leader in 1970, recalled Sardino's ``patience and wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   Sardino wrote books about police work, including ``Crime Control
Team'' (1971) and ``Police Crisis Intervention'' (1977).
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Syracuse, received degrees from Syracuse
University and joined the Syracuse police force in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Nina, 5 children and 11
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA SAURWEIN, 71, U.N. OFFICIAL
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Saurwein, who was the United Nations' top liaison
official with nongovernmental organizations from 1975 until 1989,
died July 9 in Erie, Pa. She was 71 and lived in South Salem, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   She suffered a heart attack and a stroke in February, according
to a former colleague.
</P>
<P>
   During Saurwein's tenure, nongovernmental organizations, known
as became increasingly influential at the United Nations in fields
like the environment, international law, arms control and human
rights. Such groups often play a significant role in bringing
social issues to the attention of member states.
</P>
<P>
   At the International Women's Year conference in Mexico City in
1975, Saurwein helped draft the first U.N. resolution on women's
access to credit. Later she was a co-founder and board member of
Women's World Banking, a global loan-guarantee organization. After
the Mexico City conference, she became chief of the nongovernmental
organization liaison unit in the U.N. Department of Economic and
Social affairs, a post she held until her retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Early in her career Saurwein worked as a program director at the
U.N. Association of the USA and at the Center for War/Peace
Studies. In 1970, the U.N. Development Program asked her to help
create its nongovernmental organization liaison office, which she
managed for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Saurwein is survived by a brother, George Saurwein, of Erie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
