<SLUG> BC-NY-VAMPIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NIGHT STALKER' IN NEW YORK BOARDING HOUSE JAILED AFTER ATTACKING
NEIGHBOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS _ Anyone who relishes scary stories knows that
there is one sure way to slay a vampire: drive a sharp wooden stake
through his heart while he sleeps.
</P>
<P>
   A 45-year-old Rockland County man, David Bolton, tried to do
just that to a neighbor early Wednesday, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had our share of violent attacks,'' said Sgt. Steve
Morgan of the Clarkstown police, ``but nothing with this, shall we
say, modus operandi.''
</P>
<P>
   According to police reports, at about 2 a.m. Bolton broke into
his victim's room at the Laurel Hotel, a boarding house where both
men live in Nanuet, a hamlet in Clarkstown. He was carrying a
hammer and a handmade wooden cross that had been whittled to a
spike at one end, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Bolton struck the other man, Jeffrey Todd, 22, with the hammer,
and brandished the sharpened cross as if he were about to impale
him, the police said. Todd awoke in time to wrestle the cross from
Bolton, but Bolton repeatedly hit him with the hammer on the head,
neck, shoulder and back, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   When others in the boarding house heard the commotion and came
to help, Bolton ran back to his room, where he was later arrested,
the police said. Todd, a construction worker, was treated at Nyack
Hospital and released.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said the two men had no previous dispute. Bolton told
police officers that he had ``received instructions from a higher
authority,'' the Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Bolton was being held without bail Friday at the Rockland County
Correctional Facility, charged with attempted murder, assault,
burglary and criminal possession of a weapon, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Laurel Hotel, Todd's older brother Brian said the
attack had left him and other residents too frightened to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``It freaks you out,'' he said. ``I can't sleep at night. No one
can. You see it happening in the movies, but you never expect it in
real life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 0052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
