<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE BE BACK TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Devon White figures he'll be activated as soon as
today after missing the last 69 games with a left-shoulder injury.
And when White returns, Todd Hollandsworth said he expects to drop
back into the role of White's backup in center field for the Los
Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   White went 1 for 2 with a double and walk in five innings Friday
in his second rehab game for Class A San Bernardino, and general
manager Kevin Malone said White would control when he's ready to
return _ providing the team's medical staff gives him clearance.
It's a two-game rehab stint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is still what it was,'' Hollandsworth said.
``It's been kind of weird. But circumstances are what they are.
They always have been. Nothing has changed along those lines.''
</P>
<P>
   White will be eased back, but Hollandsworth acknowledges White
will eventually be the starter again. Before the injury, White
started 19 of 26 games in center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what the circumstances were, Devo's going to be
here for the long haul,'' Hollandsworth said. ``He's under a
multiyear contract and as long as he's healthy he's going to play.
That's the way it's been.''
</P>
<P>
   White is in the second year of a three-year, $12.4 million
contract. Hollandsworth is a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers like Hollandsworth's versatility, but a team
official said it's ``extremely unlikely'' Hollandsworth would
re-sign with the club in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   __ Dusty's decision: The last time the Dodgers had a managerial
search, Dusty Baker was mentioned time and again as a leading
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   With Baker's current contract status unresolved, coupled with
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson's uncertain future, Baker's
availability and his level of interest in Los Angeles holds
relevance.
</P>
<P>
   Baker has been offered a contract extension by the Giants, but
he hasn't acted on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided to wait,'' Baker said. ``Right now, I'm going
to put all my efforts into winning. That's what I preach to my
players, `Don't worry about the contract, don't worry about the
money.' Do your job, win and the money will follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's situation is up in the air. You live life up in
the air. Davey's a fine manager. I don't know what's happened here
with Davey or what hasn't happened here. I'm just hoping that
Davey's healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers hope it never becomes an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers managing general partner and CEO Bob Daly said, ``I love
Davey as my manager and I hope he's back next season.'' But that
decision won't be made until the rest of the Dodgers season plays
out.
</P>
<P>
   A baseball official said he didn't think Baker would be
available next season, instead stating he thought the former
Dodgers player would remain with the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm going to do,'' Baker said. ``God's going
to tell me what to do. My main thing is to win. We have a number of
free agents, a number of arbitration-eligible guys.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Catcher Todd Hundley said the pain still
exists in his fractured right thumb and he won't be coming off the
disabled list when he's eligible Monday. Hundley said next weekend
in Philadelphia is his target. . . . Catcher Paul LoDuca found
himself in an unfamiliar spot _ batting leadoff. ``It's the first
time I can remember doing it. I was always a fat little kid,'' said
LoDuca, who singled in the first inning. . . . Right-hander Gregg
Olson's return remains on hold while the Dodgers iron out their
roster needs. They might not know until late next week, by which
time Hundley's and White's health should be known.
</P>
</TEXT>
