<HEADER>
A9705 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-REPUBLICAN-TAX-N     07-22 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-REPUBLICAN-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REPUBLICAN TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, July 22:
</P>
<P>
   The Republican effort to pass tax cuts that are tilted in favor
of wealthy families has until now been largely an election-year
sideshow. This week's vote to cut taxes on married couples,
including upper-income couples whom the code now subsidizes, and
previous votes to eliminate the tax on wealthy estates were not
large enough to get past President Clinton's promised vetoes. These
tax plans will die.
</P>
<P>
   But another GOP tax bill may not. The House will vote next week
whether to repeal a tax hike on high-income Social Security
recipients passed in 1993 as part of Clinton's deficit-reduction
plan. The Senate has already voted 58-41 for repeal. The Clinton
plan raised the portion of benefits subject to taxes to as much as
85 percent from 50 percent _ in effect raising the tax rate from
about 15 percent to about 25 percent. The White House argued that
it brought taxes on Social Security benefits closer in line with
taxes on private pensions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even after the 1993 rate hike, the tax code continues to
treat Social Security benefits more favorably than private pension
benefits. Repeal would make the discrepancy worse, and hand an
unwarranted $100 billion tax cut to the 15 percent or so wealthiest
retirees over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Unfairness is not the only problem. The Social Security system
is expected to run deficits over the next 75 years. This situation,
if addressed immediately, could be eliminated with modest fixes.
One would be to tax Social Security benefits fully as much as
private pensions. Repeal of the 1993 tax hike would move in the
opposite direction, eventually forcing Congress to tackle the
deficits with stiff benefit cuts and tax hikes.
</P>
<P>
   The vote in the Senate for repeal was short of the two-thirds
majority needed to override a veto. But some of the Democrats who
voted against repeal have warned their leadership that they are
likely to change their votes if it comes back to the Senate after
overwhelming approval in the House. That danger can be avoided if a
large number of House members reject the repeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
