<HEADER>
A9707 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-SENATE-APPEAL-NY     07-22 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SENATE-APPEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SENATE'S DIMINISHING APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, July 22:
</P>
<P>
   It is too soon to know whether questions surrounding
fund-raising activities in Sen. Robert Torricelli's 1996 campaign
will derail his ambitions to become the next governor of New
Jersey. What intrigues us at the moment is Torricelli's eagerness
to leave the Senate after only four years, and the light this sheds
on the relative appeal of the Senate and the statehouses. The
Senate has been described as ``the greatest deliberative body on
earth.'' Even so, Torricelli wants out, believing that as a
governor he has a better chance of getting things done and,
further, a better chance to achieve higher office should he ever
seek it.
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone in that view. Among politicians who seek
enhanced power and greater influence over social policy, the Senate
has declined in value while the governorships have risen. Leverage
is one factor. Torricelli is but one of 100 senators. An individual
senator can shape legislation and, on very rare occasions, claim
authorship. But unless a senator heads a committee, his or her
power is incremental.
</P>
<P>
   A governor, by contrast, is a chief executive, an agenda-setter
and architect. Governors make things happen. Congress rewrote the
welfare laws. But it is governors like John Engler of Michigan and
Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin _ flush with cash from Washington _ who
are actually remaking welfare in America. It is the governors who
can turn bad schools into good ones. It was a single governor,
George Ryan of Illinois, who energized the national debate on
capital punishment by imposing a moratorium on executions.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has other liabilities. It requires a personality
capable of enduring endless delays while engaging in tedious
negotiations that may produce nothing at all. Nor can senators any
longer count on foreign policy issues to help them build a national
reputation. The end of the Cold War and the increasing complexity
of global issues have effectively shrunk the stage that yielded
such big players as William Fulbright and Henry Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate's main deficiency is that for someone who aspires
to broad influence and the mantle of leadership, it is simply not
the place to amass a portfolio of politically portable
achievements. John McCain came to the 2000 Republican primaries
identified mainly with an unsuccessful if valiant effort to reform
the campaign financing system. Bill Bradley came to the Democratic
primary identified mainly with tax reform. Energetic governors, by
contrast, can write a legislative resume that cuts across many
fields and can be marketed as a coherent body of work.
</P>
<P>
   This may account for the decreasing importance of the Senate and
increasing importance of the statehouses as sources of presidential
timber. From 1960 until 1976, the Senate provided nearly all the
party nominees and most of the serious candidates for the
nomination. Former senators _ Kennedy, Johnson and Nixon _ occupied
the White House from 1961 to 1974. But for 20 of the last 24 years,
governors have run the place _ Jimmy Carter, Ronald Reagan and Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli, already outlining the makings of a campaign
platform, said that as governor he would establish a statewide
day-care system, stop suburban sprawl, give prescription drug
benefits to the middle class and broaden the public school system
to include 4-year-olds. Any one of these would be a career-defining
achievement for a senator. But for a prospective governor, such an
agenda is not far-fetched.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
