<HEADER>
A9709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-DEMOCRACY-FIJI-N     07-22 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DEMOCRACY-FIJI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DEMOLISHING DEMOCRACY IN FIJI 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, July 22:
</P>
<P>
   A model effort to create an equitable, multiethnic society in
the South Pacific island nation of Fiji has been derailed by the
forced removal of the country's first ethnic Indian prime minister.
The United States and other democratic nations should press Fiji's
new leaders to honor its Constitution, which in 1997 awarded ethnic
Indian citizens the right to hold high office.
</P>
<P>
   The recent upheaval was largely the work of George Speight, a
part-Fijian businessman who stormed the Parliament in May with a
group of armed followers and held three dozen people hostage,
including Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry, until last week. He
accused Chaudhry of promoting pro-Indian policies. Speight says
that Indians, who make up 44 percent of Fiji's population of
812,000, have too much economic and political clout. The siege
ended when military leaders bowed to Speight's demands for a new
government.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji's new president, Ratu Josefa Iloilo, and its new prime
minister, Laisenia Qarase, attempted to challenge Speight by not
appointing rebel supporters to key cabinet positions. Speight
responded by forcing Iloilo, who is elderly and ill, to make room
in the administration for rebels and possibly for himself as well.
</P>
<P>
   The international community should help Chaudhry's People's
Coalition regain power. Britain, Australia and New Zealand have
recalled their ambassadors because of the unrest, which has
included looting and arson against Indian-owned stores, and are
pushing Fiji to adopt constitutional rule again. On Friday Britain
went further, canceling assistance programs and military visits.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji's military and new government seem intimidated by Speight
and his small band of rebels. Speight is a demagogue who does not
speak for the majority of indigenous Fijians. His racist,
anti-democratic ideas will prevail unless Fiji's democrats and army
commanders work together peacefully to renew constitutional rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
