<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9711 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IRAN-WOMEN-1STLD-WRIT     07-22 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-WOMEN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1089(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN IRAN, MORE WOMEN LEAVING NEST FOR UNIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS ``effect'' to ``affect'' in 3rd graf of 2nd take)  
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ When Maryam Barati first left her home in Isfahan
three years ago to attend college in the capital, she prayed
silently as ech of the 200 miles rolled by.
</P>
<P>
   She prayed that her father, who was at the wheel, would not
suddenly turn the car around and say that she, like all the women
in her family for uncounted generations, could leave the family
nest only to get married.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very reluctant to let me go away to a different city to
study,'' recalled Barati, a 23-year-old physical education
teacher-in-training at Alzahra University in central Tehran. ``But
he finally decided it was all right, and he realized that this has
been an incredible experience for me. Here we have to learn how to
live on our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Her adventure in independence is being repeated all over Iran,
where young women now make up nearly 60 percent of university
entrants although women represent barely half the school-age
population.
</P>
<P>
   In a quiet revolution in political and social relations, they
are leaving home as single women in historically high numbers,
forsaking their conservative villages and small towns to seek
higher education wherever they can get it.
</P>
<P>
   Their self-assured mobility _ an independence of action that
their mothers and grandmothers could not even imagine _ represents
a grand social experiment whose impact is making itself felt on
campus and off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phenomenon will change the country in ways we cannot even
predict as they enter the labor market and the professions,'' said
Elaheh Koulai, an administrative dean at Tehran University and a
reformist member of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that old taboos against higher education for women
have collapsed is that Iranian universities, under the overall
control of Muslim religious leaders, offer worried parents strict
controls over their daughters' lives on campus. Often, the
prohibitions are far more severe than they would have faced at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Their dress, their visitors, even their music and reading
materials are closely monitored. Still, the women say, they are
relishing a fresh sense of freedom even as they realize that their
newfound access to education does not guarantee them jobs
commensurate with their skills.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the educational development of women has been
building for decades, as overall literacy rates have climbed and
the poor and middle-class gained access to education that was the
near-exclusive preserve of the urban rich before the Islamic
revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The women _ and men _ now clamoring for university spaces are
the children of that revolution, born in a baby boom that began in
the early 1980s and slowed only in the last few years. From 1976 to
1986, the national population grew from 33.7 million to 49.4
million. Today it is estimated at 61 million, with 40 percent of
the people under 15.
</P>
<P>
   The desire of women for university slots skyrocketed. From 1990
to 2000, the number of women entering universities tripled as baby
boomers came of age. In some disciplines, like medicine and social
sciences, women now far outnumber men.
</P>
<P>
   And while they have not yet broken into the labor force in
comparable numbers, they have made their expectations and demands a
factor in politics.
</P>
<P>
   The landslide election in 1997 of President Mohammad Khatami, a
moderate cleric who pledged wider social freedoms, is widely
attributed to his popularity among young people and especially
among young women. The failure of conservatives to retain their
hold on Parliament after elections earlier this year is also widely
attributed to a backlash from young women against their support for
hardline social restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the conservatives as a whole have begun to
really understand what the impact will be of having so many
educated young women graduating from our universities,'' said
Mohammad Javad Larijani, a veteran hard-line parliamentarian who
lost his seat in the reformist wave, in an interview after the
elections. ``These women are going to demand that society give
value to their skills and their degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   Women have long been underrepresented in politics and the
professions in Iran. They make up just 14 percent of the labor
force, according to a recent United Nations report on human
development in Iran. When they do find jobs, it is in government,
where they hold 23 percent of the public sector posts, and in
farming. They are overrepresented in comparison to men _ by a
factor of 2 to 1 _ only in the unemployment rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many trained and skilled women and girls must stay at home
because of social and traditional obstacles from their families,''
said Dr. Koulai. ``Many men in our society don't want their wives
working outside the home. But this is going to change. The process
is unstoppable.''
</P>
<P>
   Those obstacles have not deterred many families from breaking
tradition and pushing their daughters to get a university degree at
any cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our daughters don't study, they won't have anything in
life,'' said Ashraf Juyandeh, a 49-year-old cafeteria worker in the
city of Shiraz who is trying to get her two daughters into the
local university.
</P>
<P>
   ``I myself only finished sixth grade,'' she added. ``Back then,
the rich could afford to send their daughters to school, but
traditional families considered it a bad thing. My mother was never
allowed to go to university and my father could never have afforded
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Juyandeh was married at 14 and widowed at 39. She says she will
get as many jobs as she can to earn enough money to send both her
daughters to university _ anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where religious traditions and the conservative
clergy still dictate a subservient role for women in many families,
the movement of young women out of their hometowns in search of
education and work has already brought about changes in attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience I am having _ and other girls are having _ is
going to affect this country in many ways,'' said Raziyeh Bigonah,
23, an arts student at Alzahra University. ``People who leave their
homes to go to a bigger city experience different things. I'm sure
my generation of women will make itself felt in society.''
</P>
<P>
   She came to Tehran from Tabriz, about 330 miles away, leaving
behind four older housebound sisters who had no desire and no
encouragement from their parents to go to university. ``I try to
keep up my relations with my sisters,'' Bigonah said. ``But now, I
prefer to live here for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Iranian authorities have tried at different times in recent
years to control the impact of the demand by the new generation of
school-age women for higher education. For nine years, from 1989
until 1997, they limited the number of university slots for women
in order to provide space for male veterans of the war with Iraq.
They have been slow, as well, to build new dormitories at big
campuses where out-of-town women are required to live, sometimes by
their families and sometimes by the university itself.
</P>
<P>
   To control the activities of women on campus, for example, the
universities enforce strict rules at dormitories. Young women are
required to wear the traditional black chador _ the all-enveloping
cloak _ over long coats and tightly pinned headscarves, not only
outside the dorm but inside as well. There are curfews, bans on
visitors and music, and constant supervision of reading material
brought into the dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the regulations, which often are more severe than
what students faced at home, many women say they have learned an
independent way of thinking that can not be unlearned. ``I'm sure
it will affect our choices in marriage,'' said Barati, the Alzahra
student who once feared that her father would not even let her
begin studies. ``I'm educated now, and, young people like me, we
all have more expectations from life these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not talking just about economics,'' she continued.
``Actually our parents' economic situation was probably better. But
because my future husband and I will both be people who separated
from our parents to go to university and faced the problems of
being independent, we will understand each other better than our
parents probably did when they married.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9715 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IVORY-COAST-REFERENDU     07-22 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVORY-COAST-REFERENDUM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFERENDUM MAY BRING MORE POLITICAL TUMULT TO IVORY COAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS ``cocoa'' to ``cacao'' in 5th graf from end)  
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast _ This onetime redoubt of political
stability and steady growth in West Africa has been through a lot
in the last year: the fall of an unpopular president, the first
coup in its history and military misrule that twice in the last
month raised the possibility of another army uprising.
</P>
<P>
   During all this tumult the spotlight has stayed on one man, a
former prime minister and mild-mannered international banker,
Alassane Ouattara.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ouattara returned here a year ago from Washington, where
he served as the International Monetary Fund's deputy managing
director, his political fortunes have been on a roller coaster. He
is down again _ and, along with him, maybe the chances of Ivory
Coast's smooth transition back to civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Ivoirians are to vote on a constitutional referendum
whose key parts were intended specifically to exclude Ouattara from
running in the presidential election scheduled for September.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with a bitterness and a weariness that people say are
new to him, Ouattara, 58, vowed in an interview last week to win in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's this group of mediocre people,'' Ouattara said of his
main political opponents and the military government. ``They know
that they could not stand competition. They have their toys they
want to keep to themselves. They know that if we open up, they are
so mediocre they would lose everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The country's military ruler, Gen. Robert Guei, declared a
four-day state of emergency Friday , which members of his junta
said was intended to ensure that the referendum take place
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the former president, Henri Konan Bedie, who was
ousted in the coup, had tried to eliminate Ouattara as a rival by
arguing he was less of an Ivoirian than others because his father
was from neighboring Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
   Bedie's strategy was part of an overall concept of Ivoirite,
which he argued were values shared by pure Ivoirians, but which was
essentially tribalism that sought to draw a line between Christian
southerners and Muslim northerners like Ouattara.
</P>
<P>
   The cleavage was strange in a country that had long been known
for its ethnic tolerance. But even though Ouattara always
maintained that both of his parents were Ivoirian and he himself
was as Ivoirian as anyone else, ethnic divisions have widened in
the Ivory Coast in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   For a few months after the fall of Bedie, Guei, preached ethnic
reconciliation, and the two men appeared to be on friendly terms.
</P>
<P>
   But as Guei's intentions to hold on to power have become
clearer, the two men have stopped cooperating. The general, a
member of a minority ethnic group from the southwest, has adopted
the same ethnic strategy against Ouattara. A commission set up to
prepare the referendum recommended that a presidential candidate
must be Ivoirian-born of a father or mother born in the Ivory
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday evening, just six days before the referendum, Guei
issued a decree saying that a presidential candidate must be
Ivoirian-born of a father and mother born in the Ivory Coast. In a
news conference, the general claimed that 15 of the country's 18
administrative regions had pressed him to change the ``or'' to
``and.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people have expressed their wish,'' said the general, who
came to power after young soldiers mutinied throughout the Ivory
Coast in late December. ``We are here to respond to their wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   But the change was widely interpreted as another effort to
dislodge Ouattara. Another clause _ that a candidate should never
have availed himself of another nationality _ also seemed targeted
at Ouattara, who represented Burkina Faso for a regional financial
institution earlier in his career, a relatively common practice at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the December coup, Ouattara described it as a
``popular revolution.'' He said he had hoped that the new military
ruler would not try to cling to power, the way others have
typically done in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general was in retirement,'' Ouattara said. ``So we
thought he was really coming to help the process of restoring
democracy as he said he would. But obviously once in power he
wanted to confiscate and grab power. And this is quite a
disappointment for all of us who consider ourselves democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that none of these clauses affected his eligibility,
Ouattara has told his followers to endorse the referendum, as have
the country's two other major parties. So while the outcome may not
be in doubt, it will yield hints as to how September's election
might unfold.
</P>
<P>
   A constitutional court that will rule on the eligibility of
presidential candidates recently got a new head: one of Guei's
legal advisers. If Ouattara is prevented legally from running, it
is likely that the battle will spill onto the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I'll get popular support,'' Ouattara said. ``But I
hope it will not get to that point. I hope that the international
community, the regional partners and domestic pressure will put
sense into the head of the general.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, in a news conference a day after meeting
Guei, the U.S. ambassador, George Mu, said Washington was worried
about Ivory Coast's stability. The ambassador restated the State
Department's position that Guei, having seized power by force,
should not stand as a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mu's comments came after two days of rioting by soldiers in
downtown Abidjan. Displeased that they had not received money they
claimed had been promised them, the soldiers shut down businesses
and the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Guei took refuge in the police headquarters and was able to
defuse the situation only after agreeing to give soldiers about
$1,500 each.
</P>
<P>
   Guei accused Ouattara's party of fomenting the riots, a charge
he denied. The U.S. ambassador said they appeared to be strictly
over money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mutiny reduced the popularity of the general, who now
looks weakened,'' said a Western diplomat here.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was a reminder that even the general has never had
full control over the country's 14,000-member military since the
December coup. A military emboldened even further and ensuing
instability would make it harder to reverse the Ivory Coast's slide
and would turn it into a source of problems for the region, many
Ivoirians and foreigners here believe.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Second to Nigeria, the Ivory Coast is the economic leader in
West Africa. It stands as the world's largest cacao producer and at
the top of French-speaking Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But Abidjan, an African bright spot famous for its smooth roads
and solid infrastructure, is beginning to show the signs of being
led by a government that has little money left. Gaping potholes and
collapsed highway ramps have been left unrepaired for months.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he will run and win in September, Ouattara promised an
IMF-style cleanup of the Ivory Coast's economy that would include a
sweeping anti-corruption campaign and an overhaul of an inefficient
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Having left the IMF only a year ago, Ouattara said he was
pessimistic about Africa. He has seen too many African countries
ground down by men whose only concern was to capture or keep power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, if you have a system where the people can vote you
out, the situation will be different,'' Ouattara said. ``But many
people that get in are rigging elections or doing it by coup
d'etat, because they are mediocre. They know they cannot stand
competition. They confiscate power and continue to rule the
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 0114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9718 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-WACO-REPORT-1STLD-WRI     07-22 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-REPORT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL COUNSEL CLEARS GOVERNMENT IN WACO DEATHS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (CORRECTS ``bunker'' to ``construction pit'' in 7th graf) 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT21 and NYT22 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ John Danforth, the special counsel investigating the
1993 tear-gas assault by federal agents on the Branch Davidian
compound, Friday issued a sweeping report that cleared Attorney
General Janet Reno and the government of any wrongdoing in the
deadly episode.
</P>
<P>
   Reminding a crowded news conference of his initial pledge to
answer the ``dark questions'' surrounding the case, Danforth, a
former Republican senator from Missouri, did not mince words. He
declared that agents did not shoot at the Branch Davidians and did
not start the fire that destroyed the compound on April 19, 1993,
claiming the lives of about 80 people.
</P>
<P>
   He said the military was not used improperly and that the
government ``did not engage in a massive conspiracy and cover-up.''
Danforth placed blame and responsibility for the deaths on members
of the religious sect, particularly the group's leader, David
Koresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are certain,'' he said, reading from a statement. ``And I
give you these conclusions with 100 percent certainty. ``The blame
rests squarely on the shoulders of David Koresh. ``This is not a
close call.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Danforth exonerated the government, he also rebuked it.
He spoke pointedly and passionately about how public confidence in
government had eroded because certain officials failed to speak
candidly about aspects of the case. His own appointment by Reno had
come in September after disclosures that agents of the FBI, despite
repeated denials, had fired pyrotechnic tear-gas canisters capable
of starting a fire into the compound on the day it burned.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Danforth said that Reno and other high-ranking
government officials had not known that agents fired such
projectiles. But he blamed ``a few government lawyers and an FBI
agent'' for concealing the use of the projectiles. They were
launched hours before the fire and did not contribute to it,
Danforth said.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that FBI agents fired three pyrotechnic
rounds at a construction pit about 75 yards from the living
quarters of the Davidians. The rounds did not cause any damage, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   The Danforth report comes one week after an advisory jury
hearing a federal wrongful death civil lawsuit ruled that the
government was not liable for the deaths of the Branch Davidians.
The jury's verdict is not binding and the ultimate decision will be
made by the judge hearing the case.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth said he waited to publish his report in order not to
influence the jury's deliberations. He called his investigation
``95 percent complete,'' saying another 3 1/2 months will be needed
to determine whether ``further action'' is necessary against those
involved in covering up the use of the projectiles.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in a conference room at a downtown hotel, Danforth
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us should be more skeptical of those who make
sensational accusations of evil acts by government. At the same
time, government personnel, especially government lawyers, owe the
American people an openness and candor that was lacking in response
to the tragedy at Waco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the government did nothing evil on April 19, 1993,
the failure of some of its employees to fully and openly disclose
to the American people the use of pyrotechnic devices undermined
public confidence in government and caused real damage to our
country.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder issued a
statement praising Danforth's findings. ``Today's independent
review sheds further light on the truth, and discredits many of the
unsubstantiated allegations that have skewed the public's
perception of the events of April 19, 1993,'' Holder said. ``We
join Senator Danforth in wishing that this report begins the
process of restoring the faith of people in their government.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder said he was concerned about the findings that government
lawyers had withheld the information about the pyrotechnic rounds
but ``heartened'' that those rounds had not caused the fire. He
also said the report underscored the attorney general's ``diligent
efforts to learn the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Freeh, the FBI director, said: ``The simple truth, as the
FBI has maintained since April 19, 1993, has been unmistakingly
confirmed again today. The FBI fired no shots on that day and the
Davidians started the fire that ultimately engulfed the compound.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Caddell, the lead lawyer for the Branch Davidians in the
wrongful death lawsuit, expressed disappointment with Danforth's
findings and found particular fault with his conclusion that
federal agents had not fired weapons. Next month, Caddell and
government lawyers will litigate that issue as a separate, but
related, part of the wrongful death lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said Danforth disregarded flaws in a special simulation
conducted in March to help discern if weapons were fired. The
simulation was intended to determine if flashes that appeared on an
aerial, infrared videotape filmed the day of the fire were caused
by gunfire. A British company hired by Danforth to conduct the
simulation determined that the flashes were caused by reflections
from water and metal, not gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell had initially sought the test, but he later argued that
the simulation was imprecise. He said overlooking the flaws, such
as the poor quality of the simulation tape and what he termed
mistakes by the British company in carrying out the simulation,
``is both irresponsible and a disservice to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Friday's news conference, Danforth emphasized that
the scope of his probe was limited to ``whether government agents
engaged in bad acts, not whether they exercised bad judgment.'' He
said his parameters were confined to certain specific questions:
Did federal agents start the fire? Did they shoot at the Davidians
on April 19? Did they use pyrotechnic devices? Was there any
illegal use of the military? Was there a cover-up?
</P>
<P>
   An ordained Episcopal minister, Danforth was chosen, in part,
because of his reputation in the Senate for integrity and
rectitude. In conducting his inquiry, he had 16 lawyers and 38
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The Branch Davidian episode began on Feb. 28, 1993, when a
gunfight broke out as Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms agents
attempted to serve a warrant on Koresh at the compound near Waco.
Four ATF agents were killed. The ensuing 51-day standoff ended on
April 19 when FBI agents sought to subdue the Branch Davidians by
firing tear gas into the compound with tanks. The wooden structure
erupted in flames and burned to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Government critics have claimed that federal agents, frustrated
and angry, were either partly, or completely, responsible for the
deaths of those inside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The remainder of the investigation will address the actions of
those who hid information about the use of pyrotechnic rounds,
which have disappeared from evidence collected at the scene. In the
report, Danforth criticizes government lawyers for making
misleading statements about the rounds during the discovery process
of the civil wrongful death lawsuit. He also criticized the FBI's
failure, until September 1999 to release an audiotape of Richard
Rogers, the head of the FBI Hostage Rescue Team, authorizing the
use of the explosive rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth said Reno and then-FBI Director William Sessions had
sought and received reassurances from field agents that pyrotechnic
rounds had not been used on April 19. Both testified to this before
Congress in 1993. The report stated that Rogers sat behind them
silently and his failure to correct their statements was `a
significant omission that contributed to the public perception of a
cover-up, which permitted a false impression to persist for several
years.`
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said he was not paying attention to their comments during
the testimony. Danforth said the remainder of his investigation
would address questions surrounding why government lawyers and FBI
officials hid the existence of the pyrotechnic rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth's office will not pursue any further investigation of
Rogers or any other members of the hostage rescue team, the report
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
