<SLUG> BC-OLY-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAPLIN IN HIS ELEMENT AS OLYMPIC TRACK COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Those who know him figure it's the role of
a lifetime. He begs to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not playing God,'' John Chaplin insisted, deadpan. ``I'm
not smart enough _ even though a lot of you don't believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Chaplin, the irrepressible track coach at Washington State
University from 1973 to 1994, is quite far from divinity, he is in
fact something of a track god these days _ head coach for the U.S.
men's team being assembled this weekend at the trials at Cal-State
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Even at 62, his acerbic, contentious style has lost none of its
bite. His appointment to lead the world's most formidable track
team has only enhanced his legendary sense of righteousness.
</P>
<P>
   To many, including injured decathlete Dan O'Brien, that's just
about a perfect resume for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely deserving,'' O'Brien said Friday while
spectating at Hornet Stadium. The Idaho resident's years of
training in the Palouse made him a confidant, and fan, of the
ex-Cougars coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you could have gotten a better guy,'' he said.
``The biggest thing is he's not afraid to make a decision some
people won't like, and not lose a bit of sleep over it. And he's a
good decision-maker too.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin showed he was up for the media-swordfight part of the
job this week when he was bombarded with questions about relay-team
selection.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Yanks are always strongest when the track distance is
shortest, the relays are where the world expects the U.S. to
dominate.
</P>
<P>
   So when America in 1996 lost the 4x100 gold to Canada, well, the
shame was enough to inspire thoughts of barricading the northern
border. The U.S. coach, Erv Hunt, will live in infamy as the man
who failed to put Carl Lewis in the relay.
</P>
<P>
   The relay-selection process, especially for the shorter race, is
legendary for its politics, controversies and second-guessing. As a
veteran of more than 30 years in national and international track,
Chaplin succinctly summarized the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simple,'' he said. ``Win the relay, or I'm dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Prompting his denial of divinity was a series of questions
seeking his plan for selecting from a stable of great sprinters.
Growing a little exasperated, Chaplin denied any brilliance, as
well as any plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look guys, we take the six fastest, and any two others off the
rest of the team,'' Chaplin said. ``We'll sit down after the meet
and agree on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``As to who will run the relay in Sydney, we may not know until
the day before the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Chaplin said that University of Washington
sprinter/footballer Ja'Warren Hooker was still in the running for a
berth in the 4x400 pool. Although the Ellensburg native finished
seventh in the 400 finals Sunday, the top seven were asked to sign
up for pool eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ja'Warren looked very good,'' Chaplin said. ``He's got great
skills from 60 to 400 meters. We know that. We also know we have a
very good 4x4 team. But we wouldn't have signed him up if we're not
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooker still has heats to run today in the 200. If he makes the
field of eight for Sunday's finals, featuring Michael Johnson
against Maurice Greene, he might be eligible for the 4x100 pool as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The relay pools are necessary at the Olympics because the top
sprinters often skip preliminary rounds to concentrate on
individual races.
</P>
<P>
   The prickly, occasionally subjective selection process demands a
thick skin. When it comes to such matters, Chaplin has a rhino
hide.
</P>
<P>
   His unblinking steadfastness was evident the last time America
laid eyes on him. At the '96 Games in Atlanta, Chaplin was meet
referee when defending 100-meter champion Linford Christie of Great
Britain was disqualified for two false starts.
</P>
<P>
   Furious, Christie refused to leave the track, folding his arms
defiantly. It was Chaplin, virtually alone, who confronted Christie
and convinced him to move into the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have crossed Chaplin and his considerable ego may have
a different view, but others will say he has what's required for
the hot seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a long history with the man,'' said John Smith, the
1972 Olympic 400 champ who now coaches several sprinters and
hurdlers at the trials. ``He tried recruiting me to WSU. But I
thought UCLA was a little better than Pullman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a wealth of wisdom and experience that will be
instrumental in problem solving. He's experienced in all levels in
the sport _ coaching, officiating as well as administrative.''
</P>
<P>
   Some folks in Pullman might take issue with the latter, since
the Cougars spent the last two years of his tenure on Pac-10
probation. Chaplin and his baseball counterpart, Bobo Brayton, were
busted for failing to calculate tuition waivers into their sports'
annual budgets.
</P>
<P>
   The maneuver, which cost WSU its 1985 and 1991 Pac-10 track
titles, was part of Chaplin's attempts to spread his 12 track
scholarships among as many as 25 athletes.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to be forever fighting the limited resources WSU and
the NCAA gave to track. He railed loud and long about the poverty,
particularly since he had high-end tastes. He was among the first,
and perhaps the best, at importing foreign athletes, particularly
Kenyan distance runners _ ``The Long Crimson Line,'' as it was
known.
</P>
<P>
   His aggressive international recruiting earned WSU three
second-place finishes in the NCAA national meets, plus an indoor
championship in 1977. His candor and loquaciousness also served him
well in the Cougars' athletic heyday of the 1970s and 1980s when
George Raveling was basketball coach and Jim Walden was football
coach.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been hard to get kids to Pullman, but it wasn't hard
to pull a good quote out of there.
</P>
<P>
   His provocative tactics regularly drew the ire of rivals. Track
fans still talk of the time in 1978 in Eugene, Ore., when Cougars
distance star Henry Rono was on his way to a world record in a
prelim heat only to be ordered by Chaplin to slow down so the
record wouldn't be broken on the ground of the hated Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   But the most memorable facet of Chaplin for O'Brien was the
treatment of his charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``What comes through the most is he takes care of his
athletes,'' O'Brien said ``It's so impressive the way he treats his
people, especially the athletes he recruited from other countries.
Whether it was personal or academic problems, he was there for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he gets criticized for favoring his stars, but he's
been very successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's in charge of a nation's entire team of track stars.
Inevitably, there will be some who won't like it. Chaplin will be
the last to care.
</P>
<P>
   He has a relay to win.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
