<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARROS COMES TO THE RESCUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers have remained in
contention largely because of Gary Sheffield's remarkable season at
the plate, but there are times when even he doesn't come through.
</P>
<P>
   That's what made Friday so sweet for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   In a spot primed for Sheffield's heroics, he popped out in the
eighth inning. Then Eric Karros provided the hit everyone figured
Sheffield a lock to get.
</P>
<P>
   Karros' three-run homer lifted the Dodgers to a 6-5 win against
the second-place San Francisco Giants in front of a season-high
53,563 at Dodger Stadium in the first of a three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Grudzielanek led off against Giants starter Shawn Estes
with a walk and Shawn Green singled. Felix Rodriguez relieved and
got Sheffield to pop out just in front of home plate.
</P>
<P>
   But Rodriguez (3-1) fell behind Karros 3-0, and Karros
eventually hit a 3-1 pitch into the left-field bleachers to give
the Dodgers the one-run advantage. It was Karros' 26th homer of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Herges allowed a run in one inning of relief but got the
win to improve to 7-0. Jeff Shaw, the former closer who had blown
seven of 20 save chances, recorded his 14th save with a scoreless
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers starter Carlos Perez was spectacular for five shutout
innings, allowing four hits. He threw just 46 pitches, nine of
which were balls. But the sixth inning was a different story that
had a pair of sub-plots.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Giants figured out Perez. Calvin Murray started it
off with a bunt single and he went to third on Russ Davis' single
to right. Barry Bonds hit a sacrifice fly to left and Jeff Kent hit
a liner to the gap in right-center field. Shawn Green caught up to
it on the warning track for a tough running catch.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, that's where the Dodgers' fortunes turned. Green spun
quickly and fired the ball into second base, but had he realized
Davis was already at second base and instead threw to first, it
would have been an easy double play.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the inning continued. Ellis Burks singled to left, Rich
Aurilia singled in a run with a ground-rule double to left and J.T.
Snow hit a flare to short left field to score a pair of runs and
give the Giants a 4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Perez allowed four runs on nine hits in seven innings. His
control remained sharp as he didn't walk and batter for the third
time in four starts and struck out two.
</P>
<P>
   The second part was how the Dodgers typically frittered away a
great chance to tie it in the bottom of the sixth against lefty
Shawn Estes.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield led off with his second double. But Karros failed to
move him to third, instead striking out. Adrian Beltre, who's 4 for
his last 29 with runners in scoring position, and Todd
Hollandsworth each grounded out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bonds hit his 32nd homer of the season off Herges in the
eighth inning to increase the Giants' lead to 5-3. Bonds trails
Sheffield in the National League home runs race by one.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers went ahead 3-0 in the second inning, and it was
Sheffield starting the rally. He doubled to left-center to extend
his hitting streak to 12 games, one shy of his season high. Karros
and Beltre walked to load the bases and Hollandsworth delivered a
sacrifice fly to left field.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Elster struck out, but Perez helped himself with a triple
down the left field line to score Karros and Beltre. It was the
second triple of Perez's career. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
