<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9724 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     07-22 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WADE A WINNER, NO MATTER WHAT HAPPENS TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Larry Wade didn't rise to No. 3 in the world in the
110-meter high hurdles last year by running around any obstacles.
Wade can't afford to be afraid of hurdles in his path; he makes his
living facing 10 of them head-on.
</P>
<P>
   The resident of Canoga Park, a Los Angeles neighborhood, has
surmounted incredible odds to compete today at the U.S. Olympic
Track and Field Trials. On the penultimate weekend in April, Wade
was involved in a car accident so physically and emotionally
jarring, he continues to drive miles out of his way to avoid the
intersection of Nordhoff and De Soto.
</P>
<P>
   For all the hurdles he has cleared in his career, you see, Wade
can't bring himself to negotiate the crossroads where he suffered
injuries that nearly killed him.
</P>
<P>
   Wade, 25, was returning from a Sunday workout at the UCLA track
when a woman pulled out in front of the native Texan's late-model
convertible. Three months later, the skid marks from the accident
are still there, Wade said. So obviously, are the tracks on his
psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Every time he approaches the intersection, ``I drive extra slow
and my heart beats extra fast,'' Wade said. ``There's a bank right
there. It's just a couple blocks from my house, but if I need money
I'll drive blocks out of my way, to another branch. I still get a
little nervous when I get in that area. I don't know how long that
will last.''
</P>
<P>
   The violent merging of metal left Wade's car looking like a
crushed aluminum can. Wade walked away with no more, he thought,
than a concussion and a head laceration that required 15 staples to
close.
</P>
<P>
   For a week-and-a-half after the accident, Wade felt fine. Then
he started experiencing fevers, headaches and cold sweats. He was
in and out of the hospital ``four or five times,'' Wade said. His
doctors treated him for post-concussion syndrome and then a
bacterial infection and all the while Wade was feeling worse and
worse.
</P>
<P>
   His girlfriend, sprinter Inger Miller, could tell that he wasn't
feeling well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inger and I had conversations,'' Wade said. ``She kept telling
me I had to be tough. I took it totally out of context. I thought
she meant I was supposed to ignore how bad I was feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Wade kept saying he was okay when he clearly was not.
Finally, on May 17, Miller rushed Wade to the hospital emergency
room against his wishes. Doctors discovered his heart was swollen
to twice its normal size because it was absorbing fluids like a
sponge.
</P>
<P>
   They performed emergency surgery, draining a half-liter of fluid
from Wade's heart. When Wade regained consciousness, he had all
kinds of tubes sticking out of him and a six-inch incision on his
chest. His doctors said the internal bleeding was caused by his
automobile's air bag, which inflated at impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors said if I had stayed at home, I would have
suffocated,'' Wade said. ``Inger saved my life.''
</P>
<P>
   As May gave way to June, his doctors were pessimistic about the
possibility of Wade resuming his hurdling career. Certainly not
this year, they told him. They instructed him that it was a miracle
he didn't need open-heart surgery, which promptly earned Wade the
nickname ``Miracle Child'' among his Hudson-Smith International
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month after the three-hour surgery, Wade returned to
the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to teach my body to walk all over again,'' said Wade,
who walked 400 meters in five minutes that first day before
becoming too winded to continue. In those first few weeks back,
Miller and HSI sprinters Ato Boldon and Jon Drummond pumped Wade up
as best they could.
</P>
<P>
   Coach John Smith is not one to pamper his athletes and Wade was
no exception. Within two weeks, Smith had Wade doing hurdling
drills. Wade struggled mightily, but everybody persisted in telling
him how great he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody, that is, except Maurice Greene, the world's fastest
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came back from meets in Europe and said, `You look like
trash,' '' Wade said, smiling. ``Maurice is my best friend. I
appreciated his honesty. I needed to hear that from him. From that
time on, I got back to running faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked last week what kind of shape he was in, Wade was vague.
``I'm in whatever shape it takes to be in the top three,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he said his preliminary heat today _ Wade's first
race since September _ will mark the first time in months that he
has negotiated more than eight consecutive hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot better than I did last week,'' Wade said. ``It's
like I've had an extra week to cram for an exam.''
</P>
<P>
   That would seem small consolation to someone who, in a split
second on a sunny Sunday afternoon, went from a favorite to make
the 2000 Olympic team to a decided darkhorse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all fall,'' Wade said, waxing philosophical. ``We get right
back up and go again. I'm so grateful and thankful to be here. No
way can I sit here and feel bummed at what has been dealt me.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how Wade fares this weekend, he already has won. In a
split second on a sunny Sunday afternoon, Wade nearly lost his life
but gained a wonderful perspective. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
