To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-LIBEL-LAW (Undated) _ In the United States, with its
ironclad belief in the right to free speech, libel plaintiffs need
to prove not only that the speech in question is false, but also
that it was published with a reckless disregard for the truth. In
England, the burden is in exactly the other direction: the
offending speech is presumed to be false, and it is up to
defendants to prove that it is in fact true. That tends to have a
dampening effect on what newspapers print and what publishers
include in books, especially when the material is likely to offend
someone who is powerful, rich or particularly litigious. By Sarah
Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EPA-GRACE-ASBESTOS (Undated) _ The EPA is investigating why it
ignored evidence for 18 years that W.R. Grace and Co. produced ore
for its consumer products that was laden with asbestos. An agency
study in 1982 found alarming levels in material that Grace said was
virtually free of asbestos, but the agency shelved the report,
scuttled its planned follow-up studies and continued to accept the
company's lower figures, EPA officials say. Grace officials on
Friday did not dispute the EPA report, but said their own studies
have consistently shown much smaller amounts of asbestos. At issue
now is how much asbestos _ in a form known as tremolite _ made its
way into those products as a contaminant. By Michael Moss and
Adrianne Appel.
</P>
<P>
   NY-AIRPORT-DENTIST (New York) _ Dr. Robert M. Trager is the man
with the unusual title of airport dentist and the unusual
responsibility of using dental and bone X-rays to determine an
immigrant's age, which can be critical to his or her effort to gain
entry to the United States. By Chris Hedges. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT1 and NYT 2 are being sent to NYT photo
clients)
</P>
<P>
   SEX-SURVEYS (Undated) _ Sex surveyors are bedeviled scientists.
People lie about sex. Those who don't lie often say inaccurate
things. And most sex researchers aren't exactly neutral. Sex
surveys give ``a hardened imitation of reality,'' says John H.
Gagnon, an emeritus professor of sociology at SUNY Stonybrook. We
get certain answers because we ask certain questions. And we ask
certain questions because of fear. By Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIO-IV (Houston) _ George W. Bush left Yale University in
the spring of 1968 with a diploma in hand, but no plans on what to
do with it. So for five years, not unlike many young men his age,
he drifted. He lived in three states, had at least seven apartments
and at least that many girlfriends and held three full-time jobs _
one in business, one in politics and one in public service. By Jo
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Special Report, 3,600 words; an abridged version will also move.
</P>
