<HEADLINE>
AGASSI DRAWS TEEN IN OPENING ROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GERRY GITTELSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Andre Agassi, top-seeded in next week's
74th Mercedes-Benz Cup at UCLA's Los Angeles Tennis Center, will
face 19-year-old Taylor Dent _ the only teen-ager in the 32-man
tournament _ in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Pairings were announced at a launch party at Tommy Hilfiger's
Friday evening, but schedules won't be released until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, who's made almost $20,000 million in prize money and won
45 titles _ including the 1998 Mercedes-Benz Cup _ is seeded ahead
of Australia's Mark Philippoussis, Chile's Marcelo Rios and New
Jersey's Michael Chang.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterfinals begin at noon on Friday. The final is at 2 p.m. on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Pete Sampras isn't participating. Other
previous winners of the Mercedes-Benz Cup, whose history (under
various names) dates to 1927, include Richard Krajicek, Jim
Courier, Michael Stich, Boris Becker, Stefan Edberg, John McEnroe,
Jimmy Connors, Arthur Ashe, Rod Laver, Pancho Gonzalez and Jack
Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the tournament features seven of the top 10 U.S.
players, led by Agassi, Chang, U.S. Davis Cup competitors
Jan-Michael Gambill, Vince Spadea and Chris Woodruff and former
UCLA standout Justin Gimelstob.
</P>
<P>
   A 16-team doubles competition also is slated.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the tournament benefit Southern California Tennis
Association's junior-development programs. On Monday, a
pro-celebrity charity match, featuring Agassi, Chang, Dustin
Hoffman and Dennis Miller, is scheduled at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are available at the tournament office at UCLA and all
Ticketmaster outlets. Admission is free to qualifying rounds today
at 9 a.m. andSunday at noon.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Olmedo, a former USC All-American and Wimbledon and
Australian Open champion, is the tournament honoree. He'll be
inducted into the Southern California Tennis Association Hall of
Fame in a ceremony tonight at UCLA.
</P>
</TEXT>
