<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS ON THE MOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Oakland A's pitcher Tim Hudson has so much potential,
the Anaheim Angels reportedly asked for him in exchange for Jim
Edmonds during the winter meetings last December _ and the A's said
no.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Hudson has shown this season why he is so highly
thought of, taking a 10-2 record, including a nine-game winning
streak, into Friday night's game against the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, however, gave Hudson a beating unlike any he's
experienced in the majors, defeating A's, 12-3, before 13,236 at
the Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The victory propelled the Angels past the A's into second place
in the A.L. West for the first time since May 30. It also put the
Angels, who are four games behind first-place Seattle, in the lead
for the wild-card spot. Overall, the Angels have won 10 of their
past 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson (10-3) had not lost since April 20 in Cleveland, going
9-0 with a 3.56 ERA in his next 14 starts. Including last season he
was 21-4 in his career, one of only five pitchers in major league
history to win 21 of their first 25 decisions, joining King Cole,
Whitey Ford, Vida Blue and Juan Guzman.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels hammered him for nine runs and 12 hits, including
four by Orlando Palmeiro, three by Tim Salmon and home runs by Matt
Walbeck (5), Garret Anderson (28) and Mo Vaughn (25). Vaughn's
homer with one out in the sixth spelled the end for Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn also had a two-run double later in the game for five RBI,
increasing his team-leading total to 76. The Angels had 16 hits in
all.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he needed it, but Angels starter Jarrod Washburn was
the beneficiary of all the offense. Washburn (6-2) gave up one run
and three hits in six innings, continuing an impressive trend by
the young Angels starters.
</P>
<P>
   In their past 12 starts, Washburn, Brian Cooper and Seth
Etherton are 9-1 with a 3.62 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels put pressure on Hudson in the early innings. They had
two hits and a walk in the first inning but couldn't score. In the
second they got two more hits, including a solo homer by Walbeck
for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the third they finally got the big hit, Anderson's line-drive
homer over the right-field fence that followed singles by Palmeiro
and Salmon. It gave the Angels a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Washburn gave up a single in the first inning and a
walk in the second before finding trouble in the third. With two
outs, Randy Velarde walked and Jason Giambi and Olmedo Saenz each
walked to load the bases for Ben Grieve.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn escaped when Grieve flied out to left.
</P>
<P>
   The A's broke through agaisnt Washburn in the fourth when Matt
Stairs hit a high fastball into the seats in right to cut the
Angels' lead to 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels broke the game open in the fifth with two more runs.
Anderson and Adam Kennedy each had an RBI single to give the Angels
a 6-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the sixth, the Angels knocked Hudson out of the game on
Vaughn's three-run homer taking a 9-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels continued their onslaught against the A's bullpen
getting three more runs in the eighth, two on a double by Vaughn
and another on a double by Salmon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
