<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S RAIN RUNS ON RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Welcome home.
</P>
<P>
   After playing 15 of their previous 18 games on the road, the
Mariners returned to Seattle Friday night for their longest
homestand of the season and settled right in. Padding their major
league-best home record, Seattle scored seven runs in the first
inning en route to a 12-3 rout over the Rangers in front of a
packed house at Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   Just about everything clicked for the Mariners. Starter Paul
Abbott pitched seven strong innings. Shortstop Carlos Guillen,
still subbing for injured Alex Rodriguez, had a career-high four
hits, including two singles in one inning. Mark McLemore and Jay
Buhner homered. And center fielder Mike Cameron brought the 44,765
fans to their feet with a fence-crashing catch in the eighth
inning, going all out even with a 10-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, the roof still works, too, much to the dismay of
the fans who booed loudly when it slowly slid closed during a brief
thunderstorm. Which was about the only thing they jeered when the
Mariners played at home for just the fourth time since June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the longest stretch of road games since I've been
part of the team,'' Abbott said. ``It seemed like we were here for
just a blink of an eye when we played the Dodgers (two weekends
ago).
</P>
<P>
   ``The fan support is tremendous here. You feel extremely
comfortable _ it's like sleeping in your own bed. That's the
feeling you get when you walk in here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are 31-13 at home, with their next 12 games here in
an important stretch. After Texas, Seattle plays Oakland, Toronto
and Boston, all with winning records, all with post-season chances.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle and Texas have ruled the AL West since the league
divided into three divisions but things are looking bleak for the
Rangers this year. The Rangers were tied for first place as
recently as June 5 but the loss knocked Texas 10{ games back.
That's the sort of grave from which only slasher-movie villains
climb, especially when your pitching is struggling as much as the
Texas staff is.
</P>
<P>
   Texas entered the game with a 5.14 ERA and starter Matt Perisho
raised it with a terrible performance. He allowed seven runs and
didn't get out of the first inning, walking three consecutive
batters to end his brief night. The first inning lasted 44 minutes
and when it ended Seattle led 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   While Texas struggles, the Mariners continue to show they can
overcome most anything thrown their way. Jamie Moyer and Freddy
Garcia go on the disabled list the same weekend? No problem.
Rodriguez gets hurt? Big deal. The Mariners are 7-4 since losing
Rodriguez, who could return to the lineup soon.
</P>
<P>
   Guillen got off to a terrible start this season as Seattle's
third baseman but he's finally coming around while subbing for
Rodriguez at shortstop the past 11 games. He had a career high
three hits Tuesday, two hits Thursday and a career-high four hits
Friday night, raising his batting average above the Mendoza Line.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's swinging the bat well,'' manager Lou Piniella said.
``He's helping us a lot. It won't be any dilemma (when Alex comes
back). I'll be able to rotate my club a lot and keep everyone nice
and rested. Getting Alex back will allow us to play some different
combinations.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle scored another five runs in the third when McLemore hit
a two-run homer and Buhner hit a three-run shot.
</P>
<P>
   Given all the run support, Abbott didn't need to pitch
particularly well but he did so anyway, giving the Mariners another
of his strong performances since joining the rotation in May. He is
6-3 with a 3.67 ERA since then and has held opponents to three runs
or less in 12 of his 14 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's steady and relaxed,'' Piniella said. ``He goes out and
gives you a professional effort. He's been a savior for us in a lot
of ways. When we had some injuries, he stepped into the void and
solved some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or at jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
