<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9735 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-NUTRACK-LADN-(SLA     07-22 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-NUTRACK-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
...WRITETHRU 
JACOBS WINS SECOND EVENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 c.2000 San Bernardino Sun  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; SACRAMENTO _ Regina Jacobs, four-time Olympian, queen of
American distance running _ and confirmed palm-reader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can never remember what the times are supposed to be on each
lap, so my husband Tom had me write a number on my hand,'' Jacobs
said Friday night. ``He told me, `If you're close to this number
with two laps left, then you go!' &UR;  &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   The number was 12 minutes, 35 seconds, and when Jacobs checked
her palm she was some 20 seconds ahead. She went on to shatter her
own American record in the 5,000-meter run with a clocking of
14:45.35 at the U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials at Sacramento
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty awesome,'' Jacobs said with a smile, after eclipsing
her two-year-old mark of 14:52.49.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, who at 36 seems to be getting better with age, won the
1,500 here five days earlier. She said Friday she will concentrate
on the metric mile at the Sydney Olympics two months hence. But she
left open the possibility she might reconsider, however, given that
her 5,000 time is the best in the world this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got some unfinished busines in the 1,500,'' Jacobs said.
``I want to medal and I want to get under Mary Decker Slaney's
American record'' of 3:58.92. Jacobs ran 4:01.01 in winning the
1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs credited runner-up Deena Drossin, the 10,000 champ here,
for setting a fast early pace. And she credited Drossin's fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were chanting 'Deena, Deena' and I told myself they were
saying 'Regina, Regina,' &UR;  &LR; '' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, American-record holder Bob Kennedy couldn't
duplicate Jacobs' act, finishing a distant sixth behind Adam
Goucher in the men's 5,000. Last week, Kennedy passed on the men's
10,000, citing nagging injuries from an automobile accident.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Pappas, 23, was the surprise winner of the decathlon with
8,467 points, passing pre-meet favorite Chris Huffins on the final
event, the 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Kip Janvrin, 35, earned an Olympics berth in his 70th
decathlon, running a gutsy 1,500 to finish third with 8,057 points
_ just ahead of the Olympic standard of 8,050.
</P>
<P>
   Connie-Price Smith did what she always does in the women's shot,
winning her 22nd national title with an effort of 61 feet, 1
inches. Jesseca Cross was second.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA alumna Dawn Dumble was third in the women's shot but in a
replay of 1996 doesn't have an Olympics berth because she has not
achieved the international qualifying standard of 60-0. She went
57-1 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Dumble could go to Sydney if she gets a qualifying mark by Sept.
11. In 1996, a special, one-event ``meet'' was held at UCLA to
attempt to get her to the qualifying standard, but she fell short.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Deal, silver-medalist at the 1996 Olympics, dominated
hammer-throw competition, winning his eighth national championship
with an effort of 258 feet, 9 inches. Kevin McMahon was second.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprint Wars resume today, the penultimate day of
competition, with the first round of the men's and women's
200-meter run. Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene appear headed for
a Sunday collision on the men's side, and Marion Jones will attempt
to hold off Inger Miller again on the women's.
</P>
<P>
   In preliminary competition Friday:
</P>
<P>
   __ &UR;  &LR; World-record holder Stacy Dragila had no trouble moving out
of the women's pole vault prelims, clearing the opening height of
13-2 on her first try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt fast and light and quick,'' Dragila said. ``If I go in
Sunday feeling like I did today, I think you're gonna see another
world record.''
</P>
<P>
   __ &UR;  &LR; UCLA's Jess Stretzel led all qualifiers in the men's 800, at
1:46.37.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to make a name for myself,'' Stretzel said. ``The
more TV time I get, the better. I plan to go into acting and
directing.''
</P>
<P>
   The first semifinal finished in a five-man blanket finish, with
.09 seconds separating first from fifth. Khadevis Robinson won at
1:48.01, and Bryan Woodward of Long Beach was second in 1:48.06.
</P>
<P>
   __ &UR;  &LR; The Clark family moved into the final of the women's
800-meter run.
</P>
<P>
   American-record holder Jearl Miles-Clark won her semifinal heat
in 2:02.80, and sister-in-law Joetta Clark-Diggs was third. Hazel
Clark, Joetta's sister, won the first semi.
</P>
<P>
   Miles-Clark is coached by (and married to) J.J. Clark, Hazel's
and Joetta's brother.
</P>
<P>
   __ &UR;  &LR; Defending Olympic gold medalist Derrick Adkins went out in
the semifinals of the men's 400 hurdles. Adkins, a theology
student, declared his retirement from the sport. Angelo Taylor had
the top time, 48.59 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   __ &UR;  &LR; LaMark Carter led the men's triple jump prelims with a
modest effort of 54-10. Walter Davis, already on the Olympic team
as a long jumper, qualified second for the final at 54-9.
</P>
<P>
   __ &UR;  &LR; Five-time national champion Charles Austin was among 12 high
jumpers who cleared the prelim mark of 7-2, as was former
playground basketball legend Matt Hemingway, who returned to the
sport after he was spotting dunking from the free-throw line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
