<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9736 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-NUANGELS-LADN-(SL     07-22 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-NUANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ... WRITETHRU 
ANGELS ON THE MOVE
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Oakland A's pitcher Tim Hudson has so much potential,
the Anaheim Angels reportedly asked for him in exchange for Jim
Edmonds during the winter meetings last December _ and the A's said
no.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Hudson has shown this season why he is so highly
thought of, taking a 10-2 record, including a nine-game winning
streak, into Friday night's game against the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, however, gave Hudson a beating unlike any he's
experienced in the majors, and topped the A's in the process, 12-3,
before 13,236 at the Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The victory propelled the Angels past the A's and into sole
possession of second place in the AL West for the first time since
May 30. It also put the Angels, who are four games behind first-
place Seattle, in the lead for the American League wild-card spot.
Overall, the Angels have won 10 of their past 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not excited about second place,'' said Angels first
baseman Mo Vaughn, who bounced back from a beaning Thursday to go 2
for 4 with a homer and five RBI Friday. ``We're out every day doing
what we've got to do do get to first place. . . We did the things
we needed to do tonight. When you've got a team that thinks that
way, you've got a mentally tough ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if those guys look at the standings,'' Angels
manager Mike Scioscia said of his team, which improved to nine
games over .500 (53-44) for the first time since the 1998 season.
``Because it's not going to have an effect on what we do tomorrow.
We have to come out tomorrow and play another strong game.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense flexed its muscle against Hudson, who beat the
Angels July 2 in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson (10-3) had not lost since April 20 in Cleveland, going
9-0 with a 3.56 ERA in his next 14 starts. Including last season he
was 21-4 in his career, one of only five pitchers in major-league
history to win 21 of their first 25 decisions, joining King Cole,
Whitey Ford, Vida Blue and Juan Guzman.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels hammered him for nine runs and 12 hits, including
four by Orlando Palmeiro, three by Tim Salmon and home runs by Matt
Walbeck (No. 5), Garret Anderson (No. 28 and 100th of his career)
and Vaughn (No. 25). Vaughn's homer with one out in the sixth
spelled the end for Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had 16 hits in all.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't make many mistakes,'' Scioscia said of Hudson. ``But
when he did, our guys jumped on him. We had a disciplined approach.
They were able to lay off the split-finger and make him put it in
the zone. When he came with the fastball the guys didn't miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he needed it, but Angels starter Jarrod Washburn was
the beneficiary of all the offense. Washburn (6-2) gave up one run
and three hits in six innings, continuing an impressive trend by
the young Angels starters.
</P>
<P>
   In their past 12 starts combined, Washburn, Brian Cooper and
Seth Etherton are 9-1 with a 3.62 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the number of talented arms we had, this is what we
envisioned,'' Scioscia said. ``It's not about what they're doing
right. This is what we expected and they're delivering.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're doing anything different, we're just
pitching well,'' said Washburn, whose six wins are tied for the
team lead. ``I think everyone is just stepping up right now and
doing the job. It's fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone suggested to Scioscia that the Angels are playing so
well they're making it look easy, but Scioscia didn't agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at it as being easy,'' he said. ``I look at it as
the pieces of the puzzle being solidly in place. It's not always
going to go smoothly, but in this stretch of the second half,
obviously the piece of the puzzle most in place is the starting
pitching. From the All-Star break to now, they've been
tremendous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
