<HEADLINE>
IRANIAN DRESS CODE: A BURST OF COLOR IS NOW ISLAMIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the beginning of Iran's revolution, by far the most
relentless struggle over the social restrictions of the Islamic
Republic has concerned what women wear. Now, because of a slight
easing of the rules last week, prepubescent schoolgirls will be
allowed to wear colors to school.
</P>
<P>
   Under new guidelines issued by the Ministry of Education,
schoolgirls through fifth grade will be allowed to wear ``gay,
light colors,'' including light blue, beige, pink, light green and
yellow. Until now, only black, brown and navy blue were allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of light colors helps to create a cheerful
atmosphere'' and to ``safeguard the mental health of students,''
the ministry directive stated. But ``loud and gaudy colors'' that
are ``not in harmony with the spirit of education'' will not be
allowed. Although the all-encompassing black chador remains the
favored Islamic dress, it ``in no way can be imposed on the
students,'' the directive said.
</P>
<P>
   The color shift follows a campaign by Zahra Rahnavard, an artist
who is president of Al Zahra University, a school for women, to
allow girls and women of all ages to wear colorful clothing. ``As
an artist I believe colors are important,'' she told a seminar
during Women's Week last fall. ``Black is not the color of the
revolution and bright colors are divine colors that do not have an
anti-revolutionary meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   She has also claimed that osteoporosis has increased among
women, even young women, because sunlight, which helps the body
form Vitamin D, does not penetrate their dark clothing. Women in
many parts of the countryside have always worn colorful clothing.
Many dermatologists, meanwhile, complain that the rubbing of the
head covering against the skin contributes to acne and rashes.
</P>
<P>
   The easing of the rules goes only so far. Even though girls
younger than 9 do not have to wear Islamic dress on the streets,
they must do so in state-run schools. So schoolgirls will still
have to wear smocklike coats that fall below their knees; pants,
and hoods that cover their heads and necks and expose only their
faces. The dress code makes it particularly difficult for
schoolgirls to take part in sports like soccer and basketball and
run races outdoors. And what kid wants to have to cover up in
100-degree heat?
</P>
<P>
   The new decree coincides with a quiet but determined revolt
among women of all ages against the constraints of their dress.
Newspapers have published articles about teen-age girls who cut
their hair short and dress as boys to avoid having to wear Islamic
dress. Women in Tehran are wearing tighter and shorter coats over
their pants this summer. And since baring the feet is acceptable in
Islam, more women are wearing sandals and painting their toenails
in bright colors.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is happy with the new decree about schoolgirls. The
conservative newspaper Ressalat charged that the ministry had not
adequately explained why the change was necessary, and it worried
what would come next. ``This decree will allow female students to
demand other freedoms,'' the newspaper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 1013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
