</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URBAN-POVERTY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORLD OF SCAVENGERS ON THE FRINGES OF WEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines _ Roberto Aquino, 14, says he finds ``false
gold'' in garbage. A scavenger on Manila's garbage mountain when he
is not in school, he specializes in copper wire. On a good day he
can earn half as much as his fifth-grade teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people died here two weeks ago when the
seven-story-high mountain, loosened by monsoon rains, collapsed on
their shantytown. Like their neighbors, they lived here amid the
filth and flies and degradation because the living was good. Mostly
upwardly mobile migrants from the barren countryside, they were
feeding their families and putting their children through school.
Like Roberto, they had struck gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say you have a family of four,'' said Matthew Westfall, an
urban development specialist with the Asian Development Bank, which
is based here. ``The kids go to school part time and pick trash
part time. You could get up to 15,000 or 16,000 pesos a month,
possibly.'' That sum, about $400, ``puts you above the poverty
line,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The people of the dumpsite, which they call Promised Land, are
not an aberration. They are part of the changing face of poverty _
a vast population shift taking place in much of the world, from the
joblessness and hunger of the countryside to the comparative wealth
of the cities. But for most of these migrants, that comparative
wealth is found in places like the Manila dumpsite, part of a
growing sea of poverty that laps at the edges of small, high-rise
islands of urban affluence.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, where cities of 10 million people or more are spreading
as fast as anywhere in the world, this urban landscape is replacing
the fields and trees of the villages for an increasing proportion
of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five years ago, Westfall said, only one in five Asians
lived in cities. Today the ratio is one in three. Twenty years from
now, more than half the population will be urban. In 1990, he said,
the region's cities needed a total of $38 billion a year to provide
urban services like water, sanitation and transport. In 20 years
that figure is expected to rise to an impossible $292 billion.
</P>
<P>
   These huge ``megacities,'' groaning with their burden of the
disenfranchised poor, will dominate the 21st century, it is said,
the way the nation-state dominated the 20th century and empires
ruled in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Urbanization, of course, is not just an Asian phenomenon. Nor is
the misery of the poor. Garbage mountains rise in Latin America and
Africa as well. But it is in Asia, perhaps, with its enormous
population pressures, that the issue is drawn most strikingly.
</P>
<P>
   Manila today, for example, has 13 percent of the Philippines' 74
million people but generates 30 to 40 percent of the nation's
wealth. Bangkok has 10 percent of Thailand's population but
generates 40 percent of its wealth. ``People in rural areas have no
alternative but to migrate,'' said Anil Deolalikar, a professor of
economics at the University of Washington in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   But garbage dumps aside, said Naved Hamid, a senior policy
planner with the Asian Development Bank, these poor see little of
the cities' wealth.
</P>
<P>
   There is no one pattern for urban poverty and therefore no
single cure. In China, the pattern is predominantly one of a vast
floating population of migrant workers who follow jobs from city to
city. In Manila, where many urban services have broken down, it
also includes people like civil servants and teachers, whose pay
puts them above the poverty line but who often have no alternative
to living in the ugliest of slums.
</P>
<P>
   The urban underclass for the most part lives apart from the
social and economic structure of its city, invisible to most
residents and without the political weight to demand their share of
services. So they create their own separate _ though dependent _
economies. Some 80,000 squatters cluster around Manila's garbage
mountain, for example. They include perhaps 3,000 scavengers and
another 9,000 or so people whose livelihoods depend directly on
what urban experts call ``the recycling waste chain.''
</P>
<P>
   As planners seek new ways to address the growing disaster of
urban poverty, the world's millions of slum dwellers find their own
ways to survive. The art of scavenging, it appears, is one of the
great tributes to human inventiveness. There are children who dive
for golf balls in the water hazards of golf courses and there are
daring teen-agers who scurry for brass shell casings on military
firing ranges.
</P>
<P>
   In Laos, people use old bombshells to construct their houses. In
America, the urban poor dig for aluminum cans (and cold slices of
pizza) in garbage bins.
</P>
<P>
   In Nigeria this month _ in a tragedy that is a companion to the
garbage landslide in Manila _ hundreds of scavengers died in an
explosion and fire while trying to earn their living by puncturing
a pipeline and siphoning off gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   People like this not only make a living; they make a home for
themselves. The shanties at Manila's dump are hung with flower pots
and posters of soccer teams. There are tiny barbershops and ice
cream stands. There are births and weddings and school graduations.
</P>
<P>
   Nine people in the family of Jennifer Gino Evangelista died in
the landslide, including her parents. Twenty-one survived. None of
them want to move away.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, said Evangelista, 27, her father brought the
family here from the countryside after taking them from place to
place in search of a living. ``Every year we would move,'' she
said. ``We never had a permanent address. We were tourists in our
own country.''
</P>
<P>
   That homeless life ended here on the fringes of the Promised
Land dump.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where we've stayed the longest _ 12 years,'' she said.
``This is where we've multiplied. This is where we've put down
roots. So this is our home now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
