<SLUG> BC-EXECUTION-TOY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEVER SAY DIE. JUST EXECUTE. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By KARI HASKELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do you want to escape into the dark, violent world of a graphic
novel? Do you want to act out its ghastly denouement with its last,
grim death laugh? Try flipping a tiny switch and carrying out a
miniature execution.
</P>
<P>
   Death Row Marv, the rock-jawed anti-hero of the graphic comic,
``Sin City,'' by Frank Miller (Dark Horse Comics, 1994), is the
latest toy from McFarlane Toys, which is owned by Todd McFarlane,
the creator of Spawn, another comic-book anti-hero.
</P>
<P>
   Marv, who apparently needs no last name, is railroaded to the
electric chair, condemned to die for what he regards as a
justifiable revenge killing. The battery-operated toy, which is
sold in specialty shops and music stores for about $20 and marketed
for ages 13 and up, is not for the faint of heart: ``Watch Marv
convulse as the switch is thrown,'' say the words on the box,
``then hear him say, `That the best you can do?''' His eyes ``glow
red as he fries.''
</P>
<P>
   The toy's typical buyer is the 15- to 45-year-old male.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first production was completely sold out in pre-order
sales, before we even shipped,'' said Beau Smith, director of
marketing at McFarlane Toys, who did not provide production
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon, as I saw Marv _ oh, man! _ I had to have one,'' said
Eric Wahland, 34, a customer service representative and salesperson
at Spider's Web, a comic store in Seattle that is the largest
outlet for McFarlane Toys. ``We keep them up front, on top of the
counter, 10 to 15 feet from the register. Already 500 of 700 deluxe
sets ordered have been sold in just four weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Marv is half convict, half hero. He is the guy who never gets
the girl because his face is a cross between Freddy Kreuger and
Bluto; his body is a muscular mass that is as wide as it is long.
To some, he is the loser they desperately want to see win. OK, he's
an anti-hero with no charisma, good looks or any redeeming social
value.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Sin City,'' before his death sentence is carried out, Marv
has the opportunity to kill the cannibalistic sociopath who
murdered the woman he loved, a prostitute named Goldie. That gave
him a sense of vindication.
</P>
<P>
   Batteries not included.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 1019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
