<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9754 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-JERUSALEM-REV     07-22 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-JERUSALEM-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERUSALEM: THE HOLIEST CITY, THE TOUGHEST CONFLICT, THE HIGHEST
STAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ When the late afternoon sun turns the crenellated
limestone walls of the Old City to warm glowing gold, it is easy to
understand the intense emotional hold of this tiny place.
</P>
<P>
   Suleiman the Magnificent, the Ottoman sultan, built these walls
in 1538 _ rebuilt them, really, from the stones left behind by
Romans, Jews, Muslims, Byzantines, Crusaders, the Arab armies of
Saladin and the Mamelukes. They are walls that enclose sites holy
to the three great monotheistic religions.
</P>
<P>
   That well-known fact places Jerusalem at the very heart of the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict, an issue so difficult, so sensitive,
that until now peace negotiators simply put it off. The city, and
the idea of it as a capital, is a central icon to both sides. Jews,
after centuries of dispersion and persecution, still end their
Seder each Passover: ``Next year in Jerusalem.'' And in virtually
every Muslim home in every Palestinian refugee camp there hangs a
picture of the Dome of the Rock.
</P>
<P>
   But now the negotiating teams at Camp David are trying to come
to grips with Jerusalem, and they are finding it an extraordinarily
difficult task _ to imagine the unimaginable, a truly united (or
fairly divided) Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   It may be tempting to think that the easiest basis for a
settlement would be to admit that the two sides share a heritage
and guarantee all groups access to the holy sites. But in 50 years
of conflict _ and more than 20 years of peacemaking _ achieving
that kind of formula in Jerusalem has only become harder. That is
because new layers of grievance, resentment and reason for distrust
have been added on both sides. And in many Israeli and Palestinian
minds, these only reinforce the idea that their one best guarantee
of access and security is sole political control of all or part of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   For Jews, the holy place is the Western (or Wailing) Wall, the
remains of the Second Temple built on Mount Moriah after the return
from exile in Babylon. For Muslims, it is the plateau on the Temple
Mount above the wall, known as the Haram al-Sharif, or noble
sanctuary, from which the prophet Muhammad made a visit to heaven
on his winged horse. The sanctuary contains the Dome of the Rock
shrine and Al Aksa Mosque, the third-holiest site in Islam. It is
exactly the same place, and both Jews and Muslims share the belief
that the rock itself is where Abraham prepared his son for
sacrifice. For Christians, the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, a
short distance away, is where Jesus was crucified, buried and
resurrected to redeem mankind's sins.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem and its holy sites were deemed so unique that, under
the doomed 1947 United Nations partition plan for turning the
British Palestine mandate into Arab and Jewish zones, the city was
to become an international district. It was an idea acceptable then
to David Ben-Gurion and his overwhelmingly secular Zionist
associates, who had more regard for security considerations than
for controlling religious shrines.
</P>
<P>
   But the Arab armies attacked instead, and Israel as born in a
bitter war. Israeli troops fought their way desperately up the
twisting road through the hills to relieve Jews besieged with
little food or water in the new city that had grown up outside the
Ottoman walls. The rusted hulks of their makeshift armored cars
still line the road as monuments. But the Jordanian King Abdullah's
Arab Legion, trained and led by British officers, held the heights
above Jerusalem, captured the Old City and incorporated it into
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   From 1948 to 1967, Jerusalem was a divided city _ half
Jordanian, half Israeli _ with limited passage allowed through the
Mandelbaum Gate, mostly for international officials and Christian
clergy. Most important for the future, the Old City was sealed off
to Jews and many of their religious sites were defiled. Then, in
the 1967 war, Israel took all of Jerusalem and the West Bank, its
triumphant army chaplain, Shlomo Goren (later to become a chief
rabbi of Israel) blowing his ram's horn at the Western Wall.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 30 years, Israelis created their own facts on the
ground, building settlements in the West Bank, expanding Jewish
neighborhoods into East Jerusalem and neglecting services to the
Arab areas. Even since the Oslo accords, Israelis have continued to
build Jewish housing in Arab neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   All of this has made decisions on how to treat Jerusalem in a
peace settlement extraordinarily difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Khalil Shikaki, a Palestinian academic who has advised the
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, said last week that ``the
Palestinian public will not tolerate less than full sovereignty
over all of East Jerusalem, including the Haram al-Sharif.
Palestinians will not tolerate Israeli border police or Israeli
checkpoints. That is not sovereignty, that is not control.
Palestinians no longer want to ask Israelis for permission to build
their homes, to educate their children, to live their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But, at the same time, he said that if they were persuaded that
the Israeli approach was genuine, ``the Palestinian street would
certainly be flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
