<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Making Margin Calls in a Tightening Race
</P>
<P>
   In the album of Campaign 2000 cliches, get ready to paste in
``Too close to call.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a term that Americans are likely to hear frequently this
year, as strategists and journalists weigh in with state-by-state
analyses of the treacherous electoral map that confronts Gov.
George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The early conventional wisdom? It's too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   Swing states in the presidential race like New Jersey,
Pennsylvania, Ohio, Illinois, Michigan, Missouri and Washington are
all rated as tossups or moving only marginally toward Bush, who is
strongest in the South and Rocky Mountain states, or toward Gore,
whose support is heaviest on the East and West Coasts. Factor in
the participation of third-party contenders like Pat Buchanan and
Ralph Nader, and it's hard to conclude anything except: It's too
close to call.
</P>
<P>
   The tightness of the race has, if anything, intensified the
guessing game of who the candidates will choose as their running
mates. With the Republican convention set to begin in Philadelphia
in eight days, most of the attention is on Bush's choice, which the
governor said he will make imminently.
</P>
<P>
   A leading contender is Dick Cheney, the former defense secretary
in the Bush administration. Other names mentioned frequently
include the Republican governors of two big industrial states, Tom
Ridge of Pennsylvania and George Pataki of New York, as well as
Sen. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska, Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma and
former Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there is the name with star power, Sen.
John McCain of Arizona, who was reported to be softening in his
opposition to accepting the vice presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Gore was making his case for the presidency in
Bush's own back yard, traveling to Texas to criticize his rival's
reign as governor, which got some Texans' dander up. ``Texas isn't
nearly as backward and third world as the Gore campaign would make
us out,'' said Michael Levy, the publisher of Texas Monthly
magazine. Proud of its homegrown candidate, Texas is probably not
too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   The Elian of the Animal Kingdom
</P>
<P>
   On one side stands a teary-eyed Russian couple whose Brooklyn
community has vowed to go to any length to help them keep their
adopted pet monkey. On the other side is an adamant state
government backed by a host of monkey experts and the power of the
endangered-species law.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle, oblivious to all the fuss, stands Cookie
Flikshtein, a rare diana monkey who is living the good life, eating
Rocky Road ice cream and wearing frilly red miniskirts, while her
fate is being decided.
</P>
<P>
   Just weeks after the conclusion of the Elian Gonzalez custody
battle comes an even stranger scuffle over little Cookie, age 6.
Her adoptive parents, Roman and Inna Flikshtein, have argued
unsuccessfully in court that there is no better place for Cookie
than their monkey-friendly home. The state attorney general's
office, meanwhile, maintains that Cookie is a member of an
endangered species and belongs in a special animal rescue program
at the Detroit Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   There are no immediate plans to wrest Cookie from the Flikshtein
home, where she has lived for five years in such familial bliss
that 13-year-old Michelle Flikshtein refers to the monkey as her
sister. But the Flikshtein's neighbors, many of whom are recent
immigrants from Russia, have closed ranks, promising to protect
young Cookie until the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to sit here and not let people come near,'' said
Lubov Gruber, who lives down the block. ``We will protest this for
as long as it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALAN FEUER
</P>
<P>
   Congress Approves Tax Cut to Help Married Couples
</P>
<P>
   Congress finished work on a Republican bill to give an
election-year tax break to married couples. But President Clinton,
saying the measure was too costly, promised to veto it. The bill
would provide $292 billion in tax cuts over the next decade, and
was intended in part to address the marriage penalty, the quirk in
the tax code that forces many two-income couples to pay a higher
tax bill than they would if they had remained single. Democrats
said they also want to address the penalty, but do it in a less
expensive way that directs more benefits to low- and middle-income
people.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   Better Colon Cancer Test Urged
</P>
<P>
   The test used to screen healthy adults for colon cancer should
be changed, researchers say: Instead of the currently recommended
sigmoidoscopy, which examines the lower two feet of the colon,
patients should undergo colonoscopy, which probes its entire 4- to
5-foot length.
</P>
<P>
   The shorter test fails to detect abnormal growths high in the
colon, scientists warned in the New England Journal of Medicine.
But colonoscopy costs $1,500, and most insurers will not cover it
as a screening test.
</P>
<P>
   And the public has shown little enthusiasm for either test,
which require the insertion of long tubes equipped with cameras
into the rectum.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DENISE GRADY
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
