Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-SURVEILLANCE-REVIEW (Undated) _ New computer technology
enables law-enforcement authorities to troll through millions of
e-mails, honing in on the correspondences of suspects. But unlike
traditional telephone wiretaps, the technology also can capture
communications of others not suspected of a crime, raising concerns
that it could be employed to monitor people and groups far beyond
the suspected mobsters and drug kingpins who have been the
traditional targets of telephone wiretaps. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   BIRTHCONTROL-INCENTIVES-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at the use of
cash incentives for preventing unwanted pregnancies and population
control in general. One organization that pays drug-addicted women
to be sterilized uses the slogan `Don't Let A Pregnancy Interfere
With Your Drug Habit.' Financial incentives for promoting
pregnancy, and for organ donation, are also discussed. By Jeff
Stryker.
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTION-TOY-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Death Row Marv'' is a novelty
toy in which a figure sitting in a simulated electric chair can be
``fried.''
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-RATINGS-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at the relative
commercial successes of films rated PG-13 and those rated R. By
Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   SUMO-SINGER-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ The former sumo wrestler
Konishiki has crossed over into the recording arts. His debut
rap/reggae/R&AMP;B CD, `Konishiki KMS' _ short for `Konishiki Master
Sumo' _ has just been released. Some lyrics are excerpted.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   URBAN-POVERTY-REVIEW (Manila, Philippines) _ Hundreds died here
two weeks ago when a mountain, loosened by monsoon rains, collapsed
on their shantytown. They lived amid the filth and flies and
degradation because, by their standards, the living was good. They
were part of the changing face of poverty _ a vast population shift
occurring throughout much of the world from the joblessness and
hunger of the countryside to the comparative wealth of the cities.
By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-GIRLS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The most relentless struggle over
the social restrictions of the Islamic Revolution has concerned
what women wear. Last week it was announced that prepubescent
schoolgirls would be allowed to wear colors to school. One concern
has been that porosis has increased among women, even young women,
because sunlight, which helps the body form Vitamin D, does not
penetrate their dark clothing. And dermatologists have complained
that the rubbing of the chador head covering against the skin
contributes to acne and rashes. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
