<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, July 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A gathering area of low pressure near the Southeast coast will
direct showers and thunderstorms into the Carolina Piedmont on
Sunday. Thunderstorms will also develop in northern Florida, where
fitful bursts of rain will fall. Farther to the west, there will be
showers and thunderstorms along the Gulf coast as a front becomes
nearly stationary over the region.
</P>
<P>
   A slow area of low pressure in southern Canada will drag patches
of clouds and isolated showers into northern New England on Sunday.
Meanwhile, sunshine will be filtered by scattered clouds in the
Middle Atlantic states. Readings will stay below seasonal levels in
this region.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest will remain very warm with temperatures over 100
degrees in many places. Afternoon showers and thunderstorms are
likely in the Rocky Mountains and the deserts of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: THE COOLING BEGINS
</P>
<P>
   The mercury has hovered near 100 each day for the past two weeks
in much of the interior Southeast. While some relief from the
oppressive heat is occurring from eastern Texas to the Southeast
coast this weekend, heat is expanding in the West. Yet, in the
midst of the notable heat of the summer of 2000, the inexorable
slide into winter is beginning. In most of the nation, average
temperatures are at their highest during the next week. While the
change is initially subtle, normal temperatures in most of the
Northern states fall by nearly 5 degrees between now and the end of
August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
