<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AUSTRIA-HAIDER-2TAKES     07-22 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-HAIDER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRIA POLITICIAN SOMETIMES DOWN BUT NEVER OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ There is a beloved figure in Viennese folklore
named Dear Augustin, a musician who got so stupefied while
pub-crawling during the 1681 plague that he was taken for dead and
thrown in a ``pestilence pit.''
</P>
<P>
   He recovered the next day, climbed out and composed one of the
17th century's top hits, ``Oh, Dear Augustin, Everything's Gone,''
an ode to life in spite of setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a perfect simile for Joerg Haider, the Austrian
politician who is feared because of past remarks that seemed to
minimize Nazi crimes, but there are parallels. People write off the
leader of the Freedom Party for one gaffe or another, and then he
makes a comeback. Some are glad to see him, some are not _ but
everyone is a little nervous about the company he has been keeping.
</P>
<P>
   His recent visits to Libya's leader, Col. Moammar Gadhafi, for
example, have not helped matters. Nor has the possibly accidental
use of an SS motto in a speech by a young leader in his party. Nor
has Haider's suggestion that the leader of a rival party be
indicted for treason for sipping champagne with France's prime
minister _ particularly when the new minister of justice, Haider's
former personal lawyer, was beside him and agreed that the idea was
worth exploring.
</P>
<P>
   Haider, whose party's entry into government was the reason the
14 other European Union members imposed sanctions on Austria in
February, is technically not in power. He resigned as party leader;
his only national government role is on an advisory council; and he
remains merely governor of Carinthia province.
</P>
<P>
   But he does not remain in obscurity. He is still the glue
binding the Freedom Party, which he led from 5 percent of the vote
in 1986 to 27 percent and a share of government last year.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say his coalition partners, the People's
Party, think they have him where they want him: playing the game
rather than spoiling it; sinking in opinion polls; and leading a
party headed for a power struggle between him and one of his
proteges, the 31-year-old finance minister.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics like Georg Hoffmann-Ostenhof, foreign editor of Profil
magazine, say it works the other way. Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel
``still has the illusion that he's domesticating Haider, while the
fact is that Haider is Haiderizing the whole government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone mentions one photo: Schuessel recently visited Haider
in Carinthia and took a ride in his new Porsche. Photographers
caught their boyish grins, and caption writers noted gleefully that
Haider was in the driver's seat. Schuessel laughed it off, saying:
``As chancellor, I have several chauffeurs.''
</P>
<P>
   As Andreas Unterberger, editor of Die Presse, a center-right
paper, puts it, their coalition is more ``a psychological game''
than political deal-cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Haider, who Unterberger said had wide mood swings, needs to be
reassured that he is accepted rather than ostracized.
</P>
<P>
   On domestic issues, it is hard to say Haider is driving. Most of
his campaign promises have been ignored. He had backed a ban on
immigration, a flat tax, $400 monthly checks for new mothers (to
encourage larger families) and a crackdown on crime and
child-molesting.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to his campaigning, Austria had already tightened its
borders, but it just allowed immigrants hoping for asylum to hold
jobs legally. Crime and child-molesting were populist scare
tactics, never a real problem. The flat tax and $400 check ideas
have disappeared. In fact, the finance minister, Karl-Heinz
Grasser, a Haider appointee, has proposed an austerity plan meant
to balance the budget by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Austria, like Germany, recently agreed to pay reparations
to Third Reich slave workers. Some years back, Haider criticized
war reparations, saying tax money ``shouldn't go to Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Since entering government, Haider's ``blue'' party has fallen in
the polls _ as it had in the past, only to rebound at election time
_ while Schuessel's has risen. The Green Party too is up, while the
Social Democratic reds, who finished first in the 1999 election
with 33 percent of the vote but could not form a coalition, are
stumbling; their leader, Victor Klima, just quit to become a
Volkswagen executive in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   But the outside world is watching only one issue: the European
Union sanctions. They have done no economic damage, but they
humiliate Austrians, up to 80 percent of whom oppose them in polls.
``We are treated like a colony,'' said Andreas Khol, No. 2 in the
People's Party. ``France would never accept such treatment. Italy,
never. Spain, never. Germany, maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   On this issue, Haider is very influential, but one could say he
is merely driving only if ``driving'' is what goes on in
``Bullitt'' or ``Dukes of Hazzard.'' He careers.
</P>
<P>
   He demanded a referendum asking Austrians whether they wanted to
use their veto to block all European Union actions until the
sanctions were lifted. (In a recent poll, 70 percent favored the
move.) He hinted that the veto could be used for only six months,
until Sweden replaced France as the European president, since the
French are seen as Austria's persecutors. Haider called President
Jacques Chirac of France a ``pocket Napoleon.''
</P>
<P>
   Khol, going along, drafted a carefully worded referendum. It
does not use the word ``veto'' and he denies it is a threat. It is,
he says, a ``hint'' to government, ``a channeling of the wishes of
the people who say we can't sit here like a lamb until we're
slaughtered.''
</P>
<P>
   If the sanctions were dropped, he said, the referendum would be
too.
</P>
<P>
   But Haider complicates all delicate diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He visited Libya in May as a guest of Gadhafi's son Saif
al-Islam, a personal friend from a Vienna business school; he
returned in June with a group of businesspeople and then announced
that Libya would deposit $25 million in a bank owned by the
Carinthian government. Gadhafi promptly criticized the sanctions as
the European Union ``giving in to Zionist whims.''
</P>
<P>
   Khol declined to say whether Schuessel had privately asked
Haider to avoid moments like that.
</P>
<P>
   In June, a new provincial leader in the Freedom Party used the
phrase ``Unsere Ehre heisst Treue'' _ ``Our Honor Is Fidelity'' _
in a speech to party workers. He later denied knowing it was the
motto of Hitler's SS troops, saying he was born after World War II.
Haider, born in 1950 to parents who were once staunch Nazis, partly
defended him, saying honor and fidelity were good principles.
</P>
<P>
   The party's Vienna leader, Hilmar Kabas, was heard to call
President Thomas Klestil a ``lump,'' which means ``little honorless
thief.'' Cornered by reporters, he denied it, saying he must have
said ``hump'' or ``dump,'' words that mean nothing in German. He
then started posing with mascots _ two stuffed elephants named
Humpi and Dumpi.
</P>
<P>
   And several party members have coined a new word,
``Vernaderung,'' which seems to mean ``vandalism by a gnawing
rodent,'' and they now apply it to Austrian politicians who act
friendly with French officials, as Alfred Gusenbauer, the new
leader of the Social Democrats, did, prompting Haider's suggestion
that he be charged with treason.
</P>
<P>
   Haider has also unleashed a spate of libel suits to silence his
critics.
</P>
<P>
   Suits for small amounts are a feature of Austrian political
life, but they are now more intimidating, writers who have been
sued say, because the lawyer who filed many of them, Dieter
Boehmdorfer, is now the minister of justice. Also, conservative
judges are finding in Haider's favor, making awards of $500 or
more, plus legal costs.
</P>
<P>
   In Austria, libel suits can be brought over statements that are
clearly opinion, which they cannot under U.S. law. Haider sued a
major news magazine that pictured him with devil's horns on its
cover and then a small leftist weekly that reprinted the picture
with an article about the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   And, because espousing Nazi ideas is a crime, Haider sues those
who link his ideas with Nazism. He sued a University of Innsbruck
political science professor for saying on Italian television that
his remark that concentration camps were really punishment camps
``trivialized Nazism.'' He won $5,000, then sued the professor
again for a CNN interview in which he said Haider's comparison of
immigrants and parasites used ``similar feelings and prejudices''
as those exhibited by Nazis. Haider denied using the word
``parasites'' specifically against foreigners. That suit is
pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't put anyone out of business, but it's muzzling free
expression,'' said Hans Rauscher, a columnist for the center-left
daily Der Standard, who is the object of a similar suit.
</P>
<P>
   The hope of those being sued is that they will be able to turn
the tables on Haider by appealing to the European Court of Human
Rights, which is, coincidentally, in France. Its rulings give freer
rein to political comment, Rauscher said, ``and the court says
politicians have to endure more criticism than other people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 1116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9770 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-MOVIE-RATINGS-REVIEW-     07-22 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-RATINGS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOODOO BOX OFFICE: PG-13-NESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (Repeating with art note)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The story goes like this: Several people are walking
down the middle of the street in the middle of the night. Suddenly,
a truck comes along and flattens them. How can you tell which one
is the movie studio executive? He's the guy who jumps up and says,
``Here's why that just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Perfect hindsight is a common Hollywood trait. So is the ability
to explain, as though to a simpleton, exactly why such-and-such a
movie was a box-office bomb or why some superstar's latest movie
failed to open at the levels anticipated. The constantly shifting
ground upon which the Current Prevailing Wisdom rests must be
updated each weekend _ especially when something comes along that
contradicts the prevailing wisdom going into the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up the issue of PG-13 _ at the top of the Current
Prevailing Wisdom list at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, Hollywood studios are insisting that filmmakers
guarantee they will deliver a movie that will get at most a PG-13
rating from the Motion Picture Association of America _ and not an
R, which requires any moviegoer under 18 to be accompanied
(theoretically) by a parent or guardian. This is stressed in cases
of big summer releases, when it is important to get as many people
into the theaters as possible and grease _ not restrictions _ is
needed at the turnstiles. ``The question is, where does the largest
audience lie?'' said Dan Fellman, president of distribution for
Warner Brothers. ``At the end of the day, it's within the PG-13.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense on paper. Certainly if more people are allowed
into a movie theater, then the pool of ticket buyers is larger and
a movie should, by rights, have a better shot at making a bigger
pile of money. But is this Current Prevailing Wisdom really
correct?
</P>
<P>
   Follow the bouncing ball:
</P>
<P>
   On the weekend just before the Fourth of July, two major movies
were expected to compete to be No. 1 at the box office: ``The
Perfect Storm'' from Warner Brothers (rated PG-13) and ``The
Patriot'' from Columbia Pictures (rated R). In the run-up to the
weekend, ``The Patriot'' was widely seen as the likelier winner.
Both films had top-notch directors, but ``Patriot'' had a more
bankable star in Mel Gibson. Prerelease polling indicated that
audiences were more eager to see the period epic. Instead,
``Perfect Storm'' ended up making almost twice as much as
``Patriot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Monday-morning quarterbacking settled on three explanations.
``The Patriot'' ran too long for summer audiences (160 minutes).
Audiences don't really like Colonial-era stories. ``Patriot'' was
rated R.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it was said, PG-13 trumps R in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the next weekend. The only major opening was ``Scary
Movie,'' a decidedly R-rated spoof of horror films. Predicted to be
a decent-sized hit, it was a phenomenon, earning more than $40
million, the largest opening ever for an R-rated film. Wham!
Anybody get the number of that truck?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this was the movie that was the exception to the rule,''
said Paul Dergarabedian, chairman of Exhibitor Relations, which
monitors box-office performance. ``They don't come along every day,
but there are some movies where the rating doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so PG-13 is better than R _ except sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, ``X-Men'' opened. Again, the polling predicted a
sizable hit. Instead, it opened huge, earning more than $54
million. Its rating: PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   To get some historical context into this debate, Exhibitor
Relations crunched the box-office numbers for the last three
summers, the four months in which the studios do 40 percent of
their annual business.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the films that finished in first place in each of the
18 weekends from early May to Labor Day in 1999, a record year at
the movie box office, 11 weekends saw a PG-13 movie in first place,
three weekends saw a PG, one weekend saw a G and only two weekends
saw an R. In 1998, it was a closer call; eight weekends had a PG-13
movie in first place, eight weekends had an R and two had a PG.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 11 weeks of this summer, PG-13 films were in first
place on five weekends, R films on five weekends and a PG film on
one weekend.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps the difference between PG-13 and R isn't so great
after all? Not so fast, Dergarabedian said. One must also look at
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibitor Relations looked at all 265 films released last
summer. The largest number of them, 157, were rated R. Less than
half, 67, were rated PG-13. The average R film made $20 million
while the average PG-13 made $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stands to reason,'' Dergarabedian said. ``That's what R
means, restricted. You're restricting the audience. But I'd hate
for this somehow to cause a chilling effect on the artistic
process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 1122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2948 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-MOVIE-RATINGS-REVIEW-     07-22 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-RATINGS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOODOO BOX OFFICE: PG-13-NESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (Repeating with art note)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
