r a BC-FILLMORE-GROWTH-2Take     07-22 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILLMORE-GROWTH-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWTH ISSUE POLARIZES TINY CITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOSEPH GIORDONO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FILLMORE, Calif. _ Hollywood painting contractor Paul Harding
was skeptical when his wife started talking about escaping the
hectic pace of the city eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But on a weekend drive through Ventura County, the couple
discovered Fillmore, a farming community of 13,000 that time
seemingly has passed by. They fell in love with the seemingly
endless expanses of citrus groves, the mountains framing the
skyline and the downtown rebuilt in a 19th century style after the
devastation of the 1994 Northridge Earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   On that first visit, they bought a home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fillmore reminded me of what Southern California was a long
time ago, and it really appealed to me from the first time that I
saw it,'' said Harding, 52.
</P>
<P>
   The Hardings' vision of a quieter time and a gentler place is
now under threat - in great part by people like the Hardings
yearning for a taste of the rural life and city officials hoping to
improve economic opportunities for the poorest area in Ventura
County.
</P>
<P>
   Farmland and open space have been gobbled up by new housing and
commercial development. And the Fillmore City Council took a
pro-development stance when it withdrew from a lawsuit seeking to
block the massive Newhall Ranch project in exchange for a $300,000
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very clear indication to the community that the
City Council had no intention of keeping its promise to resist the
pressures for development at all costs,'' Harding said.
</P>
<P>
   Now Harding and others are fighting back, sponsoring the
Fillmore Save Open-space and Agricultural Resources initiative, a
November ballot measure that would require voter approval for
commercial and residential development outside a designated
boundary around the city.
</P>
<P>
   Several other cities in Ventura County passed SOAR initiatives
in 1998, including Camarillo, Moorpark, Oxnard, Simi Valley and
Thousand Oaks, but the Fillmore ballot might be the most
restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   Fillmore officials have countered with Vision 2020 - an
initiative that would significantly broaden the development
boundary outside the city limits. The two largest additions would
be 830 acres north of the city and 630 acres southeast of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The SOAR initiative would limit development to an area roughly
equal to the Fillmore city limits until 2021, unless individual
developments are approved by voters.
</P>
<P>
   With both measures approved for the Nov. 7 ballot, Fillmore -
the self-proclaimed ``last, best small town in Southern
California'' - is at a crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a choice between preservation and development at all
costs,'' Harding said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just a question of development. It has become an
issue encompassing history, economic priorities and race.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1998 study, ``FOCUS: Ventura County,'' Fillmore
has the county's lowest per-capita income, its third-lowest
household income, the third-highest unemployment rate and the
highest minority population.
</P>
<P>
   While the study notes that such characteristics are not unusual
for an almost exclusively agricultural economy, city officials say
the only way to improve those conditions is to diversify revenue
sources.
</P>
<P>
   And that means development and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   According to Economic Develoment Director Shirley Spitler, the
city will now focus on luring smaller high-tech companies and
promoting the area as a regional tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
   It is a natural progression for a town that is still struggling
to recover from the 1994 Northridge Earthquake, which destroyed
much of downtown Fillmore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earthquake really devastated a lot of businesses and
either shut them down or forced them to take out heavy loans to get
back on their feet,'' Spitler said. ``SOAR would keep businesses in
town from fully recovering and likely keep out some of those we are
trying to attract.''
</P>
<P>
   Fillmore Mayor Evaristo Barajas, an outspoken critic of the SOAR
initiative, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The businesses are starting to make a recovery, and we are
trying to provide a bit more of a market for them,'' said Barajas,
a real estate agent. ``The SOAR initiative is basically trying to
stop all of that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 1211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9787 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-FILLMORE-GROWTH &LR; - &UR; 2nd     07-22 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILLMORE-GROWTH </SLUG>
 - 2ndTake-LADN 
(FILLMORE, Calif: all of that)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to city officials, there are tangible signs that the
town has recovered. Three large developments totaling about 300
houses are under construction in Fillmore, with homes ranging from
$150,000 to $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   But future residential and industrial development, including an
18-hole golf course dotted with large homes planned for the open
land surrounding a state fish hatchery southeast of the city, would
be blocked if SOAR passes.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Griffin Industries, the developer of the
proposed golf course project and a sponsor of the city's Vision
2020 plan, declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not know of any developers who would be willing to go
through the entire process of courting a city's voters and pumping
in all that extra money to wait three or four years before
building,'' City Planner Kevin McSweeney said. ``They could just as
easily go somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Several shop owners declined to be quoted on the record,
expressing private concerns that their businesses could be targeted
by partisans of either side if they made their positions on the
issue known.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report by City Manager Ron Payne, the Fillmore
SOAR initiative would result in a 26 percent increase in water
rates, a 9 percent increase in sewer rates and require existing
residents to shoulder the responsibility for $2.2 million in
existing debt for capital improvements made in anticipation of
future development.
</P>
<P>
   The SOAR initiative, Payne says, will not slow population
growth. In fact, it would cause the residential area in Fillmore to
be completely built out by 2005 and cost the city some 2,500 new
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   SOAR restrictions would limit home building to the point that
the population could grow by just one person per year from 2005 to
2020, Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of SOAR say they don't oppose all development, but do
want a say in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't feel that the city is exercising a great enough sense
of economy in developing the remaining land they have,'' said SOAR
sponsor Harding.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are talking about building a golf course on 200 acres of
prime agricultural land. It makes you wonder what their genuine
concerns are.''
</P>
<P>
   SOAR supporters also criticize the statistics cited in Payne's
report, saying they only represent the worst-case scenario. Having
voters decide the fate of proposed developments does not mean all
developments will be rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Behind all of the numbers, though, some residents see a more
disturbing trend. City officials, they claim, want to lure business
and upper-income families to reshape the ethnic makeup of the
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Estate lots and golf courses and ranch homes are all ways to
say bring in upper-middle-class white families and push aside the
minorities who helped build this community,'' retiree Ron Lima said
as he sat chatting with a group of friends under a shade tree by
City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``How quickly do you think those people are going to be
forgotten if you have upper-income people just living here but
commuting to L.A. and other places?''
</P>
<P>
   City officials dismiss the claims as ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   All they are concerned with is bringing in the businesses and
residents that will keep Fillmore from being left behind as the
landscape of Southern California changes, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, many residents are wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If being left behind means not becoming overrun with SUVs and
Radio Shacks and Wal-Marts, then I'm all for it,'' said Gary Wayne,
a Fillmore native who commutes to Oxnard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agriculture is always subject to the whims of the economy and
Mother Nature, but it is the heart and soul of this community.
Always has been, and, hopefully, always will.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
