<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9798 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-G8-CLINTON-950&AMP;ADD-NY     07-22 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-G8-CLINTON-950&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
G-8 COMMITS TO `DOT FORCE' TO TACKLE DIGITAL DIVIDE AND MONEY FOR
HEATH CRISES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOGA, Japan _ Turning from what has become an annual ritual _
the gathering of leaders of the largest industrialized nations _
President Clinton Saturday shaved short his meetings here to plunge
back into the fervid search for a historic peace in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who arrived in Japan a day late from the Camp David
meeting with the leaders of Israel and the Palestinians, has
received several briefings daily on their continuing talks with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, administration officials
said. They said Clinton heeded advice from aides, however, to avoid
making calls from Japan to either Prime Minister Ehud Barak of
Israel or the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The president will depart from Okinawa half a day early, after
meeting Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain on Sunday morning, to
rejoin the Camp David talks Sunday evening, Eastern time, said the
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who is attending his last summit meeting with the
leaders of Britain, France, Italy, Germany, Canada, Japan and
Russia, spent his day in meetings with those men. American
diplomats said the Russian president, Vladimir Putin, making his
debut on the international diplomatic stage, had impressed the
group, displaying alacrity and a lack of the ebullience often
associated with his predecessor, Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   With no history to be made thousands of miles from Camp David
and no crises to distract them, the leaders aired issues that
traditionally have taken a secondary place at the annual gathering,
and issued a declaration focusing on the importance of getting the
developing world hooked up to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Participants said that in discussions that often resembled
philosophical discourses the leaders also pondered the human
genome, infectious diseases and rain forests, reaching common
ground that will be reflected in a joint statement to be released
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to previous summits meetings, overshadowed by crises
like fighting in the Balkans or the financial crisis in Asia,
``there was not one major problem we needed to address,'' said
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien. Therefore, he added, ``you
will see a list of subjects addressed in the communique.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Okinawa, I would say, is shaping up as the development
summit,'' said Lael Brainard, Clinton's adviser on international
economic issues. ``Often the summits get overwhelmed by outside
events. This year, what has been notable is a very disciplined
focus on the development agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders' new-found concern with what has become known as the
``digital divide'' _ between those who are part of the new
computer-driven economy and those who are not _ found little
sympathy from critics in nongovernmental groups that seek less
sophisticated aid to the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   Activists with Jubilee 2000, an organization pushing for debt
relief, burned a laptop computer outside the news media center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't eat computers,'' said Kewesi Owusu, the group's
African coordinator. ``People are dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Seth Amgot, a spokesman for Oxfam, the British charity with
extensive operations in the poor countries of the world, said,
``The Internet is going to have to wait until the electricity grid
is extended, the phone grid is extended and more kids learn to
read. The private sector is handling this computer revolution
pretty well on its own.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders said they would create what they called a ``dot
force'' _ or digital opportunity task force _ to marshal public and
private resources to bring the computer revolution to poorer
nations. The force is supposed to report to next year's gathering
of the leaders, to be held in Genoa, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders cited statistics showing that of the estimated 332
million people who use the Internet, fewer than 1 percent live in
Africa. Part of the problem is just telephone lines. The developed
world has about 50 phone lines per 100 people compared to 1.4
phones in low-income countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone, everywhere should be enabled to participate in and
no one should be excluded from the benefits of the global
information society,'' the leaders agreed in their statement. ``The
resilience of this society depends on democratic values that foster
human development such as the free flow of information and
knowledge, mutual tolerance, and respect for diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders also agreed in principle to revive World Trade
Organization negotiations on the launching of another round of
global trade talks by the end of this year. However, they remained
at odds throughout the day on the details of the next round.
Disagreements over that round _ principally between the United
States and Europe, but also between the developed world and poorer
nations _ proved so divisive at the world trade meeting in Seattle
last year that it collapsed in discord.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders here also discussed the importance of good health to
a functioning economy and vowed to aid the developing world in
combating infectious diseases such as AIDS, tuberculosis and
malaria. Japan led the way with a $3 billion fund to fight diseases
in poor countries, along with a $15 billion aid package aimed at
helping countries take advantage of the computer age.
</P>
<P>
   Participants said that Putin _ whose own country, Russia, has
spotty Internet access and telephone service _ came up with a
suggestion in the computer arena that quickly won the backing of
his colleagues. He suggested that the leaders themselves remain in
contact in between their annual summit meetings by electronic mail.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said Putin represented a remarkable
contrast with Yeltsin, who could be irascible at such gatherings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   During a one-on-one meeting with Clinton, Putin gave up no
ground when the president scolded the Russian for not respecting
press freedom. But Putin brought smiles to the faces of the
American delegation when he told them about his visit to North
Korea, en route to Japan, and the striking similarities with the
Soviet Union of Stalinist times. North Korea's economic situation,
Putin reportedly said, reminded him of the former Soviet Union in
the 1950s. Putin said 1 million North Koreans turned out to see
him, noting that some of them probably did not volunteer to do so.
</P>
<P>
   As with all such annual gatherings, most of the declarations
made and agreements reached came in the form of general commitments
with no dollar figures attached. Blair had sought to round up funds
from the group to relieve the debt of impoverished nations but, in
Sunday's statement, the leaders will instead restate their
intention to carry out an agreement they reached at their summit
meeting last year in Cologne.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the senior statesman among the group, was ending his
eighth and final such meeting of industrialized nations. When he
started, the group was the Group of 7. Inviting Russia was a
measure of the rapport Clinton had with Yeltsin and of America's
anxiety to draw a newly democratic Russia into the global fold. At
the group photo, the president brought smiles to his colleagues
when he said: ``This is my last photo _ so be serious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
