<SLUG> BC-R-CLINTON-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CALLS TAX-CUT BILLS BY THE GOP ILL ADVISED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add art advisory.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saying that Republicans in Congress were treating
the projected federal budget surplus ``as if they'd won it in the
lottery,'' President Clinton on Saturday defended his promise to
veto the main tax cuts passed by the House and Senate, and he
called for bipartisan cooperation in setting the nation's fiscal
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address, taped in Japan _ where he is
meeting with the leaders of the big industrial nations _ Clinton
said Republicans were rushing toward spending all of the projected
surplus outside of Social Security on tax cuts that would go
primarily to the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   He said the drive for tax cuts was putting at risk the
government's opportunity to eliminate the national debt, failing to
address the needs of working people and undermining efforts to
shore up the Social Security and Medicare systems.
</P>
<P>
   His comments came at the end of two weeks in which Republicans
completed work on two major tax-cutting bills, one that would
reduce taxes for married couples and another that would repeal the
federal estate tax. Congress is still working on bills that would
expand tax-deductible contributions to retirement savings accounts
and roll back part of the tax on Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot sign one expensive tax break after another without
any coherent strategy for safeguarding our financial future,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans showed no inclination to back down.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rod Grams, R-Minn., said Clinton did not understand that
the surplus came from tax revenues, and ought to be returned to the
people who earned it, the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   `` Clinton, we're asking you to put aside election-year politics
and help families live the American dream,'' Grams said in the
weekly Republican radio address. ``If you do your part and sign the
bills we have sent you to repeal the marriage penalty and death
tax, Americans can keep a little more of their hard-earned money,
for their families and their future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
