<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AN INSPIRATIONAL ARMSTRONG WITH A STORY TO TELL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Tour de France is a metaphor for life, Lance Armstrong tells
us, because it can be ``exalting and heartbreaking and potentially
tragic'' and it can pose ``unspeakably bad luck, unthinkable
beauty, yawning senselessness and, above all, a great, deep
self-questioning. It even tests you morally.''
</P>
<P>
   And then he declares that given the choice ``between winning the
Tour de France and cancer, I would choose cancer.'' As last year's
winner and the favorite to win Sunday, and as a survivor of
late-stage testicular cancer that had invaded his brain, Armstrong
is the only person alive who could even seriously consider such a
choice. As with any hero who has returned from somewhere dangerous,
he has a story to tell. The third happy surprise (after almost four
years of survival after diagnosis and victory in the Tour) is how
good a story it is and how well the smooth, often elegant, writing
of Sally Jenkins helps him tell it.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's new autobiography is called ``It's Not About the
Bike: My Journey Back to Life'' (Putnam) and it ranks very high on
the list of two genres of which I have read too much, the memoirs
of sports stars and of cancer survivors. Tough, direct and filled
with useful information about racing a bicycle, coping with cancer
and even in vitro fertilization, the book also offers up a
fascinating portrait of an insecure, fatherless momma's boy who is
still in honest struggle to grow up and be a good father himself.
</P>
<P>
   His mother was 17 when Lance was born and his father left them
when the boy was 2. Armstrong dismisses him as ``a non factor'' who
merely ``provided the DNA.'' When a Texas newspaper traced his
biological father last year, Armstrong not only expressed lack of
interest in finally meeting him but called the man's expression of
pride opportunistic. It is as if he is still trying to abandon the
old man right back.
</P>
<P>
   Lance's stepfather, Terry Armstrong, is described as ``a
Christian who used to beat me for silly things.'' That may help
explain why Lance later describes himself as ``agnostic.''
</P>
<P>
   At 7, he was liberated by a Schwinn Mag Scrambler; ``a bike is
freedom to roam, without rules and without adults.'' He was
probably safer on the road. His favorite game, which he invented,
was ``fireball.'' He and a friend, wearing garden gloves, played
catch with tennis balls which they soaked in gasoline, then set
aflame.
</P>
<P>
   The central character in the book is his mother, Linda, who
worked several jobs as she put herself through school, and was his
constant source of strength. She taught him to never quit. She
moved them to upper middle-class Plano, Texas, for the schools, and
then protected him from classism and the local epidemics of
adolescent drug addiction, depression and suicide.
</P>
<P>
   No football player in a football-crazy town, Lance found his
outlet in triathlons. In this lottery sports world, there is a
tendency to overpraise those who do it the hard way, but often they
have no choice. In biking, Lance admits, he found a way to inflict
physical pain on himself that smothered the emotional pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cycling is so hard,'' he says, ``the suffering is so intense,
that it's absolutely cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a perfect candidate for chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   The precancerous Lance Armstrong was known as the Texas Bull, an
aggressive, disrespectful rider fueled by the rage that covered his
fears. He likes himself much better now. Unlike most cancer
survivor/writers who profess moral improvement, his claim seems to
be more than a way of finding something worthwhile in unspeakably
bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   While he says that cancer made him a better person, more
interestingly it made him a better racer. Before his months of
chemo, he had been a star of one-day races. After chemo, he
discovered his strength was in endurance for the long haul, which
is what the 23-day, 2,274-mile Tour de France is all about. As well
as life. Without cancer, he believes, he would not have won the
Tour. Don't try this or fireball at home.
</P>
<P>
   The superstar and survivor genres come together in Armstrong's
descriptions of the computers, blood tests, online research,
emotional support and teamwork that goes into both bike racing and
cancer treatment, as well as how he channeled his attacking race
style into being an aggressive, noncompliant patient.
</P>
<P>
   Delicious small facts abound: I had no idea that he wore a heart
monitor during the Tour so his coach in a chase car could tell him
when to pedal harder or slow down. Or that EPO, the red-blood cell
enhancer banned in the Tour, was a drug he had to take when chemo
suppressed his immune system. He stopped taking EPO after his
cancer treatment ended and has been on record as fiercely
anti-drug.
</P>
<P>
   Rare among cancer survivors or superstar athletes these days,
Armstrong does not offer that kind of cloying religious advice that
fits on a T-shirt but not in the real world. What he does offer,
however, is worth taping to your handlebars: ``We can take
responsibility for ourselves and be brave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
