<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9843 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-WIZARDOFOZ-CENTENNIAL     07-22 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIZARDOFOZ-CENTENNIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'RE OFF TO SEE THE WIZARD TURN 100 
</HEADLINE>
   By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOOMINGTON, IND. _ At 5:20 p.m. sharp Thursday, Dr. Richard R.
Rutter, 68, took off over the University of Indiana in a hot air
balloon dressed as the Wizard of Oz in a top hat and frock coat
with nine plastic pigs on it.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, Rutter is a professor of orthodontics at the
School of Dentistry at the University of the Pacific in San
Francisco. But for 10 brief minutes until he drifted down to an
athletic field, Rutter imagined that he was the Wizard himself on
his way to the Emerald City, pulling baby pigs out of his sleeves
and letting them run up and down his shoulders. ``Oh, I felt very
wizardly, yes,'' Rutter said, after landing.
</P>
<P>
   Rutter was one of some 400 Oz fans who came to the University of
Indiana for a weekend celebration of the centennial of L. Frank
Baum's book, ``The Wizard of Oz.'' The event was sponsored by the
International Wizard of Oz Club, and the group was here to honor
the timeless story of a little girl, Dorothy, who is blown out of
Kansas by a cyclone and encounters the Wizard, who lives in the
Emerald City and promises to help her find her way home.
</P>
<P>
   The publication of ``The Wizard of Oz'' in 1900 ushered in ``a
new era of American children's literature,'' Michael Patrick Hearn,
an Oz scholar, said in the celebration's keynote address. ``The
fairy is eliminated _and the fearsome morality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baum dared to offer delight without instruction,'' said Hearn.
</P>
<P>
   The story has worked its way into the national psyche as a fable
of eternal hope in which things are not always as fearsome as they
seem, even lions are cowards, wizards are just pretending to be
fierce, and it is always best to be at home. ``It's like a
religion,'' said the author Alison Lurie, who was here to give a
talk. ``It has its holy relics, its laity, its clergy'' _ the Baum
descendants and the heads of the Oz fan clubs.
</P>
<P>
   With 5 million copies sold until it went into the public domain
in 1956, ``The Wizard of Oz'' was the Harry Potter of its time. It
is impossible to know how many of the Oz books have been sold since
then, Hearn said, who is the author of an annotated version of the
``The Wizard of Oz.'' But Hearn estimates that more people have
seen the 1939 MGM movie of ``The Wizard of Oz'' with Judy Garland,
and more times, than any other movie ever made. An updated
centennial version of Hearn's book, complete with references to
Ezekiel, ``The Pilgrim's Progress,'' and Ralph Waldo Emerson, is
being published this September by W.W. Norton.
</P>
<P>
   At the celebration, there were lectures on every aspect of
Baum's life and work, displays of Oz collectibles, and a church
service with an Oz theme. Three of the original Munchkins from the
1939 movie came. One, Clarence Swenson, a pituitary midget, wore a
replica of his original Munchkin soldier costume with a fez-like
hat and fuzzy plume. One participant, Ricky Birran, a professional
storyteller from Eugene, Ore., who calls himself Sir Readalot,
began a marathon reading session, intending to read from a series
of Oz books for 24 hours straight, reciting one chapter from each
from memory.
</P>
<P>
   Gita Morena, a great-granddaughter of Frank Baum, appeared
wearing a pair of silver shoes like Dorothy in the book. On
Thursday, Morena, the author of ``The Wisdom of Oz,'' gave a talk
on how she uses Oz in her psychotherapy practice. Morena said her
original name was Dorothy, but she changed it in 1981 to Gita at
the suggestion of an Indian mystic. ``I believe the magic key was
given to me to open the doors to sympathy and understanding,''
Morena said, quoting her great-grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   ``We travel together through the inner world to find our way,''
she said. ``Initiates must travel through the chaos of the
windstorm to find the storm's center point.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Morena said, ``Even though the journey is difficult,
success is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   One theme running through the celebration was Baum as a champion
of women's rights.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Erisman, a professor of literature at Texas Christian
University, said in a talk that Baum's mother-in-law, Matilda
Joslyn Gage, a drafter of the Woman's Bill of Rights with Elizabeth
Cady Stanton and Susan B. Anthony, exerted a major influence on the
author. On Friday, Lurie lectured on ``Oz and the New Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   All the activities at the celebration were centered at the
Indiana Memorial Union, which was decorated with 300 pounds of red
silk poppies in honor of the Deadly Poppy Field that Dorothy
encounters on her way to the Emerald City. A mock yellow brick road
led through the lobby to a 15-foot-high replica of the Emerald City
on the stage of Alumni Hall, with 40 Munchkin mannequins, and a
pair of huge red ruby slippers. The University of Indiana was
chosen as the site of the celebration, said Peter E. Hanff,
president of the club and deputy director of the Bancroft Library
at Berkeley, because of the extensive collection of Oz material in
the University's Lilly Library, which was on display for the event.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those attending were collectors. One of the best-known
in the group was Edith Hollister of Santa Barbara, Calif., famous
among Oz fans for owning the pencil with which Baum wrote the first
Oz book.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never too old to have a happy childhood,'' said Lee
Jenkins, a paralegal who owns an Oz store.
</P>
<P>
   Robin McMaster, who has a mail order business selling Oz items,
gave a talk that was standing room only on how to incorporate Oz
ornaments into Christmas decorations. ``I'll be going over the
ornaments one by one,'' she said, as she showed slides of her two
immense Christmas trees from last year packed with Oz figures.
</P>
<P>
   Rutter, who took off in the balloon, is another collector. He
has a room in his home in Redwood City, Calif., devoted to Oz, he
said, complete with its own yellow brick road.
</P>
<P>
   Rutter joined the international club 25 years ago after he began
collecting, ``though it's easier for me to go to Winkie meetings,''
he said, referring to local meetings on the West coast. The Winkies
are the yellow peoples of the Western part of Oz who are the
subjects of the Wicked Witch.
</P>
<P>
   Rutter attended the Friday afternoon costume party wearing his
Wizard costume with the pigs on it. Another was dressed as a field
of poppies, and one as a yellow brick road with a hat meant to
represent the Emerald City. There were several Dorothies,
``traditional,'' younger-looking Dorothies, based on the drawings
of W.W. Denslow in the first Oz book, and Judy Garland Dorothies
based on the movie. After the party, at dinner, Baum's
great-grandson, Robert Baum, gave a talk about Baum's life, and
some participants attended a performance of Patrick Shanahan's play
``Oz'' at the Bushkirt-Chumley Theater.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it was a dizzying array.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a really marvelous event,'' said Mel Rubin, a lawyer
and mediator from Key Biscayne, Fla., as he watched Rutter take off
in his balloon. Rubin, who is 56, had come to Bloomington with his
wife Susan Scholz, a psychologist. Rubin said he had been
captivated by the Oz books ever since the Wicked Witch scared him
when he was 5 or 6 years old. His wife doesn't share his interest
in Oz, Rubin said. ``She just sits there and relaxes and realizes
what a mistake she made.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rubin said, ``I wish more people would do this. I think
they'd leave each other alone, if they'd just concentrate on the
Wizard and all the great things in the Emerald City.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
