<P>
   COLOMBIA-AID _ BOGOTA, Colombia _ The U.S. Congress has passed a
$1.3 billion aid package for Colombia, but many wonder if the money
will be too little too late to save a country beset by violence,
civil war and a powerful leftist guerrilla army. Some critics fear
the U.S. is stepping into a Vietnam-style quagmire by sending
military advisors and sleek new helicopters to help battle
Colombia's drug lords, who along with Marxist guerrillas control
vast areas in the countryside. Meanwhile, Colombian President
Andres Pastrana is battling plummeting public support, a deep
recession, icy relations with the national congress, corruption
charges and stalled peace talks. (Williams, Cox News Service)
</P>
