   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   COVERDELL _ Live coverage of Saturday's memorial service in
Atlanta for Sen. Paul Coverdell (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   ALADUMP _ LOWNDESBORO, ALA. _ The historic Selma-to-Montgomery
voting rights trail, U.S. Highway 80, runs through rural Lowndes
County, meandering past tracts of dusty farmland, boarded-up gas
stations and sacred civil rights-era ground. A racially mixed group
of developers and county officials, including some who hold office
thanks to the voting rights crusade, feel the 670-acre landfill is
just the thing to jump-start the economy of one of the state's
poorest counties. But landfill opponents, also a mix of blacks and
whites, say a dump near U.S. 80 would be an affront to the memory
of the marchers and hurt both the environment and a fledgling
tourist industry. Last week, the Alabama Department of
Environmental Management granted a permit for a landfill. We take a
look a the issues. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTERS _ CHARLESTON, S.C. - As he strolls amid the history of
this city where his family has lived for more than three centuries,
Pinckney Seabrook Wilkinson is alarmed by the declining population.
Not of people, but of shutters. ``You see how silly the house looks
without them,'' said the College of Charleston English instructor
and self-appointed guardian of the historic district's exterior
window dressings. Though few, if any, are so fretful, Wilkinson
said the shutters are disappearing as well-heeled out of towners
snap up historic houses and, during renovation, are not aware, or
do not care, about zoning rules that require shutters to be
replaced. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BRUNSWICK _ BRUNSWICK, Ga. _ When Kendra McCrae stormed into the
Brunswick city manager's office recently and demanded an audience,
it was another sign of the continuing unrest in the coastal city
that has spawned violence, marches and calls for change. McCrae, a
28-year-old secretary, was upset over mistreatment she says she and
other blacks received at the hands of police during a July 4th
altercation. That holiday weekend confrontation, which eventually
turned violent, led to a subsequent protest march on Monday (July
17) with others planned. It has also revealed a wider set of
grievances. A loose coalition of residents and ministers is now
calling for sensitivity training for police, a community-wide forum
to discuss racial differences and better economic opportunities for
the city's black population. We examine the continuing evolution of
a city in transition. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BARTON-VICTIMS _ The lives that were changed by Mark Barton's
rampage; the woman who was robbed of her sight by Barton; the widow
who wakes up each day alone; the day traders who can't help but
shudder when they walk into their Buckhead office ... For this
story the reporters initially assigned to keep in touch with the
survivors and the families of the dead will go back and chronicle
how they have coped in the year since the shooting. (Judd, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
