<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9882 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ENHANCER0723-COX     07-22 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENHANCER0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sound comes alive with stereo enhancer
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Theater 2000 is a device that promises to
``enhance'' the performance of your home sound system by ``allowing
listeners to hear music or sound effects as if they were literally
in the middle of a live recording or concert hall.''
</P>
<P>
   And while it's hard to describe exactly what the unit is doing,
it actually does seem to give music a more full-bodied,
three-dimensional feel.
</P>
<P>
   Like other electronic stereo enhancement products I have tested,
the Theater 2000 seemed to be adding a bit of extra power to some
treble and bass frequencies, giving the sound a more compelling
feel. But unlike some others, the Theater 2000 didn't add
distortions that made the sound seem less natural.
</P>
<P>
   I tested the unit on an older (about 1990 vintage) stereo system
of moderate quality. It took about five minutes to connect the
Theater 2000 using cables that came with the product.
</P>
<P>
   The instructions were clear and the unit came with a remote
control that made it easy to use and adjust.
</P>
<P>
   Tapping into the Theater 2000 gave the immediate impression that
the room was more full of sound, partly because the music was
slightly louder. Flipping the system on and off and listening
carefully led to the conclusion that only certain frequencies were
being boosted, an effect that couldn't be duplicated by simply
increasing the volume in standard stereo mode.
</P>
<P>
   The Theater 2000 has two modes _ one meant primarily for music
and one for audiovisual inputs such as DVD, videocassettes and
games. The unit increased the intensity of sound in the audiovisual
mode but not as dramatically as in the music mode.
</P>
<P>
   Theater 2000 is available online at www.theatersound.com for
$199.95. Spectrum Research said the product should be available
through other electronics retailers by the end of the year at a
suggested price of $229.95.
</P>
<P>
   By clicking on an icon on the Web site you can download a sound
file that demonstrates the Theater 2000 effect.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
