<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9884 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CYC-THE-BEST0723-COX     07-22 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-THE-BEST0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surviving cancer to win last year's Tour made him a hero . . .
But is Lance the best?
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Should he claim his second straight Tour de
France championship today, Lance Armstrong will hardly be unique _
there have been 18 other multiple winners. But it would put his
accomplishment in position to spark debate over topics that have no
definitive answers.
</P>
<P>
   Does overcoming cancer to claim back-to-back titles in cycling's
most difficult and prestigious event elevate Armstrong to the
status of one of the all-time greats in the sport? Has he eased
past three-time winner Greg LeMond to become the top cyclist in
United States' history?
</P>
<P>
   The latter question is more open to speculation than the former.
Even Armstrong considers the former question a waste of time when
measured against the legacies of five-time winners Miguel Indurain
of Spain, Bernard Hinault and Jacques Anquetil of France and Eddy
Merckx of Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merckx, Indurain, Hinault and Anquetil, they were a lot more
talented than I am,'' Armstrong said at a press conference on the
off day before leading into the final week of the Tour. ``It would
be crazy for me to say I will win five in a row. If I want to win
five, I will have to ride (in) six or seven because there are lot
of other good riders and you can't win every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe you can call Jim Ochowicz crazy. The U.S. road
cycling coach for the 2000 Olympics believes Armstrong can join the
select crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' Ochowicz asked. ``It's certainly not inconceivable.
After getting the second one under his belt, it's my personal
feeling that a third one will come with it because he's in that
range.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong turns 29 on Sept. 18, the prime age for many cyclists.
``I can't tell you how long he'll ride, but he could win five
Tours,'' Ochowicz said. ``Many riders in their early 30s have won
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong also is uncertain how much longer he'll compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have the motivation through all the years, I will do it,
but I can't promise,'' he said at a press conference. Family
considerations would probably keep him from riding more than
another four years or so, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tour's five-time winners generally are acknowledged as the
absolute creme de la creme of cycling. Ochowicz readily concedes
that Merckx, who won the Tour from 1969-72 and again in 1974, is at
the top of the list, but he believes Armstrong has the potential to
be included in the exclusive club.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's all added up in the end, you'll have to put Lance in
the top 10,'' Ochowicz said. ``Maybe the top five.''
</P>
<P>
   Merckx _ the ``ck'' is silent _ usually is considered the
standard by whom all others are measured. While Armstrong is
regarded as a powerful climber, Merckx wrote the book. Tall for a
cyclist at 6 feet 4 inches, he was known as ``The Cannibal'' for
his ability to dominate all phases of the game.
</P>
<P>
   That's reflected in Merckx's record of 525 career victories in
1,800 races. Among his many accomplishments was wearing the Tour de
France's yellow jersey 96 days and winning 35 stages, both records.
At the 1969 Tour, he became the first and only rider to win the
yellow jersey (overall winner), green jersey (points winner) and
polka-dot jersey (King of the Mountains).
</P>
<P>
   ``Merckx is the big player in our sport,'' Ochowicz said. ``He
was at the top and did everything well.''
</P>
<P>
   THE U.S. DEBATE
</P>
<P>
   More intriguing is the Armstrong-LeMond matchup as the top rider
in U.S. history. It's a two-man mythical race because they are the
only Americans to win the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   LeMond also shares another trait with Armstrong: overcoming a
potentially fatal setback. LeMond was critically injured in a 1987
hunting accident when he was accidentally shot with a shotgun by
his brother-in-law while turkey hunting. Sixty pellets were found,
but doctors could only remove 30, and LeMond spent two years
recovering before resuming competitive cycling. He captured that
year's Tour de France, erasing a 50-second deficit on the final day
to win by eight seconds.
</P>
<P>
   When asked for a LeMond-Armstrong comparison, most cycling
insiders do more dancing around the subject than Fred Astaire. But
when pressed, they tend to give Armstrong the edge by an eyelash,
although LeMond has three Tour victories (1986, 1989-90).
</P>
<P>
   ``If I absolutely had to pick one, I'd probably go with Lance
because of the intangibles he brings to the table, but they are so,
so close,'' said Sean Petty, director of athlete performance for
USA Cycling, the sport's national governing body. ``Greg was so
tough and could really roll with the punches, but because of what
he's had to overcome physiologically and psychologically, I think
Lance would maybe edge him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Ochowicz: ``Greg certainly has earned the right to brag
about what he's done. But Lance has taken it a little further than
that with his ability to win it (Tour de France) with an American
team vs. Greg with a French team that had Tour winners on it in
Hinault and (Laurent) Fignon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This distinguishes Lance from Greg to a certain extent. Lance
also has quite a broader career because he's won World Cup one-day
races as well. Greg was very competitive in those, but didn't have
the same success.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Kiefel, a retired cyclist who was Armstrong's teammate for
six months when Armstrong competed for Motorola, refused to get
drawn into the hypothetical debate. But Kiefel, who now owns
cycling shops in Denver, said the two have different personalities
and competitive tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg is much more gregarious. He's very people-oriented while
Lance is very businesslike,'' Kiefel said. ``Lance is friendly, but
he likes to get the task done. Greg was focused on cycling but had
distractions. Lance doesn't allow those distractions into his life.
He just doesn't take no for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance has an incredible amount of power on the mountain
stages, but is so fluid on the bike. Greg was much more of a big
gear rider. He really wrestled with that bike to get everything out
of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't answer who's better,'' Kiefel added. ``All I know is
they've both had a huge impact on American cycling.''
</P>
<P>
   Vince Menci will vouch for that.
</P>
<P>
   Menci, 72, is events director and curator of the 14-year-old
U.S. Bicycling Hall of Fame in Somerville, N.J. He's also an
unofficial historian of the sport and was a competitive cyclist in
the late 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some very lean years in this country in the '40s, '50s
and '60s,'' Menci said. ``But it's so much better now. People like
Lance and Greg come around maybe once every 50 years or more. They
really generate a lot of interest in the sport for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of riders who are national champions, but
outside of the cycling community, no one knows they are national
champions,'' Menci added. ``But when Greg LeMond started coming up,
a new set of junior racers began to develop. And now Lance has
become a household name. He'll generate more interest and more
riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who's better, but I do know they've both been
great for the sport in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
