<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Del., Ky., Miss.)  By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Age Is a Big Issue In One Senate Race  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Delaware is a little state. But this year's U.S. Senate race
there looms large _ and, after last week, even larger.
</P>
<P>
   The state's senior senator, William V. Roth Jr., a Republican,
is going after a sixth term, and Democrats think that in Gov.
Thomas R. Carper, now finishing his second and final term, they at
last have the candidate who can take him out.
</P>
<P>
   If they are right, not only will Delaware get a brand-new
senator, but the 10-seat Republican edge in the Senate very well
might be narrowed. In only four or five other states are Democratic
hopes about the Senate as high.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder, then, that on Monday, when Delaware's Democratic
senator, Joseph Biden, introduced Carper at a rally celebrating the
official kickoff of the Carper campaign, he declared, ``This
election is a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   It became even bigger the next day with the release of a new
Mason-Dixon poll.
</P>
<P>
   Early polls had Roth trailing Carper by 10 points or so. The new
poll had him down by only 3 points.
</P>
<P>
   Both men tend to be middle-of-the-road politicians with few
sharp edges, which is the way Delawareans like their politics. So
what separates the pair more than anything else is age: the senator
turned 79 Saturday; the governor is 53. And age is what both are
focusing on.
</P>
<P>
   In his kickoff speech, Carper used the words ``energetic'' and
``future'' and the phrase ``new leadership'' no fewer than a dozen
times. Then, in his most pointed reference to Roth's 79 years _ 30
of them in the Senate and four in the House _ Carper said:
</P>
<P>
   ``For more than a third of a century, through the tenures of
seven presidents, Bill Roth has served the state of Delaware in
Washington. But this election, like all elections, is not just
about the past, it is about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth did not respond with his usual litany about having the
seniority to deliver to constituents in the future what no freshman
senator could ever hope to deliver. Rather, he pointed to the new
poll numbers and said, ``Our campaign is right where we want it to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   An Outspoken Ally Has Advice for Gore
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Paul E. Patton of Kentucky has good ties to Vice President
Al Gore and will help preside over the Democratic National
Convention next month, when Gore is officially nominated. But he
worries about how Gore is playing around the country, especially in
Kentucky, considered a swing state this year.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks back, Patton, who has a tendency to say precisely
what is on his mind, urged Gore to pay more attention to Kentucky,
noting that Gov. George W. Bush had an edge in the polls there and
had been raising a lot of money in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Now Patton has some more political analysis and advice for Gore
_ very frank and pointed analysis and advice.
</P>
<P>
   Asked the other day how the Gore campaign was shaping up, he
told The Courier-Journal of Louisville that the vice president's
problems in Kentucky, as in the nation as a whole, were largely
traceable to a lack of personality. Simple as that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the whole campaign,'' the governor said, ``is
that people know Gore and he evidently doesn't have that
personality that is causing people to come to him.''
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   Patton indicated that he thought Gore, with his latest round of
attacks on Bush's record as governor of Texas, was at last on the
right track.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he has to do right now,'' Patton said, ``is he's got to
bring George W. Bush's record out. We're exactly where we were in
1988, with a sitting vice president and an attractive governor who
can make a good speech _ and you know who won that one.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Vice President George Bush, Gov. Bush's father,
defeated Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, who had led in the
polls through most of the early and middle going.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi Democrat Is an Also-Ran Again
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1964, Mamie Cunningham, then a 22-year-old college
student, was one of the black Freedom Democrats from Mississippi
who journeyed to the Democratic National Convention in Atlantic
City, N.J., to challenge the all-white makeup of her state's
delegation. The challenge caused considerable turmoil, but in the
end she was not allowed to be a delegate and was forced to observe
the proceedings from the boardwalk outside the convention hall.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six years and a civil rights revolution later,
Cunningham, now a 58-year-old teacher, is still involved in
Mississippi politics. In fact, two months ago she was chosen to be
a delegate to the Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it will not happen.
</P>
<P>
   In the civil rights movement, too, what goes around comes
around.
</P>
<P>
   An Asian-American challenged the makeup of this year's
Mississippi delegation, saying that when it came to male delegates,
only blacks and whites had been chosen and a slot traditionally
reserved for someone of another race had not been filled. Party
officials investigated, and while they found no merit in the
challenge, they did find that the delegation had two more women
than men.
</P>
<P>
   They made Cunningham an alternate delegate and gave her delegate
slot to a man, a state senator. A delegation out of gender balance,
they explained, might not be seated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be, more or less, an observer again,'' Cunningham
lamented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
