<HEADLINE>
NFL OWNERS ARE CLOSELY WATCHING THE ESTATE TAX BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This time of year National Football League owners usually have
one thing on their minds: training camp. But in recent days their
attention has been divided. That is because they have been closely
monitoring a raging political debate that could alter the league's
ownership landscape in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   A number of millionaire owners, despite their large bank
accounts, face the possibility of losing their teams, not because
of bad investments or player salaries run amok, but because of
something that has dogged people for hundreds of years: taxes.
Specifically, estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The estate tax collects revenue from the richest Americans by
taxing estates up to 55 percent upon the death of the business
owner. Heirs are often forced to sell their estates, in many cases
farms or small businesses, to pay the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Republican congressional leaders are moving to repeal
it, saying that the tax penalizes success. Many Democrats want to
keep the tax because they feel it keeps the rich in check.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, professional football owners are nervously watching the
debate. Indeed, because of the estate tax, a number of owners and
their families, including some of the most respected football men
in the game such as the New York Giants' Wellington Mara and the
Pittsburgh Steelers' Dan Rooney, face the real prospect of losing
their teams because of the hefty tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we would like to keep the team,'' said Mara's son,
John, the Giants' executive vice president and general counsel.
``But I just don't know. At this point, I just don't know if we
will be able to do that. It could be nearly impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL, in a way, serves as the perfect petri dish for the
estate tax arguments. Should fans care if rich football team
owners, who have made millions, if not billions, off of ticket and
television revenues, lose their teams?
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, President Clinton called July legislation to
repeal the estate tax ``a budget-busting bill that provides a huge
tax cut for the most well-off Americans at the expense of working
families.''
</P>
<P>
   But does the estate tax, as owners and league officials
maintain, seriously threaten the continuity of the NFL, which in
turn would hurt the sport? And does it penalize NFL families that
have for decades spent money wisely, built traditions and pumped
jobs and revenue into their host cities?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought government was supposed to protect our property, not
confiscate it, not penalize someone because they've been
successful,'' said Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Wellington Mara, for example, has guided the Giants, the
league's flagship franchise, for decades with skill and grace,
earning a spot in the Hall of Fame. Recently, his son has taken
over the reigns, and he has evolved into a respected football
executive. Things are set up for a smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Mara family were forced to sell the team, it would
lead to a painful sale process that could last months, possibly
affecting the quality of play on the field. It is that scenario
that the league fears.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is the most prosperous of sports leagues, and currently
the sport is the healthiest it has been in decades. An issue like
the estate tax does not seem like a pressing problem.
</P>
<P>
   But owners and league officials maintain that it is a big issue.
Many of the NFL's elite owners are getting older. Some owners
believe that if the estate tax, nicknamed the death tax by
congressional Republicans, is not repealed, a string of teams could
be sold, causing the long-stable NFL to bubble slightly with
instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The estate tax may be the most important issue facing our
league in a long, long time,'' said Art Modell, the Baltimore
Ravens' owner. ``Under the present law, many owners in my league
would have to sell their teams to pay the estate taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL owners interviewed estimate that at least one dozen owners
face the loss of their teams in the coming years. It is hard to
tell exactly how many because understandably none will discuss in
detail their financial situations. Yet owners who are probably
closely watching the happenings in Washington include Buffalo's
Ralph Wilson, Tampa Bay's Malcolm Glazer, Mara and Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   Some owners, like Oakland's Al Davis, maintain they are prepared
for the estate taxes and will be able to keep the team in the
family. But most say it a serious problem.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, lawmakers did not have the NFL in mind when the
estate tax was signed into law by President Woodrow Wilson in 1916.
Eventually other presidents supported it because they believed the
tax would decrease the gap between the rich and the poor. Now, the
top 2 percent of the wealthiest Americans pay the tax, which starts
at 37 percent and climbs to a maximum of 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the tax so formidable for football owners, especially
ones where the franchise is their main source of revenue, is the
staggering bill that is due upon their deaths. If, for example, the
Giants are valued at $600 million, that could mean a tax debt of
over $300 million for the Mara estate.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the government allows the bill to be paid in some
instances over 12 to 14 years, ``that is a staggering amount and
one that we simply might not be able to pay even over an extended
period of time,'' Mara said.
</P>
<P>
   Owners are crossing their fingers that relief might be on the
way. The Senate voted 59-39 on July 14 to repeal the tax over 10
years, and in June, the House voted 279-136 to repeal. But
President Clinton has vowed to veto the bill when it crosses his
desk.
</P>
<P>
   There is history to justify the concern of owners. The estate of
the former Tampa Bay Buccaneers owner Hugh Culverhouse was forced
to sell the team in 1995 because of hefty estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   When Rooney's father, Art, bought the Steelers in 1933, he did
so for a measly $2,500. After his death in 1988, estate taxes were
a pittance compared to what NFL owners would pay now, thanks to the
increase in franchise values over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us are in precarious positions,'' Rooney said.
``We're crossing our fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
