<TEXT>
<P>
   Swann's Surface Issue
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were quietly a part of the recent Eric Swann
sweepstakes and showed serious interest in the once-great defensive
tackle. But, at first, the interest was not reciprocated.
Originally, Swann, who has been slowed by a series of knee
injuries, had crossed the Giants off his list of teams he wanted to
play for.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason was that he thought the team still played on
artificial turf, which would have been harder on his knees. But
once Swann became aware the Giants had recently changed their
playing surface to grass, he changed his mind and was willing to
visit the team.
</P>
<P>
   But interest in the Giants again waned once Swann began visiting
other teams. The Giants never made an offer.
</P>
<P>
   XFL Hiring From NFL
</P>
<P>
   Dick Butkus, recently hired to coach the Chicago team in the
XFL, pro wrestling's football league, will most likely not be the
last high profile former NFL player the upstart league will attempt
to snag. The new league's approach is to chip away at the NFL's
prestige and history by using, in some capacity, an NFL Hall of
Famer in the top media markets.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring Butkus was the first step in that strategy. According to
two people familiar with the league's negotiations, the XFL plans
to approach Hall of Fame tight end Kellen Winslow about a position,
possibly as a coach. Winslow played with the San Diego Chargers
from 1979 to 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The XFL is scheduled to begin play in eight cities in February
2001. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
