<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-HEURING0723-COX     07-22 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEURING0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Actress Heuring, 25, settles into movie star role
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Barchas
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Here's the scene: You're in the mood for a
deliciously silly movie. You trek to the theater, sink into your
seat with butter-dusted popcorn and wait for the lights to dim. And
then a preview comes on for a flick featuring you in the lead role.
Sound surreal? So it was for Austin native Lori Heuring when she
saw a trailer for ``The In Crowd,''a teen-age psychological
thriller in which she stars, while attending a different movie last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a really strange experience for me,'' Heuring
said of seeing herself on screen. ``All of a sudden I just had this
realization of, `Wow, I just reached one goal.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Starring in major studio movies is part of a long list of things
Heuring wants to do. The University of Texas graduate from the
business honors program dabbled in television and modeling before
plunging into film, where she hopes to fully explore the ``movie
star'' role. ``It's like a Peter Pan world,'' Heuring said. ``You
get to wake up and be something different, put yourself in someone
else's shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Portraying a different personality was challenging for Heuring
in ``The In Crowd.'' As Adrien, a 19-year-old recovering mental
patient with a penchant for sexual fantasies, Heuring flirted with
the thin separation between sanity and everything else. The strong
lesbian innuendoes in the movie were new for her, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read it in the script, I thought, `Ahh,' but when
you're actually doing it, you realize it's people just trying to
figure out who they are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for her role, Heuring spent time in mental hospitals,
dissecting what reality was like for patients there. ``For me, it
was just getting to that place where you don't feel loved and you
don't feel anyone listens or cares,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This feeling was foreign for Heuring, who credits her recent
success partly to the support of her parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great upbringing,'' she said. ``My parents listened to
everything that came out of my mouth, and I was told `I love you'
15 times a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Heuring's father helped jump-start her career by taking her to
Los Angeles, where she now lives, the day after she graduated from
Anderson High School. At the premiere of ``The In Crowd,'' Heuring
sat next to her dad. ``I just kind of nestled down into him and was
so nervous,'' she said. ``During the kissing scene, I covered his
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Heuring splits her time between visiting her family in
Texas (she turned down Princeton for UT partly to be closer to
home) and pursuing her career in California. Austin will be the
sight of a future Heuring film if the 25-year-old has her wa.
Heuring calls the Austin film community a ``microcosm where it's
almost more pure than anywhere else, and they're so not pretentious
with it,'' and she gushes about the Austin Film Society, which she
says ``is truly amazing in not only their knowledge, but in their
pursuit to show films that are completely obscure and completely
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Heuring hopes someday she might be making those types of movies.
The director's chair is already beckoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're an actor and you watch a really deft director do
his or her craft, you're in awe, and it'd be something that I'd
love to do someday,'' she said. ``For me, when you can sit down for
two hours at a screen and get lost in it, forget that you're even
watching a movie just because the story is so good and the
characters are so bold and blatant, that's the kind of film that
I'd love to make.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday'' is the operative word for Heuring. Right now, she's
busy reading about a dozen scripts a week as she scouts for future
films, having just wrapped up the independent feature ``Nailed.''
Don't expect her to get caught up in the superficial glamour of
Hollywood, however. Heuring lives by the advice of her father to
take what she does seriously without taking herself too seriously,
and she has no plans of forgetting where she came from.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one place that's important to me as far as my history
and myself, and that's Austin,'' she said. ``It's funny, because
I've never really felt like I was leaving Austin, because my
parents were there and it's such a part of me. It will always be
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
