<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-CLUETT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: LODGE OWNER'S DEATH LEAVES THE UPSALQUITCH QUIET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Maine)   By PETE BODO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROBINSONVILLE, New Brunswick _ The canoe, anchored at the head
of Moore's Pool, rocked like a cradle in the gentle grasp of the
Upsalquitch River. The morning, the last one of my annual trip to
Maclennan Lodge, the camp where I have fished for Atlantic salmon
for 19 years without missing a season, was overcast.
</P>
<P>
   The air was still and leaden, magnifying every sound: the
rhythmic swishing of an airborne fly-line; the lapping of the river
against the old wooden boat; the abrupt, piercing shriek of a blue
jay. I had not yet caught a salmon on this trip, and time was
running out.
</P>
<P>
   Ollie Marshall, my guide and friend, sat square-shouldered at
the downstream, stern end, of the boat, watching the Green Machine
wet fly swing around in the current.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awful quiet,'' Ollie finally observed. ``Looks like the salmon
left with Tucker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You think?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Naw,'' he said, examining a fingernail as if it were the first
time he saw one. ``Tucker loved being wicked, but he wouldn't do
that to us.''
</P>
<P>
   After a while, Ollie added, ``It's the evenings, after the
fishing, that I miss Tucker most. My God, how we all used to laugh,
sitting around the table in the kitchen. Now, every time the screen
door slams, we all still think the same thing: It must be Tucker,
going back to his cabin.''
</P>
<P>
   A. Tucker Cluett died after a brief illness last spring at age
65. A fastidious, sophisticated bachelor with loads of personal
style, a smart address in Blue Hill, Maine, and a taste for fine
art and rare books, Tucker will be missed by all who knew him. But
few people will mourn him as viscerally as his staff at Maclennan
Lodge, which he owned and operated here, among the towering spruce
trees and shimmering poplars of remote New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker, who was free from pretension, threw all his energy into
making the camp an enchanted place. But what really distinguished
him from many other camp owners was that he wanted his staff to
enjoy the same camp experience as the fanciest of his guests.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the lodge, in this largely impoverished, fiercely rural
area, became Tucker's unlikely second home, complete with a family
of five: the guides, Ollie Marshall and David and Shane Mann, who
are brothers; and the cooks and housekeepers, Nancy Thomas and Anne
Murray. The guides and Nancy had worked for Tucker since the year
after he bought the lodge, in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't like our boss,'' David Mann said. ``He was more like
a brother.''
</P>
<P>
   When Marshall suffered a detached retina a few years ago, Tucker
drove him to Halifax, Nova Scotia, for surgery, and brought him
home as well, a seven-hour drive each way. And when Shane Mann's
infant son Blake had meningitis, requiring his father's presence at
a hospital in Moncton, New Brunswick, 212 miles away, Shane was
resigned to giving up his job. But Tucker wouldn't hear of it. Each
Friday while Shane remained away, he hand-delivered Shane's
paycheck to his wife, Kathy.
</P>
<P>
   The bond Tucker developed with his staff was deep, cemented with
humor and crude practical jokes like filling Ollie's shoes with
rocks, or setting off fireworks under the kitchen table. When
Tucker set out smoked salmon hors d'oeuvres for the staff, he
always made an odd number, because he enjoyed watching the guides
fight over the last piece. No fools, the guides invariably found
ways to turn the joke around.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday paydays the staff made a point of formality, driving
Tucker to distraction by calling him by a name for which he had
little use, Cluett. One Friday morning Tucker, feigning a fit of
anger, tore up the staff's pay packets, and stomped out of the
kitchen. He then watched through a back window as Nancy frantically
fished the checks out of the trash and, finding them blank, lit out
after him.
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds a little silly, written down like this, but it
worked, probably because Tucker, who had been a painfully shy,
overweight child, got a reward he couldn't have anticipated when he
bought the camp: he got to be a kid again, and this time without
all the bad bits. And it worked because Tucker could truly be
himself among the spirited, cheerful, unspoiled people on his
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tucker fit in better here than we ever imagined,'' Nancy said.
``I think we brought out something in him that he could only
express here.''
</P>
<P>
   The salmon took my fly on the last cast of what might very well
have been my last trip to Maclennan Lodge. It leapt like a hurled
knife, destroying the oppressive stillness as it fell back into the
river with a resounding splash. Ollie moved fast now, firing up the
motor, making for shore, as the powerful fish tore off line,
heading downstream.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, time was moving, and fast. Far below, I saw a great,
momentary gleam of silver in the river. It vanished, just as
quickly as 20 years _ and a friend _ had passed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
