<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION JOURNAL: RABBI SEES OPPORTUNITY IN FIRE AT HIS SYNAGOGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore.)   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Rabbi David Bateman arrived in the United States from
Israel for a visit this month, he came with a harrowing story _ and
a determination to try to make good come from it.
</P>
<P>
   Bateman, 46, is the American-born spiritual leader of Kehilat
Ya'ar Ramot, a Conservative synagogue in Jerusalem, which became
famous a month ago after it was attacked by arsonists.
</P>
<P>
   The blaze occurred just after the Sabbath, consuming prayer
books and furniture. But it stopped short of the ark, leaving the
synagogue's three Torah scrolls undamaged. Still, the crime was so
traumatic within Israel that Prime Minister Ehud Barak declared
that it ``causes every Jew to shudder.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fire's immediate aftermath, some voiced suspicion that
the arsonists might be young men on an extreme fringe of a
fervently Orthodox group _ this in a nation where considerable
tension exists between Orthodox Jews, the dominant religious group
in a largely secular society, and the Reform and Conservative
movements, which are far smaller in Israel than in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   But when Bateman has spoken at American synagogues about the
incident, he said, he has made clear he does not want to cast
blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it only contributes to the problem that set the fire,
by pointing fingers at communities that indeed are not
responsible'' for it, he said in an interview this week. Of the
attack, he added, ``No truly religious person would perform that
kind of act.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the rabbi regards the incident as an opportunity to
create understanding across lines that divide Jews in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Although the fire caused great shock, he said, ``within 48
hours, we had a public rally that drew hundreds.'' The gathering
drew Israelis from groups that do not often rub shoulders:
``Orthodox representatives, including ultra-Orthodox, the secular
community, Reform representatives,'' Bateman said, recalling who
showed up.
</P>
<P>
   The gesture of solidarity gave Bateman and his congregation a
vision of how things might be. It was, he said, ``a kind of peak
moment, where the significant differences that divide us were put
aside.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed as a community to try to capitalize on that
peak moment,'' Bateman added, ``and hope to build with our
neighbors a communitywide program that will promote tolerance,
coexistence, and hopefully will be a model that will be replicable
in other communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Bateman grew up in Portland, Ore., in what he described as a
not-too-observant household. In his youth, he found his way to
Orthodox Judaism, trained as a rabbi and served an Orthodox
synagogue in Randolph, N.J., for more than a decade, until he moved
to Israel two years ago. Last fall, he became rabbi at Khelit
Ya'ar, with about 100 families affiliated with the Masorti
movement, as Conservative Judaism is called in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   What he and his congregation would like to create, he said, is a
long-term effort to bring people together, with a speakers' program
for adults, an educational effort in schools, a summer camp for
children from different backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked what he made of the turn his life has taken: that
after he immigrates to Israel, he finds himself articulating a
vision of social peace and unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord works in mysterious ways,'' Rabbi Bateman replied.
``For years, I've considered myself a principled pluralist, which
is what enabled me to make the transition from a primarily Orthodox
orientation to the Masorti community. I've been deeply concerned
with the divisions among the Jewish community, and wanted to get
involved in narrowing those rifts and bringing people together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Through circumstances not under my control,'' he said, ``I've
been thrust into the middle of that undertaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Episcopalians Call For the Removal of Guns
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, when leaders of the Episcopal Church were wrapping
up their General Convention, a policy-making gathering that meets
every three years, news centered on how they handled a statement on
human sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   But the Episcopalians also adopted several other resolutions,
with far less fanfare, one of which calls on members of the
2.4-million-member church to remove guns from their homes, as a
step toward protecting children from gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   The convention, says the resolution, ``calls upon all members of
the church to work intentionally in their several communities,
legislatures and institutions toward the removal of handguns and
assault weapons from our homes, other residential communities and
vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution came from the church's Diocese of Chicago, which
adopted a similar statement this year. ``I think people are just
fed up with the amount of violence in our society and the ready
availability of guns for people of any age,'' said Bishop William
D. Persell of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``So often in the church, we call on the government or we call
on someone else to do something,'' he said. ``For credibility, we
should talk about our own lives first.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
