<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ALDRICH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL ALDRICH, 51, NEUROLOGIST AND AUTHORITY ON SLEEP DISORDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mich., Va.)   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Sherman Aldrich, a neurologist who explored and
explained the mysteries of sleep and sleep disorders, died on July
18 at his home in Ann Arbor, Mich. He was 51.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was bone cancer, said the University of Michigan
Health System, where Aldrich founded the Sleep Disorders Laboratory
in 1985. Three months ago the university named it for him.
</P>
<P>
   When Aldrich established the center, sleep disorders were still
regarded largely as a domain of psychiatry. He approached them as a
neurologist, looking for their roots in nervous conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a person like Mike Aldrich to start systematically
studying normal sleep and abnormal sleep, and connecting sleep
problems to neurological disorders,'' said Dr. Sid Gilman,
neurology chairman at the university.
</P>
<P>
   Aldrich's earlier studies involved strokes, degenerative disease
and blindness with a neurological cause.
</P>
<P>
   After his focus shifted to sleep disorders, he contributed to
the understanding of apnea, which temporarily stops a sleeper's
breathing. He also became an expert on the effects of alcohol on
sleep and the interaction of sleep and epilepsy.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular interest to Aldrich was narcolepsy, a frequent,
overpowering desire to sleep. He studied its causes and symptoms
and developed diagnostic techniques that allow physicians to
distinguish it from other types of abnormal sleepiness. His
knowledge of the subject gained him an international reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Aldrich's research produced four books, some 60 articles, and
many book chapters and abstracts. His latest book, ``Sleep
Medicine: Normal Sleep and Its Disorders'' (Oxford University
Press, 1999), presents a concise and comprehensive text for
clinicians, researchers and students.
</P>
<P>
   Under his stewardship the Sleep Disorders Laboratory grew into a
top-ranking center not just for research but for the diagnosis and
treatment of unusual sleepiness, insomnia and related conditions.
It also became a training ground for specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Aldrich grew up in Chicago where he developed an
interest in the field as a high school laboratory assistant to a
leading researcher of sleep deprivation, Dr. Allan Rechtschaffen,
at the University of Chicago. He continued to work in his mentor's
laboratory between semesters at Swarthmore College, from which he
graduated in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   While attending medical school at the University of Virginia he
became familiar with the psychiatric aspects of sleep disorders
when he spent a period with an expert in Edinburgh. He received his
medical degree in 1980 and trained in neurology at the University
of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Aldrich is survived by his wife, Dr. Leslie Aldrich; their three
children, Brian, Matthew and Jennifer; his parents, Dr. C. Knight
and Julie Aldrich of Charlottesville, Va.; two brothers, Robert, of
Washington, and Dr. Thomas, of Pelham, N.Y.; and a sister, Carol
Barkin of Hastings-on-Hudson, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
