u a BC-OBIT-CAMPBELL-NYT &LR;      07-22 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CAMPBELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN CAMPBELL, 88, EXPERT ON U.S. FOREIGN POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   By ERIC PACE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Coert Campbell, a former member of the State Department's
policy planning council and director of political studies at the
Council on Foreign Relations, died July 16 at his home in Cohasset,
Mass. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, a political scientist, wrote extensively on the Middle
East and U.S. foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   He was a consultant and adviser to the State Department from
1963 to 1980 and a member of its policy planning council in 1967
while the Arab-Israeli war was going on and in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s he also served on an advisory panel for the State
Department's Bureau of Near East and South Asian Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   His earlier State Department posts included specialist in
Eastern Europe from 1942 to 1946. He was officer in charge of
Balkan affairs and a member of the policy planning staff from 1949
to 1955.
</P>
<P>
   In his 27 years as a senior staff member of the Manhattan-based
Council on Foreign Relations, he drew on his firsthand experience
in making policy to provide analyses of world affairs. He was the
council's director of political studies from 1955 to 1962, senior
research fellow from 1962 to 1978 and director of studies from 1977
until 1978, when he retired.
</P>
<P>
   His writings on the Middle East include the books ``The West and
the Middle East'' (1972), written with Helen Caruso, and ``Defense
of the Middle East'' (1958).
</P>
<P>
   In a 1982 essay on the Middle East, he wrote, ``Every new
administration needs time to find its footing in foreign affairs,
especially in a complex and changing area like the Middle East, and
the Reagan team has taken as much or more time than its
predecessors.'' He added philosophically, ``Earlier
administrations, after all, broke their heads on these same
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   He was on the board of governors of the Middle East Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Among his writings on Eastern Europe are the books ``American
Foreign Policy Toward Communist Eastern Europe'' (1965, Books on
Demand) and ``Tito's Separate Road'' (1967). He won an award in
1980, for contributing to Slavic studies, from the American
Association for the Advancement of Slavic Studies.
</P>
<P>
   A native New Yorker, he received from a bachelor's degree, a
master's degree and a doctorate, all from Harvard. His doctoral
dissertation was on Romania.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Mary, whom he married in 1936; two
sons, Allan R., of Auburndale, Mass., and A. Bruce, of Denver; and
three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
