<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-WEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS HELPING TO MAKE THE NEW A . L. WEST THE DOMINANT DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (With BBO-NOTEBOOK)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because the New York Yankees have been in first place since the
All-Star game, they have not been in the wild-card race. But they
have not been so far in first place that they have not had to
notice the wild-card race. And when they look at the wild-card
race, what do they see? A couple of American League West teams as
close to them as their own breaths.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the West is challenging the East as the dominant
division in the league. The Yankees, the Toronto Blue Jays and the
Boston Red Sox? They have nothing on the Seattle Mariners, the
Anaheim Angels and the Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday's games, the West trio was a collective 6 1/2
games ahead of the East trio. The second-place Angels, the AL Wild
Card leader, were only 3 percentage points shy of the first-place
Yankees and the third-place Athletics were a game behind. More than
two months remain in the season, but before the wild-card race is
over, the Yankees could find out how well they had it when they had
huge division leads and did not have to pay attention to the teams
fighting for the fourth playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Stoneman, for one, is not surprised at the developments in
the new West. He is the first-year general manager of the Angels, a
team that has extricated itself from the muck engendered by a
dysfunctional family and become a playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody looked at the division with skepticism,'' said
Stoneman, not only the leader of a division contender but also a
cheerleader for the division. ``Everybody but those of us in the
American League West. I don't think this is a surprise. It's
happening because there are some good clubs out here. If it hadn't
been for some injuries, Texas might be right with us and they're
close.''
</P>
<P>
   And then Stoneman added, ``It's possible and maybe even likely
that the wild-card club will come out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   What a shock that would be to the East, especially if the
Yankees should slip out of first and join the ``fourth-division''
race.
</P>
<P>
   It was mid to late-May when the Angels and the Athletics had
losing records. But in nine weeks before Saturday, the Angels had a
34-23 record (.596, translating to 96 victories for a whole season)
and in nearly eight weeks leading to Saturday, the Athletics had
compiled a 26-18 record (.591, or 95 season victories).
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, in comparison, had a 28-32 record since May 10, a
.467 winning percentage that would produce 75 victories for the
entire season.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics have surprised no one because they served notice
last season that they were ready to play for the playoffs. The
Angels, on the other hand, began the season as an unknown. They had
a collection of good young players, but the team was devastated by
internal turmoil last season and no one knew if they would suffer a
lasting effect.
</P>
<P>
   It is now obvious they have not.
</P>
<P>
   With Mike Scioscia, the new manager, providing a calming
presence, the Angels' young players have performed so well that
Stoneman credits them with providing the foundation for the team's
good play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we didn't know,'' he said, ``was how comfortable
would some of the younger guys be, most particularly our young
starting pitchers and our catcher and our second baseman. How would
they perform and how comfortable would they be at this level for
the season? I think we're finding out to our delight that they
belong here.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Kennedy, acquired with Kent Bottenfield in the Jim Edmonds
trade, has been the second baseman all season, playing in all but
three games. Bengie Molina has been the primary catcher. Brian
Cooper, Seth Etherton and Jarrod Washburn make up three-fifths of
the active starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, Molina, Cooper and Etherton are rookies, Washburn not
far removed from rookie status. The three pitchers began the season
in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the members of the team who are more experienced
than that group but still young: Darin Erstad, Troy Glaus, Garret
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who'da thunk it _ 26 home runs at the break?'' Stoneman said,
discussing Anderson's career-high contribution. Who could have
anticipated Erstad's 158-hit contribution entering Saturday's
games, giving him 28 more hits than the next most prolific hitter?
</P>
<P>
   But third baseman Glaus, at 23 the youngest regular in the
lineup, had a .610 slugging percentage, best on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Did someone mention Edmonds?
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew all winter and almost all spring that four outfielders
didn't fit into three positions,'' said Stoneman, who also had
Anderson, Erstad and Tim Salmon. ``All four were quality
outfielders. Something was going to give here. It helped us fill
second base and stabilize our starting pitching, particularly at
the start of the year. It gave us a little bit of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield (6-8), as it developed, has the only losing record
among the starting pitchers. But that's the beauty of the
development of the young Angels, to have Washburn at 6-2, Etherton
5-1 and Cooper 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just single out the young guys,'' Stoneman said,
``but they've been the surprise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
