u s BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      07-22 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARKIN DISCONNECTED; ANDERSON-TYPE PLAYER; UNDERCUTTING ROBINSON
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBA-WEST)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a long time, callers to the Cincinnati Reds offices were
greeted by a recording: ``Hi, this is Barry Larkin. Thanks for
calling the Cincinnati Reds. It's always nice to hear from a fan.''
</P>
<P>
   A caller mentioned to Jim Bowden, the Reds' general manager,
Friday afternoon that if he traded the team's shortstop, the Reds
would have to change the greeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably should do that anyway,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours later the voice of an anonymous woman had replaced
Larkin. ``Thank you for calling the Cincinnati Reds,'' she said.
She did not announce that the Reds had traded her predecessor to
the Mets, contingent on his approving the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do what Barry wants,'' Bowden had said, without
disclosing the trade. ``We have a lot of respect for what he's done
for us so if he feels it's in his best interests to be traded now,
we'll trade him. If he wants to finish the year with the Reds,
he'll finish the year with the Reds.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said he had met on July 8 with Larkin, who has spent his
entire 14-year career with the Reds. ``He said he wanted to be
signed or be traded,'' Bowden said. ``He wanted it behind him. He
didn't want all the negativity. If we can't pay him the $27.9
million he wants _ and it's not negotiable _ and we can't sign him,
we should trade him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden sounded as sad as he was deliriously delighted when he
acquired Ken Griffey Jr. last February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always envisioned him finishing his career with the Reds,''
the general manager said, ``have his last at-bat with the Reds,
take his jersey off and carry it to left field and put it on the
wall. But things have changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson-Type Player
</P>
<P>
   Sparky Anderson, who goes into the Hall of Fame Sunday, would
have loved Shane Halter. The former Cincinnati and Detroit manager
loved to use players at different positions _ the ubiquitous Tony
Phillips was a favorite _ and Halter would have been perfect to
have on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Halter is on the Tigers' bench now, that is, he is there when he
is not playing one of the positions on the field. This season he
has played all but the one on the mound, and he has started at all
of the others except the one behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Halter, 30, with three years in the major leagues, has started
five games at first base, one game at second, six at shortstop, 11
at third, one each in left field and right and three in center. He
also caught one inning in a July 4 game against Tampa Bay. Before
the season is over, maybe he will have an opportunity to match his
1998 experience _ he pitched an inning, a scoreless inning, for
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Hocking of Minnesota has not started at all of the
positions Halter has, but he has made more starts: 14 at second,
seven at short, eight at third, eight in left, seven in center, six
in right, a total of 50 to Halter's 28. Terry Shumpert of Colorado
has started 32 games at six positions: one at first, nine at
second, two at short, six at third, 13 in left and one as
designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Maxwell, a Twins rookie, has become a junior Hocking,
startig 23 games at four different positions: nine at second, one
at short, 12 at third, one in right.
</P>
<P>
   Joe McEwing has not played as much with the Mets as he did with
St. Louis last season (128 starts at five different positions), but
he has displayed his versatility: three starts each at second and
third, six in left, 10 in center.
</P>
<P>
   Undercutting Robinson
</P>
<P>
   Frank Robinson has been labeled the dean of discipline, but it
is not likely that he will hold the position beyond this season if
Paul Beeston, baseball's chief operating officer, continues to
slice his sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The latest reduced suspension was for Pete Vuckovich,
Pittsburgh's pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   When Leonard Coleman was National League president, he fined
Vuckovich for his choice of vulgar phrases in arguments with
umpires. Last month the coach also bumped umpire John Hirschbeck in
an argument over a balk call. Robinson suspended him for three
games; Beeston lowered it to two.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding the discipline for Carl Everett after he twice
bumped umpire Ron Kulpa, Robinson was apparently leaning toward a
longer sentence than the 10 games he issued, 12 games perhaps. But
baseball lawyers urged him to make the suspension no longer than 10
games. If Beeston reduces this one on appeal, it could nudge
Robinson closer to suspending his position.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 1457EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
