<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9948 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-OLY-RAINES-KELLY-     07-22 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-OLY-RAINES-KELLY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR KELLY AND RAINES, OLYMPIC DREAMS BEGIN FAR FROM THE MAJORS
</HEADLINE>
  By IRA BERKOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEWATER, N.J. _ Uncustomarily, the two former New York
Yankees _ both, it happens, coming from Florida _ paid for their
own flights, dug into their own pockets for rental cars and lugged
their own luggage to the hotel in order to play in four games for,
yes, the Somerset Patriots, an independent team ensconced in the
middle of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Both Tim Raines, the outfielder, and Pat Kelly, the second
baseman, had been cut from the Yankees and the Angels,
respectively, in spring training and, after illness and injuries,
it appeared that the sun had sunk on their playing careers.
</P>
<P>
   Raines, at 40 and a veteran of 21 major league seasons with four
teams, was sitting home in Lake Mary, Fla., organizing the opening
in late summer of the Tim Raines Baseball School in nearby Sanford,
when he received a phone call in June from Bob Watson, the former
Yankees general manager and now chairman of the selection committee
for the U.S. Olympic baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim,'' Watson said, ``do you think you can still play?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Why, yes,'' replied Raines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, do you want to play?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where?''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Bridgewater.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bridgewater!''
</P>
<P>
   ``With hopes of making the Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' said Raines.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, in Tampa, had received a similar call from Watson, while
at home with his wife, Rebecca, who had given birth on March 31 to
their first child, Charlotte. ``I was just home playing dad when
Bob called,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, at 32 and primarily a fringe nine-year major league
player with four teams, had retired from baseball after a last
attempt with the Angels last spring, and after a third operation on
his right shoulder, the one he uses to throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob knew that Rebecca is from Australia, and that her family
still lives in Adelaide,'' Kelly said. ``And since the Olympics are
in Sydney this year, he thought I might have a special interest in
trying out for the team and going there.'' He laughed, recalling
this. ``When I told Rebecca, she said, `Get that arm going!'''
</P>
<P>
   So here he was, before the game last Tuesday evening, in the
dugout and wearing the pinstripes of the Somerset Patriots. And
Raines, a seven-time All-Star, was nearby. Each was hoping to
impress the selection committee, to show not only that they have
retained a semblance of their hitting and fielding skills, but that
they were truly dedicated to contributing to the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if I had to come here to do that,'' Raines said, ``I
thought it would be worth the try. What an opportunity _ to have a
chance at an Olympic gold medal, to go along with my World Series
rings. The Olympics were always a dream for me, but making the
major leagues was a bigger dream. And I achieved that. And the
Olympics were always held during the baseball season, and they were
always for amateurs, so there was no chance for me. Now there is.
Now everything has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said, ``To be wearing the `USA' across your chest, to be
representing your country, is an honor. I thought my shoulder would
hold up, and so I wanted to give myself a shot at making the team.
And it's my last chance to play in an organized setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Some former big leaguers were not so enthusiastic about having
to audition for the Olympic team. Wade Boggs, Jimmy Key and Chili
Davis apparently believed that their resumes were enough to warrant
consideration for a spot on the team. They weren't. Terry
Steinbach, the catcher, is the only other former major leaguer with
legitimate Olympic aspirations. He is playing in an independent
league in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday evening, Watson himself was in the stands at
Somerset Baseball Park to observe the two former Yankees, and give
himself a better idea of whom to recommend to the selection
committee. What Watson saw was a somewhat chubbier-than-normal
Raines and a still youthful-looking Kelly, both brimming with
enthusiasm. They were playing against good competition _ most of
the players in the league have had at least some Triple-A
experience, and some of them have played in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no hometown beer league,'' said Sparky Lyle, the
former Yankees pitcher and manager of the Patriots who, at 56,
retains his handlebar mustache, though it is now mostly white.
``Some are young and were on the bubble of making it from college
to signing with a major league organization, and some are older and
at the end of their rope. But all these guys can play.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the four games would be a legitimate test for both
Raines and Kelly, both of whom were coming back from physical
problems. Last season, Raines, while playing for Oakland, had
contracted lupus, a disease that attacks the body's immune system.
The stocky, 5-foot 8-inch Raines had lost 15 pounds and a lot of
strength, going down to 170, but has recovered and put back those
15 pounds, plus perhaps another 20. The Yankees gave him another
look in the spring, but he broke his toe, and that ended his
chances.
</P>
<P>
   Both Raines and Kelly had worked out on their own before coming
to New Jersey. ``But hitting off a tee and running sprints,''
Raines said, ``isn't the same thing as live competition.''
</P>
<P>
   In their first three games, all against the Bridgeport Bluefish,
Raines and Kelly had traded off being the designated hitter, as
well as serving time in the field. Each was playing his first game
in four months. Raines had two hits in eight tries with one run
batted in _ one of his hits came on an infield roller that the
one-time base-stealing ace beat out, though he appeared winded from
the sprint. Kelly was 2 for 9, with one run batted in as well. Each
had performed adequately at his position in the field.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when guys retire, they shut down,'' said Watson,
before last Thursday's game against the Atlantic City Surf. ``And
both Raines and Kelly retired. I want to see what their enthusiasm
is, how they set up in the field _ if they're in the game _ and how
they run and field and hit. I want to see what their bat speed is
like, if they've knocked some of the rust off. Right now, there are
about 70 candidates for the 24 positions on the Olympic team, plus
six alternates. For Tim and Pat, their credentials speak for
themselves. But they still have to be better than someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   In last Thursday's game, with Watson watching, Raines had two
hits in three at-bats, with a double off the center-field fence
that missed being a homer by about a foot. Kelly also went 2 for 3
_ two singles _ and threw well but made an error when the ball
popped out of his glove on a tag play at second.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Watson said he was impressed with Raines and Kelly. ``I
like what I've seen,'' he said. ``I like their body language. They
took up my challenge to play in competition. I feel positive about
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Raines, who thinks he may also have a few more major league
seasons left, and Kelly, who knows he doesn't, understand that even
if they make the Olympic team, they may not even be starting
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team will be mostly Triple- and Double-A All-Stars,'' said
Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   In the two previous Olympics in which baseball was a medal
sport, the United States team consisted only of amateurs and ended
up with one bronze medal to show for its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the selection committee may be looking for guys like
Tim and me for experience, guys who've been in pressure situations
_ like the playoffs and World Series,'' added Kelly. ``If we can
work with the younger guys, and maybe even just be there for
important pinch-hitting, that'll be fine with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Raines agreed. ``If I'm not selected, I won't feel snubbed,'' he
said. ``If it's the end of the road, it's the end of the road.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
