u f BC-DAYTRADING0723-COX     07-22 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTRADING0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Day trading phenomenon hangs on despite regulators' concerns
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Day trading has not gone away.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two years after regulators began investigating the
industry, and one year after the killing of nine people at two
Atlanta firms heightened attention on the business, individuals
continue to try their hand at day trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in an era where people come in and try to learn,
and then move on to something else,'' said John Berner, a regular
at InstaTrade and Pro Trader Securities in Atlanta. Berner, a
former stockbroker, has been day trading for about two-and-a-half
years. He also trades, not necessarily on a day-trading basis, for
a hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear how many other people are day trading. But
apparently there is enough interest to keep a half-dozen firms in
business in Atlanta. That's about the same number Georgia counted
last year following the killings by Mark Barton, a money-losing day
trader.
</P>
<P>
   If estimates are correct, day trading still occupies a small
niche, based on the number of people involved. A year ago, the
Electronic Traders Association, which represents day trading firms,
estimated 4,000 to 5,000 people were active. In February, the
Securities and Exchange Commission put the number at fewer than
7,000.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, there are estimates that almost 78 million
Americans were invested in stocks directly or through mutual funds
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The potential influence of day traders exceeds their numbers,
however, because of their heavy trading. The SEC estimated in
February that day traders may account for 15 percent of the
Nasdaq's daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   According to Momentum Securities, its 24 offices _ including one
in Atlanta _ produced an average of 93,203 trades a day in the
first quarter and total trading volume of nearly 1.8 billion shares
over the three months. Trading picked up with the market's
volatility in the second quarter, with Momentum Securities
reporting 112,149 trades on an average day and total volume of 2.08
billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   Trading is not investing, as regulators point out. And as long
ago as November 1998, they were cautioning individuals about it.
``For the typical retail investor, day trading isn't investing,
it's gambling,'' said Philip Feigin, at the time executive director
of the North American Securities Administrators Association.
</P>
<P>
   Day traders buy and sell stocks quickly, sometimes holding onto
them only seconds, in hopes of profiting from small price changes.
They commonly operate on borrowed money.
</P>
<P>
   Day trading firms offer customers access to real time stock
quotes, like professional traders on Wall Street see.
</P>
<P>
   What put securities regulators and the industry at odds were the
former's concerns that customers had not been adequately warned
about the risky nature of day trading. Regulators also felt some
advertising included exaggerated claims about the chances of making
money. The lending practices of some firms, as well as the
arranging of loans between customers, also became issues.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the SEC approved two rules aimed at the industry. One
would put the onus on firms to determine if day trading is
appropriate for potential customers. The other would mandate a
specific warning about the financial risk.
</P>
<P>
   Last week also brought additional publicity in the form of more
regulatory complaints. NASD Regulation, which oversees brokerages
and brokers, charged All-Tech Direct and some company officers with
violating National Association of Securities Dealers' rules.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, NASD Regulation charged that All-Tech
Direct, based in Montvale, N.J., and Chairman Harvey Houtkin ``made
misleading, exaggerated, and unsupported statements in a number of
print and radio'' ads.
</P>
<P>
   A complaint alleging different rule violations was filed against
Stock USA, based in San Diego. Both firms, which have offices in
Atlanta, said they would contest the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a bill was introduced in the Georgia Legislature that
contained language similar to that of the day trading rules
approved by the SEC. The bill did not become law, but the Georgia
Secretary of State's office expects it to be introduced again in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Less clear is the state of Georgia's continuing investigation
into day trading. Robert Terry, the state's top securities
regulator, declined to comment. But the state is more likely to be
concentrating on scrutiny of day trading as it affects individual
trading accounts than focusing on a broad-brush investigation that
would duplicate the efforts of national regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
