<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9951 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DIGITAL-MUSIC0723-COX     07-22 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-MUSIC0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Music industry on the defensive
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Digital music is one of the Internet's final frontiers
_ but not for long.
</P>
<P>
   Many industry watchers say music lovers will be able to buy
music online or download digital music _ legally _ from online or
at the local music store before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   However, that can't happen until the music recording industry
embraces the Internet and agrees to distribute music via digital
download.
</P>
<P>
   The recording industry is adamantly resisting that possibility,
filing lawsuits and mounting marketing campaigns to protect its
ownership of the music. Meanwhile, millions of young people are
happily, and illegally, using simple technology to download
practically any music they desire, free.
</P>
<P>
   That pending, but as yet unconsummated, shotgun marriage of
music and technology will be at the center of debate at Jupiter
Communications' annual Plug-In Conference in New York Monday and
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   There, musicians' representives and recording industry insiders
will come face-to-face with the Internet mavens who have figured
out how to make their products widely available using the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Between the two sides will be scores of new companies that have
grown up around products to help users more easily download music
using their computers and the Internet, as well as send the
appropriate nickels back to the recording companies and artists.
They are dying to do business with both sides but can't do anything
until the two sides agree to wed. Interestingly, no more than a
half dozen such companies exhibited at last year's digital download
conference. This year close to 100 companies will show their wares.
</P>
<P>
   The rush to market, or at least the desire by the Internet
industry to rush to market, is fueled by the amazing success of
Napster (www.napster.com), an extremely popular and completely
illegal _ according to the recording industry _ digital music
file-sharing system.
</P>
<P>
   Napster said last week its community of users now exceeds 20
million people _ and has doubled since the end of April. Not bad
for a site that launched just over a year ago and has done
virtually no marketing. That was about the time several
universities began banning Napster, saying the number of downloads
was clogging their computer networks. The Recording Industry
Association of America, the trade group that represents the major
recording companies, sued Napster, claiming the California-based
company is breaking the law by offering pirated music for free. A
federal judge will decide this week if Napster's technology is
illegal and could temporarily shut down the site.
</P>
<P>
   Despite additional negative publicity from the RIAA lawsuit and
bands like Metallica, and the fact that it violates nearly every
legal definition of ``fair use,'' Napster continues to grow and
increase in popularity and the number of downloads.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because people love it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are not going to stop using Napster because an
artist tells them to,'' says Adam Sinnreich, a music analyst at
Jupiter. ``They'll go through legitimate channels once they're more
fun, more convenient and offer more value than illegitimate
channels.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hardie, a former analyst with Forrester Research who now
heads up his own music distribution company called MusicTeller
(www.musicteller.com), says the record companies are missing a huge
opportunity to distribute music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did I go to get a copy of Bruce Springsteen's `41
Shots?' I found it on Napster. That's a disgrace,'' he says. ``The
record companies should have been right there with the song. People
want it and are willing to pay for it. The longer the record
companies hold out, the more opportunities they miss to reach out
to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner President Richard Parsons _ one of the keynote
speakers at the Plug-In conference _ knows this is a critical time
for the music industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't just about a bunch of kids stealing music,'' he
told the Los Angeles Times. ``It's about an assault on everything
that constitutes the cultural expression of our society. If we fail
to protect and preserve our intellectual property system, the
culture will atrophy. And corporations won't be the only ones hurt.
Artists will have no incentive to create. Worst-case scenario: The
country will end up in a sort of cultural Dark Ages.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with Parsons' dire scenario, neither Time Warner nor
any of the major recording companies has been able to come up with
anything that will provide a compelling alternative to Napster's
easy and quick file-swapping technology.
</P>
<P>
   Instead they have continued to pursue legal avenues to force
Napster and MP3.com to cease and desist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Napster's popularity emphasizes the music industry's failure
thus far to satisfy online consumer demands,'' says Stacey Herron,
another Jupiter analyst. ``The controversy surrounding this type of
networked music-sharing community proves that artists and labels
continue to feel threatened by online music.''
</P>
<P>
   Napster has captured the hearts of millions and the wrath of the
music industry with a very simple file-sharing technology.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the illegitimate Napster is the best game in town.
</P>
<P>
   Type in the name of nearly any artist you can think of from Bob
Dylan to the Backstreet Boys, and hundreds of songs scroll down the
computer screen, all available for download _ every single one of
them free.
</P>
<P>
   Metallica has been the most vocal artist opponent of Napster and
has staged elaborate publicity stunts asking Napster to take their
songs off its site. Several other artists have also requested
payment from Napster.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Herron says the popularity of Napster should be a clear
sign to the music industry that there is a large audience for
legitimate online music sales. ``Despite minimal marketing efforts
and an imperfect technology, Napster has amassed a large amount of
content and high traffic levels in just a short time,'' she said in
recent report. ``Paired with retail offerings, artist information,
tour dates, artist participation, community features such as
instant messaging, and other supplemental content, a networked
music-sharinto the users' online musicbank accounts, where they can
download the songs or just play them on their PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday the company signed an agreement with Virgin
Megastores but won't launch the service until other music
retailers, including online retailers like Amazon.com and CDNow,
are on board and the major labels agree to let the music be
delivered digitally to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are never going to stop shopping,'' Hardie says. His
company, ETC Music, plans to introduce a product called MusicTeller
that will also use ATM-like kiosks to deliver music to the growing
number of portable digital music players.
</P>
<P>
   Hardie also says the sheer size of the $40 billion music
industry and its decades-old investment in music manufacturing and
distribution channels is part of the reason for its reluctance to
go digital.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody at the top executive levels of these companies
who are Net guys,'' he says. ``There are some pretty smart people
at most of the labels, but they don't understand what the Internet
can do for their businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
