u s BC-CYC-ARMSTRONG-NYT     07-22 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-ARMSTRONG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG NEARS SUPERSTARDOM ALONGSIDE JORDAN, WOODS AND GRETZKY 
</HEADLINE>
 (With CYC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROYES, France _ The American Embassy in Paris phoned officials
of the U.S. Postal Service bicycle team a few days ago to ask when
it would be convenient on Sunday for Lance Armstrong to receive
another congratulatory call from President Clinton. The two last
spoke on the phone a year ago, hours after Armstrong won his first
Tour de France. A few months after that, the rider visited the
White House to give the president a bicycle and a helmet.
</P>
<P>
   That is the standard star treatment, as were Armstrong's
appearance on the David Letterman show and his visit to the New
York Stock Exchange, where he became the second athlete residing in
Austin, Texas, to ring the opening bell. (Ricky Williams, the
former University of Texas running back, was the first after he won
the Heisman Trophy in 1998.)
</P>
<P>
   So what awaits the Tour de France's leader and certain winner
when he visits New York again on a publicity blitz Tuesday? A
ticker-tape parade? A speech to a joint session of Congress later
in the day? The stakes have changed. Nearing a second consecutive
victory in the world's greatest bicycle race, Armstrong appears to
be rising from what his agent calls ``the clutter'' of mere stars
to superstardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``That level has less to do about money, annual endorsement
fees, than becoming a household name,'' the agent, Bill Stapleton,
said. ``That level is Michael Jordan, Tiger Woods, Wayne Gretzky.
Lance is joining them.''
</P>
<P>
   At least publicly, Armstrong himself scoffs at such talk.
Interviewed from an adjoining car as he rolled through the German
countryside Friday morning on a training ride before a long
individual time trial, he said with a laugh, ``I'm not a superstar,
I'm a regular guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Whichever, he was relaxed and friendly, bantering at 40
kilometers an hour (25 mph) as he worked up a sweat and readied his
legs for his 58.5-kilometer race (about 36 miles) against the clock
four hours later. ``A regular guy,'' he repeated, ``and I'll show
'em what a regular guy can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is the way Jordan, Woods and Gretzky talk the talk,
too. Discussing those superstars, Stapleton said that Armstrong has
been ``in the tier right below them'' with endorsements in the
range of $5 million to $7.5 million a year, a realm that he
explained was occupied by the top 20 to 25 athletes. To an agent,
especially a witty one with a hot property, that is ``relative
obscurity'' in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, however, Armstrong vaulted into superstardom with his
first victory, three years after he learned he had spreading
testicular cancer and had to undergo three months of chemotherapy.
Bicycle racing is a major sport here, usually second only to
soccer, and the winner of the Tour de France is widely honored.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Burgh, a vacationing Dutchman standing by the side of the
Tour's road in Switzerland this week to cheer the riders, summed up
the European reaction to Armstrong: ``He's a great hero. What he's
done touches the imagination. The cancer, that too, but really
because he won the Tour and now he's winning it again.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, bicycle racing remains a niche sport and
the magnitude of Armstrong's comeback seems not to have taken hold
until this 87th Tour de France started July 1. The Texan captured
the overall leader's yellow jersey 10 days later and has held it
securely ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much bigger than last year,'' Jim Ochowicz, Armstrong's
close friend and his former coach with the defunct Motorola team,
said of Tour coverage in the states, ``and so is Lance. He's in the
Jordan-Gretzky class now.'' Ochowicz credited Armstrong's
autobiography, ``It's More Than the Bike,'' published this spring
and still high on the best-seller lists, with introducing him to a
large audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's become known as a great American hero, not just a great
American athlete,'' Stapleton said with an agent's hyperbole.
``It's a sport most Americans basically don't understand, so his
marketing focuses on the depth of what he's been through.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of the Tour is its linear time element. A golf
tournament lasts four days. The Super Bowl, even with all the
hoopla, is six hours. The Tour goes on for three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen major companies have signed Armstrong to
endorsement contracts, including Nike, Bristol-Myers Squibb, Yahoo
and Visa. Many of their executives are part of the entourage at the
Tour, and more are arriving daily before the finish in Paris on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   John Kouten, associate director of public affairs for
Bristol-Myers Squibb, flew in this week with nine cancer survivors
from a handful of countries. They will meet with Armstrong, who
heads a cancer foundation in his name, and sign with him the
Charter of Paris Against Cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance is going to reach a much broader audience,'' Kouten
said. ``Many more people in the United States are going to know his
name now with a second victory. Last year, some folks might have
thought that his victory was a fluke. Now he had a whole other year
to relapse from his cancer and he didn't. That's a very encouraging
message.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike has had Armstrong, 28, under contract for a half-dozen
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance is very important to our brand and I think he's becoming
more important,'' said Scott MacEachern, emerging sports marketing
director for Nike. ``He is already a big story. If Lance is
fortunate enough to win this Tour, I think he will be a very big
story going into the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong is not overly enthusiastic about leaving his wife and
infant son to go to the Olympic Games in Sydney, Australia, in
September, noting that he has participated in the Games twice
before, in Barcelona, Spain, in 1992 as an amateur and Atlanta in
1996 as a professional.
</P>
<P>
   Then why is he going? ``Go ask Bill Stapleton,'' he replied
jovially.
</P>
<P>
   For a superstar, it's always business before pleasure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 1522EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
