<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CYC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NY     07-22 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN WINS 20TH STAGE, BUT ARMSTRONG'S LEAD IS SOLID 
</HEADLINE>
 (With CYC-ARMSTRONG) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROYES, France _ The star German sprinter Erik Zabel finally
crossed the finish line first in the Tour de France on Saturday,
ending three years without a victory (three years and nine days,
but who's counting besides him?). ``Whew,'' Zabel said with a broad
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Zabel, who races for the Telekom team, has registered many
successes since his last of seven Tour victories. Among them are
triumphs in the esteemed Milan-San Remo classic in March, which he
has won three times, and in the Amstel Gold Race classic in May, as
well as the overall lead this year in the World Cup series of
one-day races.
</P>
<P>
   Until this 20th of 21 stages Saturday, he had 15 victories this
year, a big number, but none of them in the Tour since July 13,
1997. After that he had 10 second places in the Tour, including two
this year, and five third places, including three this year.
</P>
<P>
   Zabel won with a fine display of teamwork, getting strong
leadouts from two teammates in the final few hundred meters and
then powering his way to victory by half a bicycle wheel over
Robbie McEwen, an Australian with Farm Frites, and Jeroen
Blijlevens, a Dutchman with Polti. Bumped by another rider in the
stretch, Blijlevens could only pound his handlebar once in
frustration as he finished.
</P>
<P>
   Zabel was timed in 6 hours 14 minutes 13 seconds for the
158-mile (254.5-kilometer) ride from Belfort in eastern France to
Troyes. Lance Armstrong maintained his unassailable overall lead of
6:02 over Zabel's teammate, Jan Ullrich.
</P>
<P>
   The length of this stage, one day before the finale in Paris,
was denounced by many riders, who noted that this was the third
stage over 150 miles in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insane,'' Frankie Andreu said beforehand. He finished in 111th
place, 2:43 behind the winner, but was untroubled.
</P>
<P>
   Andreu did not ride for high placing Saturday nor in the final
individual time trial on Friday nor in the two breakaways he joined
as the race made its way to the Pyrenees and Alps. That's not his
job; he needs to save himself to work for Armstrong, the leader of
their U.S. Postal Service team.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to help the team,'' Andreu, 33, explained before the
stage. ``We're here to get the yellow jersey, and I'm here to
protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Andreu is widely known as one of the most selfless and most
durable team workers in the sport. When the race finishes on
Sunday, Andreu will have completed his ninth Tour de France in nine
appearances. Among the 128 riders left of the 177 who set out July
1, few can match his record.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little bit is determination and just suffering through the
hard parts,'' he said. ``A lot of it is luck, being able to stay
out of crashes. You can't always control where you are, and
sometimes things just happen.''
</P>
<P>
   When they do, he remounts and keeps going.
</P>
<P>
   As a team worker, Andreu gets few chances to ride for individual
victory because he must remain near Armstrong, who has no need to
contest a final sprint and no chance to jump into a mass breakaway.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Armstrong wore the leader's yellow jersey, Andreu
was occupied by his duties of riding ahead of Armstrong and
sheltering him from the wind or offering his wheel if the leader
had a flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first week, when Lance didn't have the jersey, our job
was to keep him in the front and to keep him as rested as
possible,'' Andreu said. Leaders try to stay at the front to avoid
sudden attacks and mass crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a hard Tour,'' Andreu said, ``partly because of
the weather. It was so windy the first week, and that meant a lot
of work to keep Lance in the front. And then, when he took the
jersey'' _ on the 10th day _ ``there's a lot of energy that you
don't realize you're expending trying to stay in the front and
battle the wind. You're paying the price the last week.''
</P>
<P>
   That price is weariness. ``It's not the wind now,'' Andreu said
Friday. ``Now it's the legs. Now it's plain fatigue. I'm tired.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked hard in the mountains, where he does not shine. At 6
foot 2 and 180 pounds, Andreu is too big to climb the Pyrenees and
Alps easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to work before the climbs,'' he said, ``and then the
first part of the climbs. I have to stay in the front for the first
part of the climb until I blow. Then I've just got to suffer like
mad to stay in the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's got a job and you've got to do what you've got to
do _ save the climbers as long as possible so they can do their
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of jobs, Andreu surprisingly reported that he has not
yet been signed for a fourth year with the Postal Service team and
a 13th year as a professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm unemployed right now,'' he said. ``So I'm looking. I'm
still talking with Postal Service, and I've got to talk with some
other teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Wherever he winds up, he agreed, if he returns to the Tour de
France next year, he expects to work hard for his leader and
attempt to stretch his own record of finishing the race. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
