<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-CONVENTION-NYT     07-22 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CONVENTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WRITING CONVENTION SCRIPT, DEMOCRATS SEARCH FOR RIGHT ROLE FOR
CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Democrats unveiled details Saturday for their
August convention intended to gently disengage Vice President Al
Gore from President Clinton and establish him as an independent
leader while still celebrating the Clinton policies that have
helped create the longest economic boom in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   Over four days, from Aug. 14 to 17, the convention will build
gradually from heralding Clinton's record and policies to the
highlights of Gore's biography to a climax on Thursday, when Gore
will be nominated as his party's standard-bearer.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing lessons from the 1988 Republican convention, the
Democrats will have Clinton and Gore make a joint appearance
somewhere outside the convention location in Los Angeles to show a
changing of the party's guard.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, President Reagan symbolically passed the torch of
leadership to Vice President George Bush in a brief ceremony at an
Air Force Base near the Republican convention in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the 1988 event, the Democrats said Clinton's
appearance would be substantive and extensive. Though aides want to
use the convention to move Gore out of the president's shadow,
Clinton remains popular with the loyal Democrats and the Gore
campaign does not want to appear to be shunting him to the side.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton would also address the convention in prime time on the
opening day, Monday, Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly our having the president speak on Monday and then
appear with the vice president shows how proud we are of the
success of this administration and how we will tout that success,''
said Chris Lehane, a spokesman for Gore. ``This event won't be a
photo-op. It will be real substance.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention's overall themes, ``Progress and Prosperity'' and
``People, not the Powerful,'' have been drawn from the oratory of
Gore's recent campaign appearances, where he has attacked big oil
and drug companies, and his Republican opponent, Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, saying Bush is beholden to special interests.
</P>
<P>
   The convention will open with a focus on the nation's
prosperity. Besides Clinton, the speakers will include Hillary
Rodham Clinton, who is running for the Senate in New York, and
other prominent female candidates. The evening will also feature
testimonials from people talking about how they have benefited from
the administration's policies.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, under the theme ``You ain't seen nothing yet,'' a
favorite stump line of Gore's, some of the party's most prominent
leaders will talk about the important choices facing the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Prime time speakers will include the Rev. Jesse Jackson and
former Sen. Bill Bradley, who challenged Gore during the primaries.
There will also probably be a keynote address by a speaker yet to
be named.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to evoke images of President Kennedy, who was nominated
in Los Angeles in 1960, the Democrats will also have Carolyn
Kennedy Schlossberg, his daughter, and Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., his brother, speak on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, under the theme, ``The Principled Fighter,'' the
convention will begin focusing more heavily on Gore, using
testimonials and videos to highlight his biography, from his time
as an Army reporter in Vietnam to his work as a newspaper reporter
in Nashville to his years as a congressman and senator from
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president is famous but still not well known,'' said
an adviser to Gore. ``We believe that the more people learn about
him, the more they like him. And I think a lot of the things we
present to people that night will be new.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's running mate will also be nominated that night. Karenna
Gore Schiff, Gore's eldest daughter and one of his closest
advisers, will give one of the nominating speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will spend the first three days of the convention
campaigning around the country. Because the television networks are
not planning to devote much prime time coverage to the convention,
the Gore campaign is planning to use the vice president's
off-convention events to try to pick up additional television
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president will arrive at the convention on Wednesday
night and receive the nomination on Thursday evening. He will be
introduced by his wife, Tipper; his aides said it was possible that
there would be other nominating speeches as well.
</P>
<P>
   After the convention, Gore and his running mate are scheduled to
make a four-day tour of states bordering the Great Lakes and the
Mississippi River, a region where the election seems particularly
close. One plan called for having Gore travel across the Great
Lakes states while his running mate traveled up the Mississippi,
having the two meet somewhere in the Upper Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Republicans, the Democrats are not planning to devote
one night of the convention to making partisan attacks on their
rivals, though they are leaving the door open to criticizing
specific elements of Bush's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Lehane said there may also be some cameo appearances by
Hollywood stars. Barbra Streisand, for one, is scheduled to sing at
a event near the convention center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 1559EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9975 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-G8-CLINTON23-COX     07-22 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-G8-CLINTON23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    G8 SUMMIT FOCUSES ON THIRD WORLD DISEASE, TECHNOLOGY GAP
 &HT;    Moving in (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAGO, Japan _ With most of their economies in decent shape,
leaders of the Group of Eight countries focused their summit talks
Saturday on helping poor countries fight infectious diseases and
get into cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   The G8 members announced a Digital Opportunity Task Force,
dubbed the ``dot force,'' charged with finding ways to bridge the
global digital divide. The group is to report to next year's G8
summit in Italy on possible solutions for individual countries.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, officials said, is that technology will let poor
nations leapfrog obstacles to development, taking advantage of the
information age to improve education and health care.
</P>
<P>
   The G8 members _ the United States, Canada, Britain, Japan,
France, German, Italy and Russia _ also announced new programs and
funding to help prevent the spread of diseases such as AIDS,
tuberculosis and malaria.
</P>
<P>
   Several countries made financial pledges, including $3 billion
by Japan over the next five years. Clinton has requested $4 billion
in the 2001 budget for a vaccine program, research on HIV/AIDS and
international aid for various infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Lael Brainard, Clinton's deputy national economic adviser, said
that while past G8 summits have been more centered on the economic
problems of the member nations, Okinawa ``is shaping up to be the
development summit, with a focus on creating opportunity for the
least-developed.''
</P>
<P>
   However, about 50 non-governmental organizations who came to
Okinawa to monitor the summit were not impressed by either
initiative. They accused the G8 leaders of failing to address the
fundamental problems that cause poverty and disease, and instead
offering only superficial solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're quite angry,'' said Marlene Barrett, a spokesperson for
Jubilee 2000. ``This (digital divide effort) is an empty gesture
which will obviously benefit all of their industries. It's just to
distract attention away from the fact that they failed to cancel
the debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Jubilee 2000 burned a laptop computer on a beach here
in Okinawa to show their disappointment with G8's failure to
fulfill last year's promise to cancel up to $100 billion in Third
World debt.
</P>
<P>
   So far, just nine countries have qualified for debt relief of up
to $15 billion. Jubilee 2000 says debt relief is the first step to
ending the cycle of poverty, since poor countries are spending more
money to pay back debt than on basic needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't eat a laptop,'' said Barrett. ``It's a crisis, it's
an emergency, and it's something that they've failed to deal with
this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicins Sans Frontieres criticized the G8 program on infectious
diseases, saying that merely spending money to treat diseases does
not solve the core problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If part of this money is going to be used to buy expensive
brand-name drugs when we know there are cheaper, generic brands
available, that's public money going to private interests in the
West,'' said spokesperson Ellen 'T Hoen(cq).
</P>
<P>
   She said she was disappointed the G8 leaders did not address
patent issues that would allow, for example, local companies to
produce cheaper versions of pricey AIDS drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just saying, 'this is a serious issue and we're making money
available to deal with it' without giving clear direction on how to
do that is really a missed opportunity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on the digital divide, President Clinton
acknowledged that technology is not the answer to all the problems
of the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet if we fail to ensure that all nations have the opportunity
to participate fully in the network economy and society, we run the
risk that the divide between nations will grow,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night, Clinton addressed U.S. troops and their
families on Okinawa. His speech was rescheduled from Sunday
afternoon to allow him to leave Japan several hours early and
return to the Mideast peace talks late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton gave an upbeat speech lasting less than 10 minutes that
did not directly address the issues that have led Okinawans to
protest the U.S. military presence on their island, which numbers
about 26,000.
</P>
<P>
   Local residents have complained about instances of misbehavior
and crime, including killings, rapes and thefts. The presence of
about 4,000 children fathered out of wedlock by U.S. military
personnel has further strained relations.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton thanked the forces for their work and stated
the need to be good neighbors to their Okinawan hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each one of us has a personal obligation to do everything that
we can to strengthen our friendship and to do nothing to harm it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   For more information:www.g8kyushu-okinawa.go.jp
</P>
<P>
   Julie Chao's e-mail address is juliec(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 1603EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0156 </DOCNO>
