<HEADER>
A9978 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT &LR;      07-22 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPAIN OUSTS UNITED STATES IN DAVIS CUP SEMIFINAL
</HEADLINE>
  By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTANDER, Spain _ It wasn't meant to be, and if John McEnroe
needed more evidence that his dream of captaining the United States
to a Davis Cup on his first try was dying, he got it in the second
game of the fifth set here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It was break point for Spain, already ahead by 1-0 in the set,
but there were Todd Martin and Chris Woodruff, in the middle of the
court, sending Alex Corretja deeper and deeper behind the ad court,
in the corner, almost to the runway leading off the court.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and Woodruff kept hitting overheads. Corretja kept
finding a way to flick them up in the air to get them back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris hit a couple early in the point and I said, `Don't hit
it to Corretja,''' Martin said later. ``Then I got one, the easiest
one and I hit to Corretja.''
</P>
<P>
   And then the ball was back again, from almost an impossible
backhand angle. The Spaniards were back in a point that Juan
Balcells would win with a shanked backhand winner into the open
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of Alex's greatest qualities _ his defensive
skills,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans would recoup that fifth-set break, but the
symbolism of Corretja's athletic returns and sheer refusal to give
up on a point was the story of this Davis Cup semifinal, settled
Saturday by Spain's makeshift doubles team of Corretja and
Balcells, 7-6 (6), 2-6, 6-3, 6-7 (5), 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Having never won the Davis Cup, and without an appearance in the
world group finals since 1976, Spain will play Australia in a
December final as the favorite on the clay court surface that suits
the players' dogged style so well.
</P>
<P>
   This was the match that McEnroe had contemplated playing
himself, and in hindsight it was probably a good idea he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe had considered Saturday to be the best U.S. chance to
win any match here, after Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi pulled out,
citing injury. Earlier in the week, before his players talked him
out of playing, McEnroe had asked: ``Who the hell is Juan
Balcells?''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, he found out, calling Corretja's unheralded partner
``strong as an ox'' and saying he had the ``best 83-mile-an-hour''
serve in tennis.
</P>
<P>
   While neither Spaniard has ever been an accomplished doubles
player, their heavy topspin returns and lightness afoot would have
been even more overwhelming for a 41-year-old, as McEnroe is, than
it was for Martin and Woodruff.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, as it turned out, played a game match but far
more than the fifth set would go home lamenting a first set that
Martin failed to serve out at 5-3, wasting two set points. In the
tiebreaker, they had set point twice more but could not convert.
Particularly frustrating was Martin's choosing not to volley a
Corretja backhand up the line, thinking it was long. The ball
dropped a foot inside the baseline in the doubles alley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Missed opportunities,'' McEnroe said, wearing a Yankees' cap
in his post-match news conference. ``The first set was ours. No way
in the world we should have lost that set.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff, the fifth-match hero of the first round in Zimbabwe,
took the blame, saying he played with a ``little too much fear,''
not going for volleys when Martin served for the set at 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   The United States forced a fifth set by winning a fourth-set
tiebreaker. It went down a break early in the fifth and rallied
back on serve, only to cough up serve and, in effect, the match in
the eighth game.
</P>
<P>
   Martin flubbed two forehand volleys to start the game. Then,
just to make sure he put one in play, he sent a third volley into
Corretja's wheelhouse for a forehand pass down the middle. On the
first break point against Woodruff, Corretja nailed a backhand up
the line, sending the crowd into a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Corretja proceeded to serve out the match at love, with Balcells
reminding McEnroe of who he was again, kissing off the last three
volleys. A wild celebration ensued, with the Spanish players
dancing in a circle and later spraying champagne at the fans in the
front rows.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the result, McEnroe, for the record, had little to
complain about this weekend, with the exception of a hosing down of
the court between the fourth and fifth sets. He later said it had
been agreed to water the court (making it play slower, to the
Spaniards' favor) only after the second set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say we lost the match because they watered
the court,'' he decided.
</P>
<P>
   Or the semifinal, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   His best players didn't come. The draw was not good. His first
year as captain, which he called ``surprising and disappointing,''
was over. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
