<SLUG> BC-NY-BUG-BATTLE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC HEALTH AND PUBLIC RELATIONS IN BATTLE OF BUGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLEASANTVILLE, N.Y. _ West Nile II, the summer sequel, was
preparing to air. Television cameras recorded the trucks waiting to
roll from Westchester County's fire training center, and the
publicist for the mosquito-control company had orchestrated a
demonstration run of a pesticide truck well in time for the 11
o'clock news.
</P>
<P>
   Then, close to midnight Thursday, the driver of a beige pickup
stopped on a dark road and pushed a button. With that, the spraying
was under way. The pump on the back hummed, the truck's yellow
lights flashed and a plume of pesticides fell on Pleasantville.
</P>
<P>
   As a police car led the pesticide truck through sleepy streets,
people reacted like unwitting extras in a science fiction movie.
Drivers rolled up their windows and scooted away. A few residents
clicked on their outside lights as the fog machine rolled by.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Rodriguez, who was outside on Vanderbilt Avenue, was urged
into his truck by the police as the sprayer approached. He played
his part beautifully, sitting in his truck bug-eyed as the
sweet-scented haze melted away, muttering through a cracked window,
``It's a strange thing.''
</P>
<P>
   A half-year after navigating Y2K, we are in the grip of another
threat that combines the specter of disaster with what may
eventually be seen as overwrought drama. It's another group grope,
not for an exotic computer bug this time, but for a familiar insect
once kept in check with a spritz of Off! and a quick slap.
Uncertainty has bred an atmosphere of concern in some counties and
crisis in others, in response to much the same threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a moving target in the night,'' said C. Scott Vanderhoef,
the Rockland County executive. He ordered pesticide spraying along
all 470 miles of roads in Clarkstown on the recommendation of state
and federal health officials, but he wonders how dangerous the
virus really is. ``There's been no one who's been able to tell this
county executive how big a threat this is to humans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got two calls this morning, both angry,'' Vanderhoef said.
``One lived in an area where there is spraying. She said `How dare
you do this?' The other one was asking: `Why aren't you spraying
us? Are you waiting for a child to die?'''
</P>
<P>
   Just across Rockland's border with Bergen County, N.J., the West
Nile scare feels vastly different.
</P>
<P>
   Birds infected with the virus have been found in both counties.
But Peter Pluchino, Bergen's 30-year-veteran mosquito-control
officer, plans no widespread spraying. ``We wouldn't want to spray
a residential area or spray into the air where there are no
mosquitoes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mosquitoes have been such a scourge in New Jersey that not only
have they been called the state bird but a mosquito-control
apparatus has been in place since 1914. The focus is on killing
mosquito larvae year round _ a practice the rest of the New York
region adopted after last year's West Nile outbreak _ rather than
spraying adult mosquitoes, which New York City and surrounding
counties are now doing.
</P>
<P>
   Bergen County has increased its surveillance for West Nile
virus, but Pluchino said, ``The majority of the population really
isn't at risk, as far as I know.'' Still, many people think that
they are. These days, he said, ``any flying insect is a mosquito to
most people.'' He added, ``People see a dragonfly on the screen and
trap it in Tupperware until we get there.''
</P>
<P>
   In Westchester, the state of readiness is palpable. Officials
there decided to spray along 1,500 miles of roads _ or half the
distance to California, if stretched end to end _ after finding the
virus in two dead birds and a cluster of mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Lipsman, the county health commissioner, acknowledges that
the virus is not comparable to a public health threat like tobacco.
But like a crime wave, it is potentially deadly and looms large in
the public consciousness. He noted that last year there were seven
deaths, including one in New Rochelle, out of 62 known cases,
although a follow-up study estimated that hundreds more were
infected with the virus but showed little or no effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's new,'' he said. ``It's foreign. It's particularly
unpredictable as to who could be hit next. And it's potentially
deadly.'' Therefore, he said, it made sense to spray the pesticide,
which he called ``fairly nontoxic.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, attacking West Nile was a balancing act between
minimizing fear and minimizing disease. With the public wary of
pesticides, he said that spraying from trucks was preferable to the
spraying from airplanes that took place in other areas last year.
``People's image of aerial spraying is like radiation fallout.''
</P>
<P>
   With uncertainty everywhere, it is not always clear where public
health ends and public relations begins. When the Town Board of
Lewisboro, citing environmental concerns, informed Westchester
officials that they did not want to be sprayed, the town
supervisor, Thomas D. Herzog, said he was reminded that the county
was in a health emergency. ``I think the powers that be don't want
to have the accusations come back that they were negligent in
protecting the public health,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
