<HEADER>
A0009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-UPSTATE-RAIN-NYT &LR;      07-22 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-UPSTATE-RAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WESTERN N.Y., FARMERS' FAITH IS TESTED BY ENDLESS RAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ They once prayed for rain here, looking
heavenward for lasting relief from the droughts that had cracked
the earth and withered their crops. But that was last summer, and
the two before that.
</P>
<P>
   Now these farmers can't pray enough for the rain to end.
</P>
<P>
   Since April, torrential downpours have washed away newly planted
seed, drowned sweet corn and peas before they could be plucked, and
transformed acre after acre of fertile soil into lifeless muck.
Rain-battered farmers throughout the stretch of western New York
from Syracuse to Buffalo say they expect to lose half their crops _
worth millions of dollars _ to the worst rainy season they can
remember in at least 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us feel there's almost nothing that can't be
overcome,'' said Nicholas Breslawski, 52, who prayed in church last
Sunday for cloudless blue skies. ``But this rain, it's been hurtful
down into your soul because it's one thing we've been unable to
control with our own hands. You can beat things with will, but you
can't beat constant rain.''
</P>
<P>
   In what has become a test of faith for many farmers,
unexpectedly heavy rain and hail have devastated crops all over the
state, from apple orchards to wheat fields, and pounded a state
agricultural industry already teetering from depressed food prices
and low profit margins. Gov. George Pataki has requested federal
disaster aid for farmers in more than 30 counties. None has been
granted yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``During a year when fuel prices are at their peak and commodity
prices are weak, the excessive rain that the state has been
experiencing could be the final straw for many farmers,'' Pataki
said in a written statement. ``It is critical that we help these
farmers withstand these disastrous weather conditions, as they
serve as the backbone for our rural communities.''
</P>
<P>
   The rains have fallen especially hard in outlying areas of
Monroe County surrounding Rochester, where thick corn stalks brush
up against neat subdivisions, and dairy cows graze along the
roadside.
</P>
<P>
   The county's 605 farms produced $41.9 million worth of crops in
1999, or roughly 4 percent of the state's $1 billion in crop sales,
according to the most recent estimates from the U.S. Department of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Since April, storm systems have stalled here and poured down
more than a foot of rain _ twice as much as last spring. In June
alone, rain fell on 22 days and set a record for that month. ``I
don't expect it to turn dry anytime soon,'' said Jeff Warner, a
meteorologist at Pennsylvania State University who monitors weather
patterns in western New York.
</P>
<P>
   Many farmers had hoped for a bountiful harvest when the rains
came earlier this year. But then their fields flooded. And the rain
just kept falling. ``We went from one extreme to another,'' said
Bob King, an agricultural specialist for the Cornell Cooperative
Extension in Monroe County. ``There won't be any profit for most
farmers. They'll be lucky if they cover their costs. It's another
nail in the coffin, because we've been having tough times anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   With mounting anger and frustration, these farmers and their
families are forced to wait out the heavy rains. ``I have woken up
in the middle of the night hearing the rain, and lay there not
being able to get back to sleep because I'm thinking of them not
getting into the field,'' said Ann Breslawski, 48, who is married
to Nicholas Breslawski. ``I watch the lightning and I pray, `Please
God, don't let it rain.' It affects you. It's on your mind all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The surviving crops still carry scars. Corn stalks are a foot or
more shorter than they should be at this time of year. Wide swaths
of wheat fields lie flat on the ground and have begun to turn black
from mold. The soggy pea fields, which are being harvested by
hulking machines, have been pockmarked with tire tracks.
</P>
<P>
   And the farmers say they can no longer find joy in a rite of
spring here _ driving by a neighbor's fields to peek at the crops
in a bit of friendly competition. ``There are no good-looking crops
this year,'' said Breslawski as he pointed to his 1,000 acres of
cabbage and soybeans. ``I can take you to a field so bad that I
can't stand to look at it. Now I say, `My field is worse than
yours.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Stettner, 48, a farmer who lost 30 acres of peas out of
200 and all 400 acres of feed corn to the rain, said he would
probably have to borrow money to plant next year's crops. The
constant rain has darkened his mood and cast a gloom over his home
_ so much so that his wife, Patricia, says she often wants him to
stop farming.
</P>
<P>
   But as reliably as the frost comes every fall, Stettner and many
others say they will return to their fields again after the storms
and droughts have passed. ``There's a great sense of accomplishment
in growing a crop,'' Stettner said. ``There's a lot of pride in
what we do. That's the reason we stick with it.''
</P>
<P>
   At St. Elizabeth Ann Seton Church last Sunday, the 8:30 a.m.
Mass was unusually well attended by farmers who tend to disappear
into their fields at that hour, even on Sundays, during the growing
season. Breslawski and his family came. So did their friends and
neighbors in this rural community. It had rained again the night
before, making the ground too wet to work that morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Paul Ryan prayed for the struggling farm families, as
he has done many times before. Then his members stood together in
the wood-and-stone church and sang an inspiring hymn: ``Jesus gave
to me, I'm going to let it shine, let it shine, let it shine, let
it shine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The prayers aren't magic,'' said Ryan as he looked outside at
gray skies. ``I think it would be fair to say God is challenging
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
