<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     07-22 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GOLF'S ROAD TO RUIN
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ Nearly a century ago, Bernard Darwin,
who was to golf writing in Britain then what Dan Jenkins is to it
in America now, described the 17th hole at the Old Course at St.
Andrews, the dreaded Road Hole, as having been ``more praised and
more abused'' than any other golf hole in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The green,'' Darwin wrote, ``lies between a greedy little
bunker on one side and a brutally hard road on the other. Many like
it, most respect it and all fear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last century nothing has changed. Over the last several
centuries for that matter, nothing has changed except for the
surface of the road behind the green.
</P>
<P>
   Once a dusty dirt path for horse-drawn carts taking farmers to
market in this gray medieval town on the North Sea, it is now a
crusty black tarmac. But the long angled green, the road behind it
and their stern sentry, that pot bunker shaped like a mine shaft,
are basically the same for Tiger Woods in this British Open as they
were over the years for Old Tom Morris, Harry Vardon, Bobby Jones,
Sam Snead, Arnold Palmer, Jack Nicklaus and Tom Watson.
</P>
<P>
   After a par 4 on this 455-yard outdoor torture chamber in each
of the first two rounds, Woods had a bogey 5 there Saturday when he
3-putted from 20 feet, but with a birdie 3 at the 18th he completed
a 67 for a six-stroke lead going into Sunday's finale.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, the 17th has often been the pivotal hole here
in the British Open, but Woods has approached it with his usual
clinical perspective, beginning with the blind tee shot that must
be aimed over the Old Course Hotel Resort and Spa sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to step up there and choose a line, what letter in
the sign you want to hit it over,'' he said. ``The letter changes
every day, depending on the wind and how far you want to hit it
down there. Today I went for the emblem because the wind was coming
into me from the left, which means I can't drive it that far. The
further you want to drive it, the more right you have to go into
the lettering.
</P>
<P>
   ``On my 7-iron, I tried to hit a one-yard draw, and I was able
to do that, but it started about two yards left of where I wanted
it,'' Woods said. ``That's why I landed on the slope. It skipped
over the Road Hole bunker slope. I had an easy putt. It broke a
lot, I knew that. The speed was a little slow, so I gave it a
little extra trying to get it in there. I let the blade release and
coming back, I held on and yanked across it.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the Road Hole a bogey 5 is a virtual par for any of the
world's best golfers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a par 5 to me,'' Seve Ballesteros has said. ``It is the
hardest hole in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The ghouls in the grandstand wait like vultures for disasters to
occur. Going into Sunday's final round, the 17th had yielded only
13 birdies as opposed to 41 double-bogeys and 12 triple-bogeys or
worse. The average score there was 4.70, virtually half a stroke
more treacherous than the next most difficult hole, the 430-yard
13th.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's opening round, Notah Begay was the early leader at
7 under until he drove into the left rough on the 17th, couldn't
escape on his second, then squirted his third into the Swilken Burn
that usually comes into play only on the first hole. With a
triple-bogey 7, he disappeared from the leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   Begay was in good company in the Swilken Burn. In other years,
Fred Couples and Ballesteros hit their tee shots into the burn,
what in America would be called a narrow creek. Japan's Tommy
Nakajima was on the leader board with his ball on the 17th green in
two in 1978, but his putt curled down the slope into the sand of
the deep pot bunker with the sod-packed steep wall. Slashing away
with his wedge, he finally extricated his ball on the fourth try,
then needed two putts for a 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you lose concentration'' he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he replied with a smile. ``I lost count.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, the Japanese pro's adventure there has been known as
the Sands of Nakajima.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the Road Hole's road.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984 Tom Watson, in a final-round duel with Ballesteros, hit
a 2-iron that bounded across the green and across the road, hit the
short stone wall and stopped in the grass near it. He jabbed a chip
beyond the cup, then two-putted for a bogey as Ballesteros was
draining a birdie putt on the 18th for what would be a two-stroke
victory.
</P>
<P>
   In winning his third British Open, Ballesteros had only five
bogies in that British Open, but three were at the Road Hole where
Watson lost a chance for his sixth British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I've been asked if there was one shot in my career that I
would like to be able to hit over,' Watson has said, 'it would be
that 2-iron at the Road Hole. In 1984.''
</P>
<P>
   It's believed to be the only golf hole in the world that has had
a book written about it: Sidney L. Matthew's ``Wry Stories On the
Road Hole,'' (Sleeping Bear Press, $22). One of those stories
involves one David Ayton who was leading the 1885 British Open by
five strokes as he walked toward the 17th green.
</P>
<P>
   But his chip shot squirted into the bunker. He blasted out to
the road, left his fifth on the road, knocked his sixth into the
bunker again, left his ball in the bunker twice, finally got on the
green in nine, two-putted for an 11 and walked off the green
trailing by six strokes.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty (and the beast) of the Old Course itself, is that
it's a public course. Anyone with an accredited handicap of 24 or
better can enter the daily tee-time lottery. If your name is drawn,
you pay roughly $130 for the privilege of challenging the Old
Course, especially the Road Hole where a visiting duffer once
turned to his local caddie after his ball disappeared into the pot
bunker.
</P>
<P>
   ``What should I do now'' the visitor asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were you,'' his caddie said, ``I'd take the 9:40 train
out of St. Andrews.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
