<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR VICTORIOUS SPANIARDS, THERE IS NO `I' IN TEAM
</HEADLINE>
  By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  SANTANDER, Spain _  Spain has been one big happy tennis family
here this week, including its latest addition, Joan Vehils, the
television journalist who married Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario on Friday
night in Barcelona, a wedding attended by 650 and featuring a cake
that was bigger than the bride.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Before I finish, I would like to congratulate Arantxa and we
hope everything will be great for her,'' Alex Corretja said Friday
evening, to the enthusiastic applause of the Spanish news media.
</P>
<P>
   United they stood, divided we fell.
</P>
<P>
   While the U.S. players had to talk Captain John McEnroe out of
putting himself in Saturday's doubles, the Spanish captain, Javier
Duarte, was extolling the virtues of his team's ``technical
committee'' that selected its lineup. While Pete Sampras and Andre
Agassi went to great and suspicious lengths to claim they were
injured, Spain's hottest young player, Juan Carlos Ferrero, happily
took a seat on the bench when the ``technical committee'' didn't
name him for singles.
</P>
<P>
   While Sampras and Agassi looked right past the Davis Cup
semifinals to the U.S. Open, the Spanish players blew off Wimbledon
to train even harder on their beloved clay courts for their best
shot at the 31-time champions from across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``For now, everyone thinks the same way,'' Corretja said after
defeating Jan-Michael Gambill in four sets and giving Spain a 2-0
lead Friday in the best-of-five competition. ``We sacrifice many
things to play Davis Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in southern California, Sampras was yawning in the
morning sun and dipping his toes into a pool as the Spaniards
Corretja and Juan Balcells defeated Todd Martin and Chris Woodruff,
7-6 (6), 2-6, 6-3, 6-7 (5), 6-3, in Saturday's doubles to eliminate
the United States, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras had called Corretja and Albert Costa ``childish'' when
they stormed out of Wimbledon in supposed protest of the seeding
process. Corretja called Sampras ``lazy,'' for refusing to return
to Europe and play for his country a week after dropping another
Wimbledon title into his bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would sacrifice an important title to win a Davis Cup for
the team, for our country,'' Corretja said. ``It would be bigger
than an individual prize.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is much easier to adopt this attitude when your
country has never won the Davis Cup and you are as likely to win
Wimbledon or even the U.S. Open next month as the Americans were to
survive here without their stars. Would any of these Spanish
players be so happy about interrupting their French Open training
to run off to Australia to play on grass?
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, on clay, the Americans were in trouble, regardless
of which players returned the captain's call. Luck of the draw. The
other day, asked what the United States' chances here would have
been with Sampras and Agassi, McEnroe, who is big into percentages
these days, thought it over and said, ``About 40 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to popular belief, Americans are not the only tennis
players who stiff their Davis Cup captains. Mark Philippoussis
always has an excuse for Australia. As a veteran, Boris Becker
feuded with the German authorities. Comfortable in Connecticut,
Ivan Lendl tuned out the Czechs.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States has won 31 times, somebody good has usually
been playing. It is not as if Sampras and especially Agassi, as
young players, never gave at the office. No one hailed the
Americans as national heroes when they played Davis Cup. They
aren't traitors when they don't. McEnroe was always up for playing,
but even that claim must be made with an asterisk. He didn't win
Grand Slam titles beyond his mid-20s.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi turned 30 last April. Sampras will be 29 next month. With
the exception of Martina Navratilova, there hasn't been a player in
years who has played at the championship level into his or her 30s.
At this stage of their careers, Sampras and Agassi have delicate
decisions to make, considerations and preparations designed to
squeeze every last Grand Slam tournament out of their bodies before
they run dry.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi campaigned for McEnroe as captain, and signed on for a
maiden voyage that took him to Zimbabwe for the first round the
week after he had finished a brutal six-week road run that carried
him to the Australian Open title. Agassi was on top of his game
then, as fit as he has ever been. The last we saw of him in the
thin air of Harare, he was vomiting into a flowerpot. He hasn't
been the same since. His best surface has always been hard courts.
Should he have tired himself, delayed his Open training,
jeopardized his chances to win next month in New York, by coming
here?
</P>
<P>
   Even Corretja had to admit, finally, that the conditions for the
Americans could not have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, we didn't play Wimbledon and had time to
practice,'' he said. ``It is pretty difficult to play Wimbledon, go
home and come back to clay.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of this was good for Spain. The draw was better.
</P>
<P>
   If Davis Cup is about anything, it is soil and surface. The
Spaniards, who last reached the world group final in 1967, can now
win the whole thing this year without having to leave home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good working system and the players are happy,''
said Duarte, when asked to explain his team's success, a year after
a first-round loss to Brazil got the coach, Manuel Santana, fired.
``But of course, this year we are playing at home, so we are lucky.
It always helps to choose the surface, your own balls and
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The technical committee couldn't have planned it better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
