<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MILLENNIUM-WEBSITE     07-22 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MILLENNIUM-WEBSITE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESS REMAINS FROM MILLENNIUM WEB SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With 2 million people crammed into the Times Square
area last New Year's Eve and more than a billion watching the
cascade of fireworks, laser beams and confetti on television,
Renada McGriff should have been thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   Her Web site, TimesSquare2000.com, was the official site of the
``global celebration at the crossroads of the world.'' McGriff had
said it would become the portal to entertainment and culture in
Times Square, and to build it she had enlisted a Who's Who of the
Internet world: Oracle, USWeb, Proxicom, Iomedia and several
others. She had attracted entrepreneurs and bankers to invest or
lend about $6 million for a venture that they all hoped would make
a fortune.
</P>
<P>
   But while sanitation workers swept up 35 tons of debris on New
Year's Day, the mess that McGriff left behind is still haunting
Times Square and the Internet industry. Although she said the Web
site had 20 million hits during the 26-hour New Year's celebration,
her critics contend that it was far from the grand, technologically
sophisticated site that McGriff had promised.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that worked on the project say they are owed millions
of dollars. Investors are demanding to know where the money went.
And more than 14 lawsuits have been filed in state and federal
courts against McGriff and her company, TimesSquareMedia. The
courts have handed down at least five default judgments against
McGriff, totaling over $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, analysts and executives said that the story of
TimesSquare2000.com provided a glimpse into the Wild West character
of the Internet, where untested entrepreneurs and get-rich-quick
schemes abound. Until April, when Internet stocks took a beating,
investors had been more than willing to gamble on many ventures in
the hope that just one might succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a classic Web story,'' said Jeffrey A. Strauss, president
of Countdown Entertainment. Countdown represents the owners of One
Times Square, home of the New Year ball drop, in marketing the
annual event, and it licensed TimesSquare2000.com as the event's
official Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``She spun a wonderful story, got a lot of people excited, but
in the end couldn't deliver on her promises,'' Strauss said.
</P>
<P>
   McGriff, who declined to be interviewed, said in a statement
that she was trying to arrange a merger with another Web site or
sell her company, attributing her problems to investors who had
failed to provide promised financing.
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Korian, the president of Iomedia, stated in an
affidavit filed in New York State Supreme Court that McGriff had
``stiffed'' his company and others, using ``systematic deceit'' to
get goods and services without paying.
</P>
<P>
   Today, even with the venture under legal siege, Internet
executives and people who poured their life savings into McGriff's
company still say she had a brilliant concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Renada's a great salesperson, a very talented woman,'' said
Peter Dugan, vice chairman of DVCi Group, a marketing and
information technology company that won a $500,000 judgment against
her for unpaid bills. ``And it was a great concept. If done
properly, it would have been huge.''
</P>
<P>
   The executives said that they had been willing at first to
overlook McGriff's inexperience and increasingly grandiose plans.
But according to interviews with dozens of executives involved in
the project and claims made in numerous lawsuits, McGriff began
bouncing checks to one company after another for software, hardware
and consulting services, and then refusing to return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   McGriff said in her statement that venture capitalists she did
not identify had not provided the money they had agreed to invest,
and had ``incited'' her relationship with various vendors, using
them as ``pawns'' in an attempt to take control of her company.
</P>
<P>
   According to former executives at TimesSquareMedia, McGriff
battled with Sunrise Securities, an investment bank that worked
with her to raise financing, and Warburg Pincus Asset Management,
which invested about $2.9 million. Executives at the two companies
declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, Renada Watson McGriff, 43, seems an unlikely
candidate to start an Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   McGriff, described even by her critics as bright, articulate and
persuasive, worked as a secretary or executive assistant for
several companies in the 1980s before becoming vice president of
sales in 1988 for Spectacolor Communications, a sign company in
Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to what she told her employers or stated in business
plans circulated to investors, school records show that McGriff did
not graduate from either City College of New York or Arizona State
University.
</P>
<P>
   Although McGriff has said in press material that she produced
Mickey Mouse's 60th-birthday party in Times Square for Disney in
1988, her client was actually Eastman Kodak. The film company
wanted to put Mickey's image on a huge Spectacolor sign in Times
Square, and McGriff played a key role in organizing a promotional
event there featuring Mickey Mouse.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, McGriff was again a secretary, in the communications
department at Sony. After six months, she moved to Disney, where
she worked for a senior lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   McGriff began her first Internet venture in 1998, when she
proposed creating a Web site to sell gift certificates from
expensive retailers to corporate executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a time when everyone was trying to latch onto the next
big wave,'' said Stephen Galluccio, who wrote the business plan for
her company and is suing her for $70,000. ``It was a really good
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   She called it Citigroup, and challenged Travelers and Citicorp
when those merging companies adopted the same name. She settled
with the company for $300,000, according to a former business
adviser. At the same time, McGriff sought money for the project
from Flatiron Partners in New York and investors from California
with the help of an old boss, Larry Bridge, a former vice president
for investor relations at CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Flatiron was willing to invest $1 million, but only if someone
with more business experience than her would be chief executive of
what was then called Gift Certificate Network.
</P>
<P>
   McGriff rejected the deal, and as the project collapsed, she and
her daughter took a trip to Greece. Since then, she has been sued
for a total of $110,000 by the travel agency, Galluccio and a
printer. The agency won a default judgment in state Supreme Court,
and the other two cases are pending.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, in December 1998, McGriff talked to Strauss
of Countdown Entertainment about TimesSquare2000.com. She described
a site that would broadcast the New Year's Eve celebration from New
York and other cities worldwide, and have virtual concerts,
electronic postcards, chat rooms, ticket sales and merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came to us with a wonderful idea,'' Strauss said. ``She
set up meetings with major players at Excite, AOL, USWeb and
Oracle. At the time it was the dot-com craze.''
</P>
<P>
   Strauss signed a four-year licensing agreement with Countdown in
March 1999 in return for 10 percent of profits from advertising and
merchandise sales. McGriff's company, in turn, would provide
information about Times Square festivities and programming for the
five huge video screens in Times Square.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   McGriff started the venture with her own money, but soon she was
signing contracts with Internet companies and raising over $1
million from investors, including $750,000 from a group in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, on June 15, McGriff convened a remarkable
meeting at a hotel in Times Square. More than 50 top executives
from USWeb, Oracle, Sun Microsystems, EarthCam and DVCi, as well as
her corporate lawyers and investors, crowded into the room to
discuss how the Web site was taking shape. For each executive, the
presence of so much talent in one room seemed to confirm the wisdom
of their decision to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed by the meeting,'' said Tom Hyland, who heads the
new media group at the PricewaterhouseCoopers accounting firm and
worked briefly with McGriff. ``She's a very articulate, convincing
marketing woman who appeared to be well connected. There's a
momentum when you get certain names together.''
</P>
<P>
   A person who was there said that ``in a matter of minutes'' some
investors pushed their revenue projections from $10 million a year
to $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   But there were tremors below the surface. McGriff's publicists,
Middleberg &AMP; Associates, quit. They were replaced by Urge Public
Relations, and then, after a dispute over payment, by Ruder Finn,
which has filed suit for more than $123,000 in unpaid bills.
</P>
<P>
   By Thanksgiving, USWeb, which is now known as MarchFirst, and
Oracle had also quit the project over unpaid bills. Jennifer Glass,
a spokeswoman for Oracle, said that her company was owed more than
$1 million and was considering legal action. DVCi followed USWeb
and was later replaced by Proxicom, which won a $540,000 default
judgment in U.S. District Court this year against McGriff and her
company.
</P>
<P>
   A rudimentary version of TimesSquare2000.com went up in
September, and McGriff announced her greatest coup: Her site would
be the global sponsor for America Online's ``Party of the
Millennium.'' But the alliance broke up over concerns that the site
would not be able to handle the enormous Web traffic it was
expected to generate.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Thanksgiving, Warburg Pincus invested $2.2 million
and promised more. A month later, a Japanese businessman, Yuji
Suzuki, gave McGriff the first of two installments on a $1 million
loan, in return for stock options.
</P>
<P>
   But more work had to be done on the Web site in the frantic
weeks leading up to New Year, and while McGriff sought new
investors to provide $20 million, that big infusion never came.
</P>
<P>
   A few days before the celebration, McGriff called a news
conference at a restaurant in Times Square. But she did not show
up, and among the 50 people who did were creditors demanding to be
paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``She sent me there, but didn't tell me there'd be these irate
people,'' one executive said. ``People were literally lined up in
front of the press.''
</P>
<P>
   New Year's Eve in Times Square was a huge success. McGriff's Web
site displayed information about Times Square and New Year's Eve
events and views of the ball drop, but was unable to offer hotel
and restaurant reservations and other features she had once
described.
</P>
<P>
   ``She cast the only dark cloud over an otherwise spectacular
event,'' said Brian Cury, chief executive of EarthCam, an Internet
company with cameras throughout Times Square. ``We wanted to
participate in a substantial event that would enhance the Times
Square celebration. She threw out some insane amount of money that
made people think, even if I get a third of it, it'd be great. We
had a $2.7 million deal, and she stuck me.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, McGriff turned to Barr Financial Group in Tampa,
Fla., to revive the venture. At that time, the company's founder,
Alfred Barr, said that only $5,000 remained of the $6 million
invested in the venture.
</P>
<P>
   As he waded through piles of bills, promissory notes and stock
options, Barr said that McGriff told him that a lawyer for Suzuki
had shown up at her penthouse in Manhattan, saying that she had
pledged company stock and personal assets as security for his $1
million loan, which had come due in February. Warburg Pincus made
similar claims, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Barr said he had already raised $40 million from two groups of
investors, but McGriff refused to agree to their terms.
</P>
<P>
   In April, McGriff announced that she was reviving
TimesSquare2000.com as GothamLive.com, an entree to New York
restaurants, entertainment and culture. A company called On2.com
was to be the host of the site, but the partnership did not last.
``We're in a dispute with her over her payment under the contract
for our services,'' said Douglas McIntyre, chief executive of
On2.com.
</P>
<P>
   But McGriff is still at it. The Web site TimesSquare2000.com is
still up. McGriff said she was trying to sell TimesSquareMedia or
merge with a larger company.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's actively trying to do it as a way to realize the full
value of the company,'' said her company's current lawyer,
Christopher Boies, ``and to satisfy her potential investors.''
</P>
<P>
   McGriff met recently with executives of Cablevision Systems and
Primedia, a publisher of magazines, but an executive at Cablevision
said that nothing would come of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
