<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0017 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BROOKLYN-TOUR-NYT &LR;      07-22 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BROOKLYN-TOUR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREES, IF TOUGH ENOUGH, STILL GROW IN BROOKLYN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is not easy being a tree in New York City, the
tour guide said Saturday, as he walked a group of nearly a dozen
guests through Fulton Park in Bedford-Stuyvesant.
</P>
<P>
   The guide, Orville Edwards, 26, said the biggest threats to
trees in New York were pollution and cars knocking them over.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most commonly planted tree in the city,'' Edwards
said, pointing to the thick trunk of what was a cross between an
American sycamore and an Oriental sycamore, in Fulton Park. ``They
are very resistant to most disease and pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   When most outsiders think of Bedford-Stuyvesant, Edwards said,
images of fires, crime scenes and dilapidated buildings of a
so-called asphalt jungle fill their heads, based on things they
have seen on television.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday, Edwards, a native of Jamaica and a resident of
Bedford-Stuyvesant, took a group on a nature tour through the
neighborhood. The tour is one of several dozen offered each summer
by the Brooklyn Center for the Urban Environment, which is based in
Park Slope.
</P>
<P>
   The tour of Bedford-Stuyvesant is somewhat unusual, organizers
said, in that it brings people _ many of whom have never been to
the neighborhood they associate with urban blight _ face-to-face
with a place where nature merges with the urban landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pretty much have more brownstones than anywhere in New York
City,'' Edwards told the tour group, as he pointed out magnolias
and gardens along tree-lined Stuyvesant Avenue in the historic
district.
</P>
<P>
   He talked not only about the squirrels and yellow-bellied
sapsucker woodpeckers that frequent backyards and parks, but also
about where the limestone and brownstone on the buildings came
from.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see much limestone in the neighborhood,'' said
Edwards, an environmental coordinator with the Magnolia Tree
Environmental Center. ``The brownstone is the most popular
facade.''
</P>
<P>
   They talked about the history of the neighborhood: the Woolworth
family once had a mansion there; many of the more wealthy white
residents moved out as blacks moved in from the Lower East Side in
the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   As the group strolled down Bedford-Stuyvesant's avenues and side
streets, they at times seemed out of place. Most residents and
business owners waved, while others offered only questioning
stares. Rodrique Morara, 59, a retired truck driver who lives
across from the Boys and Girls school where the group stopped to
look at an American birch tree, gently needled the group as he
smoked a cigarette nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is trying to tell them about the tree?'' Morara volunteered
to no one in particular. ``That's poison ivy, of course, that is
elementary.''
</P>
<P>
   Stella Jouranis, 64, a retired secretary from Bayside, N.Y., in
Queens County, said she had never been to Bedford-Stuyvesant and
was surprised by its charm.
</P>
<P>
   Jouranis said it was surprising that ``the neighborhood is so
beautiful and it has a lot to offer, and how clean they keep the
streets, and how kind all the people are. They all say hello.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
