<HEADER>
A0019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CITY-ISLAND-2TAKES     07-22 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CITY-ISLAND-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL-TOWN WAYS ENDURE ON TINY BRONX ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   By N.R. KLEINFIELD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jacqueline Kyle Kall was doing what she does best,
talking. Here she was coming into Artie's restaurant for lunch.
Everyone seemed tickled to see her. She ate here a lot. The
waitress plunked down her usual drink _ known as Jackie's Martini _
a double martini.
</P>
<P>
   She lived and sold real estate here on City Island in the Bronx,
a place that seems endowed with confirmed stasis. She was 75, with
a doctorate in conversation, able to pontificate at length on the
mannerisms of the snug island or most anything else. She could do
an hour on Artie's menu alone.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke of how City Islanders stayed put, how houses did not
turn over much. Some were passed from generation to generation. A
few dozen hit the market in any given year. She picked up the
thought: ``On my street, nothing has sold in 35 years. I sold a
house on Horton Street that had not been sold in 80 years. When I
see the pallbearers go by my office, I know I have a house. Or like
Lil Hansen. She had a stroke and went into the nursing home. I got
a house.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhoods in New York are forever changing, refuting one
image and embracing a fresh one, but there are pockets of
immutability, places that seem to insist on staying as they are.
City Island in the Bronx is one of those places. People come and
go, new housing sprouts up, businesses change hands, but the tenor
and intonation of the place have persisted for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it a cross between Mayberry and Cape Cod,'' said Robert
Carmody, 43, who has a real estate business and actually would like
to see more development than many others would.
</P>
<P>
   It is just a wisp of an island _ one and a quarter miles long
and about a quarter of a mile wide, encircled by Long Island Sound
and Eastchester Bay. Around 5,000 people live on it, mostly in
modest clapboard houses hunched close together. There is one main
strip, City Island Avenue, clotted with seafood restaurant after
seafood restaurant. The only place to stay overnight is a bed and
breakfast called Le Refuge. There are no public beaches. There is
no movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   Talk occasionally circulates about how City Island could become
a grand tourist destination, with hotels and resorts, more condos,
the whole bit. Fernando Ferrer, the Bronx borough president, is
among those who hanker for some augmentation, while keeping the
island's flavor. But the prospect of further development sends
prickles down many spines. Last year, when the parks department
proposed a water park for nearby Orchard Beach, the residents said
think again. The park went away. Some people are a bit miffed at
Peter La Scala, who sold a plot of land opposite his yacht
brokerage business not long ago because taxes got too high, he
said, and now 20 houses are going up on it. Residents relish
inactivity.
</P>
<P>
   City Islanders have their own idiom to classify people. Anyone
born on the island is known as a clam digger. Residents born
elsewhere are mussel suckers. Even the obituaries published in the
island's monthly paper, The Island Current, will sometimes identify
people as clam diggers, thus bestowing on them a stature that
extends beyond their other mortal achievements. People neither born
on the island nor living there are known as off-islanders, as in,
``I'm having an off-islander over for cocktails next Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Sadler is a classic clam digger. He was born 84 years ago
in the same upstairs bedroom he now sleeps in. His grandfather
built the house, passed it on to his parents, who passed it on to
him. He is a small, bent man, his face runnelled with lines. A
retired fireboat pilot, he keeps busy adjusting compasses on boats.
``I do the big yachts and the Coast Guard vessels,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Viewed across its lengthy history, City Island has actually
witnessed a good deal of change. Originally the home of the Siwanoy
Indians, it became an English settlement in 1685. Norwegians and
Germans settled there, and the place evolved into a prominent
shipbuilding and yachting center. During the world wars, PT boats,
submarine chasers and other battle craft were built in its
boatyards. The sloops that competed in the America's Cup were
constructed on the island. As Fiberglas replaced wood as
boatbuilding material starting in the 1960s, the boatyards got out
of building boats. What remain today are marinas, yacht clubs,
sailmakers and marine supply and repair shops.
</P>
<P>
   Decades ago, the island was emphatically rural. Herb Hild, a
71-year-old clam digger who owns a business that makes canvas
covers and cushions for boats and now lives on an island in nearby
Rye, remembers how empty the place was when he was a child. The
grocery store shut down for lunch. He marched to school to the
distinctive ring of the caulking hammers at the boatyards.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, mainly working-class people have occupied the
island, with a lot of police officers and firefighters. But houses
have been turning over at enlarging prices, and the island has
gotten more diverse (except racially; it is almost entirely white).
A good many doctors and other medical personnel from the Bronx
hospitals now live there.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Campbell, 40, the publisher of Spin magazine, arrived
from Manhattan with his family five years ago. He rambled off his
neighbors: a detective, an accountant, a carpet salesman, an
installer for a phone company.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Whitcombe, an artist, was painting a sailboat in his small
cottage on Ditmars Street that he shares with his wife, Elizabeth.
He has lived on the island for 45 of his 57 years. The couple do
not own a car. They ride bicycles. A coal stove heats the house. In
recent years, several artists have moved to the island, pleasing
Whitcombe.
</P>
<P>
   Like any small town, the island boasts its share of Gothic
tales, Whitcombe said. A man named Beau Barton used to live down
the block. So the story goes, he had his hopes pinned on receiving
a French honor in eighth grade. When he did not get it, he was
shattered. He rebuffed society. He lived with his sister, who ran a
bookstore, and he rarely showed himself outside.
</P>
<P>
   His sister died, and he made do on his own. He was known to take
the bus at 4 in the morning to stores off the island to fetch
groceries, the better to stay invisible. He had no heat in his
house. One cold winter day about 10 years ago, he was found frozen
to death.
</P>
<P>
   Residents moan when they hear about new condos going up, and
they get worked up over traffic congestion. On the weekends, City
Island Avenue shudders with cars of off-islanders heading for the
restaurants. Residents avoid leaving the island for fear of how
long it would take to return.
</P>
<P>
   Even things on-islanders dislike don't seem to change. Across
the bay in Pelham Bay Park is Rodman's Neck, a police firing range
as well as where the bomb squad detonates confiscated bombs and
fireworks. Pretty much every day, residents and businesses facing
the range hear the irritating rat-a-tat-tat of gunfire as officers
get in their practice. Less frequently, but more noticeably, the
bomb squad sets off a bomb. The island shakes.
</P>
<P>
   A noise-deadening barrier is soon to be built on the range, but
La Scala, like other residents, is dubious it will solve the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Boat Livery is on Bridge Street, on the water. It's a dark,
scruffy place. In the late afternoon, nearly a dozen people were
grouped around the bar, getting their $1 beers. It was hot and
humid, and they were telling fish stories and otherwise gossiping.
</P>
<P>
   Trader John, as he is known, runs the place. His full name is
John Persteins. He's 58, and he moved to the island with his
parents when he was 2 months old, missing the honor of being a clam
digger by those 60 days. He also has a used boat equipment shop.
The Boat Livery is strictly a beer and wine bar. As Trader John put
it, ``There's enough problems with beer and wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen rent skiffs from Trader John, buy bait from him and
fish. Then they return, quaff some drinks and tell about what got
away.
</P>
<P>
   A buffalo head hangs behind the bar. When a newcomer stops in
for a drink, one of the regulars will say, ``Go outside to see the
other end.'' When the duped rookie steps outside, everyone has a
good laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole bear standing over there,'' Trader John
pointed out. ``People sometimes dance with it. But when you start
to talk to the buffalo, that's when you're turned off. You've had
enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
