<SLUG> BC-CAR-PENN-500-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LITTLE THINGS COUNT AT POCONO 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE CALDWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG POND, Pa. _ Jimmy Makar suddenly noticed something wrong
with Bobby Labonte's bright green race car Friday afternoon. Makar
strode purposefully over to the front fender, fished in his pocket,
pulled out a pocketknife, and meticulously whittled away a loose
sliver of fluorescent red tape no more than a \-inch wide.
</P>
<P>
   Makar, laughing, would say later that such minor surgery would
probably not make a bit of difference when the Pennsylvania 500 was
run Sunday. But you never know. The crew chief of the top car on
the Nascar Winston Cup circuit cannot afford to take chances,
especially not with Labonte in the middle of a bristling points
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't let the little things slide as much as we used to,''
Makar said.
</P>
<P>
   With only 18 of 34 races complete, the race for the Winston Cup
championship is far from decided. Labonte, the quiet 36-year-old
driver from Corpus Christi, Texas, holds only a 45-point lead over
Dale Earnhardt and a 68-point lead over Dale Jarrett. Labonte's
momentum has been slipping, if only slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte has not won since the second race of the year. He has
finished in the top five in only one of his last four races. He is
not even the hottest driver in his owner Joe Gibbs' formidable
racing garage. That would be Tony Stewart, 29, who has gained four
places in the points standing in the last six races and smashed the
track qualifying record here Friday with a lap at 172.391 mph.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Labonte's approach to driving comes into play. His
approach to life, actually.
</P>
<P>
   He does not seem to be too upset about being locked in a battle
with two former champions for his first Winston Cup championship.
He just spent eight days on vacation with his family, far away from
the team's garage.
</P>
<P>
   After he posted the 13th-fastest qualifying time for Sunday's
race, Labonte climbed the steps to the roof of his team's trailer
to calmly review the run with Makar, and stayed there for a long
time. Most drivers disappear quickly after qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't worry about it,'' Labonte said of the points race.
``We let other people worry about it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there was just a hint of a grin. Labonte, who finished
second a year ago to Jarrett, is pretty much where he wants to be.
The team has not radically changed its approach from last year,
when Labonte won five races and led a substantially higher
percentage of laps.
</P>
<P>
   The team simply has been more consistent. Labonte has finished
every race. He has finished lower than 13th only twice. The idea is
still to win, not just to run near the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you end up being consistent if you run for wins,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   You also apparently end up having more fun, which, in turn,
leads to more success.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at that `18' bunch, and they're all excited about
being there,'' Earnhardt said recently, referring to Labonte's team
by his car number.
</P>
<P>
   Now Labonte has another valuable ally in Stewart. As soon as
Stewart set the track record Friday, Makar hustled over to
Stewart's garage for some inside information from the crew chief
Greg Zipadelli on how Stewart did it. ``We share everything but
households and credit cards,'' Stewart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
