<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS-DUVAL DUEL IS SET FOR BRITISH OPEN FINALE
</HEADLINE>
  By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ As Tiger Woods stood on the precipice of
golf history, David Duval hoped to stand in the way.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens during Sunday's final round of the
British Open, it will be memorable. Woods, 24, who ended Saturday's
third round holding a six-stroke lead, could become the youngest
player to win the career Grand Slam. But Duval, the world's No.
2-ranked player, will be paired with Woods in the final group _ a
showdown between No. 1 and No. 2 that will be their first pairing
together in a major championship.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras will click. Fans will roar. Emotions will run high. But
only one player will hoist the precious claret jug, symbolic of
winning the game's oldest major championship, on the Old Course at
St. Andrews, recognized worldwide as the home of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Who could ask for more? Heading into the final round, Woods will
not need to ask for strokes. Shooting a third-round 67, his third
consecutive round in the 60s, Woods was 16 under for the tournament
(67-66-67 _ 200) six strokes ahead of both Duval (10 under,
70-70-66) and Thomas Bjorn of Denmark (69-69-68). Darren Clarke,
Loren Roberts and David Toms were tied for fourth place at 9-under,
but anyone further behind could probably kiss their chances of
winning goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, even Duval and Bjorn are long shots to catch
Woods, who has won 18 of 20 professional tournaments that he has
led after three rounds. And if Woods wins, he will complete the
career Grand Slam, adding the British Open to his three other major
championships _ the Masters (1997), the PGA Championship (1999) and
this year's U.S. Open, which Woods won by a record 15 strokes. Only
four other players have won all four modern majors _ Gene Sarazen,
Ben Hogan, Jack Nicklaus, and Gary Player.
</P>
<P>
   Woods also has a chance to break the British Open record to par,
18 under, set by Nick Faldo at St. Andrews in 1990. Will Woods feel
pressure Sunday? You bet. But does he think he can handle it?
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger the lead, the more pressure you feel,'' said Woods,
who had a 10-stroke lead after three rounds of this year's U.S.
Open, and who held a nine-stroke lead after three rounds of the
1997 Masters. ``I know the public has wanted to see No. 1 and No. 2
against each other in the final round of a major championship, and
now they will see it. If you don't end up winning, you're not going
to feel too good about yourself. But I've had big leads before, and
I've been able to succeed. We will see tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what Duval hoped to do, and he put himself in contention
despite playing the entire tournament with a sore back. And Duval
did not hide his excitement about teeing off against Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Asked the advantage of being in the last twosome against Woods,
Duval said: ``You get to look him in the eye. If I can swing the
golf club like I have the last few days and putt like I have, I can
show him I've got a little game going right now, too. Absolutely,
it would mean more to beat him. I want you to know that when you're
at your best, I can beat you. That may sound cocky, but it's simply
wanting to compete at the highest level. I'm going to be trying to
win my first major championship, and he's going to be going for the
career Grand Slam. So there's going to be some pressure on both
parties. But yes, I'm excited. How could I not be?''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his news conference, Duval stood to relieve the pain
in his back, which he injured shortly after the U.S. Open. Duval is
not sure how he sustained the injury, but he was in less pain
Saturday than at any time during the tournament. And it showed in
his game, as Duval birdied four of his first nine holes to roar
into contention, then secured his spot in the last group with a
birdie at No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Duval's tee shot at the par-4 18th was well right and nearly
sailed out of bounds. But it kicked left after hitting the ground
and it stayed in play, allowing him to hit a nice pitch shot from
75 feet that set up an 8-foot putt that he converted for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Woods never relinquished the lead, and he doubled the
three-stroke lead he began the day with. A crucial stretch came
when Woods reached No. 8 at 11 under, holding just a one-stroke
lead over Steve Flesch, and a two-stroke lead over Duval, Ernie Els
and Toms.
</P>
<P>
   Like a motorist stepping on the accelerator, Woods pulled away,
making five birdies on his next seven holes. At the par-3, 175-yard
No. 8, Woods hit a gorgeous 6-iron tee shot that landed 18 inches
from the cup, then he tapped in for birdie. At the par-4 No. 9,
Woods birdied again, hitting a 9-iron approach shot to 15 feet,
then making the putt.
</P>
<P>
   At the par-4, 314-yard No. 12, Woods drove just short of the
green, hit a splendid chip to 3 feet, then made the putt. At No.
13, he made a 20-foot putt for birdie, then at the par-5, 581-yard
No. 14, he reached the green in two shots, then two-putted from 40
feet for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' streak of bogey-free holes at major championships ended
at 63, when he three-putted for bogey at No. 2, and he also
three-putted for bogey at No. 17. But Woods regained his six-stroke
lead on the final hole, when he made a 10-foot putt for birdie and
pumped his fist, knowing he had put himself in excellent position
to win.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Els most likely lost his chance to win with a crucial
double-bogey at No. 12, hitting his tee shot into the gorse. Els
ended the day tied at 8 under with Flesch, who double-bogeyed No.
13, Tom Lehman, and Dennis Paulson.
</P>
<P>
   But all the pursuers would need help from Woods to win. Even if
Woods shot par on Sunday, Duval and Bjorn would need 66s just to
tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not invincible, but he's playing great,'' Clarke said of
Woods. ``He is going to be very, very difficult to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   So Woods had a six-stroke lead to sleep on, a showdown with
Duval to look forward to, and perhaps a victory speech to deliver.
Woods hoped to seize the moment. And after three rounds of superb
and strategic golf, he appeared on the verge of seizing a special
victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
