<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0031 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      07-22 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POTENTIAL, POWER AND PRIDE KEEP DISPUTED GROUND A PRECARIOUS
PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOLAN HEIGHTS _ The rocky, deeply carved landscape of this
volcanic upland is raked by a dry wind and parched almost
unrelievedly brown under a beating summer sun.
</P>
<P>
   On such a day, it is hard to imagine why anyone could think so
inhospitable a piece of land _ less than 40 miles long and 15
across at its widest _ would be worth spending so many lives to
own.
</P>
<P>
   But that first impression, of a desolate wasteland, is very
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the year the climate is beneficent. Spring rainfall
is plentiful, and during that season, it's said _ though I've never
seen it _ the hillsides are awash with green and the colors of
wildflowers.
</P>
<P>
   The June 1967 Six-Day War saw Syria driven from the Golan and
the establishment here barely a month afterward of the first
Israeli civilian foothold.
</P>
<P>
   When I traveled the region on assignment in 1970, everywhere you
could see the ruins of abandoned Syrian villages. And Jewish
settlement was salted only thinly across the heights in a dozen
farming outposts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, on the Jewish holy day of Yom Kippur, Arab armies
launched a surprise attack whose declared objective, in the words
of Syria's President Hafez Assad, was to destroy Israel and drive
its people into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   He must have suspected that was a fatuous hope, but at a
minimum, Assad hoped to regain his lost territory. Instead, he
ended up losing more.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing 27 years, the number of Israeli settlers on the
Golan has more than doubled, to some 17,000. They coexist
peacefully, if not always easily, with about an equal number of
Druze people who stayed on the Golan when the Syrian villagers
fled.
</P>
<P>
   And in fields cleared of the rubble of black basaltic stone,
their grain crops, pastures, orchards and vineyards prosper.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from its agricultural potential, the area supplies another
and more precious resource. Everywhere in the arid Middle East,
water defines the possibilities of habitation and development.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one-third of Israel's growing annual need is supplied
from the Jordan River and Sea of Galilee, fed by rivers with
sources in the occupied Golan and by spring runoff and snowmelt
feeding down through steeply eroded canyons from the flanks of
Syria's Mount Hermon.
</P>
<P>
   So water and productive land both are important. But there is a
third factor, still more urgent.
</P>
<P>
   If you stand on the brow of the Golan escarpment, at the bunkers
from which Syrian gunners rained shells on vulnerable Israeli
/{kibbutzim/} in the Galilee below, the military advantage gained
by control of this commanding terrain is immediately obvious.
</P>
<P>
   It is this combination of strategic and practical concerns on
Israel's side, and wounded pride on Syria's side, that has made the
Golan Heights one of the major sticking points in the search for a
comprehensive settlement that would bring an end to the Middle
East's interminable agony.
</P>
<P>
   That was the topic of conversation with an Israeli traveling
companion during a refreshment stop on the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   Assad, long reported to be in precarious and failing health _
leukemia, diabetes and inoperable heart disease _ had vowed
repeatedly that peace with Israel could be possible only if every
inch of Syrian territory is returned. Thus, the chance of a
breakthrough has seemed slim.
</P>
<P>
   How long, we wondered aloud, would Assad cling to life and
power? If the deadlock were prolonged, was it not likely that any
slight momentum toward a final regional accord would be lost?
</P>
<P>
   And what might his passing mean? A measure of flexibility by his
successor, or an eruption of instability in Syria, perhaps followed
by renewed fanaticism and recklessness?
</P>
<P>
   But those, we agreed, were questions for the future. By some
estimates, Assad should have been dead months ago, and he keeps
proving them wrong.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS)Later the same day:(END ITALICS)
</P>
<P>
   Descending from the Golan in the waning afternoon, we drive a
short way west, then north to the uppermost town in Israel _ to the
one-time resort village of Metulla, on a narrow finger of land
extending into Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   I remember standing 30 years ago with the town's mayor at the
chain-link fence separating the two countries. On the near side
were Metulla's apple orchards. On the Lebanese side were
Palestinian terrorists who regularly lobbed rocket shells over the
fence at the village.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors no longer came to Metulla on holiday. The hotels were
empty. But the villagers stayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the mosquitoes are not good, or if the flies are not good _
or if the shooting is not good _ it is the same,'' the mayor said.
``We build fences, we put out our guards, we dig foxholes, and we
continue to live. It is our land.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, we cannot get to the fence even if we cared to.
</P>
<P>
   A detachment of Israeli soldiers blocks the road a mile or more
from the frontier. Through binoculars, two flags can be seen flying
at the border. On the near side is the blue and white flag of the
Jewish state. On the other is the yellow banner of the de facto
rulers of southern Lebanon, the Shiite guerrilla organization
Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in gathering dusk, we take the road south to our
night's lodging in the historic mountain town of Safed, a center of
ultraorthodox Judaisim and, in more recent times, a magnet for
artists.
</P>
<P>
   In the hotel lobby the television is playing and replaying the
top story in the news, with pictures of emotional crowds thronging
the streets of Damascus and Syrian officials, faces buried in their
hands, shaken by demonstrative grief.
</P>
<P>
   A familiar visage flashes repeatedly on the screen, followed by
images of that man's son.
</P>
<P>
   The future has arrived, it seems, and no one can know the
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   This day _ June 10 _ Hafez Assad, Syria's ruler since 1970, is
dead.
</P>
<P>
   NEXT SUNDAY: What Might Yet Be
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
