<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0035 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-NET-ENVELOPES0723-COX     07-22 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NET-ENVELOPES0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet pushing the envelope
 &HT;    By Peralte C. Paul
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it comes to paying his bills, Kip Montgomery says
he's got a system that has the traditional ``check's in the mail''
system licked.
</P>
<P>
   The 41-year-old college professor hasn't bought postage stamps
in three years, and he tosses the return envelopes that come with
his bills.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Montgomery pays all his bills electronically
through a PC-based account with Alpharetta, Ga.-based NetBank.com.
Roughly 47 percent of NetBank's 105,000 customers _ 49,350 account
holders _ use the online bill-paying service.
</P>
<P>
   Even the 3-year-old bank is weaning itself from traditional
mailings. By 2003, it wants to reduce its outgoing mail volume by
30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the fastest-growing Internet bank, but we're not going
to have the fastest-growing postal expense rate,'' said Mike
Fitzgerald, NetBank president. ``We're going to see the application
flow become much more electronic.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words aren't welcome news to the $3.19 billion U.S.
envelope manufacturing industry.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of plain, letter-size and return bill-pay envelopes
accounted for about 8 percent of total sales last year, according
to the Envelope Manufacturers Association. The industry expects
that figure to begin declining in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   On the upside, e-commerce will drive the growth of the
direct-mail and niche market packaging to a projected $500 million
this year, said Maynard Benjamin, president of the Envelope
Manufacturers Association.
</P>
<P>
   That's up from about $12 million 10 years ago, he said. The
direct-mail and niche market accounts for about 69 percent of the
industry's total sales.
</P>
<P>
   The ``new economy'' also is forcing manufacturers to experiment
with ways to make envelopes and packaging more tech-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The envelope of the future is going to have more information
on the outside than on the inside,'' Benjamin said.
</P>
<P>
   The EMA will test market an envelope and package system this
fall designed to make it easier for customers to return or exchange
merchandise ordered online.
</P>
<P>
   Customers will be able to use a scanner to ``read'' a bar code
imprinted on the outside package, Benjamin said.
</P>
<P>
   The scanner, connected to a home computer, will call up the
customer's order online so if the customer wants to return it or
exchange it, he or she can immediately input that information onto
a retailer's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   It also will allow folks returning merchandise to print a return
mailing address label, Benjamin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything becomes functional in the future,'' he said. ``The
envelope industry is right in the middle of that world.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Envelope Co. of Atlanta is developing a system to embed
computer chips into an envelope or package.
</P>
<P>
   Using a radio-frequency system, companies could track the
location of mass mailings, down to the exact time and delivery of
each piece of mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that (the Internet) trend is having an
effect,'' said Randy Zook, Atlantic Envelope's president and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   The larger envelope manufacturers say they're prepared for the
Internet's impact because the bulk of their business isn't in
business-size, white envelopes. They're making more, larger
shipping envelopes and packages, which account for more sales. And
those sales are coming from the business-to-business segment, which
still wants a paper trail when conducting transactions with
consumers, manufacturers said.
</P>
<P>
   But even that may be changing. Last month, the American Bankers
Association released a survey that showed financial institutions
decreased their outgoing mail from 9.6 billion pieces in 1996 to
7.9 billion last year _ a 17.7 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that drop is attributable to banks' cutting costs, the
ABA says, but it's also because of changing federal regulations
that no longer require paper transactions in some cases and the
growth of e-mail and faxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're finding better ways to reach customers,'' said John
Hall, an ABA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based BellSouth Corp. has been accepting online bill
payments since 1997. By 2003, the company expects 3 million of its
22 million customers to receive and pay their bills online.
</P>
<P>
   The company eventually hopes that 50 percent of its customers
will switch to e-billing and e-payments, said Brad Hahn, senior
manager of online billing and payment for BellSouth's e-business
group.
</P>
<P>
   Just meeting that 3 million benchmark would save the company
about $1.05 million in postage and envelope costs, _ roughly 35
cents a customer _ BellSouth said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Postal Service, processor of most of the mail sent to
the nation's 130 million households, is watching these envelope
trends carefully. The agency had revenue of about $63 billion last
year, of which $17 billion, or 27 percent, came from consumers
paying their bills.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service could see that $17 billion evaporate during
the next 10 years, according to a General Accounting Office study.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the agency is integrating Internet services into
its offerings, such as an electronic bill-paying service for
customers it launched in April with Norcross-based CheckFree Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But some envelope manufacturers say that not everyone is jumping
on the e-bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still going to be a segment of the population that
still needs to be reached somehow,'' said Rick Gould, president of
Ohio Envelope Manufacturing Co. in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the Internet will undoubtedly change the
industry. ``I can't imagine we're going to be here 25 years from
now the way we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
