<HEADER>
A0042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-DICTATORS-NYT &LR;      07-22 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DICTATORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: REAL ELECTIONS CAN BE DANGEROUS TO DICTATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TINA ROSENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From communist general secretaries to Latin American
generalissimos, dictators have long confirmed their rule with what
they called ``elections.'' Occasionally, however, autocrats hold
somewhat free elections _ and to their great embarrassment, they
sometimes lose. Augusto Pinochet in Chile, Ferdinand Marcos in the
Philippines, the Sandinistas in Nicaragua and the communists in
Poland in 1989 were all voted out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Now another undemocratic group, Mexico's Institutional
Revolutionary Party, has lost an election.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, this unexpected respect for the people's will
came from those within ruling parties _ like President Ernesto
Zedillo in Mexico _ who sincerely wanted to modernize and
democratize their nations.
</P>
<P>
   But others, including many in Mexico's PRI, had no intention of
relinquishing power. They wanted the internal legitimacy,
diplomatic recognition, foreign aid or increased trade that comes
with winning elections, and they were certain they would win,
because the very habits of authoritarianism allowed them to delude
themselves about their own popularity. They forced people to march
in their rallies and shout their slogans, and then they believed
what they saw and heard.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, for example, the PRI pressured newspaper and
television news editors not to report on pre-election polls that
showed the party's candidate, Francisco Labastida, trailing Vicente
Fox. Perhaps that is one reason Labastida told a television
interviewer after the election that he never dreamed he would lose
until he saw the exit polls.
</P>
<P>
   The election of the first noncommunist government in the East
bloc in 1989 illustrates how dictators imprison themselves with
their own repression. The Polish communists convinced themselves
they could beat Solidarity in a real election.
</P>
<P>
   Poland was in economic collapse. Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski
decided to legalize the banned Solidarity movement, give it a share
of power and use it to rally support for price hikes and plant
closures.
</P>
<P>
   He thought the party could contain Solidarity in part because
regional party officials, who were his main source of information,
dutifully reported that the average Pole rejected Solidarity.
Jaruzelski was sure he could persuade Poles not to blame the party
for their poverty. He fervently believed that more and better
speeches produced more and better communists. The head of the
communist labor unions was sure he could win a televised debate
with an uneducated electrician named Lech Walesa.
</P>
<P>
   They erred. In elections the next year, Solidarity won 99 of 100
seats in the Senate, and all the 161 seats it was allowed to
contest in the lower house _ familiar numbers in East bloc
elections, now with a new twist.
</P>
<P>
   Autocratic systems isolate the men at the top. When Pinochet
held a plebiscite in 1988, he and his acolytes could not conceive
of losing. They lived in luxury apartments or bucolic estates. But
they could not see that the boom they enjoyed was not shared. The
poor, whose consumption levels had dropped steadily, were invisible
_ in part because bus fares were so high people could not leave the
slums to beg.
</P>
<P>
   Hijacking a vote count _ or worse, annulling an election gone
awry _ is costly for dictators interested in legitimacy. It is very
visible, and by the time a dictatorship is defeated, democratic
forces have usually acquired a momentum that is hard to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Autocrats prefer subtler forms of manipulation _ bribing voters,
intimidating the opposition, blocking voter registration and
monopolizing television. They design rules to allow them to keep
power even if they lose. Robert Mugabe in Zimbabwe controls the
appointment of 30 members of Parliament. In Cambodia, Hun Sen's
electoral rules in 1998 allowed him to convert minority popular
support into a parliamentary majority.
</P>
<P>
   Until the world can organize a conspiracy of pollsters who will
assure autocrats that they are so beloved that they can afford to
call off the thugs and give the opposition equal television time,
it must take manipulation of the campaign climate and election
rules as seriously as election-day fraud. No election with these
flaws should be declared ``free and fair,'' as a U.N.-sponsored
group termed Hun Sen's 1998 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, monitors from the Organization of American States
pulled out of Peru before the electoral runoff because the campaign
had been so orchestrated. Nevertheless, the OAS accepted Alberto
Fujimori's re-election. A spotlight on campaign abuses will help
only if outsiders are serious about defending democracy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
