<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-LARKIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS MAKE DEAL FOR, NOT WITH, LARKIN
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The New York Mets are prepared to go to great lengths
to get Barry Larkin to agree to join them for the stretch run. But
the one thing they seem unwilling to do is the one thing Larkin may
want most from them. Unless the Mets give him a contract extension,
Larkin, the 36-year-old Cincinnati Reds shortstop, seems likely to
stay put.
</P>
<P>
   Mets general manager Steve Phillips, who reached an agreement on
a deal for Larkin on Thursday, received permission from the
commissioner's office to speak with him starting 10 a.m. Saturday.
The Mets have until 10 a.m. Tuesday to persuade Larkin to accept
the deal. As a 10-year veteran who has spent the last five years
with one team, Larkin has veto power over trades.
</P>
<P>
   Before Phillips spoke Saturday with Larkin and his agent, Eric
Goldschmidt, he told Reds general manager Jim Bowden of his
intentions regarding Larkin. Phillips told Bowden he intended to
retain Larkin for the rest of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin said ``it depended on if the Mets were willing to sign
him to a multiyear contract,'' Bowden told The Cincinnati Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said our understanding at this time was that they're not
interested in doing that,'' Bowden continued. ``He didn't answer me
right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said Bowden's characterization of his position was
accurate. While the Mets could offer Larkin a bonus for agreeing to
a deal, the 11-time All-Star seems to be insisting on an extension.
The Reds turned down Larkin's request for a three-year, $27.9
million contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets played an afternoon game in Atlanta Saturday and have a
night game on Sunday. But when Phillips spoke with Larkin and
Goldschmidt Saturday morning, he offered to bring a contingent of
Mets to meet with Larkin in Cincinnati Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said manager Bobby Valentine, the former Larkin
teammates John Franco and Lenny Harris of the Mets, plus one or
both of the Mets owners, Nelson Doubleday and Fred Wilpon _ and any
other interested Mets personnel _ were prepared to take Wilpon's
private jet to meet Larkin. But Goldschmidt told Phillips he wanted
to ``talk through the issues'' before agreeing to a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are off on Monday, and Phillips said such a meeting is
more likely to take place then. But the general manager is eager to
get together, even though Wilpon's plane was still in the New York
area Saturday morning. ``They're revving the engines on the
runway,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who called Larkin on Friday night but had not heard back
from him before Saturday's game, said that he had no plans to fly
to Cincinnati and that he doubted Larkin would be influenced by a
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think so,'' said Harris, who considers Larkin
one of his best friends. ``Barry just wants to get paid. If they're
going to take care of his contract, he'll be here playing. Simple
as that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are resisting signing Larkin to a long-term deal
because they have committed $16 million over the next three years
to the injured Rey Ordonez, and because they covet Seattle
shortstop Alex Rodriguez, who, like Larkin, can be a free agent
this winter. Larkin's skills have not declined markedly despite his
age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he still has years ahead of him,'' Phillips said. ``He
still is moving well and has his agility, his acceleration in his
stride.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin continues to play for the Reds even during the 72-hour
negotiating window, and Phillips said the Mets will not hold out of
action the players they have agreed to trade to the Reds, wherever
they are in the organization. A baseball official said the former
No. 1 overall draft pick Paul Wilson, who has not pitched in the
majors since 1996 but is doing well at Triple-A Norfolk, may be
part of the package.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips also said the Larkin trade is not holding up other
deals. The Mets continue to explore other deals, with pitching
their first priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing that we're talking about hinges on this,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
