<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   G8-CLINTON _ Okinawa _ The Group of Seven industrialized
nations, plus Russia, holds a three-day summit meeting to discuss
everything from U.S. plans for a national missile defense (NMD)
system to increased trade to Third World debt. Developing. (Chao,
Cox News Service) Expected to move spot in both
International/Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-AID _ BOGOTA, Colombia _ The U.S. Congress has passed a
$1.3 billion aid package for Colombia, but many wonder if the money
will be too little too late to save a country beset by violence,
civil war and a powerful leftist guerrilla army. Some critics fear
the U.S. is stepping into a Vietnam-style quagmire by sending
military advisors and sleek new helicopters to help battle
Colombia's drug lords, who along with Marxist guerrillas control
vast areas in the countryside. Meanwhile, Colombian President
Andres Pastrana is battling plummeting public support, a deep
recession, icy relations with the national congress, corruption
charges and stalled peace talks. (Williams, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-FARC _ SAN VICENTE, Colombia _ Fueled by tribute from
coca-growers and drug lords, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia or FARC has become one of the most potent leftist
insurgencies in Latin American history. Ceded a Switzerland-sized
chunk of territory last year by Pastrana, the FARC shows no signs
of compromising in peace talks as they consolidate their control.
Profile of the group, its leaders, origins and history, set in San
Vicente, the capital of the rebel-held territory. WITH PHOTOS. With
map of map of Colombia and areas controlled by rebels and
coca-growing regions; chart of U.S. aid to Colombia over the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
   MOVED Wed., July 19.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DIVORCE _ BEIJING _ The southern province of Guangdong,
one of China's most prosperous, has seen a resurgence of a feudal
practice the Communists eliminated 50 years ago: concubines.
Affairs and divorces have been on the upswing for years in China,
but men in Guangdong have taken marital infidelity to a new level _
they are known to take a mistress _ or even two or three _ set them
up in a house, even have children with them. For wives who want a
divorce, laws are so inadequate, it could mean years of poverty for
them. The problem has become so serious, the province issued anew
legal directive that makes it easier for wives to get a share of
what their husband bought for the other woman. (Chao, Cox News
Service) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   COVERDELL-MOOD _ Live coverage of Saturday's memorial service in
Atlanta for Sen. Paul Coverdell. (Martz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COVERDELL-MAIN _ Main story on Sen. Paul Coverdell's death.
(Foskett, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COVERDELL-BAXTER _ Column on Coverdell's legacy. (Baxter,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COVERDELL-SUCCESSION _ What happens now with Coverdell's seat? A
look at what Gov. Barnes will do. (Sherman, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   ALADUMP _ LOWNDESBORO, ALA. _ The historic Selma-to-Montgomery
voting rights trail, U.S. Highway 80, runs through rural Lowndes
County, meandering past tracts of dusty farmland, boarded-up gas
stations and sacred civil rights-era ground. A racially mixed group
of developers and county officials, including some who hold office
thanks to the voting rights crusade, feel the 670-acre landfill is
just the thing to jump-start the economy of one of the state's
poorest counties. But landfill opponents, also a mix of blacks and
whites, say a dump near U.S. 80 would be an affront to the memory
of the marchers and hurt both the environment and a fledgling
tourist industry. Last week, the Alabama Department of
Environmental Management granted a permit for a landfill. We take a
look a the issues. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTERS _ CHARLESTON, S.C. - As he strolls amid the history of
this city where his family has lived for more than three centuries,
Pinckney Seabrook Wilkinson is alarmed by the declining population.
Not of people, but of shutters. ``You see how silly the house looks
without them,'' said the College of Charleston English instructor
and self-appointed guardian of the historic district's exterior
window dressings. Though few, if any, are so fretful, Wilkinson
said the shutters are disappearing as well-heeled out of towners
snap up historic houses and, during renovation, are not aware, or
do not care, about zoning rules that require shutters to be
replaced. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BRUNSWICK _ BRUNSWICK, Ga. _ When Kendra McCrae stormed into the
Brunswick city manager's office recently and demanded an audience,
it was another sign of the continuing unrest in the coastal city
that has spawned violence, marches and calls for change. McCrae, a
28-year-old secretary, was upset over mistreatment she says she and
other blacks received at the hands of police during a July 4th
altercation. That holiday weekend confrontation, which eventually
turned violent, led to a subsequent protest march on Monday (July
17) with others planned. It has also revealed a wider set of
grievances. A loose coalition of residents and ministers is now
calling for sensitivity training for police, a community-wide forum
to discuss racial differences and better economic opportunities for
the city's black population. We examine the continuing evolution of
a city in transition. (Chapman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BARTON-VICTIMS _ The lives that were changed by Mark Barton's
rampage; the woman who was robbed of her sight by Barton; the widow
who wakes up each day alone; the day traders who can't help but
shudder when they walk into their Buckhead office ... For this
story the reporters initially assigned to keep in touch with the
survivors and the families of the dead will go back and chronicle
how they have coped in the year since the shooting. (Judd, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GROWING PAINS FOR THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   Eds: The following two stories, about growing pains for the
Internet in a period of rapid worldwide growth, are suitable for
twinning or use as a series.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-HARDWARE _ WASHINGTON _ Even as the Internet is hailed
for expanding the horizons of millions of users and energizing the
world economy, there's concern it could become the victim of its
own success. Rapid growth of sites and users poses the very real
nightmare that this massive online structure,
</P>
<P>
   representing a $650 billion investment, could come crashing down
in gigantic cyber-traffic jams. (Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HARDWARE-DATA _ For a graphic, growth in number of computers
attached to the Internet. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Both stories MOVED Monday in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SOFTWARE _ WASHINGTON _ WWW.any-site.com. To American
ears, this familiar pattern identifies a World Wide Web site on the
Internet. The system seems simple and settled, but a global battle
is being waged this summer over how addresses will be assigned to
keep pace with rapid Internet growth. The stakes are enormous. If
plans to establish private control over the Internet's address
system founders on technical details and political disputes, the
global expansion of the online community could become gridlocked.
But if it succeeds, Americans will have to get used to having the
Internet governed by an international body that may be located in
Switzerland (Geewax, Cox News Service)
