<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0046 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT &LR;      07-22 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REED IS SHARP;   LARKIN TRADE   NOT COMPLETED
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This was the game Rick Reed wanted to pitch nine
months ago. Reed was the New York Mets' scheduled starter for the
seventh game of the National League Championship Series last
October, and twice in the late innings of the sixth game, the Mets
took the lead and seemed poised to give Reed his chance.
</P>
<P>
   That never happened, of course, as the Atlanta Braves came back
to beat the Mets and capture another World Series berth. The Mets
went home and had months to dwell on what could have been.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets will bolster their chances for advancing further this
season if the Cincinnati Reds' shortstop, Barry Larkin, agrees to
be traded to New York by Tuesday. But Larkin is not with the team _
though the Mets' courtship has formally begun _ and as manager
Bobby Valentine said, ``I believe it's not the best team that wins,
but the team that plays the best.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets played the best Saturday, and Reed had much to do with
it. The right-hander has said he never thought much about his
missed opportunity last fall; this is a new season. But it takes a
while to break a spell, and the Braves have one on the Mets,
especially at Turner Field. Reed did his best to overcome the hex,
and his seven shutout innings led the Mets to a 4-0 victory. They
won for just the second time in their last 17 games here.
</P>
<P>
   At his best, Reed pitches like Greg Maddux, the Braves' ace, who
opposed him. His stuff is not overwhelming, but he can throw it
with uncanny precision and is very tough when he does.
</P>
<P>
   The two were nearly identical Saturday _ Maddux threw 88
pitches, including 60 strikes, in eight innings; Reed threw 87
pitches, including 57 strikes, in seven innings. Maddux permitted
five hits, Reed just four. Both pitchers issued one walk.
</P>
<P>
   But Reed (5-2) won because he kept the Braves from hurting him
when it mattered. The Braves batted seven times with a runner on
base, and had no hits in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets battered Maddux at Shea Stadium on July 1, scoring
seven runs in two innings in Maddux's shortest start in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, the four-time Cy Young award winner, was better
Saturday, making the Mets put the ball in play and his only walk,
to Melvin Mora in the fifth inning, was intentional.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Zeile had opened the fifth with a double, and Jay Payton
singled him to third. After a ground out advanced Payton to second
and Mora walked, Reed came up and lofted a fly ball to center, deep
enough to score Zeile and give the Mets a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The lead could have been wider had Payton been called safe
trying to advance to second on a single in the second inning. His
hit scored Mike Piazza, and when Payton was called out advancing,
Valentine bolted to the field to argue the call.
</P>
<P>
   He continued the argument after the inning, jawing with the home
plate umpire, Andrew Fletcher, before another umpire got between
them and Valentine retreated to the dugout. He spoke with the
umpires some more after Armando Benitez recorded the game's final
out.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell, who had a .175 career average off Maddux in 57
at-bats, homered to lead off the sixth inning to increase the Mets'
lead to 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, meanwhile, could do almost nothing with Reed,
although their Nos. 2 through 6 hitters came into the game with a
combined average of .329 off him. Only one Brave advanced to second
base against him.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who was shaky in the early innings of his last start but
finished it strong, opened this game with perfection. He set down
the first eight hitters, gave up a single to Maddux, then got a
strikeout to end the third inning and double plays to help him out
of the fourth, fifth and seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh inning was typical. Reed stayed ahead in the count
on Chipper Jones, who finally bounced a ball up the middle and beat
out an off-balance throw by second baseman Joe McEwing. Brian
Jordan promptly grounded into his second double play of the day,
and after Reed allowed a single to Andres Galarraga, he patted his
chest as he looked at Piazza, his catcher: My fault, and no
problem. Bobby Bonilla flied out softly. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
