<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0047 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COVERDELL-SUCCESSOR07     07-22 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-SUCCESSOR0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Everyone's chatting on who will fill vacancy
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes made an unexpected flying visit
Wednesday to Blairsville, which happens to be near Young Harris,
which happens to be the home of former Gov. Zell Miller.
</P>
<P>
   But such is the level of intrigue following the death last week
of Sen. Paul Coverdell that Barnes's aides refused to say whether
the two Democrats met, much less whether they discussed Miller's
willingness to take Coverdell's place in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Georgia's congressional Republicans met twice
last week in an effort to figure out who among them would run for
Coverdell's seat. Those discussions were inconclusive, but at least
five of the eight Republicans have some level of interest, said two
House members who attended the meetings, but would not be quoted by
name.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans are even talking about getting Coverdell's
widow, Nancy Coverdell, to run for the seat. Asking her ``would be
a correct protocol,'' said Georgia GOP chairman Charles ``Chuck''
Clay.
</P>
<P>
   But Clay said he is unaware whether the issue has been broached.
Nancy Coverdell had little involvement in politics during her
husband's long career in elected office.
</P>
<P>
   The public silence surrounding the issue of succession is, in
part, a show of respect in the immediate aftermath of Coverdell's
death. No politician wants to seem too opportunistic at a moment
better reserved for mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, who also met with former Sen. Sam Nunn for more than a
half hour Friday, declined to discuss the appointment issue before
Coverdell's memorial service Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to talk about it. I think it's inappropriate and
I think it's disrespectful,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   But the political reality is that the identity of the next
senator is all anyone in Georgia politics is talking about.
Coverdell's death has transformed a sleepy political year in
Georgia and created an opening the likes of which was last seen in
1971, after the death of Sen. Richard Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes presumably will announce Coverdell's interim successor in
the coming days. But that person will have to win the seat again in
a special non-partisan election in November.
</P>
<P>
   The opening has implications for the presidential campaign in
Georgia. The selection of an African-American, for instance, could
produce a record turnout among heavily Democratic black Georgians
and boost Vice President Al Gore's chances in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of vice presidential running mates also could affect
the Senate contest, especially if Republicans select a minority,
said Merle Black, an Emory University political scientist.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Miller is the first and last name among Democrats.
``He'd be as formidable as anybody I know,'' said Rep. Larry Walker
(D-Perry), the Democratic leader in the state House.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Miller will accept is anyone's guess. He declined to
run against Coverdell two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   If he should decide to remain in political retirement, Barnes
faces a potential headache. ``He'd have all of the factions
lobbying hard,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Other names that have surfaced in the event Miller is not
interested include: Secretary of State Cathy Cox, a rising
Democratic star; former Rep. George ``Buddy'' Darden, an old friend
of the governor; Rep. John Lewis, who has openly indicated his
availability; former Secretary of State Lewis Massey; Rep. Cynthia
McKinney and state Sen. Charles Walker of Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   All but Lewis are little known statewide, an obstacle in so
short a campaign. Lewis, McKinney and Walker are black, and no
black candidate has won a high-profile statewide election in
Georgia, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans agree that Miller is the only Democrat who is likely
to cause some Republicans to stay out of the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller's candidacy might not scare off Republicans who hope
to raise their profile for the next round of statewide elections in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jack Kingston has made a reputation for himself in
Washington as a bright, articulate Republican whose youthful
appearance and sense of humor takes the edge off his conservative
politics.
</P>
<P>
   But Kingston is virtually unknown outside the Savannah area, and
even in what could be a losing effort against Miller, Kingston
could win favorable reviews that would make him the choice of
Republicans two years from now, when Sen. Max Cleland is up for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think that he would be interested in building name
recognition for the next time,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   The deliberations of Georgia's congressional Republicans are
complicated by the strong possibility that some of their seats
would fall to Democrats if no incumbent is running.
</P>
<P>
   Kingston, Bob Barr, Saxby Chambliss, Johnny Isakson and John
Linder are exploring to different degrees whether to run for the
Senate, said the two Georgia House members.
</P>
<P>
   Barr's and Chambliss's seats in particular would be vulnerable
if they were to run. And with Republican control of the House
hanging by a thread, the GOP can ill afford to lose two seats they
are now favored to hold.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson might at first blush appear to be the GOP's strongest
candidate, with his previous experience in statewide campaigns and
his suburban Atlanta base.
</P>
<P>
   But conservative groups are unlikely to allow Isakson to have
the field to himself because of his moderate politics, especially
on the abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson indelibly etched his support of abortion rights in
television commercials for his 1996 Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Isakson's colleagues are unenthusiastic about his
candidacy and will not stand aside for him, the two congressmen
said.
</P>
<P>
   The group agreed that no one would declare his candidacy before
the delegation's next meeting, which may take place as early as
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
