<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0050 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-NEGLECT-CASE-2TAKES-K     07-22 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEGLECT-CASE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN AGENCY DOESN'T HELP, GRANDPARENTS GO TO COURT FOR CUSTODY OF
BABY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONNA McGUIRE  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With sidebar slugged NEGLECT-SIDE
</P>
<P>
   SEDALIA, Mo. _ The digital clock read 2:36 a.m. when a phone
call jolted Len and Carol Hall awake.
</P>
<P>
   Len snatched the receiver and handed it to his wife. He scurried
to another phone and clicked on a tape recorder. It was their son,
John.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have your grandparents' rights pulled,'' John
snarled. ``You're dead to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are trying to do,'' Len said, ``is protect our
granddaughter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You,'' John answered, ``are not going to see your
granddaughter again.''
</P>
<P>
   Len filled with anger. Tears streamed down his wife's face.
</P>
<P>
   For months, they had argued with their son and daughter-in-law
about feeding, hygiene and other issues involving their infant
granddaughter, Becky. They fretted when she threw up after being
fed sour and weak formula. They photographed a diaper rash that
oozed. They kept a log that eventually grew more than an inch
thick.
</P>
<P>
   State child-welfare workers intervened, then withdrew, saying
that there wasn't enough neglect for them to act and that the
agency's involvement had worsened relations between the families.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us our standards were too high,'' said Carol Hall,
52.
</P>
<P>
   To the elder Halls, this was a clear case of a child needing
protection. They thought the Missouri Division of Family Services,
which once had named Carol Hall its volunteer of the year, had let
them down.
</P>
<P>
   But Family Services doesn't require perfect parenting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that we are not doing what they would like to see
happen and they could do a better job,'' said Anna Stone, who
oversees Family Services' child-welfare programs. ``But that's not
where we start. We start by looking at the family itself to see
what services we can offer to keep the children in their own
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by Family Services' failure to do more, Len and Carol
Hall ultimately hired a lawyer to help them prove their son and his
wife were unfit parents. The middle-of-the-night phone call from
John had come after he had received the court papers. In coming
months, the grandparents would spend $6,000 to win guardianship of
Becky.
</P>
<P>
   The postal worker and his wife said it never should have come to
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could come up with enough for a judge, Family Services
could have done more,'' said Len Hall, 52. ``How many more kids are
out there who don't have family who will go through hell like we
did?''
</P>
<P>
   The threshold for removing children from their families is
loosely defined, varies between communities and evolves over time.
</P>
<P>
   Family Services doesn't provide workers a list of situations to
consult. There's not even a hard rule on when a child can be left
home alone. Unless abuse is severe, responses aren't black and
white. The situation is similar in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   A national agency once sent photographs showing welt marks on a
boy's back to jurisdictions around the country and asked: Does this
constitute abuse?
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who said yes were appalled by those who said no,''
said David Kierst Jr., a Jackson County Family Court official.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, the Child Welfare League of America asked state
agencies whether the abuse threshold had changed. Nearly half said
they turned away cases they had handled five years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In neglect cases, it's difficult for courts to remove children
unless the neglect is flagrant, said Linda Spears, the Child
Welfare League's director of child protection.
</P>
<P>
   Many neglected children aren't in imminent danger but may be at
risk for long-term harm, she said, and the child welfare system is
poorly structured to measure that harm.
</P>
<P>
   Agencies and courts usually take their cues from community
standards. Yet in Jackson County, Family Court's standards
sometimes disagree with Family Services' standards, said Kierst,
who wants a committee to develop uniform guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life would be simpler if there were real black and white
rules,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Len and Carol Hall would agree.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-month romance, John and Coby Hall married in October
1996.
</P>
<P>
   He was 21 and rebellious. He said he saw the marriage as a way
to jab his parents, who disapproved of Coby.
</P>
<P>
   She was 19, divorced and six months pregnant with her fourth
child. Each had a different father.
</P>
<P>
   None of her three other children lived with her. After
abandonment allegations, her two oldest went to Family Services.
Her ex-husband had the third. When the fourth arrived three months
after her marriage to John, Coby gave it up for adoption. John was
not the father. Coby said she was unsure who was.
</P>
<P>
   The Halls' granddaughter, Jadelynn Rebecca Hall, arrived April
27, 1998. The next month, medical records show, Becky was diagnosed
with her first of six infected diaper rashes.
</P>
<P>
   Blame poor hygiene, the grandparents say. They complain that
Coby routinely left soiled and wet diapers on Becky too long.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, Coby said. Becky was allergic to certain diapers, that's
all.
</P>
<P>
   The families argued often over formula, inappropriate foods,
constipation remedies and living conditions. The grandparents
worried about Becky's small size, a possible sign of inadequate
nourishment.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the spreading diaper rash blistered and oozed,
reminding Carol of raw hamburger. After a pediatrician refused to
call Family Services, the Halls agonizingly chose to tattle on
their own son.
</P>
<P>
   State law prohibits child-welfare workers from discussing
specific cases. But, statewide, most neglect allegations wind up
unsubstantiated. In this case, Family Services left Becky with her
parents in Sedalia. The agency even recommended that the courts
return Coby's two oldest children to her care.
</P>
<P>
   Len caught Family Services' decision to withdraw on a tape
recorder hidden in his pocket during a meeting also attended by
Carol and Coby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not finding the level of neglect that would remove the
children from the home,'' a Family Services worker said. ``We
continue to get reports through the hot line and are unable to
substantiate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Becky, a blond baby with dark chocolate eyes, was 4 months old.
</P>
<P>
   Days later, Len Hall photographed conditions inside his son's
home. One picture shows mold on food-encrusted dishes. Another
shows bare mattresses on the floor in the children's rooms. A third
shows a door lock on the outside of a bedroom door, allowing
parents to lock the children inside.
</P>
<P>
   The Halls returned to Family Services with their new evidence
and more pleas for help. Again they were rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them: If this is what Family Services considers
acceptable,'' Len recalled in a wavering voice, ``then I don't care
for them anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Let down by an agency they had supported for years, including
shopping for foster children at Christmas, the Halls searched for
other options.
</P>
<P>
   They found help in a place they thought handled only wills and
estates.
</P>
<P>
   Probate court?
</P>
<P>
   The Halls were surprised. Their lawyer said they could seek
guardianship of Becky in Pettis County probate court.
</P>
<P>
   There were no guarantees. Plus, guardianship carried a risk.
Unlike the finality of terminating parental rights in family court,
guardianship could be overturned if John and Coby changed their
ways.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   ... changed their ways.
</P>
<P>
   John and Coby had just moved to Kirksville when they were served
with the court papers. Becky was about 7 months old.
</P>
<P>
   Her age would double before the case reached Judge Robert
Koffman's Sedalia courtroom in the summer of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first witnesses, a psychologist who had examined John
and Coby, doubted their ability to be good parents. He said John
had a personality disorder, though not a monumental one. He said
Coby lacked nurturing ability, got no gratification from mothering,
felt no compassion for others' pain, lacked the ability to bond and
could not learn from mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Would she cook for her kids? Not unless she was hungry, the
psychologist said. Would she be able to change diapers regularly?
That would be beyond her capacity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A former baby sitter testified that she left Becky's diaper bag
on her porch because roaches crawled from it. She described diaper
rashes that bled and recounted bathing Becky three times a week
because she arrived dirty. She said she wouldn't let her dog live
in John and Coby's home.
</P>
<P>
   An acquaintance of John and Coby's recounted watching Coby throw
pieces of pizza on the floor for Becky to eat _ an allegation Coby
later denied.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the testimony from Coby's ex-husband, who
fathered her third child. He told how, at one point after they
divorced, Coby gave him their infant daughter to keep Family
Services from taking her.
</P>
<P>
   The baby appeared sick, so he took her to a hospital. She had
pneumonia, E. coli bacteria in her bloodstream and a severe urinary
tract infection. She had gained only 3 ounces since her birth six
months earlier. Doctors hospitalized her for 10 days. Coby later
said she hadn't realized the infant was ill, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After several others testified, including Becky's grandparents,
it was John and Coby's turn. They denied most accusations. They
pleaded to keep Becky.
</P>
<P>
   Said John: ``I love that little girl with all my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Coby: ``I try to be a good parent. Children don't come with
a manual. I was 15 years old when I got pregnant and had my first
kid. I'm not saying I'm perfect, but I try my damndest _ my
darndest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sorry about what you've done?'' Coby's attorney asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' she replied, sniffling. ``I've never been proud of
what I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, the grandparents' attorney raised
questions about John and Coby's character.
</P>
<P>
   Though John had stolen money from an employer to buy a mobile
home, he said, he later paid it back. Yes, he had worked more than
15 jobs in two years. Yes, he once gave his parents written
permission to care for Becky after Coby ran out on him. But Coby
returned.
</P>
<P>
   How many times had Coby been hot lined? At least 20, she
answered. Yes, she had smoked marijuana, but only as a child. She
had been partying too much to know who had fathered her fourth
child.
</P>
<P>
   After closing arguments, Koffman took a recess. He would
announce his decision in 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Len and Carol Hall's attorney flashed them a thumbs-up sign. He
felt confident.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Halls had knots in their stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's probate courts routinely handle guardianship cases
involving minors. The number of cases has increased through the
1990s. The latest statistics, from June 1999, showed 10,356 open
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Grandparents, other relatives and foster parents are among those
who seek guardianship for various reasons, often because of
parental deaths or imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Koffman handles two or three cases a month in Sedalia and
expects the number to increase.
</P>
<P>
   In Clay County, Judge Larry D. Harman estimated that
grandparents were involved in a third to a half of the 251 cases
his court had as of May 31.
</P>
<P>
   Often, Family Services is not involved. When a former Division
of Family Services case ends up in probate court, that doesn't mean
Family Services has failed, judges say.
</P>
<P>
   That includes the Hall case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see DFS doing anything bad here,'' Koffman said months
after issuing his ruling in the Hall case. ``If this were an abuse
case, yes. But there were no physical injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   There are times Family Services directs family members to
probate court, which might do something when juvenile or family
courts cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Stangler, Missouri's social services director, pointed that
out in a letter to Len and Carol Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Removing a child from a parent is something that juvenile
court judges take extremely seriously, and do so only when all
other reasonable efforts to protect the child have failed,'' the
letter said. ``In situations like that, we may recommend to family
members who are concerned that they seek advice from a private
attorney regarding possible legal courses of action. In your case,
you did so.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter didn't placate the Halls, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's costing us out the wazoo,'' Len said. ``Not everyone can
afford to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   During Becky's hearing, Koffman warned the parties that a
cluttered house showed nothing and that he couldn't remove a child
just because parents were poor.
</P>
<P>
   As he summarized key testimony, his tone and words conveyed the
direction in which he was heading.
</P>
<P>
   Len and Carol Hall began to cry softly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt this child is at risk if allowed to remain
with the parents at this time,'' Koffman said that July day a year
ago. ``The court finds by full and convincing evidence the parents
are unfit and unable to perform duties of natural guardians.''
</P>
<P>
   He named Len and Carol Hall as Becky's guardians, announced a
visitation schedule and then looked at Coby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, Coby,'' he began, ``if I had jurisdiction over
your other kids, I'd have taken them, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Coby broke into sobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't. So that's the way it is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Now more than 2 years old, Becky Hall has a corner bedroom
decorated in a Precious Moments motif. It's where MaMaw, as Becky
calls her grandmother, rocks and sings her to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Becky's weight has more than doubled in the past year. She now
falls in the middle of growth charts instead of in the bottom
quarter. Her diaper rash is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Even her dad, John, thinks she looks better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my daughter is in the best place for her right now,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   John and Coby separated six weeks after losing Becky. They now
have visitation on separate weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Were his parents' standards too high, as Family Services said?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' said John, who is living in Sedalia again.
He realizes now that his parents only wanted Becky to have the same
care he had growing up.
</P>
<P>
   John eventually would like to regain custody of Becky. So would
Coby.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I know that will be a while,'' Coby said.
</P>
<P>
   After winning guardianship of Becky, the grandparents continued
their child protection crusade.
</P>
<P>
   They filed a complaint with the Missouri Board of Healing Arts
against the pediatrician who refused to call the child-abuse hot
line. They testified in Jefferson City for a bill that would have
relaxed child-abuse confidentiality laws, which might have helped
them obtain previous hot line reports involving Coby. They won
revised visitation so neither Coby nor John could keep Becky
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   They remain upset that Family Services didn't do more. They fret
about possibly losing Becky to John or Coby some day.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they're glad they found a way to rescue Becky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God,'' Carol said, ``for Judge Koffman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
