<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0053 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-NEGLECT-SIDE-KAN &LR;      07-22 0313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEGLECT-SIDE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT LINES AVAILABLE TO REPORT CHILD ABUSE AND NEGLECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Undated sidebar to NEGLECT-CASE-2TAKES
</P>
<P>
   Missouri and Kansas operate toll-free hot lines for people to
report suspected child abuse and neglect. Those hot lines are the
first step toward getting children removed from dangerous
situations.
</P>
<P>
   State investigators look for physical injuries, sexual abuse or
the failure to provide nutritional, medical or other care.
</P>
<P>
   In most Kansas and Missouri cases, allegations are not
substantiated.
</P>
<P>
   When abuse or neglect has occurred or is suspected, workers
often offer services to help parents correct problems. State
agencies want to preserve families whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   If agencies fear for children's safety, they seek court
permission to have the children removed into foster care or a
relative's home. This is done through juvenile or family court.
</P>
<P>
   Judges usually appoint a lawyer to represent the child as the
case progresses. Sometimes, judges terminate parental rights and
remove the child from its parents.
</P>
<P>
   If relatives feel child-welfare agencies or juvenile courts have
not done enough, they can challenge the parents in court, judges
and lawyers say.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, relatives have the right to file a
child-in-need-of-care case, which is handled in juvenile court. If
the case is proven, the judge may name the relative as guardian or
may choose to send the child to foster care or somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, relatives can seek guardianship in probate court,
where they must prove the parents unfit. The judge usually appoints
a lawyer to represent the child. Parents being sued have to obtain
their own attorney or represent themselves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State child abuse//neglect hot lines: Missouri: (800) 392-3738;
Kansas: (800) 922-5330
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
