<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olympic dreams
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After winning the final Tour time trial on Friday in near
record-breaking fashion, Lance Armstrong has set his sights on a
gold medal at the Olympics in Sydney in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning a gold medal would be one of the special highlights of
my career,'' said Armstrong, who is guaranteed a spot on his third
Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong finished sixth at the 1996 time trial. Two months
later, he was diagnosed with advanced testicular cancer.
</P>
<P>
   His main competition in the Olympics should be Jan Ullrich, who
finished 25 seconds behind Armstrong in Friday's 34.5-mile time
trial. Armstrong has won four of the last five individual time
trials the Tour has held, with his only loss coming in the 10-mile
prologue on July 1. David Millar beat Armstrong by two seconds.
</P>
<P>
   CATCHING UP ON JERSEYS
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong will wear the yellow jersey today, barring a
monumental crash.
</P>
<P>
   But the Tour also awards other jerseys. Here's a rundown on
who's wearing what:
</P>
<P>
   Green jersey for best sprinter: Eric Zabel. Polka dot jersey for
top climber: Santiago Botero. White jersey for best young rider:
Francisco Mancebo.
</P>
<P>
   An award with no jersey is the most combative rider. Erik Dekker
will earn this distinction. The top team is Kelme-Costa Blanca,
with Armstrong's U.S. Postal team in fourth place.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVELOGUE
</P>
<P>
   The Tour stopped in champagne country Saturday when the riders
traveled to Troyes. The city is on the River Seine, and it was
founded sometime in the third century under the Gallo-Romans. It
came of age in the Middle Ages thanks to the leadership of the
Comte de Champagne, who started the champagne fairs. The fairs were
an important exchange for merchants throughout Europe and the
Orient.
</P>
<P>
   The city, about a two-hour drive from Paris, doesn't just make
sparkling wine. It's also famous for its textiles and hosiery.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
