<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0056 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BRUNSWICK0723-COX     07-22 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUNSWICK0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Police battle with blacks spawns plans for change
 &HT;    By Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUNSWICK, Ga. _ It was a festive gathering of families marching
hand-in-hand, of children on bikes, of laughter and song.
</P>
<P>
   But when the 200 protesters reached Gloucester Street last
Monday and mounted the concrete steps to the Old City Hall, the
camaraderie disappeared. Preachers and citizens railed against the
``injustice'' and the ``disrespect'' shown by the police, the mayor
and other community leaders in their reactions to the July 4th and
5th violence which ended in injury and arson.
</P>
<P>
   One called Mayor Brad Brown a liar. Another demanded the mayor
apologize _ or resign. Yet another disparaged Brown ``and his
compadre Negro woman Venus Holmes'' _ the head of the local NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   Minister Odis Muhammad of the Nation of Islam summed up the ugly
events and warned the troubles may not be over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could've been a lot worse, and if we don't deal with it,''
Muhammad prophesied, ``it's going to get a lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody _ black or white, citizen or elected official, low-income
or high-roller _ wants more violence. It was bad enough, all say,
when the combustive mix of fireworks, alcohol and police exploded
in Brunswick and nearby St. Simons Island.
</P>
<P>
   But the episodes highlighted long-simmering resentment and
disrespect between many blacks and police in this coastal
community. It fueled the anger and animosity of those left behind
the Golden Isles economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   It also showed the deep chasm between young blacks and
Brunswick's old-guard black leadership, particularly the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People. Long the
country's pre-eminent civil rights group, the NAACP struggles to
recruit its next generation of members.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some good may come from the bad in Brunswick. The newfound
spirit _ an awakening of civil rights _ is engendering calls for
social and economic changes. The city manager responds with a slew
of cultural awareness and economic-development proposals.
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps the next generation of Brunswick's
up-from-the-streets leadership is coming of age. Kendra McCrae, a
28-year-old single mother and secretary, personifies the new
activism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm put here for exactly yet, but whatever I
can do for my people _ for anybody _ I will do,'' McCrae said the
morning after the march on Old City Hall. ``It's time. I want to be
heard.''
</P>
<P>
   McCrae grew up in and around the McIntyre Court public housing
complex where the partying run amok led to the minor injuries of
five police officers and the incineration of two cop cars.
</P>
<P>
   She witnessed the July 4th disturbance at Massengale Beach, when
police tried to arrest the father of her child for riding a
four-wheeler illegally on the beach. Under a hail of fireworks and
bottles, the police fled, only to soon return and order McCrae and
the other black beachgoers to leave.
</P>
<P>
   McCrae returned to her New Town neighborhood and watched the
party get crazy with fireworks and gunshots aimed skyward and
hundreds of people milling about. She witnessed the police arrest a
man _ her cousin _ for firing a gun into the air. She saw dozens of
men and women encircle the cops who tried to restore order. But
then the police fled, fearing for their lives, leaving behind two
patrol cars which were torched.
</P>
<P>
   McCrae doesn't condone the violence by the predominantly black,
youthful crowd. But she understands its genesis: years of being
ordered by police to move along, quit loitering, empty your
pockets, get out of the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're caging us up. They treat us like animals,'' she said.
``We might as well walk around with a bull's eye on our backs.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the melees from official Brunswick was swift. The
mayor, council members, the NAACP, and assorted preachers condemned
the violence and those who perpetrated it. Yet it was the mayor's
comments denigrating those involved in the disturbance _ ``all
hoodlums, drug dealers pimps for prostitutes'' _ which further
inflamed the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brad Brown is not my mayor,'' said McCrae, a high school
graduate who has lived in Hawaii and California. ``But I don't hate
him. I dislike what he said. You've just got to pray for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown backed off a bit from his incendiary comments. But he
dismissed calls that he apologize or resign. Brown blamed the media
for stirring things up and said the hullabaloo over the violent
events of July 4th and 5th was ``dying down and the community is
getting back to a normal scene.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was another, larger march Thursday evening with
protestors again demanding Brown apologize.
</P>
<P>
   For Monday's march, McCrae passed out hundreds of fliers and
begged, cajoled, and pressured folks to participate. (Her
grandmother showed up.) Once the windy preachers finished, McCrae
meekly read her speech from the steps of the colonial-styled Old
City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   McCrae comes by her newfound activist streak naturally. She's
known along I Street as a woman to turn to for a meal, for help
with a light bill, for a shoulder to cry on when a boyfriend or
husband does wrong. So it only seemed natural, she said, to call up
Brunswick's city manager, Roosevelt Harris Jr., and request a
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found her to be a well-spoken lady who seemed to understand
the needs of the young people of that particular area,'' said
Harris, who's black. ``It takes people like her, committed to the
community, to really get involved and help make some changes.''
</P>
<P>
   McCrae suggested after-school programs in her New Town
neighborhood, perhaps with adults as tutors. She mentioned creating
a jobs program for under-employed residents. McCrae, who also
complained to police about their actions July 4th and 5th, asked
that officers undergo greater cultural sensitivity training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put a lot into this,'' said McCrae, wearing an ``I'm A
Georgia Voter'' sticker on Election Day. ``I don't know why. My
heart says to do it. And I want is to be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said he'll bring his department heads together, including
the police chief, to determine what needs be done for one of
Brunswick's poorest neighborhoods. Harris talked of a nonprofit,
economic-development group and, perhaps, the purchase of a building
to house start-up businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Harris is also considering ``sensitivity sessions'' between
neighborhood residents and city and county officials to discuss
what transpired earlier this month and how to keep it from
happening again.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Holmes, for one, was ``outraged'' by the disturbances
which she found ``disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The black folk that did all that rioting _ they just put us in
a bad spotlight,'' said the president of the Brunswick branch of
the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   Yet those comments angered and alienated many blacks, young and
old, who disagreed that the melees could be characterized as riots.
They claimed Holmes was out of touch and didn't speak for the
majority of black Brunswick. Holmes didn't attend Monday's rally,
but the mention of her name was met derisively by marchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NAACP is not for us,'' McCrae later said. ``I can't
believe she made comments like that, that it disgusted her. She
shouldn't be down on us. Our own people got to quit talking
negative about us.''
</P>
<P>
   The discontinuity between Holmes and McCrae highlights the
divide between Brunswick's traditional black leadership and younger
blacks. It's also representative of the difficulty NAACP chapters
have in recruiting the new members.
</P>
<P>
   Inez Bouncer is the Brunswick Youth Council adviser. (She's 83.)
Her membership rolls have dropped precipitously. Two years ago,
there were 688 members younger than 21, Bouncer said. Today, there
are a ``little better than 300'' members.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes, an NAACP member for 37 years, defends her organization's
so-far tepid response to the July 4th and 5th troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NAACP can not jump into everything,'' said Holmes, who
plans to meet with the mayor this week to discuss his comments.
``We have to weigh things and find out what's going on. ... We want
to be part of what is good for the community. We're hoping that
these young kids, after all that has happened, realize that things
don't have to be the way they were.''
</P>
<P>
   McCrae vows that they won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be changes,'' she said. ``We will start
getting everybody involved. This is just a first step. Now, we're
ready. We are ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
