u k BC-GOTTLIEB-COLUMN25-COX     07-22 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOTTLIEB-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Tuesday.
 &HT;    TV's Downplaying of Conventions Raises Questions about Their
Role
 &HT;    By Martin Gottlieb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The political parties are upset that ABC, NBC and CBS don't
</P>
<P>
   plan to cover the national political conventions much. Ohio
Republican Party Chairman Robert Bennett, for example, whose party
is not known for antipathy to the make-a-buck ethic, wants the
networks to ``forgo their cash-cow entertainment shows to engage in
a little force-feeding of Democracy 101.''
</P>
<P>
   He charges that the networks foster low voter turnout when to
make their best pitches, make them repetitively, and make them to
the biggest possible audiences. That, typically, is the process
that resolves election. After that, the American people don't hear
much they haven't heard before. If they don't change their minds,
we shouldn't be surprised.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that what happens at conventions determines
who
</P>
<P>
   wins. Circumstances in the country (and the success of the
incumbent party in dealing with the problems of the country)
determine who wins. It's just that by the time the conventions are
over, the public has focused as much as it ever will upon those
circumstances. This focusing happens partly because both
presidential candidates look pretty impressive as individuals at
the conventions. So people stop thinking about personality so much.
</P>
<P>
   What about the future? Will the conventions stop being so
important if the networks downplay the conventions?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. After all, 2000 will not be the first year the
networks
</P>
<P>
   have cut back on convention coverage. The gavel-to-gavel
principle died long ago, and still we have seen no campaigns in
which the conventions didn't pretty much resolve things.
</P>
<P>
   The conventions still get enormous coverage. Besides whatever
prime-time coverage they get, they are featured in the regular news
shows.
</P>
<P>
   They dominate newspapers (which may still matter a little bit).
</P>
<P>
   The acceptance speech of a presidential nominee is an event of
</P>
<P>
   interest even to people who normally have little interest in
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who don't hang on every word hear an awful lot about
it.
</P>
<P>
   If television in general were to stop paying any attention to
the
</P>
<P>
   conventions at all, that might reduce the importance of
conventions in speeding the public toward a final judgment on the
candidates. But that probably would require a series of decisions
by more than ABC, CBS and NBC about more than prime time. It
doesn't seem to be in the cards.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, whether ``Who Wants to be A Millionaire?'' gets
pre-empted (fat chance) probably doesn't matter much.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Gottlieb writes for the editorial pages of the Dayton
Daily News. His book, ``Campaigns Don't Count: How the Media Get
American Politics All Wrong'' is available, free, online at
www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 1848EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0058 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HALL-OF-FAME0723-COX     07-22 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALL-OF-FAME0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A once in a lifetime tribute
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ This is the day Tony Perez and Sparky
Anderson never thought about while Perez was driving in runs in big
bundles and Anderson was leading The Big Red Machine to victories
in equally impressive big bundles.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's Hall of Fame is for Babe Ruth and Ty Cobb and Ted
Williams and Joe DiMaggio and Cy Young, baseball's icons.
</P>
<P>
   And this afternoon, in the gentle undulating hills outside of
Cooperstown, the Hall of Fame embraces Perez and Anderson, along
with catcher Carlton Fisk, Cincinnati outfielder Bid McPhee and
Negro League star Turkey Stearnes. Longtime Reds radio play-by-play
announcer Marty Brennaman also will be honored with the Ford C.
Frick Award for broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   It is a terrific twist of irony that Anderson, Perez and Fisk go
into the Hall of Fame at the same time because their lives are
intertwined back to Game 6 of the 1975 World Series and the
12th-inning game-winning home run hit by Fisk, a towering drive
right down the left field line on which Fisk stood at home plate
waving at the baseball to stay fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Fisk) was pulling it fair and I was pulling it foul,''
said Perez, who stood at first base and watched the pitch hit off
Pat Darcy clear the wall and stay fair for a 7-6 Boston Red Sox
victory. ``People ask me if Fisk said anything when he ran past me.
No way. I felt a breeze stir up after the ball landed for the home
run and it was Fisk sprinting past me as fast as he could go, blew
by me like a jet.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Anderson, ``Fisk made me sick. I didn't sleep and that
helped my team win the next day because I wasn't involved. Too
sleepy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Anderson's modus operandi, always deflecting credit and
praise the other way.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds won Game 7 in 1975, then swept four straight from the
New York Yankees in 1976. After that season, Perez was traded to
Montreal and the Reds were never the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already told Tony this and I've done it publicly from a
microphone. . .he deserved to hear an apology from me,'' Anderson
said. ``Tony Perez should have never, ever left Cincinnati. Bob
Howsam (the general manager who traded Perez) will tell you that
and I will stand up and take 50 percent of the blame because I
agreed to it. It was a terrible mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say he was good with our Latins? I'll tell you what? He
was good with every living human being on that club and, when he
left, and I started realizing right away, 'Something is wrong
here,' and it wasn't me,'' Anderson said. ``They could have kept
Perez and sent me to the Bahamas and they could have won again,
believe me. You can't undo it, but you have to stand up and be
counted about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson played only one year in the majors, a full season with
the Philadelphia Phillies, then disappeared back to the minors
forever as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never came close again,'' Anderson said. ``I realized that
the major-league level was not me. I was a star in Triple-A, but I
couldn't hit. (Phillies Manager) Eddie Sawyer let me play every
day, but he pinch-hit for me more than Casey Stengel pinch-hit for
Willie Miranda.''
</P>
<P>
   So Anderson turned to managing and became the only manager to
win the World Series in both leagues _ 1975-76 with Cincinnati and
1984 with Detroit and is on the brink of baseball enshrinement into
posterity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all dream, and every morning when I go for my walk I think,
'How did a boy from South Dakota leave a little town of 600 people
(Bridgewater) when he was 9 and get to this?''' Anderson said.
``And I'm very serious when I say it will take me, after coming
here this year, four or five more trips before in my heart I
believe I belong in this house. It is overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cincinnati made me very smart,'' Anderson added. ``And that
was hard because I'm a dummy and they had to work hard at it, but
that baseball team got the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, of course, swung the spotlight toward Atanasio Rigal
Perez, who waited nine years after he was eligible to win the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is such a beautiful game and you see somebody like
Tony Perez and you realize what the beauty of the game is,'' he
said. ``Here is a young man who came from Cuba and to know what
kind of a person he is. It is a wonderful to be a great player, but
it is not wonderful if you are a great player and cannot back it up
by being a great person. If you can't do that, you are just a
phony, God gave you great ability and you just took it and took it
to the Hall of Fame. But you don't really belong there because you
didn't back it up by being a great person. Tony Perez is a real
person, a great person.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson admitted he'll have jangling and tingling nerves when
he steps to the podium. Perez said he won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be nervous,'' Anderson said. ``Tony won't because he is
never nervous, which is what made him the outstanding clutch player
he was. I'm going to be wondering, 'What in the hell did I get into
and how in the hell did I get here?' The fear of God will be with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Perez, whose wife has worked hard on his speech with him
and made him practice, ``I feel great, although I was a little
disappointed in my golf game today. I've waited nine years, so I'm
not worried about my speech. I feel great to just be here, I'm
going to feel great and enjoy it because it's once in a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Perez paid tribute to all eight regulars of The Big Red Machine
_ not just the Hall of Famers like Johnny Bench, Joe Morgan and the
Hall of Fame-should be, Pete Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those guys _ George Foster, Ken Griffey, Dave Concepcion,
Cesar Geronimo _ those guys were as important for us as Bench or
Pete or Morgan or myself and if I was voting, all those eight guys
would be in the Hall of Fame,'' Perez said. ``I never played with
with a group of players like that where every one of them knew
exactly what to do every day to help the team win a ball game. For
Pete Rose not to be here in the Hall of Fame yet is something I
don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
