<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0059 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-REDS-LARKIN0723-COX     07-22 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDS-LARKIN0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Larkin takes a wait and see approach
 &HT;    By Sean McClelland
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEREA, Ohio _ A few of the Reds were having trouble figuring out
the dress code Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``See what Barry says,'' one said to another.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds have come to rely on shortstop and captain Barry Larkin
for so much. On the field. In the clubhouse. In the offseason,
luring superstars to town. It's a stretch to say they can't get
dressed without him, but sometimes it seems that way.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the Reds beat the Arizona Diamondbacks, 7-3, on
Saturday while wearing black undershirts and black caps with red
bills. Maybe it was Larkin's last day in a Reds uniform. If it was,
he will remember it for the standing ovation that lasted several
minutes when he came to bat in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an emotional at-bat,'' Larkin said later, his immediate
baseball fate nine innings closer to realization.
</P>
<P>
   Rooting for the captain to remain a Red has become pastime No. 1
for those who share his clubhouse. They know all about baseball's
economics and how some teams can afford big payrolls and others
can't. But they also wonder about loyalty _ not to marginal or
fringe players, but to such icons as Larkin, who grew up here,
became famous here and, to the best anyone could figure it, twice
took less money to stay here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure don't want it to happen,'' winning pitcher Ron Villone
(8-6) said of the trade with the New York Mets that is awaiting
only Larkin's approval. ``He's a mainstay, a leader and a great
player. He knows how to handle things. He doesn't get shaken _
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves what he wants. The guy is a class act. I guess
loyalty doesn't always mean you're going to be rewarded, but
sometimes you have to give it to someone who deserves it.''
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 42,568 obviously shared this opinion, showering
Larkin with cheers even after his third-inning strikeout. He went
1-for-5, hit into a double play and was caught stealing. Afterward,
he dressed quickly, paused to field a few questions and then went
to find his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to consider everything,'' Larkin said. ``You have to
see what happens. I thought I might not be here today, but I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Villone tortured the Reds for six innings. Starting in place of
Larry Luebbers, who had complained of forearm soreness, he threw 40
pitches in the second inning alone on his way to 123. But big hits
eluded the Diamondbacks and Villone, helped by what Arizona manager
Buck Showalter said were ``about 30'' missed pitches by home plate
umpire Darryl Cousins, somehow muddled through.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a good job getting through six innings,'' Reds manager
Jack McKeon said. ``He gets you (ticked) at him, but he battles
out. We were lucky to get six out of him the way he was going.''
</P>
<P>
   Helpful to Villone's cause was his own two-run single in the
second inning as the Reds seized a 3-1 lead. They never trailed
again, adding two in the third, two in the seventh. Juan Castro and
Dmitri Young had three hits apiece as the Reds abused three Arizona
pitchers, including the previously sensational rookie Geraldo
Guzman, a 27-year-old former carpenter who had been 2-0 with a 0.56
ERA in two starts.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin responded to his first ovation with a single. He made it
to second on a wild pitch, but tried to steal third and was gunned
down by Damian Miller. The crowd cheered anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are plenty of possibilities,'' Larkin said. ``I know
everyone is not in a situation where they can do exactly what I
want. We'll just have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
