<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0060 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-MISSOURI-VOTERS-KAN &LR;      07-22 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-VOTERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI'S UNDECIDED VOTERS COULD HELP DECIDE THE PRESIDENTIAL
RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOBERLY, Mo. _ For Al Gore and George Bush, the road to the
White House is likely to pass through places such as the Family
Tradition Restaurant in Moberly, where Bill Staggs is a regular for
morning coffee.
</P>
<P>
   History says the fall election will be decided by people such as
Staggs _ undecided voters in a state such as Missouri, which has
gone with the winning candidate all but once, 1956, in the past
century.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Gore and Bush would be wise to listen to Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore, he's pretty wishy-washy, and Bush, I just don't know the
man,'' said Staggs, retired from the U.S. Department of
Agriculture. ``I may not vote, but that doesn't solve anything,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with two dozen persons across Missouri during Gov.
Mel Carnahan's whistle-stop tour of the state last week indicated
that Gore and Bush had failed to define themselves, and neither was
seen as inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   On sunny railroad platforms and under cool shade trees, people
who came out to cheer Carnahan or simply listen were asked how they
felt about Gore and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Gore has the steeper hill to climb with voters, bearing
out a poll two weeks ago showing that he trailed Bush by 11 points
in Missouri while running nearly neck and neck with Bush
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apathy at the polling place will be his problem,'' said
retired farmer Ray Dunwoody of Moberly, a Democrat backing Gore.
``This is pretty much a Democratic stronghold here, and if he can
harness that vote, it will help.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has tried to exude more energy and passion on the stump,
but to some Missouri voters he still comes across as stiff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of like a mechanical man,'' said Bush supporter
Jesse Kruse on the front lawn of a house in Salisbury, next to the
Carnahan train. ``He looks like a robot, not like a real person.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has had a hard political act to follow in Clinton, some
supporters said. Indeed, Gore's years under Clinton seem to be a
mixed blessing in Missouri. The Monica Lewinsky scandal hasn't been
forgotten, but neither has the economic prosperity of the Clinton
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he can disassociate himself from Clinton,'' said
Bill Burke, a Louisiana, Mo., YMCA director who backed John McCain
but now supports Bush. ``History will recall the eight years of
Clinton and Gore as lacking values, and (a time) of dishonesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Brumbaugh, a restaurant manager in Hannibal, agreed that
a lot of people mentioned Gore and Clinton in the same breath.
Brumbaugh kept his distance from the Carnahan rally, leaning
against a shady picnic table with arms folded as he listened to the
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I'm a true Democrat or true Republican,''
Brumbaugh said. ``I've got to feel Bush is our next president, with
all the stuff that went on with Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The scandal may do the most damage with conservative or
religious Democrats in places such as Moberly that might otherwise
lean to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of religion in this area, so that may have a
little bearing,'' said Ted Thornburg, a Moberly Democrat running
for General Assembly. He said a good economy would offset some of
the Lewinsky scandal for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But even Clinton's strengths as president work against Gore with
some voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a big Clinton fan, but he's pretty good at finding
middle ground, and I don't know if Gore has that capacity,'' said
Jim Grotewiel, a cattle farmer and implement dealer from Clifton
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Gore needs to set out his own agenda, but his chances still
hinge on what credit he gets for the nation's economic boom,
several people said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democratic administration expanded the American Dream,''
said Maxwell Boafo, a Gore backer in Moberly. Bush, with no
experience on the national stage, would be less effective, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, appears to be doing a better job holding
Republicans in Missouri than Gore is holding Democrats, based on
interviews. Everyone who said they normally voted Republican said
they would back Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's honest,'' said Jeffrey Lloyd, a Lutheran minister from
Independence. ``I listen to Gore, and I don't think he's any more
honest than Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Bush backers based support for him partly on a disdain for
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very bland and not that bright,'' said Sydne Tustison, a
Moberly engineer.
</P>
<P>
   But some Democrats think Gore will intellectually outshine Bush,
whose intelligence has been the target of jokes by comics and
skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a lightweight,'' said Mary Abbott, a Kansas City area
real estate agent who was at the Independence rally for Carnahan.
``He bores me to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Personality and experience appear to be playing a key role in
Missouri voters' decisions on the candidates, but their stands on
the issues are also a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Tustison said that she liked Bush's views on abortion, taxes,
the death penalty and education and that Gore was hypocritical when
he criticized big oil companies while his family trust had a large
financial stake in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Several people said they preferred Gore because they thought he
was more pro-environment than Bush. But Gore's support for strong
emission standards handicapped some industries, said undecided
voter Grotewiel.
</P>
<P>
   The race in Missouri probably will be up in the air until
Election Day if everyone is like college-bound Robert Murphy, 18,
of Moberly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got pretty good candidates,'' Murphy said. ``It will be
a decision I will have to make right when I get there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star's Daniel Gutman contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
