<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0061 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-VEEP-1STLD-WRITE     07-22 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VEEP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-880(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BUSH LOOKS TO SAFE AND SOLID IN PICKING HIS RUNNING MATE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., N.Y., Mo., Pa., Ky., Wyo., Neb., Ohio, Tenn.) (ADDS ``foreign policy skills'' to 2nd graf of 2nd take)  
 (Eds.: 2nd take could be used as a separate story on pros and cons
of the possible choices.)  
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Walter Mondale tapped Geraldine Ferraro as his
running mate in 1984, he was so far behind that he felt, as he put
it the other day, he had to ``reshuffle the deck because the
economy was good and Reagan was popular.''
</P>
<P>
   When George Bush turned to Dan Quayle in 1988, his media
adviser, Roger Ailes, hoped that the young senator would have such
sex appeal that women might try to tear at his clothes.
</P>
<P>
   And when Bob Dole settled on an old foe, Jack Kemp, four years
ago, a crucial consideration was that it would be a surprise. Scott
Reed, the Dole campaign manager, said his boss had not worried
about how they would get along in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all about winning the election,'' Reed said. ``I had
confidence that the compatibility issue could be worked out
later.''
</P>
<P>
   But this time, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas seems to be steering
clear of the glamour and gloss _ and more toward the safe and
solid.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush secludes himself at his Texas ranch this weekend to make
up his mind on his single most important campaign decision so far,
a leading choice, his advisers say, is Richard Cheney. Cheney is a
respected but hardly electrifying former defense secretary and
former congressman who is running Bush's search for a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Others who have apparently survived to the homestretch include
two governors who are known more for their steadiness than star
quality: Frank Keating of Oklahoma and George Pataki of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheney is the CPA choice,'' one prominent Republican
strategist said. ``Competent. Quiet. And dull.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be by design. Bush's advisers say the governor is so
confident he will win the election that he is focused less on bald
electoral calculations for November 7 _ like whether his running
mate would make a state more competitive _ and more on who he wants
beside him on January 20, when he expects to be sworn in as the
next president.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason Bush appears to be less concerned about a No. 2
with pizazz is his recognition that, thanks to Bill Clinton, the
role of the vice president has broadened markedly. In picking Al
Gore, Clinton made the vice presidency more than an understudy's
job. It is now one that voters expect to be filled with a person of
substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be thought that vice presidential nominations were
decided on the basis of a hunch or right off the top of the head,''
said former Sen. John Danforth of Missouri, who apparently also
sits high on Bush's list _ and is known for his rectitude, not his
personality. ``Nowadays, it's a much more serious thing. The role
of the vice presidency has changed. It's not just the cipher job
that it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney would make ``a terrific choice,'' Danforth said, because
he has the credentials and temperament to function well in the
White House. Asked about another possibility, Sen. John McCain,
Danforth alluded to lingering strains between Bush and McCain from
the hotly contested primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``A president has to pick somebody he likes and is very, very
comfortable with,'' Danforth said. ``Or else, the vice president is
going to be stashed in a closet somewhere. It would be a reversion
to the previous idea of what a vice president is.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week on CNN's ``Larry King Live,'' Bush himself said:
``There's been the time in the past where people, competent people,
said, `Well, let's just pick the vice president. Don't worry, we'll
dump him once we get elected.'
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words,'' he added, ``use the person just for the
election vehicle. I'm not going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a choice that does not appear to be baldly political _
unlike picking Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania so he could deliver
his state's 23 electoral votes _ may have more appeal among voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush may be moving toward a less flashy choice because there are
only so many flashy possibilities. Several of his advisers agreed
that there was only one true marquee candidate who would bring
added value to the ticket _ Colin Powell _ and that Bush would snap
him up if he thought Powell was interested.
</P>
<P>
   Many advisers said McCain would also enliven the ticket, but
that Bush questioned how well he would tolerate McCain in the White
House. Some Bush advisers also said the governor would cringe at
the perception that he was forced to turn to McCain to assure him a
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain would add the most oomph to the ticket,'' said Sen.
Arlen Specter, R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Kellyanne Fitzpatrick, a Republican pollster, agreed, saying
McCain accomplished something few other Republicans have: ``He is
such an incredible choice that he's even had people in Hollywood
give him money.'' But she said ``an unexciting choice'' like
Keating or Cheney would be safe because ``we know in the end people
decide whom to vote for based on the top of the ticket rather than
the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be, of course, that Bush is using the speculation over
Cheney as a distraction while he readies his true decision, and has
a colossal surprise in mind. Maybe (with help from his father) he
can persuade Powell after all. Maybe there is even a mystery
selection.
</P>
<P>
   But Jack Kemp suggested that even Powell might not be so
perfect. ``The fact that he doesn't want it,'' he said, ``makes
them want him even more.''
 &UR;  &LR; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Powell aside, for every prospect, the upsides seem to cancel out
the downsides.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush picked Cheney, he would win plaudits from Republicans
who think Cheney would bring dignity, weight and foreign policy
skills to the ticket. And while he has a solidly conservative
voting record in Congress, Cheney has always worked well with
moderates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big leaguer,'' said Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who
has pressed for Cheney for weeks. ``No one would say, `I can't see
this guy as president.'''
</P>
<P>
   Others warned that Cheney, 59, is from a small state, Wyoming,
that is already safe bet for Bush to win. And, they said, he is
risky because of his health: He has had three heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   If he picks Keating, Bush would win raves from Republicans who
admire Keating's handling of the Oklahoma City bombing and his
credentials as a former prosecutor. Another plus is that he is
Roman Catholic, and Bush has been trying to reassure Catholics
after opponents suggested he was anti-Catholic. Others warn that he
is from a small state that is already solidly Republican and that
his conservative background would not broaden the ticket's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of McCain would energize moderates and
independents. But many conservatives warn that they would not abide
such a selection _ and would openly denounce McCain when the
Republican convention opens in Philadelphia in a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of problems,'' said David Keene, chairman of
the American Conservative Union. ``A lot of conservatives would be
very upset. It's hard to see him as a loyal team player who would
not be trying to upstage everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   There are pros and cons to the other prospects. Ridge, for one,
has a riveting rags-to-respectability biography and comes from a
battleground state. But some conservatives would deride his
abortion rights stand. Sen. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska has a
compelling military history and he has the foreign policy expertise
that Bush lacks. But he is relatively green in national politics.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki hails from a big state, but not even his own advisers
predict that he could deliver it to the Republicans. Another
factor, seemingly trivial, is that Pataki is about a half-foot
taller than Bush, and nominees never like being overshadowed.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, who would bring
vitality and a knowledge of Congress. But he has what some Bush
advisers say is the Quayle problem: he exudes youthfulness _ and
seems to lack gravitas.
</P>
<P>
   One who has star quality is Sen. Fred Thompson of Tennessee. He
was a movie actor, after all. But some Bush advisers express
concern that as a single man, Thompson would not project the
appropriate family image.
</P>
<P>
   The new imperatives for a running mate have made the selection
process complicated, if not confounding. Bush, and Gore, face often
conflicting pressures: They want running mates who can be both be
effective on the stump and in governing. They want someone who can
excite party loyalists but also attract independents.
</P>
<P>
   They want drama. But they have to be mindful that reaching for
the spectacular can be like a blind date with history. The result
can be fresh and intoxicating _ like Gore eight years ago _ or
disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   When Mondale picked Ferraro, he thought she would be an instant
draw for women. He was wrong. Four years later, the elder Bush
thought voters would find Quayle fresh and exciting. They did not,
but the ticket won anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Quayle did carry shock value. He was so little
known, even by Bush's own aides, that in New Orleans, the site of
the convention, they busily photocopied his biography in the
Almanac of American Politics so they could find out just who he
was.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides said their candidate has learned from his father's
experience that he need not be fixated on springing a surprise
(though he does like surprises) and that, more important, the
campaign has to be well prepared before announcing the choice. Bush
also learned a lesson from watching his father serve as Ronald
Reagan's No. 2 for eight years: He wants someone who is as loyal to
him as his father was to Reagan, but who also offers sound advice _
and does not stir the pot.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be so much simpler _ and swifter. In 1976, President
Gerald Ford began his deliberations in earnest only hours before
his No. 2 was announced. ``The meeting to decide on the nominee
didn't begin until 3:15 a.m.,'' Ford wrote in his memoirs, ``A Time
to Heal.'' Among those in the room was his chief of staff who would
resurface decades later in vice presidential politics: Dick Cheney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 1905EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
