<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0063 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-DUVAL-NYT &LR;      07-22 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DUVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR DUVAL, 2ND PLACE IS A PAIN
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ One of golf's oldest sayings is,
``Beware the ailing golfer.'' And through the years, ailing golfers
have won championships: Ken Venturi staggering with heat
prostration in the 1964 U.S. Open, and Ben Hogan wobbling on weary
legs in the 1950 U.S. Open after recuperating from injuries in a
highway crash.
</P>
<P>
   But if David Duval, six strokes behind Tiger Woods going into
Sunday's final round of the 129th British Open, were to somehow win
on the Old Course, he would justify the saying.
</P>
<P>
   Duval's ailing back was painful enough for him to stand instead
of sit throughout his news conference in the media center following
his 6-under 66 in Saturday's third round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was the best I've felt all week,'' he said. ``For the
most part I played pretty much pain free, but I just tried to do
what I was instructed to do, which is not sit very much, and go lay
down when I'm done and give myself the best chance to be pain free
tomorrow.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With a birdie 3 on the 18th hole, Duval finished at 10 under,
which means he will be playing with Woods in Sunday's final
pairing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I most definitely wanted to get there,'' he said, referring to
the final pairing. ``It will be a circus. It will be exciting. It
will be a slugfest, whatever you want to call it. You get to look
him in the eye. To get in the last group with undoubtedly the best
player in the world right now is an experience you want to have.
You're going to need to be there for this week and the PGA
Championship and for the next time it comes about.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Duval did not sound intimidated by Woods' six-shot lead with 18
holes remaining. ``Even if I'm as much as seven behind, I have a
chance because I've won from that far behind before,'' Duval said.
``I'm going to be trying to win my first major championship. He's
going to be going for the career Grand Slam. So there is going to
be some pressure on both parties.' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 1999 Bob Hope Chrysler Classic, Duval was seven strokes
behind going into the final round but won with a 59 that tied the
PGA Tour record. In the 1998 Shell Houston Open, he was six strokes
behind and won with a 64. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine I would need to shoot 66 again, if not a few
better,'' Duval said. ``I feel like I got a lot out of my round
today. It's one of the first times in a while where I walked off
thinking that's the highest score I could have shot.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Needing a birdie on the 18th, Duval watched his tee shot drift
toward the white cement out-of-bounds stakes along the street named
The Links. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I walked off the tee and saw it land and saw it did
not kick hard right like you would expect and it just fell left,''
Duval said, ``I felt I was getting the breaks I hadn't been getting
lately. It was nice to see that again. When I made the birdie putt,
I thought, `I just turned a 6 into a 3.' That's what you need.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday, with the way Woods is playing, Duval knows he
will need a super round, like another 66 or even a 63, and that
still might not be enough. That kind of round would be asking a
lot, even for an ailing golfer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
