<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0065 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COVERDELL-MOOD0723-CO     07-22 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-MOOD0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'He gave politics a good name.'
 &HT;    By Ron Martz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shaded from the midday Saturday sun by her red
umbrella, Louise Kemp of Atlanta waited patiently on the sidewalk
outside Peachtree United Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   It was 91 degrees in the Atlanta neighborhood of Buckhead, and
90 minutes before the funeral services for Sen. Paul Coverdell were
to begin. But Kemp, 83, and her friend, Geraldine Sudderth, 71, of
Atlanta, were determined to get two of the few dozen seats
available to the public in the church that would soon be
overflowing with national, state and local politicians and business
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp and Sudderth said they decided to brave the traffic
congestion on Peachtree Road, the heat and the crush of dignitaries
to pay their last respects to the state's senior senator because of
the type man he was. Neither admitted being active in politics, and
Kemp said she met Coverdell only once, a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admired his thinking,'' said Kemp. ``He was his own man.''
</P>
<P>
   Sudderth nodded in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was a very fine person,'' she said. ``I liked the
way he handled himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Those a few dozen average citizens who came to the services said
they did so to honor Coverdell the man, not Coverdell the senator
or Coverdell the politician. They remembered a man who dealt with
them sincerely, honestly and with little of the overblown sense of
importance that professional politicians often have of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very well-mannered man. He was always kind to me and
took care of me,'' said Albert ``Smitty'' Smith, of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he served Coverdell room service meals at the old
Marriott Hotel in downtown Atlanta when the then-state senator
stayed there during his days in the General Assembly. Now sports
ambassador for the Marriott Marquis, Smith said he remembered
Coverdell as a kindly, courtly man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming here today is just my way of remembering him,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Millie Rogers dealt with Coverdell on a more political level,
but she fondly recalled many of the same qualities in him that
others did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very gentle man,'' said Rogers, a vice chairwoman of
the Cobb County Republican Party and assistant to Cobb Commission
Chairman Bill Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was also very courteous, which you don't often see in
public life,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   That courtesy, she said, enabled people to feel comfortable with
him and open up to him about issues which concerned them. ``He
always seemed to be close to the pulse of the public,'' Rogers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that was a result of his staff, she said, which extended
that same sense of courtesy to the senator's constituents and made
his office ``all about customer service.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Pollack of Atlanta said she first met Coverdell at a
Christmas party a few years ago, shortly after moving to Georgia
from Pennsylvania, where she had become a Republican ``because I
felt the Democratic Party had deserted me.'' She said she thrust a
banana nut chocolate chip cake into Coverdell's hands and he
thanked her profusely. She immediately became a supporter of his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was a courageous man,'' she said. ``When he voted
he voted for the right things, not for something somebody wanted
him to vote for.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day of eulogies and remembrances for Coverdell by leaders
of every political stripe and stature, perhaps one of the most
telling came from Pollack. In an era in which there is little to
like about most politicians, she said, ``He gave politics a good
name.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
