<HEADER>
A0066 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COVERDELL-BAXTER0723-     07-22 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-BAXTER0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grief and ambition, in equal measure, filled some church pews
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Newt Gingrich got there a good 45 minutes early, and
was led to the third row of the sectioned-off front half of
Peachtree Road United Methodist Church. Sam Nunn and his wife
joined him a little later, and for a long time they sat alone in
the large empty space, waiting to say goodbye to Paul Coverdell.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the three figures, poignant reminders of the influence
Georgia had in Washington only a short time ago, was a study in the
loneliness of power.
</P>
<P>
   But when the side doors were opened and the rest of the invitees
_ the most powerful figures in Congress, governors, the Republican
presidential nominee _ came bustling in, the late senator's
memorial service suddenly also became a lesson in how crowded
politics can be.
</P>
<P>
   When all the seats had been filled and the carefully planned
service begun, that church seemed in a nearly perfect state of
equipoise between sincere grief and frank ambition.
</P>
<P>
   On the front aisles sat nearly every one of those who have been
mentioned as a possible successor to Coverdell, alongside at least
a couple of those still thought to be possible vice presidential
running mates for Gov. George W. Bush, who sat with his wife behind
Nancy Coverdell during the service.
</P>
<P>
   Moving one's gaze farther down the aisles, it was possible also
to spot any number whose political plans might be changing, as
speculation about one race raises the possibility of openings in a
dozen others.
</P>
<P>
   In those same aisles were also family members, who knew the part
of Coverdell that he kept shyly hidden in his public life;
volunteers from his past campaigns, for whom he became an unlikely
hero; and congressional colleagues, Republican and Democratic, who
had come to count him as a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the strongest Republican I ever met, yet he never let
party get in the way of personal relationships that transformed
party,'' Gov. Roy Barnes, holding back tears, said. More of that,
he said, would ``take away the nastiness and the acrimony that we
have now in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The four eulogies seemed intended to reflect the different
theaters of Coverdell's life: the first from a family friend, Clyde
Rodbell; words from Sen. Phil Gramm, who learned about Coverdell's
loyalty during rocky days of Gramm's presidential campaign, Barnes'
unexpectedly emotional words, and finally, longtime Republican
activist Fred Cooper, reading words from former President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's death has been the occasion for the first meeting of
the entire Georgia congressional delegation in years, so we can't
be entirely certain his untimely passing won't shake some
politicians into emulating his civility.
</P>
<P>
   But his death also precipitates a defining moment in Georgia
politics.
</P>
<P>
   It will be shaped not only by what Barnes decides to do but by
what kind of consensus, if any, the Republicans can work out, and
ultimately on what the voters think.
</P>
<P>
   As all the people affected by this unexpected turn of events
filed out of the church after paying their last respects to
Coverdell, there was a palpable sense that that defining moment
will not be long in coming.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
