<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta sprinter runs fastest 400 hurdles of the year
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Edwin Moses nodded his head approvingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no doubt,'' Moses laughed.
</P>
<P>
   It proved a perfect afternoon for the intermediate hurdling
tradition that has taken root in Atlanta. Wanting to follow in the
footsteps of Moses, Derrick Adkins &AMP; Co., former Georgia Tech
sprinter Angelo Taylor set himself up for a run at Olympic gold,
blazing to a world-leading this year 47.62 second clocking in the
400-meter hurdles Saturday at the Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   Looking down from his perch atop a VIP suite, Moses found that
he could speak with confidence that the newcomers to his craft
hadn't passed him by _ witness his trials record from 1988 (47.37),
left to stand another four years.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor caught his eye, though. Like the Moses of old, the
21-year-old charged to the lead early and called on his strength to
frustrate any late challengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a real, real good race after three days (of
prelims),'' said Moses, impressed. ``That's excellent running.''
</P>
<P>
   What Taylor lacks in hurdling technique, Moses said he makes up
for in flat-400 speed. The kid has enough to land himself a spot on
the 1,600-meter relay in Sydney. No matter how many times Moses
asked for a 1,600 slot, he got the cold shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Intermediate hurdlers were outsiders, a fraternity all their
own. Until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches always treated us like we were stepchildren,'' Moses
said of relay selections. ``Even in my peak, they had a negative
attitude towards us. They didn't think hurdlers had the power to
run the 400.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 400 hurdles final, U.S. relay coach Bubba Thornton
said the staff would be ``negligent'' if Taylor wasn't in the relay
group for Sydney. U.S. head coach John Chaplin added: ``I like the
fact that he runs like hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor intends to pick up the torch for Moses, and one of the
reasons he came to the hurdles is the Morehouse College grad.
Taylor sat in front of his TV watching Moses at the 1984 Los
Angeles Olympics. He grew to appreciate his unmatched dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I saw Edwin, I liked his style,'' Taylor said.
``He went out strong and didn't look back.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest successor to Moses put down the seventh-fastest time
in U.S. history. Just two weeks ago, Taylor was bedridden with food
poisoning, 10 pounds shed from his 180-pound frame, and wondering
if he'd regain his strength come the trials.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor can laugh about it now.
</P>
<P>
   What'll he do differently for Sydney? ``No more seafood.''
</P>
<P>
   It all worked out so perfectly. His fiancee, Florida State
400-meter runner Tangela Wobbleton, by his side after the race.
Subrena Everett cheering as he raced towards home, ``Angelo's Mom''
written across the back of her shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Here he is 21, not yet in his prime, using the Olympic trials as
a stage to send a message to the Llewellyn Herberts and Samuel
Matetes of the hurdling world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran the fastest time in the world _ that should say
something,'' Taylor said, peaking ahead to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
