<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUN0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Johnson burns up the track in the 200 meters preliminary heat By
John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Shortly after Maurice Greene won his
preliminary heat in the 200 meters, he looked back across the field
and motioned with his hand, as if to say, bring it on, bring it on.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson brought it.
</P>
<P>
   Superman smoked a 19.89-second 200, compared to Greene's rather
pedestrian 20.29. Greene tried to shut it down after about 120
meters only to have to kick it into gear again to eke out his win
in the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage, Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But not for long. Shortly after his heat, Johnson, who
obliterated the 200 record with a 19.32 clocking at the 1996
Olympics, motioned for a trainer to massage his right quadriceps
and quickly had a cold pack placed on the suddenly worrisome area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it in the curve,'' Johnson said. ``I was able to finish
the race, so that's encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will have to run a semifinal and the much-anticipated
final today. He was asked if the injury was going to be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope not. There's no way of knowing,'' he said before
hurrying off.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a twinge or an injury, it just adds to the hype for
today's showdown with Greene. Rival sprinter Ato Boldon, from
Trinidad and Tobago, likes Johnson, but thinks Greene has enjoyed
one edge this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Maurice has won the war of words,'' Boldon said.
``Maurice is doing what he does, which is talk. That's what he does
to me or anyone else in the 100 meters. Michael doesn't usually
have anything to say. The really, really, really good Michael
Johnson would not have things to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people will enjoy the matchup more than Boldon. He said both
Johnson and Greene seem to think the other will break down after
the curve.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may not happen,'' said Boldon, who would love to see them
still neck and neck after 195 meters. ``I get to watch two of my
greatest competitors kill each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Others advancing to the semifinals included Rohsaan Griffin and
Floyd Heard. Heard, a former Texas A&AMP;M star, was ranked No.1 in the
world at the distance way back in 1987. He won his heat in 20.14
seconds and said, ``I'd love to be the spoiler . . . I'm not one of
the guys moving their mouths.''
</P>
<P>
   The talk among the women sprinters even got to Marion Jones, who
tries to stay above it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of all the talking. If you're going to talk, put up.
Come out to the track and run,'' Jones said. She coasted to the
day's fastest time of 22.62 seconds in the women's 200 meters in
spite of being rushed to the start line when the heats were
redrawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't ready for it,'' said former Texas Longhorn Nanceen
Perry, who qualified by finishing second to Jones in her heat.
Another Texas ex, Carlette Guidry finished third in the loaded heat
and also advanced, as did former Texas high school star Chryste
Gaines.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the finals contested Saturday, 21-year-old Angelo
Taylor negotiated the 400-meter hurdles in 47.62 seconds, while
Eric Thomas and James finished second and third. Former Reagan High
runner William Porter finished fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor overcame a case of food poisoning, caused by some bad
crab legs, a few weeks ago that caused him to lose weight and miss
a week of training.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more seafood,'' Taylor said. ``I ran the fastest time in
the world, so that says a little something.''
</P>
<P>
   In another final, Nicole Gamble, American record-holder Sheila
Hudson and Tiombe' Hurd went 1-2-3 in the triple jump, although
none of them have yet met the ``A'' Olympic qualifying standard.
</P>
<P>
   Former Elgin High and Texas A&AMP;M star Larry Wade had his own
standard here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God I made it over 10 hurdles,'' Wade said. It was his
first race since April, when he totaled his 1999 Mustang in a car
accident. Wade later suffered complications from the accident and
checked with a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said if I hadn't come in that day I would have died,'' Wade
said. Instead he was alive and running a 13.48-second 110 hurdles
that was the fifth-fastest effort of the day.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's 100 hurdles preliminaries, Gail Devers was the
class of the field, running 12.57. Texas ex Angie Vaughn advanced
by finishing second in her heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's okay. I was a little nervous,'' Vaughn said. ``The first
race is to get some of that nervousness out. I feel I've got
nothing to lose here. I haven't been running a whole lot. I'm not
injured; I just haven't been able to get many races.''
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's late events, Regina Jacobs shattered an American
record in the 5,000 meters by seven seconds with a 14:45.35
clocking. Deena Drossin and Elva Dryer took second and third.
Jacobs also won the 1,500 earlier in the competition and that left
her with a dilemma: which to run in Sydney. Even though her effort
Friday was the world's best time to date in the 5,000, she's
leaning toward the 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, in a battle of the running wounded, Adam
Goucher won in 13:27.06 and Stanford's Brad Hauser took second.
Nick Rogers was third but just missed the Olympic qualifying
standard of 13:29.00 by less than a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is amazing,'' Goucher gasped. ``The race was pure guts.''
</P>
<P>
   This year Goucher overcame an Achilles' tendon injury suffered
in February and at the trials was nursing a strained back he got
while doing some landscaping work at his new house. Hauser also had
a bad back, but an acupuncture treatment worked for him.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fortunate was Bob Kennedy, the best of America's distance
runners. Kennedy, 29, could never make up for lost training time
after a May auto accident in which he suffered a bruised vertebra.
He scratched from the 10,000 meters earlier in the competition and
after struggling in the prelims of the 5,000 meters tried to take
the kick out of the competition by setting the pace Friday. Fans
cheered his efforts, even clanging cowbells to urge him on, but
after leading for six laps Kennedy faded to sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accident set me back four weeks and you can't make that
up,'' Kennedy said after having his Olympic hopes extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   But today, after all the fanning of flames, Johnson or Greene
should establish himself as the gold medal favorite for the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be the most memorable race on U.S. soil in the
sprints in a very long time,'' Boldon said without a trace of hype.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
