<HEADLINE>
KANSAS BOARD OF EDUCATION RACE SURGES TO THE ELECTION FOREFRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE BEEM and TOM PERRIN  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With sidebars slugged EDBOARD-HOLLOWAY, EDBOARD-GAMBLE,
EDBOARD-ISSUES and EDBOARD-GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   SHAWNEE, Kan. _ Most years, Kansas Board of Education races get
pushed into the election background.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   The 2nd District GOP primary contest between incumbent Linda
Holloway and challenger Sue Gamble is being cast as a battle
between conservatives and moderates for control of the state's
education system. Some even see it as a referendum on evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway, a conservative, was chairwoman of the state board in
August 1999 when it approved science standards that downplay
evolution and don't mention the age of Earth or the big-bang
theory. Gamble, a moderate, says the new standards could keep
Kansas students from learning important scientific concepts.
</P>
<P>
   What happens in their Aug. 1 primary and in other contests
across Kansas could change the philosophical makeup of the state
board. Five of the board's 10 seats are up for election this year.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway and Gamble say they both want what's best for the
state's schoolchildren. They just don't agree on what that is.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway says the best comes from the tried and true, the
educational concepts and priorities that have been in place for
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In educational trends, so many people want to be out on the
cutting edge,'' she said. ``Sometimes it's better to let someone
else be out on the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamble is more likely than Holloway to allow those who run the
Kansas Department of Education to set a course for the state's
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state board provides competitive, rigorous standards,''
Gamble said. ``The local boards use that to improve their
curriculum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
