<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0074 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-EDBOARD-HOLLOWAY-KAN &LR;      07-22 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDBOARD-HOLLOWAY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIENCE ON BOARD HAS MADE LINDA HOLLOWAY STRONGER, SOME SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM PERRIN  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sidebar to story slugged EDUCATION-BOARD
</P>
<P>
   SHAWNEE, Kan. _ Linda Holloway never counted, but she figures
the e-mails in her home computer last August numbered more than
1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The messages came from all over the country in response to the
Kansas Board of Education's vote to delete some references to the
theory of evolution from state science standards.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway, who was board chairwoman and a supporter of the
revised standards, at first intended to read them all, but soon
left the job to a few friends and associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some were terribly vicious, terribly evil,'' said Holloway,
50, a conservative Republican and evangelical Christian. ``One of
them said, `Your God needs you. Commit suicide.' And that was one
of the milder ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Holloway's husband, Jerry, said he would have been concerned for
his wife's safety if not for their faith in God. However, he still
wanted to make sure someone read all the e-mails to ensure that no
serious threats were made.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year later, Holloway, a former teacher, is seeking
re-election in the 2nd District in the Aug. 1 Republican primary.
She has her husband's full support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her, `Yeah, I think you need to. If you don't, it will
reverse what you've done and you don't want that to happen,' ''
said Jerry Holloway, a retired engineer. ``It's not time to turn
tail and run.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Holloway and work closely with her agree that her
three-plus years on the board, particularly the year as chairwoman,
have made her a stronger person and a more confident board member.
</P>
<P>
   The vote to exclude from the science standards any mention of
macroevolution, or major evolutionary change of species, received
worldwide media attention _ much of it critical. Holloway's
leadership position on the board made her its designated
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how anybody could have handled it differently or
better,'' said Harold Voth of Haven, this year's board chairman and
a moderate who joined the five conservatives and cast the decisive
vote on the standards. ``Talk about pressure. When you have 10 TV
microphones around you, that's not an easy job.''
</P>
<P>
   Another moderate board member wasn't as complimentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got real testy,'' said Val De Fever of Independence, Kan.
``But when you're under attack, that could happen to any of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her term as chairwoman, Holloway, an only child, was
making monthly trips to the Atlanta area to look after her father,
who was in failing health. He died in March.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1999 she had lost more than 10 pounds, which she
attributes to her hectic schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Being tagged with a label has long been part of politics, and
for Holloway the labels are often ``conservative Republican'' and
``evangelical Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't back away from either, but one label Holloway is
concerned that people might look past is ``former teacher.'' She
taught for 20 years, mostly in the Kansas City School District. And
for most of her career she was in special education, teaching
students with severe physical and mental impairments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being an educator herself is one of her outstanding
strengths,'' said board member Janet Waugh, a moderate who is
friendly with Holloway but is supporting Holloway's primary
opponent, Sue Gamble. ``I think we probably consider Linda the
expert person on special ed. We don't rubber-stamp her, but we
listen to what she says on special ed.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Highland of Overland Park met Holloway through a women's
organization before her first campaign for the state board. One
thing that impressed Highland and made her a supporter was
Holloway's teaching background and master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real-life experiences are the best teacher,'' said Highland,
who has become a friend of Holloway's.
</P>
<P>
   Highland thinks the poise Holloway developed teaching special
education, coupled with her faith in God, prepared her for the
difficult times she has faced on the state board.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway, whose grandchildren will be entering kindergarten and
third grade in Kansas public schools, has those personal reasons
for wanting to improve education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's real committed to kids,'' De Fever said. ``I
think she has the best intentions in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But De Fever said she thinks Holloway and other conservatives
are guided too much by a religious agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Comments like that upset Holloway.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I ran before, they threw a stereotype on me _ even when I
was teaching special ed in the inner city _ and it was religious
bigotry,'' she said. ``It goes back to the `Inherit the Wind'
stereotype, that people of faith have no intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Cashill, a conservative activist and friend of Holloway's,
is quick to come to her defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been called every which thing you could possibly
imagine, and for doing the right thing,'' he said. ``And that right
thing will not be recognized by everyone immediately, but in time
it will.''
</P>
<P>
   Holloway knows the evolution vote is still the main issue for
many people, and she doesn't duck questions about it. However, she
also hopes voters know there are other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway points to the board's progress in changing the way
Kansas teachers are certified, its approval of new curriculum
standards for social studies and math, and a requirement that
second-graders take a reading diagnostic test.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway also has a goal of streamlining Quality Performance
Accreditation, the state's school improvement program that
accredits schools based on how well students perform.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about evolution's place in the big picture of what the
board does, she said, ``It's about this big,'' holding her thumb
and index finger slightly apart. ``It's a really small part.''
</P>
<P>
   Holloway has received endorsements from U.S. Sen. Sam Brownback,
a conservative Republican; and Kansans for Life, a statewide
organization that campaigns for abortion restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow board members say that she is approachable and will
listen to different opinions but that she is unlikely to change her
views.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have grown to appreciate her more because of her
steadfastness,'' conservative board member Steve Abrams said.
</P>
<P>
   As much time as she spends on board business and studying
issues, Holloway still tries to make time for her family and
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Every day she takes a 40-minute walk, covering a mile or two,
depending on her pace.
</P>
<P>
   Friday nights are set aside to spend with her husband. They go
out to eat and spend time talking. They also attend their
grandchildren's baseball games and other activities.
</P>
<P>
   Few who know Holloway but disagree with her on issues will take
shots at her character or integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not enemies,'' Waugh said. ``I personally like her.
She's a nice person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
