<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0075 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-EDBOARD-GAMBLE-KAN &LR;      07-22 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDBOARD-GAMBLE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANDING UP FOR EDUCATION ISSUES KEEPS SUE GAMBLE IN SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE BEEM  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sidebar to story slugged EDUCATION-BOARD
</P>
<P>
   SHAWNEE, Kan. _ It's not apparent from her record _ more than 20
years on elected boards and a hard bargainer at the negotiating
table _ but Shawnee Mission school board member Sue Gamble is a shy
person.
</P>
<P>
   Talking in front of large groups makes her anxious. She almost
backed out of a recent radio debate because of nerves.
</P>
<P>
   But there's one thing that can push Gamble out of her shell and
into the public arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody has to stand up for what's right,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, the Shawnee woman left a comfortable existence as
a stay-at-home mom to take part in battles over gifted education
and boundary changes within the Shawnee Mission School District.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gamble, 58, a real estate agent, is challenging incumbent
Linda Holloway for a seat on the Kansas Board of Education, which
oversees the state's 304 school districts. The two will face off in
the Republican primary Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Gamble said, the stakes are the highest she has
encountered in 20 years as an elected official: the chance to
determine whether Kansas education focuses on the
back-to-the-basics approach favored by many social conservatives or
on the ideas championed by national education groups.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway, 50, a conservative Republican from Shawnee, led the
state board in August 1999 when it approved new science standards
that don't include references to the age of Earth, the big-bang
theory and some aspects of evolutionary theory. The standards are
important because they help determine what Kansas students will
learn and are tested on.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing national and international flap over the science
standards, Gamble held fast to her feeling that the state board had
overstepped its bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of developing broad educational policies for local
districts to follow, the state board has begun micromanaging
curriculum, said Gamble, a 13-year veteran of the Shawnee Mission
board and a past president of the state school boards association.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, our standards are being weakened, and the
education of our children is being weakened over time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gamble prefers to discuss issues other than evolution,
it's the first thing most voters ask about, she's learned in more
than a month of neighborhood canvassing. Like other moderate
candidates, Gamble thinks students should be taught evolution
because it's the theory accepted by a consensus of the science
community.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives counter that the vote on science standards was
more about academic freedom than evolution, the theory that living
things share common ancestors but have changed over time. The
board's actions don't ban evolution but allow local districts to
decide whether to teach that theory or another in science classes,
Holloway has said.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Kris Van Meteren is concerned, the candidacy of Gamble
and the other moderate Republicans running against board members is
motivated by animosity left over from 1998, the year moderates
wrested control of the state party away from conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're using this evolution issue as a vehicle to stamp out
as many other conservative Republicans as they possibly can,'' said
Van Meteren, executive director of the conservative Kansas
Republican Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gamble does carry the hopes of moderates in Johnson
County and across the state. With her years of board experience and
statewide ties through the Kansas Association of School Boards,
Gamble is seen as a good counter to Holloway, who spent 20 years as
a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   That's what motivated people such as Gene Troehler of Leawood to
walk door to door with Gamble one steamy night in mid-July. And
that's what brought Martha Lewis to the Indian Hills Country Club
and a Gamble fund-raiser earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need someone very strong in there to lead the board,'' said
Lewis, clutching several green and white Sue Gamble yard signs.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble has garnered endorsements from the political action
committees of the Kansas National Education Association and the
Mainstream Coalition, a moderate watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anybody more passionate about kids and school
than Sue,'' said Mike Gamble, her husband of 38 years. ``There's a
phrase in my head from when she was on the KASB board and the
Shawnee Mission board: `It's my job.' She leaves her paying job to
go take care of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought the timid young girl who attended 18
schools in a dozen years would end up on the board of one of the
largest school districts in Kansas, let alone running for the state
school board?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not Gamble, who spent much of her time in school as
the new kid, in the background, listening. Her father's wanderlust
moved the family during the 1940s and 1950s back and forth between
the West Coast and the Midwest, with a few stops in between.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble graduated with the Turner High School class of 1959.
There, she was fast friends with someone she'd bump into again
later in life: Janet Waugh, now the 1st District state board
member.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble sang at Waugh's wedding. They even worked for the same
company after high school before losing touch as their lives got
busier. They rejuvenated their friendship after both were elected
to local school boards, Waugh to Turner and Gamble to Shawnee
Mission.
</P>
<P>
   The qualities Waugh most remembers about Gamble from high school
are the ones that serve her the best in her school board work,
Waugh said: her ability to ask probing questions and her honesty.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble definitely has opinions, said Nancy Gebhart of Lenexa,
who served 12 years on the Shawnee Mission board, most with Gamble.
The two weren't close and didn't always agree, but Gebhart said she
respected Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sue is not afraid to stand alone on an issue and to speak for
that issue,'' Gebhart said. ``She will move past it once the vote's
done, but she will vote on her own.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamble's ability to stick with the issues but avoid holding
grudges resonated with Janet Agron of Leawood, who has known Gamble
for 22 years. The two met when Gamble was on the Shawnee Mission
Northwest Advisory Board and Agron was president of the Mill Creek
Elementary School PTA.
</P>
<P>
   It was the late 1970s, and the school district was closing
schools in its older areas, where the student population was
shrinking. But in Shawnee and Lenexa, a building boom was
contributing to crowded schools and cries for new buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Agron remembers having several arguments with Gamble over
boundary changes for Mill Creek, but Gamble was always willing to
listen to Agron's side. Gamble will gracefully acquiesce if the
facts don't support her view, Agron said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her mind is not closed,'' Agron said. ``You can't ask for more
than that. You can't vote for someone just because they always
agree with you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
