<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0076 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-EDBOARD-ISSUES-KAN &LR;      07-22 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDBOARD-ISSUES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES HAVE SAME CONCERNS ABOUT EDUCATION, BUT THEIR VIEWS
DIFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE BEEM  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sidebar to story slugged EDUCATION-BOARD
</P>
<P>
   SHAWNEE, Kan. _ Take evolution out of their Kansas Board of
Education race and you have to dig a little deeper to find
differences between incumbent Linda Holloway and challenger Sue
Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   They are both Shawnee Republicans. Both are unassuming and good
listeners. They ask questions. And they agree that Kansas education
faces large obstacles, from a shaky school finance picture to
dwindling populations in some of the state's 304 school districts.
</P>
<P>
   But at the core of both women's campaigns for the board's 2nd
District seat is a conviction about what's good and bad about
Kansas education. That's where their true differences lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe she (Gamble) cares about kids and education, but we
have different ideas,'' Holloway said.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway, who spent more than 20 years as a teacher, thinks
education has turned away from ideas that work, such as phonics and
other emphases on basic skills. Gamble rose from PTA member to the
Shawnee Mission school board and thinks Kansas students need the
basics and more to keep up in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at their views on issues the state board faces in
the next four years:
</P>
<P>
   QUALITY PERFORMANCE ACCREDITATION
</P>
<P>
   Holloway and Gamble agree that some aspects of Quality
Performance Accreditation work.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide school improvement plan, tied to 1992 changes in
the state's school finance law, brings educational accountability
to how schools are accredited. Instead of counting books and
buildings, districts receiving state accreditation must prove that
students are learning what they're being taught.
</P>
<P>
   But Holloway sees teachers drowning in a sea of paperwork, being
dragged away from the business of teaching to fill out forms for
the state. She has carried in her platform since 1996 the goal of
streamlining the accreditation process so teachers don't lose
classroom time.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble says Quality Performance Accreditation has forced
teachers and school administrators to take responsibility for
whether students are achieving. The resultant paperwork can be
unwieldy _ and should perhaps be streamlined _ but it's basically a
system that works, Gamble said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fewer and fewer teachers and administrators are blaming the
student for failure,'' Gamble said.
</P>
<P>
   ACHIEVEMENT GAP
</P>
<P>
   State officials in 1998 identified a growing gap in the test
scores of white upper- and middle-class Kansas students and those
of minority and poor white students. It's a gap that has continued
to grow under Quality Performance Accreditation, Holloway said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, along with the rest of the nation, are doing a lousy job
of closing the gap between the haves and have-nots,'' Holloway
said.
</P>
<P>
   She praises a statewide reading diagnostic test, given to
second-graders, that was unanimously approved in 1998 by the
philosophically divided state board. Those test results will help
teachers determine early on the students who need help.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway also favors studying programs from other states that
have successfully raised test scores of less-advantaged children.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble agrees that it's important to study those programs, but
she says raising expectations might be just as important. Thirty
years ago, students who didn't perform well in school had job
opportunities in the service sector. That's not true anymore, as
the economy has become more dependent on technology.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional education hasn't always worked for the neediest
students, Gamble said.
</P>
<P>
   Educators have to believe all students are able to learn, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what school improvement is all about _ raising
expectations to meet the needs of a service//technology-driven
society,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ROLE OF THE STATE BOARD AND LOCAL CONTROL
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates agree on this: Despite recent moves to
abolish the state board or curb its powers, the board should remain
an elected one. That provides an element of accountability when
members come up for re-election every four years.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway said the state board should maintain its general
oversight of the public schools and those private schools, such as
most Catholic schools, that opt for state accreditation. The board
also oversees teacher certification, a process recently overhauled,
Holloway said.
</P>
<P>
   But she doesn't think it's the state board's place to send
mandates to local boards of education. Along those lines, Holloway
holds up her vote for science standards that don't include
macroevolution, or change from one species to another, as
preserving local districts' control over what their students learn.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new science standards, approved on a contentious 6-4
vote in August 1999, districts are free to expose students to more
than just evolution, Holloway said. She calls that academic
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The new standards prohibit teachers from censoring evidence that
contradicts a current theory, Holloway said. Districts still are
free, then, to teach evolution, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never an intent to ban evolution ever by anybody on
the board,'' Holloway said.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble says the local-control argument is a red herring.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas school districts always have had local control, or the
ability to determine their own courses. The changes wrought by the
1992 school finance law and Quality Performance Accreditation have
imposed requirements that districts prove students are learning,
but they say nothing about what they learn.
</P>
<P>
   Quality Performance Accreditation did require the state to set
curricular standards for local districts to use as guidelines, but
they're not mandates. And Gamble thinks the state board should
champion standards that are rigorous and world-class.
</P>
<P>
   The new science standards don't fit that definition because they
omit theories accepted by a consensus of the world's scientists,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble said that if she's elected, she will vote to throw out
the new science standards and adopt a version that was written by
27 Kansas science teachers. That version, rejected by the current
board, listed evolution as a cornerstone of science education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state's responsibility is to provide the highest, most
challenging and competitive standards from which local districts
can draw their local curriculum,'' Gamble said. ``This is
legitimate local control.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star's Tom Perrin contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
