<HEADLINE>
KANSAS BOARD OF EDUCATION RACES AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THE KANSAS CITY STAR STAFF  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Undated sidebar to story slugged EDUCATION-BOARD
</P>
<P>
   The 10-member Kansas Board of Education has been evenly divided
since 1996, with five conservative Republicans and five moderate
Republicans and Democrats. Seats in the board's five even-numbered
districts are up for election this year, and Republicans in four of
the districts are facing primaries. There are no Democratic
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   2nd District
</P>
<P>
   Current member: conservative
</P>
<P>
   Candidates: Incumbent conservative Republican Linda Holloway of
Shawnee, a former teacher, and moderate Republican Sue Gamble of
Shawnee, a real estate agent and member of the Shawnee Mission
school board. The winner will face Democrat Ron Patton of Fairway,
a Presbyterian minister, in November. The district covers eastern
Johnson County and Lake Quivira.
</P>
<P>
   4th District
</P>
<P>
   Current member: moderate
</P>
<P>
   Candidates: Incumbent Democrat Bill Wagnon of Topeka, a Washburn
University history professor, has no primary opponent. In November,
he'll face conservative Republican Patrick Hill of Topeka, chief
executive officer of a transportation company.
</P>
<P>
   6th District
</P>
<P>
   Current member: none; the seat was recently vacated by Scott
Hill, a conservative Republican who moved to Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates: Conservative Republican Brad Angell of Junction
City, a business owner, former teacher and past member of the Geary
County school board, and moderate Republican Bruce Wyatt of Salina,
an attorney. The winner will face Democrat Eloise Lynch, a retired
teacher and former Kansas House member, in November.
</P>
<P>
   8th District
</P>
<P>
   Current member: conservative
</P>
<P>
   Candidates: Incumbent conservative Republican Mary Douglass
Brown of Wichita, a former teacher, and moderate Republican Carol
Rupe, a Wichita School District employee and former Wichita school
board member. The winner will face Democrat Dick Williams of
Wichita, a retired Wichita State University instructor, in
November.
</P>
<P>
   10th District
</P>
<P>
   Current member: conservative
</P>
<P>
   Candidates: Incumbent conservative Republican Steve Abrams, a
veterinarian from Arkansas City, and moderate Republican Roger
Rankin of Longton, a retired school superintendent. The winner will
face Democrat Wayne Holt of Haysville, a retired school
administrator and member of the Haysville school board, in
November.
</P>
</TEXT>
