<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0079 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0723-COX     07-22 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Gore courts union vote
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking to shore up his support from labor, Democratic
presidential hopeful Vice President Al Gore on Friday pledged to
union members that if he is elected he will raise the minimum wage
by $1 an hour. Speaking to the AFL-CIO convention in Washington,
Bush charged that if his Republican rival Gov. George W. Bush were
elected, he would gut the federal minimum wage law and drain
working people's retirement safety net while giving huge tax cuts
to the wealthy. Gore pointed out what he said were budget overruns
in Texas and again accused Bush of wanting ``to bring those same
budget busting tax policies to the nation as a whole.'' Gore, who
secured the labor federation's endorsement months ago, has met with
resistance from the Teamsters and the United Auto Workers, who have
withheld their support and may be considering backing Green Party
candidate Ralph Nader. Both groups were angered this year by the
Clinton administration's support of free trade legislation.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Nader told steelworkers in Columbus, Ohio: ``When
organized labor can say to these candidates, `You're not going to
take us for granted anymore, we have an alternative and the
alternative is Nader and the Green Party.' ''
</P>
<P>
   GORE SOAKING UP TAXPAYER FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   In a year of record-breaking fund-raising, Vice President Al
Gore has made his own mark: He has received $14.6 million in
taxpayer funds for his campaign, more than any other presidential
candidate ever. Gore, who agreed to limit his spending to $40.5
million in exchange for the taxpayer subsidies, broke the old mark
of $13.5 million by 1996 Republican presidential nominee Bob Dole.
Campaign aides expect Gore to eventually receive $15 million in
taxpayer funds. And as the Republican National Convention to be
held in Philadelphia next month nears, Gore's use of taxpayer funds
will become more evident as his rival Bush is expected to become
the first candidate since 1976 to receive a major party's
nomination without agreeing to limit his spending. Bush has smashed
all fund-raising records by taking in $96 million and spending $88
million. He has not taken any matching taxpayer funds.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL PARTIES FUNNEL MONEY THROUGH STATES
</P>
<P>
   Seizing another loophole, Democrats and Republicans are
funneling money through state parties to buy their television ads
in a tactic that preserves the limited dollars they can spend
directly on candidates in the fall. If the national parties had
bought the ads themselves, they would have been required by federal
regulations to use mostly ``hard money'' _ the limited
contributions that can be spent directly in support of candidates.
But by routing dollars first to state affiliates, the parties can
use a greater portion of ``soft money.'' This summer, the DNC has
spent nearly $20 million on TV ads in 17 states promoting Gore. The
RNC has spent more than $17 million on ads touting Bush. Virtually
all of it has been channeled through state parties.
</P>
<P>
   DNC CHAIR WORRIES ABOUT GORE'S IMAGE
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky Gov. Paul E. Patton, who will preside over the
Democratic National Convention next month in Los Angeles has had
some recent advise for Gore to improve his personality in order to
attract more voters. ``The problem with the whole campaign,''
Patton told The Courier-Journal of Louisville recently, ``is that
people know Gore and he evidently doesn't have that personality
that is causing people to come to him.'' Patton suggested that Gore
should continue to criticize rival Bush's track record as governor
of Texas. ``We're exactly where we were in 1988, with a sitting
vice president and an attractive governor who can make a good
speech _ and you know who won that one,'' Patton said referring to
1988 when then-Vice President George Bush, Gov. Bush's father,
defeated rival Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, who had led
in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
