<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
 
MacPHAIL'S PURGING OF CUBS BEGINS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Chicago Cubs general manager Ed Lynch traded for Eric Young
and Ismael Valdes in December, it was viewed largely throughout the
industry as a move to save his job.
</P>
<P>
   Silly Lynch. What was he thinking?
</P>
<P>
   While Young's had a very good year, Valdes, the key to the move
considering the Cubs' need for starting pitching, had worn out his
welcome by May. And he went a large way toward costing Lynch his
job.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Cubs president Andy MacPhail is also the general manager,
which he's scheduled to be until his contract runs out after the
2001 season. And the purging has begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it became evident that we were going to make a change,
and (the responsibility) was going to be mine, I looked at it like
it's Ahab and the white whale,'' MacPhail said. ``Either I'm going
to get this done or I'm not. We're not going to have any confusion
about who's responsible. From here on out, it's on me.''
</P>
<P>
   MacPhail already traded Glenallen Hill to the Yankees, but
that's only a small piece of what he wants to accomplish by the
July 31 trading deadline. He also wants to trade Valdes, Henry
Rodriguez, Jeff Reed and Felix Heredia for prospects. Baseball
officials also said right-handers Kevin Tapani and Rick Aguilera
could be had. They both have no-trade clauses, but they would be
waived in the right situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes a little activity is a good thing for the sake of a
little activity,'' MacPhail said. ``This is one of those times.''
</P>
<P>
   MacPhail also must deal with the Sammy Sosa situation. Sosa had
a nine-game stretch when he hit eight homers, and he's hoping the
Cubs present him with a serious offer to a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   The waiting game: Dodgers right-hander Mike Fetters and
shortstop Kevin Elster, both of whom signed one-year non-guaranteed
contracts in the offseason, are interested in contract extensions.
However, it'll have to wait until after the season.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Kevin Malone said he won't talk about contract
extensions during the final two months with any player. It's the
same stance the organization took at the end of last season. During
the offseason, they inked Eric Karros, Mark Grudzielanek, Antonio
Osuna and Dave Hansen to deals.
</P>
<P>
   Trade winds: Cincinnati's Pete Harnisch has become a coveted
pitcher, and while the Chicago White Sox are the lead team in the
sweepstakes, Arizona is searching doggedly for a No. 2 starter that
could complement Randy Johnson and make it possible for the
Diamondbacks to pull away from the rest of the National League
West.
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch is 3-5 with a 5.27 ERA, but he's pitched two
complete-game four-hitters at Enron Field and Coors Field, and he's
3-1 with a 1.45 ERA since coming off the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk and joke a lot about (the trade rumors),'' Harnisch
said. ``The guys are (ticked) with me because they think I'm
pitching my way out of here. But we feel like there may be some
people trying to give up on us a little bit. We don't feel that
way. If we can keep a couple of guys here - every day we lose
somebody else - we feel we have a shot (at contending for the
postseason).''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Curt Schilling fodder continues in Philadelphia.
Schilling brought up his please-trade-me speech last week, then
backed off it when it angered teammates and fans. He then went on a
Phillies pregame show and said how much he loved Philadelphia and
wanted to stay.
</P>
<P>
   But it just so happened that at the same time Denny Neagle was
telling reporters he saw Schilling at the movies, the right-hander
was talking about how jealous he was that he wasn't the one traded
to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling's value has increased because he's pitching well
again. In his past seven starts, he pitched at least seven innings
and is 4-2 with a 2.17 ERA. However, the Phillies are asking for
the world in return for Schilling, who has a no-trade clause, and
it's unlikely he'll be moved by the July 31 trade deadline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
