<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0082 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-SPARKY-LADN     07-22 1514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SPARKY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKY ANDERSON HAS HAD QUITE A CAREER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. -- While Sparky Anderson was pacing the
visitor's dugout that famous night in Fenway Park 25 years ago, Tim
Belcher was back in Ohio matching him step for step.
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of 13-year-old Cincinnati Reds fans allowed to
stay up past midnight, listening to broadcaster Marty Brennaman
call the game they hoped would bring them a World Series title.
</P>
<P>
   When Boston's Carlton Fisk hit a dramatic 11th-inning home run
that forced a Game 7 in what many think is the greatest series of
all time, Belcher and Sparky were stunned - a thousand miles apart
but together in their misery. The Big Red Machine was sputtering on
the cliffs of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone lived and died with those Reds teams, mostly died
that night,'' said Belcher of the Angels, who is winding up a
distinguished 13-year major-league career. ``But we knew Sparky
would get those guys through.''
</P>
<P>
   He did, of course. Tony Perez hit a two-run homer in Game 7, Joe
Morgan won it with a base hit in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   And today, in this sleepy village in upstate New York, more than
40,000 fans are expected to come here and remember it all.
Anderson, who managed the Reds to titles in 1975-76 and the Detroit
Tigers to a championship in 1984, will be inducted into baseball's
Hall of Fame along with Perez, Brennaman, Fisk and old-timers
Turkey Stearns and Bid McPhee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would give anything to be there,'' Belcher said. ``For
anyone who grew up with the Reds, it is a dream come true. Sparky
and Marty and Tony Perez all going into the Hall of Fame on the
same day. Even Carlton Fisk.''
</P>
<P>
   The day is even more special for Belcher because he later got a
chance to play for Anderson in Detroit during the 1994 season and
finally brush up against the most successful manager of the modern
baseball era.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher already knew the numbers, third place behind Connie Mack
and John McGraw in career victories (2,194), the only manager to
win World Series in both leagues, the winningest manager in the
history of the Reds and Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   But it was during that disastrous, strike-shortened 1994 that
Belcher, who started 0-9, learned what made Sparky tick. Instead of
giving up on his pitcher, Anderson became Belcher's biggest fan,
admiring his grit and work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same quality that spirited George Lee Anderson, 66,
through Dorsey High School in West Central Los Angeles, Cincinnati,
Detroit and the same home of 35 years in Thousand Oaks, to the top
of the baseball world.
</P>
<P>
   Simply, he cared about people.
</P>
<P>
   His career also included his firing from the Reds in 1978. Free
agency had arrived and Cincinnati traded Perez to Montreal rather
than sign him to a long-term deal. The same was true with Tigers
catcher and leader Lance Parrish, who left after Detroit won the
Series in 1984. But Anderson embraced the new players the way he
had the stars. There was no other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not only one of the greatest managers of all time, but
he's also one of the greatest human beings of all time,'' said Reds
new general manager Jim Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   ``A very giving man who cares about people, always put the
people before his job and was very successful with the ability to
motivate players and know when to kick them in the rear and when to
pat them on the back. A man who always speaks with honesty,
integrity and character.''
</P>
<P>
   It was those qualities that impressed former USC coach Rod
Dedeaux, who first met young George at a college game in the early
1940s and made him a Trojans batboy for six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The same virtues caught the eye of Reds general manager Bob
Howsam, who offered Anderson, a prematurely gray, 35-year-old coach
with the San Diego Padres, the manager's job in 1970. In honor of
Howsam, Anderson's plaque bears a Cincinnati cap.
</P>
<P>
   Other influences were Lefty Phillips, the Brooklyn Dodgers scout
who signed Anderson out of high school after Dorsey won a record 42
consecutive games. Anderson credits Phillips with teaching him more
about baseball than anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Another was George Scherger, Anderson's first professional
manager at Class D Santa Barbara. When Sparky became manager of the
Reds in 1970, he brought back Scherger as one of his coaches.
</P>
<P>
   All left a message. As great as the game is, it is the people
who make it special.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I feel best about,'' said Anderson, who earned the
nickname Captain Hook for his quick use of his bullpen. ``I might
not make everybody happy. You pinch-hit a guy, take him out of a
game. But I've never had a situation where I run into a player
later and he was upset with the way he was treated. It's good to
hear a guy say, `One thing about you, you always told the truth.'''
</P>
<P>
   It never has been more true than the past month, when Anderson
has been on a treadmill of public appearances and celebrity golf
tournaments. Last week he flew to Detroit to do charity work for
former University of Michigan football coach Bo Schembechler, came
back to California for one day, then returned to Michigan for his
own golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never says no,'' said Irv Kaze, former Yankees and Raiders
publicist who has a sports talk show on KIEV radio in Glendale.
``He says he'll be on and he's on. I think that's because he never
forgot when he wasn't on top. To George, a head of state is no more
important than a clubhouse guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson remembers what it was like to be a career
minor-leaguer. He played just one season in the majors, batting
.218 in 1959 with the Philadelphia Phillies. Managers became his
heroes. His idol is John McGraw, the former New York Giants manager
who died Feb. 25, 1934 three days after Anderson was born in
Bridgewater, S.D.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson remembered his first opening day at Cincinnati's
Riverfront Stadium. Bands were playing and there were wreaths at
home plate for him and Montreal manager Gene Mauch.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this stuff is going on and I feel a tug on my pants,''
Anderson said. ``It was Gene. He said, `Remember today, because
you'll never get this memory again.' I never forgot that. It will
stay there for the rest of my years.''
</P>
<P>
   Also among the dignitaries today will be Hall of Famer and
former Dodgers manager Tom Lasorda, who in his first year ended
Anderson's reign of World Series titles in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the Reds and the Dodgers in the 1970s was the greatest
rivalry in baseball history,'' Anderson said. ``The Giants and
Dodgers weren't even close. It was so intense, every game, and the
cities were 2,000 miles apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Tommy's first year, we played the Dodgers 18 times, nine in
Cincinnati, nine here. Each game was a sellout. I never heard a
ballpark so loud. More than a million fans saw us play the Dodgers
that year.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson never was as boisterous as Lasorda, but he is a vivid
storyteller who was an Angels TV broadcaster after retiring from
the Tigers in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But his voice gets soft when he talks about the most important
face in the crowd - Carol, his wife of 47 years.
</P>
<P>
   The two have known each other since grade school, married and
reared three children in the same Thousand Oaks house they built
with an $8,000 loan from her father.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Anderson is never interviewed, rarely photographed and
prefers to remain outside of the trappings of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is the boss,'' he said. ``Her thing was always the
children, she just did the whole raising. I couldn't even take 5
percent of the credit. I'm not proud of that. I never was there. I
was so involved with baseball. I wish I had chosen the other path.
They forgave me for that and now we are so close. She did all of
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason I was successful was the fact she allowed me
to be free. She was not one trying to gain the limelight with all
the fancy clothes and cars. I'm so proud being married to her.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sons Lee and Albert and daughter Shirlee, there
are 14 grandchildren. All are expected here today.
</P>
<P>
   So are many of his players, including Hall of Famers Morgan and
Johnny Bench.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the gate will be Pete Rose, the all-time hits leader who
was banished form the game a decade ago for allegedly gambling on
baseball. Although Rose is not officially allowed to participate in
major-league functions, he has come to Cooperstown that past few
years to sign autographs and remain visible to his many fans.
</P>
<P>
   With such a strong contingent from Cincinnati, there has been
speculation that either Perez or Brennaman will make pleas during
their acceptance speeches to reinstate Rose. Anderson has been
outspoken in his support of Rose but says he will not debate the
issue at the podium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony might say something,'' Anderson said. ``I always say if
you feel you should, then you should. But to me, this is not the
playing field to embarrass anyone, not the commissioner on this
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do that. I'm not there for that. I'm there because
this game is so beautiful. And always will be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
