u i BC-G8-SUMMIT-BOS &LR;      07-22 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-G8-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREAD OF TECHNOLOGY TO POOR NATIONS TOPS GROUP OF EIGHT AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHARON MOSHAVI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAGO, Japan _ There were no smashed Nike stores, no black ski
masks. But the specter of forces who oppose globalization hovered
Saturday as the leaders of the world's richest countries pledged to
take steps to bring the world's poorest into the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   Information technology and the ``digital divide'' topped the
agenda at the summit this weekend of eight industrialized nations.
The topic was a clear attempt to assure globalization's naysayers
that the wired economy is not for the wealthy alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone should be able to enjoy access to information and
communications networks,'' the group said in a charter signed by
all leaders. They also urged governments to avoid regulating
information technology tightly, and vowed to protect intellectual
property rights on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Group of Eight also set up a ``DOT Force,'' or digital
opportunity task force, which will work toward providing computers
and Internet access to the world's poor.
</P>
<P>
   Some people applauded the drive as altruistic; others argued
that poor nations need electricity and clean water, not modems and
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't eat computers,'' said Kewese Owusu, coordinator for
Jubilee 2000, a group that campaigns for debt relief. ``People are
dying.''
</P>
<P>
   To underscore the point, members of the group set fire to a
laptop on an Okinawan beach.
</P>
<P>
   With most of the G-8 countries enjoying prosperity, it is
politically astute to turn attention to the developing world. But
the agenda also reflects a growing sense, especially from the
United States, that there is an obvious advantage to getting
technology into as many hands as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``With us leading in cutting-edge technology, America has an
interest in having more people use it,'' said Jake Siewart, White
House deputy press spokesman, who said President Clinton had played
a big role in pushing information technology onto the G-8 agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton issued what the administration is calling a ``global
call to action'' to promote information technologies. The
statement, supported by 50 major US foundations and companies,
including America Online and IBM, promises to help developing
countries with everything from regulatory policy to e-commerce to
wiring remote places.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton resisted a notion that the United States is trying to
bully the rest of the world into technology, or that globalization
means to sweep away local identities. The United States recognizes
``that the diverse conditions and needs of developing nations
should be taken into account, and that local cultures be preserved
and promoted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers applauded the G-8 initiative, arguing that
governments are needed to spur private business to wire the
developing world. ``The problem won't simply be solved by market
forces in globalization,'' said Denis Gilhooly, an aide at the
United Nations Development Program.
</P>
<P>
   But many remain skeptical about how much the G-8 nations can
accomplish. They point to the G-8's inability, highlighted again at
this year's summit, to make inroads into debt relief for poor
nations.
</P>
<P>
   At last year's G-8 summit in Cologne, Germany, the rich nations
promised debt relief for 40 of the world's poorest nations. But few
nations have qualified for the stringent requirements, and
according to Jubilee 2000, only $15 billion of the $100 billion
promised at the Cologne meeting has been forgiven. The US Congress
has held up the $600 billion that Clinton had promised.
</P>
<P>
   UN Secretary General Kofi Annan expressed dissatisfaction with
the pace of debt relief. ``For four years we have had too many
promises and too little action,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how much money the G-8 governments will spend to
bring the Web to the world. Only Japan, whose prime minister,
Yoshiro Mori, is just learning to use a computer mouse, agreed to
pony up a specific amount _ $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Replying to questions about what the other countries would pay,
a US deputy national economic adviser, Lael Brainard, said: ``There
is a general expectation that everybody will participate by
mobilizing government resources, by helping to mobilize focus and
energy at the multilateral organizations, by energizing the private
sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides say Clinton has been taken with the effect that technology
might have on poor regions of Africa and India. Clinton often
speaks of how impressed he was when he saw a mother in India's
Rajasthan state getting data on caring for her baby off the
Internet at a community center.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 5 percent of computers with Internet access are in
developing countries. And most people in poorer countries don't
have a telephone connection. If that doesn't improve and the
developed world keeps moving ahead at the same pace, the richer
will get richer and the poor poorer, many worry.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the world's leaders in touch with technology, the
Russian president, Vladimir V. Putin, suggested that they stay in
touch via e-mail. ``The suggestion was accepted unanimously,''
German spokesman Uwe-Carsten Heye told journalists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
