<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SOPRANOS-CASTCALL-ART     07-22 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOPRANOS-CASTCALL-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTING CALL FOR `THE SOPRANOS' A REAL MOB SCENE: 20,000 SHOW UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to correct, in 21st graf, number of Emmy nominations; 18 is
correct, not 86, as sent) 
(ART ADV: Three photos, NYT1, NYT11, NYT12, are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By VINCENT M. MALLOZZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.J. _ I grew up on Pleasant Avenue, the wiseguy
capital of the world.
</P>
<P>
   I was holding my father's hand on the summer morning when
Francis Ford Coppola and James Caan visited the old East Harlem
neighborhood to film a scene for the first ``Godfather'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   All the guys from the ``old man's club'' were out in their
skimpy T-shirts that morning, sipping cappuccino from plastic cups,
their diamond pinky rings glaring in a mean sun. Jimmy the Cat.
Vito the Bat. Patti Apples. Talk about filming on location.
</P>
<P>
   In the scene, Sonny Corleone, played by Caan, kicks the wise out
of his wiseguy brother-in-law. Casting agents on the set were
offering $50 to any kid who wanted to be an extra, asking them to
simply play in front of a fire hydrant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are all my friends,'' I said. ``Dad, I wanna go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' my father said flatly.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing this, a gentleman who had earned the nickname Joey
Aggravation rushed over to my dad from the Pleasant Tavern and
shrieked, ``C'mon Frankie, let the kid go!''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' my dad said again, squeezing my hand. ``You're not a
gangster.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the closest I ever got to being in a movie, especially
the kind of movie that romanticized the lifestyles of the kind of
people I grew up with.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 30 years later, I got in line for another part. I was one
of thousands who showed up at Harrison High School on Saturday for
a much-publicized casting call for the hit HBO series ``The
Sopranos,'' which happens to be my favorite.
</P>
<P>
   With several relatives in tow, I arrived at the high school at 9
a.m. to find that thousands of young, cigar-chomping men in muscle
T-shirts and women with tall hairdos and spiked heels were already
there, the dizzying smells of perfume and hair spray filling the
hot air.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Lt. Charles Trucillo of the Harrison Police
Department estimated, 4,000 or 5,000 people were already in line.
</P>
<P>
   Trucillo said 400 to 500 people had slept in front of the school
overnight to improve their odds of successfully dropping off their
portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Using the power of my connections _ my ID card from The New York
Times, where I work as a news assistant _ I broke ranks to
negotiate a better deal somewhere up the line.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for the right place to jump in, I spotted a large man in
a silk suit. His name was Lou Roca. Other than the fact that he was
wearing handcuffs to the casting call, and handing out business
cards with the words ``You Lookin' at Me?'' written in bold letters
across the front, he seemed like a harmless guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got a problem with me standing here, pal?'' I asked with a
sly smile. ``I'm with the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Roca, who had made the trip from New Castle, Del., replied,
``Make me an offer I can't refuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can stand here if you get a message to Tony Soprano for
me,'' Roca said, referring to the lead character in the series,
played by James Gandolfini. ``Tell him I can help him with his
family problems. I can be on the muscle end of the family, the
fixer. I can make things go away.''
</P>
<P>
   By 9:45 a.m., the lines behind me had snaked down and around six
city blocks. I thought about my sister Donna, who could play
Carmela Soprano's dark-haired sister, waiting way back in line for
a chance that might never come.
</P>
<P>
   I know that feeling, which is why I worked out a the deal with
``Lou Rocks,'' as Roca refers to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Just before 10:30, when the doors were scheduled to open, I made
my first contact, bumping into Henry Brunchtein, a co-producer and
production manager for ``The Sopranos.'' He explained the enormous
turnout for the hugely popular show, which recently garnered 18
Emmy nominations, about Tony Soprano, who copes with the problems
of everyday family life while struggling to maintain his status as
a mob boss in the suburbs of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was, we were going to do a casting call and
announce it in a couple of small papers, expecting maybe a thousand
people, but then it got picked up by Regis and Howard Stern, and we
started to get a lot of phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were calling us, saying they were flying in from other
parts of the country, and many of them slept here overnight. We got
a call from a guy from New Mexico who wanted directions to Harrison
from Newark Airport.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time my conversation had ended with Brunchtein, the
crowds had swelled to nearly 20,000 people, eclipsing by 5,000 the
population of Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:45, I arrived at the steps of the school's gymnasium, and
as I began to head toward the casting directors _ men were in one
line, women in another _ I tapped into a few conversations some of
my would-be gangster friends were engaging in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Break a leg,'' Joe Oliveto of Roosevelt Island, N.Y., said to
another man on his way to meeting a casting director.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?'' asked the man, unsure about Oliveto's remark. ``You
talking to me?''
</P>
<P>
   As I got closer to my second chance at the big time, I heard a
young assistant casting director, Jarred Bryant, ask a bald man
with a big belly, 40-ish, ``Are you in the business?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' said the man, ``I'm in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What have you acted in?'' asked Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, not that business,'' said the man, smiling wide. ``I'm in
 &UR; the  &LR; business.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was my turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any acting experience?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, no,'' I said shyly. ``But almost. Thirty years ago, I
...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, thanks, and maybe we'll give you a call,'' said Bryant,
dropping my 5 by 7 glossy and a brief information form into a large
pile.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping outside, I heard an HBO official shouting into a
bullhorn, telling all the men in silk suits, and all the women in
high heels and short skirts, that they were closing the doors, and
offering an address for those who had been unable to see a casting
agent to mail in their mini-bios.
</P>
<P>
   I worked my way back through the crowd, and went home.
</P>
<P>
   I told my wife that if Tony Soprano called, I had a message for
him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
