<HEADLINE>
SPARKS TO FACE CONTENDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ After one day's rest, the Los Angeles Sparks
return to the Forum at 5 p.m. today when they meet another likely
playoff contender in the Sacramento Monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   Center Lisa Leslie had a solid game with 30 points and 16
rebounds, plus two key free throws, to help the Sparks pull off a
74-68 victory Friday at Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks (20-3) clinched their second consecutive playoff
berth with the victory, their fourth straight and 16th in 17 games.
Three-time defending WNBA champion Houston is the only other team
to have clinched a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento and Phoenix, which played late Saturday night, are in
a battle for the third playoff spot in the Western Conference. Four
teams advance from each conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks are 1-1 against the Monarchs, who caught the Sparks
on the second day of back-to-back games. The Sparks had defeated
the Mercury the night before and less than 24 hours later were in
Sacramento, where they suffered their first loss five games into
the season, 75-68.
</P>
<P>
   Forward-guard Mwadi Mabika scored 23 points to help the Sparks
avenge that loss with a 76-61 victory this month.
</P>
<P>
   This is the final regular-season meeting between these teams.
But it's possible they can meet again in the playoffs. Last season,
they met in a one-game playoff format with the Sparks winning,
82-80. But the Monarchs (14-9 before Saturday's game against
Phoenix) were without star center Yolanda Griffith, who suffered a
season-ending knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks are a much more experienced team than a year ago, and
Griffith, the league's MVP, Defensive Player of the Year and
Newcomer of the Year, has overcome her injury. Her average for
points (16.0 from 18.8) and rebounds (9.5 from 11.3) are down
slightly from last season, but the former Long Beach StingRay's
determination is as high as ever. She played on the Western
Conference All-Star team with Leslie, Mwadi and DeLisha Milton.
</P>
<P>
   Monarchs point guard Ticha Penicheiro is questionable for today.
She has a sore right foot, which prevented her from playing
Thursday against Minnesota.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
