<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBB'S 68 SEPARATES HER FROM THE FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL FIELDS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GURNEE, Ill. _ The golf was terrific, and the comparisons were
obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after Tiger Woods forged a large lead in the third round
of the British Open Saturday, Karrie Webb _ who has dominated her
peers in the last 18 months on the LPGA Tour the way Woods has on
the PGA Tour _ followed suit at the United States Women's Open,
shooting a four-under-par 68 for a seven-under 209 total at the
Merit Club to take a four-stroke advantage over Meg Mallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty uncanny that it has been so similar,'' said Webb,
who will have enough points to qualify for the LPGA Hall of Fame if
she is able to win her first United States Women's Open on Sunday.
``I'm out there trying to do my best. He's out there trying to do
his best.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods has won 13 times since January 1999, while Webb has
captured 10 titles. Each has won two major championships in that
period, including one apiece _ Woods by 15 strokes at the 2000
United States Open and Webb by 10 at the 2000 Nabisco Championship
_ by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   Each golfer is able to separate from the field. After Mallon,
the closest pursuers to Webb are four golfers _ Mi Hyun Kim, Rosie
Jones, Laura Davies and Dorothy Delasin _ at even-par 216.
</P>
<P>
   It was a frustrating and painful day for the 44-year-old Hall of
Famer Betsy King. She began the round tied with Webb at three
under, one stroke behind Mallon, but injured a muscle in her lower
back while hitting her tee shot on the 172-yard second hole.
</P>
<P>
   After aggravating the injury while hitting a shot out of the
rough on No.3, King requested medical treatment. A trainer massaged
her back, applied a therapeutic balm and gave her pain relievers,
but King was in obvious discomfort. She managed a birdie on the
fourth hole but quickly went into a tailspin and did not make
another par until the 11th hole.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to get through the round, King shot an 82 to tumble
from contention at 223, seven over par, but she got admiration from
Mallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the greatest rounds I've ever seen anybody
play,'' Mallon said. ``I'm not sure how she stayed out there. She
told me it felt like a knife was going through her back every time
she swung. I felt terrible for her.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury was particularly bad luck for the two-time Open
champion because as a former longtime student of Ed Oldfield, the
Merit Club's president, King had played the course 20 to 30 times
and was more familiar with it than any player in the field. In
fact, she is an honorary member of the club.
</P>
<P>
   Webb found little trouble on the Merit Club's course. Going out
on a partly cloudy day with light wind, she started fast. Accurate
approaches set up birdie putts within 15 feet on four of the first
seven holes. Webb took the lead with a seven-foot birdie putt on
the fourth hole and was not caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did feel pretty good about things today even though I was
pretty nervous,'' Webb said. ``When I birdied the second hole that
really calmed me down a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb has not been as uncatchable as Woods when holding the lead
in a tournament with one round to play, but her record is
formidable. Leading 19 events since 1995 with one round left, Webb
has won 11, finished second seven times and tied for seventh once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I've had some success on Sundays,'' she said. ``I
can always feed off that. But every Sunday is different. I've got
to stick to my game plan, don't do anything silly and try to make
some birdies.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallon, who had an up-and-down round that included playing up
the wrong fairway on the 14th hole, looked ahead to the final round
with some realism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen some funny things happen on Sunday,'' she said,
``but I don't expect it out of Karrie. She has one of the strongest
heads out here. But I'm going to play my heart out and try to get
close to her or catch her.''
</P>
<P>
   About 4,000 miles away, another group of golfers was feeling the
same way about a certain leading man. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
