<SLUG> BC-GLF-KING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK PAINS PUT KING OUT OF TITLE CONTENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIBERTYVILLE, Ill. _ Superior course knowledge could not
outweigh the impact of intense back pain yesterday for Betsy King,
who dropped off the leader board at the U.S. Women's Open with a
third-round 82.
</P>
<P>
   King, 44, had been bidding to become the oldest winner in the
tournament's 55-year history. A long-time student of Ed Oldfield,
the Merit Club president, King is an honorary member of the course
and had played it more than 30 times _ tops among the Open
competitors _ before emerging as a front-runner heading into the
weekend rounds.
</P>
<P>
   King's status changed radically after she pulled a muscle in her
lower back while hitting her tee shot on the second hole. King, who
began the third round at 3-under par and finished it at 7-over,
said she ``felt something pop'' in her lower back while hitting the
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every swing after that, it felt like a was knife going through
my back,'' said King, who indicated it is probable that she will
withdraw before today's 10:05 a.m. tee time, unless recurring
muscle spasms can be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the injury, King played on yesterday. When the situation
worsened after hitting out of the rough en route to a bogey at the
third hole, King received permission to have LPGA Tour trainer
Keith Kennedy visit her on the course.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the U.S. Golf Association's rules committee permitted
King a five-minute break after completion of her fifth hole to
confer with Kennedy. By that point, the damage to the scorecard had
begun in earnest with a double-bogey at No. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Before King headed to the sixth tee box, Kennedy massaged her
back, applied therapeutic balm and administered some pain
relievers. King, a two-time Open champ, took bogeys on the next
five holes after Kennedy's visit. For the day, King posted five
pars, two birdies, 10 bogeys and a double-bogey. She fell from
second to 28th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt sick for Betsy,'' said Meg Mallon, her playing partner.
``She was in a lot of pain. That was one of the gutsiest rounds
I've ever seen anyone play.''
</P>
<P>
   King said she continued playing in hope that muscle relaxers
might make the pain subside. That never happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had been any other tournament, I might have withdrawn on
the spot,'' King said. ``I couldn't make one swing without hurting.
It's the first time in 23 years on tour that something like this
has happened to me. I'm disappointed, but I've had more than my
fair share of good health and chances to win tournaments.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
