<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ESPN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPN EXTENDS ITS COMPETITIVE SPIRIT TO THE GREAT OUTDOORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB HOOD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The network that brought you the X Games has done it again.
</P>
<P>
   You might have seen the ESPN commericals. You know, the funny
ones. This time, it's not baseball or football or hockey or even
basketball. It's log rolling and tree chopping that makes us laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign promotes the inaugural ESPN Great Outdoor Games,
held this weekend in Lake Placid, N.Y. ESPN has planned 171/2 hours
of programming that involves more than 200 athletes, both humans
and dogs, whose four days of competition for a total purse of
$288,850 concludes today. The network plans to televise the events
next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Games are the latest in a run of ``alternative'' sports
made-for-TV shows that seem to be entering the mainstream. The
recent revival and increased popularity of professional wrestling
has opened the door for more alternative programming. Since ESPN
debuted the X Games in 1995, the network has followed with more
than a dozen other programs, including the Winter X Games, the X
trials, the ACC-Big Ten Challenge, the Great 8 Basketball Festival
and D3: Bikes, Boards and Blades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proprietary programming like the X Games and the ESPY Awards
is definitely a trend and development in the '90s,'' ESPN spokesman
Dave Nagle said. ``And for good reason. They are events that we
own. We can run them to our own specifications, which helps
broadcasting. There are no rights fees, and no one can take it away
from you.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's goal is to reach out to a bigger audience by providing
alternative sports, and to ``open people's eyes as to what is
sports and what can be televised.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as with the X Games, we feel we can make these sports
entertainment whether you participate or not,'' Nagle said. ``But
millions of people participate in these sports. Tons of people own
fishing and hunting licenses. Tons of people own dogs. Not many
people participate in the timber sports, but lots of people have
saws in their back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception 21 years ago, ESPN has changed the
definition of sports broadcasting, and Nagle said it has always
been looking for ways to improve its product and to increase its
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the beginning, people have always asked, `How can you
fill 24 hours a day with sports programming?' This is how. Now we
have ESPN2 and we fill 48, not to mention ESPNEWS and ESPN
Classic,'' Nagle said.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Games include 21 events in four categories _
fishing, target shooting, timber sports and shooting dogs
competition.
</P>
<P>
   After this week's coverage, ESPN2 will air one-hour segments of
the Games at 10 a.m. from July 31 through Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   In filming each event, ESPN officials said they not only used
some of the most sophisticated equipment available but also
invented new ones especially for some contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at every event with a fresh and creative eye,
willing to rewrite whatever rules existed in covering these
sports,'' said Dave Miller, ESPN senior coordinating producer.
``Our mission is to present programming that is entertaining and
informative, whether you have ever cast a rod, chopped a log or
called a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the high-tech equipment used to film the events is a
DogCam, which is worn on the collar by freelance ``stunt dogs'' as
they perform runs on an agility-testing course. A PoleCam was used
to film underwater shots during the fishing coverage, and an
accelerometer, which is similar to a seismograph used in measuring
earthquakes, will be used for timing and scoring many of the timber
events.
</P>
<P>
   The accelerometer was created by ESPN and is said to be more
accurate for measuring the exact moment chopping begins and ends
and feeds the results into the scoring and production computers.
</P>
<P>
   Other special effects were accomplished by placing cameras
beneath the archery targets to show incoming arrows, in a
low-flying plane where announcer Jerry McKinnis interviews bass
fishermen over a cell phone, and one mounted atop the 120-meter ski
jump tower at Lake Placid for scenic shots.
</P>
<P>
   A 15-person team of announcers will provide insight for the
Games. The team includes Mark Malone, a former NFL quarterback who
has worked with ESPN since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors were chosen from accomplishments in their
categories, and a few earned berths through special try-out
sessions, said Robert Massey of Fort Worth, who was invited to
compete in the rifle competition but was forced to cancel due to
business obligations. Texas is represented by 12 competitors,
including Laura Yarbrough of Dallas, who has entered her dog in the
sporting dogs event, the Top Dog Racers team of Dallas, and Scott
Robertson of Flower Mound in the shotgun shooting event.
</P>
<P>
   Anglers will have two types of competition, fly fishing and bass
fishing. Twelve fly fishermen will earn a berth to a one-fish
tournament through fly casting competition on the Ausable River.
Likewise, 10 bass anglers fishing on Oseetah Lake will compete to
capture a spot in the five-angler finals field to see who can catch
the largest bass.
</P>
<P>
   The bass-fishing event carries the largest purse at $21,000,
with $5,000 going to the winner. Other first-place prizes average
between $2,000 and $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   Among the pro bass anglers will be Keith Green, top money winner
of the Wal-Mart FLW Tour, and Randy Howell, runner-up for the 1999
FLW Angler of the Year. Terry and Windy Gunn, fishing guides on the
Colorado River at the head of the Grand Canyon, will be among the
fly anglers.
</P>
<P>
   Sporting dogs will have five events where the canines will run,
jump, slide and retrieve. Eight contests will test men and women
for endurance, wood chopping and climbing, plus target competition
for archers, rifle shooters and shotgunners.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be creative and keep presenting things that
capture people's attention, because people's attention spans have
gotten so short and the remote is always in their hand,'' Nagle
said. ``So the idea is to create something they haven't seen
before, and people haven't seen the Great Outdoor Games before.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 2021EDT &QL; 
