<SLUG> BC-MOTHER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAP-CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
 OF SLAIN RAPPER SPEAKS AT KANSAS CITY CONFERENCE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK WIEBE  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The mother of slain rapper Notorious B.I.G.
defended graphic rap lyrics during a speech Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Voletta Wallace _ whose son Christopher Wallace was killed in a
1997 drive-by shooting in Los Angeles _ addressed an audience of
about 30 mostly young persons at Christ Temple Pentecostal Church
in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The graphic violence and profanity found in some rap lyrics, she
said, simply mirrors the harsh life some rappers have escaped.
Focusing attention on this violent world, she said, is one way to
recognize that a problem exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rapper has nothing to do with this,'' Wallace said. ``He's
just telling you what's out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's speech was one of several events that took place
during a two-day conference that began Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The conference brought together local rap artists, community
activists and politicians to discuss strategies for giving young
people alternatives to drugs and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who received a proclamation from Mayor Kay Barnes
before her speech, said that rap lyrics can provide a launching pad
for exploring some of those alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``(These artists) are asking us to change,'' she said. ``They're
saying, `Help me, help my street corner. Because if you don't, I'm
going to talk about it.' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what Wallace's son did. Notorious B.I.G., who also went
by the moniker Biggie Smalls, used his music to depict a life of
drugs and crime, of dodging bullets and of living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Those lyrics, though, fueled the controversy about whether rap
music like his actually promoted violence and drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace doesn't think it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not put down the art,'' she said. ``Let's not put down
the person. Let's stop the problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
