<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SPELLMAN-TEX </SLUG>
 
Spellman amazed by altered image 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS _ Mention defensive tackle Alonzo Spellman's name
to anyone on the Cowboys, and you'll likely get a smile followed by
a lengthy narrative.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody has a feel-good story about Spellman, who seemingly
has gone from outcast to savior in 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   A year after the Cowboys took a wait-and-see approach when he
joined the team during the 1999 training camp, Spellman is being
hailed as a team leader, a role model and a key to any success the
Cowboys hope to have on defense.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is certainly not lost on the deeply religious
Spellman. However, just thinking about his altered image can render
him speechless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at a loss for words ... I've changed a great deal in the
last year,'' he said softly.
</P>
<P>
   Raising his head after a practice recently at Midwestern State
University, Spellman, 28, continued: ``I do see a difference and
feel a difference of the perception of myself to other people. I
don't get that scared look anymore. I get a smile, and that's a
good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another good thing is that the mountainous Spellman is finally
smiling back.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4, 292-pounder says he was in control of his problems
when he joined the Cowboys a week into training camp last year. A
six-year stint with the Chicago Bears ended in the spring of 1998
after a string of emotional incidents relating to what was
diagnosed as bipolar disorder. Spellman sat out the 1998 season,
and says he even contemplated suicide.
</P>
<P>
   A religious rebirth and confidence in the support programs laid
out by the Cowboys' behavioral department paved the way for his
return to football.
</P>
<P>
   However, Spellman said he also was somewhat skeptical about the
future when he took the field for the first time last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I was smiling when I got here,'' Spellman said. ``It was
just under a whole lot of problems. So I had kind of a half-smile
last year. This year, I'm grinning like a Cheshire cat. It's a
great thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow defensive tackle Chad Hennings says Spellman's new
outlook is evident in his play and how he interacts with teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alonzo is a much different person this year,'' Henning said.
``He is totally at ease. He's come out of his shell and bonded with
the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Spellman's personal redemption, however, is only part of the
story.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, the former defensive end is ready to build on a
successful transition to tackle. He supplanted former Pro Bowl
standout Leon Lett in the starting lineup last year and is billed
by the Cowboys as an All-Pro candidate in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Spellman also is using his experiences as a learning tool for
others, an even greater part of his story. Second-year defensive
end Dimitrius Underwood, whose troubled rookie season included
being released by two teams and a suicide attempt, joined the
Cowboys largely because of Spellman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk almost every day,'' said Underwood, who also has
bipolar disorder. ``A lot of his past is similar to what I went
through and what I'm going through. He tells me how to deal with
it. He's been a big help.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said Spellman's leadership, however,
is not limited to helping Underwood. He said Spellman's work ethic
and play on the field is worthy of emulation by all of the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said it warms his heart every time he thinks about how far
Spellman has come in the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were unbelievable early days this time last year in camp
for Alonzo,'' Jones said. ``It was quite a struggle for him, coming
off a huge layoff, plus dealing with the challenges he was having,
plus being around new people, the skepticism, the whole nine yards.
But he's stepped up here and gained the respect of everybody. He
ought to be a leader. I'm proud of how far he's come.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Jones said it all with a smile. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
