<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0093 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-COVERDELL-MEMORIAL-NY     07-22 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-MEMORIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIAL FOR COVERDELL: SAYING GOODBYE TO A QUIET MAN WHO GOT
THINGS DONE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The political elite of Washington and Georgia paid
tribute here on Saturday to Sen. Paul Coverdell as an ordinary man
with extraordinary people skills and political talents who got
things done.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell, who died Tuesday at age 61, was a quietly influential
member of the Republican leadership. An ally and friend of
President George Bush, Coverdell was the chief liaison in the
Senate to the presidential campaign of Bush's son, Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Governor Bush and more than 50 senators and
representatives from both parties _ including Sens. Trent Lott of
Mississippi, the majority leader, and Edward M. Kennedy, Democrat
of Massachusetts _ joined 900 other mourners in an emotional
memorial to a man who defied the bitter political partisanship that
grips the Capitol today. President Bush did not attend, but his
tribute was read by a family friend of the Coverdells in the packed
Peachtree United Methodist Church in the fashionable Buckhead
section of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved politics and was a clear example of politics being a
noble calling,'' President Bush wrote. ``He leaves behind a legacy
that quiet is good, caring about the other guy matters.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day of celebrating Coverdell's life, even the fevered pitch
of the presidential campaign was temporarily laid aside. Before and
after the service, Governor Bush declined to comment on reports
that Dick Cheney, the former secretary of defense, had risen to the
top of his list of potential running mates.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers attending the service, including other Republican vice
presidential candidates like Fred Thompson of Tennessee and John
McCain of Arizona, were whisked to waiting cars or buses. But one
Senate Republican, Mike DeWine of Ohio, said a Bush-Cheney ticket
this fall would be a winning combination. ``Dick Cheney has got
what it takes,'' DeWine said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the legislators and other family members and friends of
Coverdell here Saturday declined to talk politics, focusing instead
on the unpretentious former backbencher in the Georgia State Senate
who rose to the fourth-ranking position in the Senate Republican
hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde Rodbell, an Atlanta businessman and longtime friend of
Coverdell, recalled that the senator hated anyone making a fuss
over him, and took umbrage that his job might earn him favors from
constituents or anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Inside and outside the church, former colleagues remembered a
self-effacing man and tireless worker who pushed for issues he
believed in, from education vouchers to aid to help Colombia fight
drug traffickers, without caring who received the credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sweet, selfless, loyal, caring, courageous, and _
incredibly for a United States senator _ humble,'' Sen. Phil Gramm,
a Texas Republican, said in his eulogy. Coverdell's efforts to help
and get things done crossed partisan lines. Gov. Roy Barnes of
Georgia, a Democrat, said that when he joined the Georgia state
Senate as a 26-year-old legislator, Coverdell took him under his
political wing, even though he was the leader of the chamber's
Republicans. It was a friendship that lasted more than a
quarter-century, with the two men having breakfast regularly,
Barnes said. ``He showed that people of different parties could
discuss their personal strengths and weaknesses,'' Barnes said, his
voice catching while giving his eulogy. ``I never worried that Paul
would disclose anything I said.'' Under Georgia law, Barnes has the
authority to appoint an interim successor to Coverdell's Senate
seat until a special election is held on Nov. 7. He is expected to
announce his choice in the next few days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
