<SLUG> BC-BKO-MOKESKI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOKESKI DENIES ALLEGATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The lawyer for former NBA player and Crespi High
basketball player Paul Mokeski denied reports that Mokeski was a
regular drug user following his arrest for misdemeanor possession
of cocaine Thursday in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Mokeski vehemently denies the inflammatory reports
concerning the allegations regarding drug use,'' said his attorney,
Douglas Horn, in a prepared statement. ``While it has become
popular to convict professional athletes before all the facts and
evidence are known, to do so is irresponsible prior to the
conclusion of the legal process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Mokeski is confident that the legal process in Wisconsin
will be quickly resolved in a fair and just manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Mokeski could face a year in jail and a $5,000 fine if
convicted. Last year, he moved back to Southern California and was
an assistant coach at USC. He resigned in May to become head coach
of the Kansas City Knights of the new American Basketball
Association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
