<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-BRITOPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALLING UNDER SCOTLAND'S SPELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ Tom Weiskopf returned to the home of
golf last week to take part in a past champions dinner and
four-hole tournament as a prelude to the 129th British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Or, more accurately, Weiskopf was pulled back, a hopeless
romantic when it comes to the charm of golf in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   What was the appeal? Weiskopf had a long list of factors, from
the architecture that you see on strolls downtown, to the aura of
links golf, to the signs of rich history that are everywhere. But
most of all, said Weiskopf, he loves the people. He had noticed on
his first visit, in 1970, that they loved their golf and respected
its heritage, ``but they were pretty guarded with their applause.
Unless it's a really good shot, there's not a lot of applause.''
</P>
<P>
   To prove what he meant, he related the story he told at the
dinner Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was a practice round at Carnoustie before the 1975 British
Open, which would be won by Tom Watson in a playoff against Jack
Newton. Late in the afternoon, Weiskopf was playing with Jack
Nicklaus, John O'Leary, and Newton when they came to the par-3
eighth. There weren't many spectators on the course, but as they
prepared to tee off, Weiskopf did notice two men sitting near the
green.
</P>
<P>
   Weiskopf tells the story:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a medium-length par-3, wind blowing real hard left to
right. Jack (Nicklaus) hit a very good shot, kind of turned it
right against the wind. The wind caught it and moved it sideways 15
feet. Beautiful shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I aimed at those two old gentlemen on the left side of the
green. I just said I'd start my ball right at them, try to turn it,
and see what happens. I did just that, the wind got it, knocked it
right down near the hole. Then I got there, and nothing. Just two
guys just sitting there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Where's my ball?' I looked in the bunker, my
ball's not in there. I walked over the green, but my ball's not
over the trees. I look around and Jack says, `Can you believe it?
Your ball's in the hole.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm standing by these two gentlemen, and I said, `Excuse
me, but did you see my shot?'
</P>
<P>
   `` `Yes, Laddie, we saw your shot.'
</P>
<P>
   `` `It was a hole-in-one. There was no response. You didn't even
clap.'
</P>
<P>
   `` `Aye, Laddie, but it's only practice, isn't it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Weiskopf rocks with laughter. ``I'll never forget that as long
as I live,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On his fourth try at a British Open, in 1973, Weiskopf triumphed
at Royal Troon. It remains his most treasured memory. That victory
puts him in a special category over here, for former champions are
always beloved figures. Still, Weiskopf couldn't help notice that
as he did some Christmas shopping in the tented village the other
day, the spectators pretty much left him alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they respected that I was shopping,'' said Weiskopf.
``They're great people.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another Scotland story that tickles Weiskopf, arising
from a few casual holes of golf at St. Andrews one evening years
ago. Weiskopf, Nicklaus, and others were commuting from St. Andrews
to the Open venue, so after dinner they decided to go out and play.
Weiskopf told the others he would join them after a phone call, and
in his rush to catch up, he went to the only set of tees from which
he had ever hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laddie, excuse me,'' came a voice from the side of the first
tee. ``That is reserved for championship play only.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiskopf was dumbfounded. ``You're telling me that Jack Nicklaus
hit from there?'' said Weiskopf, pointing to the other set of tees.
The man nodded his head, so Weiskopf relented and moved to those
tees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laddie, your ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My ticket?'' said Weiskopf, again dumbfounded. ``I'm a former
British Open champion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your name?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Weiskopf.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have any proof?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It says so right there on my bag,'' said Weiskopf, by now
exasperated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had that one pulled on me before,'' said the starter, by
now a winner in the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Weiskopf paid his green fees and went on his way, forgetting
about the starter until the next year when he was out hitting balls
at Royal Birkdale on a cold, raw night in preparation for the Open.
Out of the corner of his eye he noticed the starter he had
encountered at St. Andrews. The man explained he had taken vacation
time just to come watch Weiskopf.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think about that,'' Weiskopf reflected. ``Here's a guy just
doing his job. Can't hit from that tee. Gotta need a ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Exhibition of greatness
</P>
<P>
   The past champions four-hole exhibition Wednesday proved a huge
hit, with fans and players alike genuinely getting a kick out of
it. Some highlights:
</P>
<P>
   --Sam Snead, at 88 the oldest living winner, said he can't see
his golf ball once it goes more than 50 yards, so he definitely
didn't see his drive as it traveled dead-straight some 200 yards
down the first fairway. Coming over the Swilken Bridge at the 18th,
Snead did a little soft-shoe. Why? ``Oh, I've always loved music,''
said Snead.
</P>
<P>
   --Roberto de Vicenzo, remembered for his 1968 Masters gaffe and
not for his major triumph over Nicklaus in 1967, drove it pin-high
at the 357-yard closing hole. ``He turned it loose,'' said Watson,
smiling. Watson and Nicklaus _ eight British Open titles between
them _ were paired with de Vicenzo, which thrilled the proud
77-year-old Argentine. ``It would be nice today, tomorrow, any
day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   --Ian Baker-Finch, one of the true gems in the game, finished
with birdies at the par-4 17th and par-4 18th, no small feat for a
guy who walked away from the game after a mysterious loss of skill.
``I hung on to the drive at the first a little bit and it went a
little right,'' said Baker-Finch, who now works for ABC. He won the
British Open in 1991, but a few years later he couldn't even keep
his opening drive in-bounds at St. Andrews's first hole, which has
a fairway wide enough for a pair of 747s. His story was sad, but
there was a smile on his face as he took part in the exhibition.
``I felt a lot more comfortable than I did in, say, 1996-97,'' said
Baker-Finch, who would like to come back and play a few PGA Tour
events next year. Is that possible? He did birdie 17 and 18
Wednesday, so more improbable things have happened. ``I am an
announcer now, but coming and playing occasionally and getting my
fix of tournament golf _ yeah, I would like to go do that.''
</P>
<P>
   --But a lowlight Wednesday was the story in a local tabloid
(which right away tells you about its validity) that said Arnold
Palmer had rejected an invitation to play in the exhibition because
he had not been extended the same rights for the regular
tournament. Former champions (Palmer won in 1961, '62) are exempt
until age 65, which for Palmer came in 1995, when he played right
here at St. Andrews. It made for an emotional farewell, the walk
over the Swilken Bridge leaving a most memorable photograph, no
doubt an experience that could never be duplicated. Palmer is
playing in this week's Senior PGA Tour event, and Hugh Campbell,
chairman of the British Open championship committee, denied that
Palmer had asked for (and been denied) entry into the British. ``He
never put it to us like that,'' said Campbell. ``He did (tell me
his reasons), but I think some of that was a little private for me
to want to comment on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For old time's sake
</P>
<P>
   Butch Harmon was at a book signing recently when he noticed a
man selling golf memorabilia, among them an old gutta-percha ball.
``Actually, a replica,'' said Harmon, who was intrigued by the
hard, rubber-coated ball. Harmon bought the ball and for a few
laughs tossed it to Tiger Woods during a practice round Tuesday.
``He hit it a few times,'' said Harmon, ``but then played it for
the entire ninth hole,'' a par 4 of 352 yards. ``He hit his drive
(with his regular ball) to the edge of the green, then hit the
gutta-percha well behind it. I stepped it off _ 113 yards
shorter.'' Woods played a 5-iron into the pin, 125 yards away,
``but he had too much club,'' said Harmon, laughing. ``He probably
should have hit 7.'' Still, Woods got the gutta-percha up-and-down
from behind the green to save par . . . Jean Van de Velde on his
Ryder Cup experience last fall: ``I really enjoyed the atmosphere
and the battle of it, but I didn't enjoy the fact that I didn't get
to play, knowing I had qualified as one of 10 players. The players
who qualify should be assured that they are going to play and not
just in singles because they have to. What's the point in having a
qualifying system?'' . . . Weiskopf on the emotions he felt at the
past champions dinner: ``I think you would be hard-pressed to find
a group of people in sports with the compassion and respect that
golfers have for each other. And you could see that at that dinner,
you really could.'' . . . Brought to the St. Andrews interview
area, Snead looked at the crowd of reporters on the other side of
the barrier and asked: ``Won't they let you in?''
</P>
</TEXT>
