<HEADLINE>
BURKHART TOOK LONG, TOUGH ROAD TO MAJORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was lost in the wilderness, a discarded soul clinging to the
last strand of a tattered dream. Anyone who bothered to look deemed
Morgan Burkhart too short, too slow, too old, too second-rate to be
all he hoped: a big-league baseball player.
</P>
<P>
   With no fork left in his road to glory, Burkhart landed in the
early-morning swelter of a construction job in a Kansas City
warehouse. The kid who would have welcomed much less from baseball
than a Hall of Fame plaque was lugging steel. ``The worst thing,''
he said, ``was thinking I was all done, that I'd never take the
field again.''
</P>
<P>
   Think again. In a storybook tale of promise and perseverance as
remarkable as any, the castaway spent the next seven years
thrashing his way out of the darkness. He survived an attack of
killer bees on a baseball diamond in Colombia, endured two winters
of langourous bus rides in the Mexican outback, and labored four
long summers in the aptly named Frontier League, all in a quixotic
apprenticeship that delivered the promising slugger to the Red Sox
last month in their hour of need.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely in the 98 years since Piano Legs Hickman donned the Red
Sox colors has a player so obscure _ and with such a roundabout
resume _ achieved such a milestone. Burkhart all but fell out of
the sky to help rescue the Sox from a disastrous June slump and
keep them in playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   And to this day, his new boss, Sox manager Jimy Williams, eyes
his potential folk hero and wonders aloud, ``Who is that masked
man?''
</P>
<P>
   The hitter from nowhere is a child of Missouri's storied
Mississippi River valley, a 5-foot-10-inch Paul Bunyan, with a
lumberjack's arms and farm boy's grit. Until last month, when he
wheeled his aging Camaro into the players' parking lot at Fenway,
an area that glittered with custom-made Mercedeses and luxury SUVs,
Burkhart, 28, had never seen the bright lights of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   He climbs into his uniform in the clubhouse an arm's length from
millionaires whose ascents to the big show were almost never in
doubt. And he is a world apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I was going to be here, especially when I
started getting older, 26, 27,'' he said last week in the dugout as
a soft rain fell before a game with the Montreal Expos. ``I said,
`No way, no one's going to want you.' That's not easy when all you
ever wanted to do was play baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkhart seized a chance to trade his work boots for baseball
cleats in 1995 when someone suggested he try out for the Frontier
League, which he had never heard of. He said he did it for love of
the game. And no one who has watched him since then has doubted
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time he hit the field, you could see in everything he
did how much he loves and respects baseball,'' said Duke Ward, part
owner of the Richmond (Ind.) Roosters, where Burkhart toiled from
1995-98. ``If there is a soul on the planet who deserves this kind
of break, he's the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkhart worked for weeks to earn as much as he made his first
day in a Sox uniform (he is currently paid the Major League minimum
of $200,000). He rode in vans to play the Canton (Ohio) Crocodiles
and London (Ontario) Werewolves when the Roosters couldn't afford a
bus. And he scraped by on the league's top pay of $275 a week by
living with a ``host'' family and working as a substitute teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, he was making less than the paperboy,'' Ward
said. ``Now, he's reaffirming the dream for everyone else who is
still here.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Burkhart shunned warnings against playing winter
ball in Colombia because of the country's crime rate. ``It turned
out to be rough,'' he said, ``but the baseball was great.''
</P>
<P>
   His worst scare came on the field, when a swarm of killer bees
swooped in. Amid the frenzy, Burkhart escaped injury by heeding
cries from Colombians to dive to the ground because the bees
apparently don't attack that low. ``It was crazy,'' he said matter
of factly, as if all big-leaguers paid such dues.
</P>
<P>
   At every stop on his odyssey, Burkhart proved himself to his
peers, winning Most Valuable Player honors three straight years in
the Frontier League and last winter in the Mexican League. Indeed,
the Frontier League recently voted to rename its top prize The
Morgan Burkhart MVP Award.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, unlike the overwhelming majority of big-league players who
are drafted and nurtured through minor-league systems, Burkhart
went undrafted and never spoke to a scout until the Sox picked him
up in 1998 as an amateur free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, the Sox never invited him to their big-league spring
training camp, despite his 35 home runs last year in their Single A
and Double A affiliates in Sarasota, Fla., and Trenton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   But he kept thrashing. ``I just wanted to keep playing, hoping I
could make a living playing somewhere,'' he said. ``Luckily, I got
the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   His break came in February when the Red Sox, temporarily short
of players during spring training, summoned him from their minor
league camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first I heard of him, someone told me he was tearing up
the Mexican League,'' Williams said. ``But he came up that day in
Florida and hit a home run into the wind that just kept going and
going. I said to myself, `My goodness.' ''
</P>
<P>
   When Trot Nixon, Boston's starting right fielder, injured his
hamstring last month, the Sox sent for Burkhart from Triple A
Pawtucket. Since then, despite his shortcomings as a fielder and
baserunner, Burkhart has won over many of his teammates with his
enthusiasm and respect for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so rare to see in a young player, that they appreciate
life in the major leagues,'' said Mike Stanley, who has more than
12 years of major league experience. ``So many kids come into the
league thinking they were destined to be here anyway, that it was
just a matter of when they got their shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at all the wars he's gone through . . . This is all gravy
to him. This is the ultimate reward we shoot for, and he never
thought he'd get here.''
</P>
<P>
   He endured his worst outing in the majors last Thursday, when he
went hitless and struck out five times in a day-night doubleheader
against the Baltimore Orioles. Still, in 19 games with the Sox
going into Saturday, he has knocked in 15 runs, hit two homers, and
posted a .444 on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even now, he remains a mystery to many in baseball. In
Baltimore, the giant scoreboard identified him as ``Morgan'' rather
than ``Burkhart.''
</P>
<P>
   But anonymity means little to a man whose lost years could
define obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   He still lives in the shadows of the Sox luminaries, listening
to Metallica as he drives home after a game to a cut-rate hotel in
Boston, while his teammates motor home to their gated suburban
enclaves and pricy downtown condos.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he counts his blessings. ``The hard times were good for
me,'' Burkhart said. ``It makes me appreciate everything I have.
Every day I get to play baseball is another day I'm not (working
construction).''
</P>
<P>
   In the mercurial world of baseball, Burkhart's job may always be
in jeopardy. His first scare could come as early as this week when
Nixon returns. But Williams, in a game where business almost always
trumps emotion, seems to have a place in his heart for his rookie
from the frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be fine,'' Williams said. ``He's done a great job for
us. I may not know where he came from, but I'm sure glad he's
wearing a Red Sox uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Edes of the Globe staff contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
