<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG WILL BE CYCLING FOR OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROYES, France _ It's obvious Lance Armstrong is becoming
attached to the color yellow. He's expected to win the winner's
yellow jersey in the Tour de France when the race ends in Paris
Sunday, and hopes to keep the color theme going this fall in the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Amstrong is looking forward to that return. He went in 1992 as
an amateur and didn't medal, and again to Atlanta in 1996, when he
finished 12th in the road race and sixth in the time trial;
surprisingly disappointing results after a successful summer of
racing. But what was more surprising is that three months later
Armstrong was diagnosed with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   So now, after chemotherapy, an eventual clean bill of health,
and an expected two Tour victories, Armstrong is ready to go back
to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it just goes to show that what your mind doesn't know
really doesn't affect you so much,'' Armstrong said of his naivete
in Atlanta. But he said he's eager to ride the time trial in
Sydney, ``because it's a race I think I can be competitive in.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States can send a team of five to compete on the
road, two of whom will ride the time trial.
</P>
<P>
   The track team has been announced, but the road team will be
finalized Aug. 1. Three of the five definites are Armstrong, who is
the top-ranked American in international racing points; George
Hincapie, the highest-ranked American in World Cup points; and
Antonio Cruz, who won the road time trials last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Other hopefuls at the Tour include Tyler Hamilton (from
Marblehead, Mass.), who was an alternate for the 1996 team; Fred
Roridguez, who won the US Pro Championship last June has taken
third and fourth place in two Tour stages, and Frankie Andreu, who
finished fourth in the '96 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong will ride in the road race: ``I told George (Hincapie)
that I'll do everything for him, but will concentrate on the time
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think focusing on the time trial is going to be the smartest
thing I can do,'' he said, noting that the training regime involves
shorter workouts. ``It won't be seven-hour days, but four-hour
days.''
</P>
<P>
   US coach Jim Ochowicz, who is here watching the Tour, wouldn't
say who the favorites are to fill the last two spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not one overwhelming person,'' said Ochowicz. ``We're
lucky it's a hard decision, though, and I think we're going to have
a strong team no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   Ochowicz said that Armstrong's presence should give the US an
automatic gold in the time-trial race.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a real no-brainer,'' said Ochowicz after watching the
American blow past everyone in Friday's time trial.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Armstrong said he has mixed feelings about Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning a gold medal would be very special, one of the
highlights of my career,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, after the summer he has spent on the
podium, with more racing to go next month, he's being cautiously
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to speak about it right now because I'm so caught up
in the Tour, and afterward I'll be caught up in trying to recover
from this Tour physically and mentally,'' he said. ``So it's going
to be tricky to finish here, to try and recover, go back down, then
go back up for a race six or seven weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tour drains you so much, physically and mentally, that
it's going to be hard to rally, but it is a big goal. I've been
twice, and the last two times were disappointments. I'd prefer it
was in August, but I'm not going to sit at home.''
</P>
<P>
   But why go to Sydney if the Tour is so draining?
</P>
<P>
   The rider in the yellow jersery just smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I think I can win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
