<HEADLINE>
WEBB TAKES COMMAND OF US OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GURNEE, Ill. _ Their birthdays are nine days apart, and if they
both win Sunday, they'll have each won three of their last four
major tournaments for their gender. But Karrie Webb and Tiger Woods
have been in the same group only once and, as Webb put it, ``that's
about all the contact I've ever had with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it is dangerous to compare genders, it must be noted how
long Webb hits the ball off the tee, how she was over the 522-yard,
par-5 eighth hole here at Merit Club in two shots Friday, and how
resolute her approach is to winning golf. Similarities abound.
</P>
<P>
   But more important to Webb as she heads into the final round of
the 55th US Women's Open with a four-shot lead is that this would
be her first Open win after four failed and frustrating attempts.
And . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``If I win, you know,'' said the 25-year-old Australian, ``I
have enough points to be in the LPGA's Hall of Fame. And that is,
you know, my ultimate career goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Already.
</P>
<P>
   Webb's 4-under 68 Saturday, putting her at 209 and 7 under for
the first three rounds of the Open, left only her and Meg Mallon
(213, 3 under) with below-par scores for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But all that was overshadowed by the pain in Betsy King's back.
</P>
<P>
   King threw out her back on her tee shot on the second hole. The
courage the 44-year-old displayed from then on was remarkable. She
completed her round despite every shot from then on feeling, she
said, ``like a knife going through my back.''
</P>
<P>
   The pain for King was both physical and emotional.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA even took mercy, allowing her to take a five-minute
break between the fifth and sixth holes to enable the LPGA's
doctor, Dr. Keith Kennedy, to apply therapeutic balm, give her a
massage, and dispense painkillers.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the USGA abandoned its usual strictness on slow play and
allowed King and playing partner Mallon to fall farther and farther
behind the group in front of them, as King had difficulty merely
walking from green to tee.
</P>
<P>
   On the 14th tee, for instance, after a short walk from the 13th
green, she collapsed to the grass and writhed in agony before
rising to hit her tee shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know about it until the third green,'' said Mallon, a
close friend of King's. ``She came up and said, `My back went out.'
I hadn't heard anything. All I knew was that it took an awful long
time for her to walk to the third tee. Then she said it was like a
knife going through her back every time she was going through her
swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, on the sixth tee, ``she was taking Advil and her father,
who's a doctor, was walking with her, and he was giving her
Tylenol,'' recalled Mallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``She called me by another name. I said, `Betsy, you'd better
stop taking those drugs.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The pain was emotional, too. King fired a brilliant 70 Friday,
putting her only one stroke behind Mallon, the leader. This may
have been her last chance to win a major. ``Hopefully, there'll be
other chances,'' a resolute King said through clenched teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'll be able to play (the next round) or not,
but if I can, I will be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Without doubt, said Mallon, ``that was the bravest performance
I've ever seen on a golf course.'' King parred the first two holes
Saturday but, after her back went out, she could only wince through
a 10-over round of 82.
</P>
<P>
   Webb, meanwhile, seems close to stamping herself as the world's
best women's golfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to talk to myself every now and then, try to calm
myself down so I don't get too far ahead of myself,'' she said. ``I
just have to think of the shot at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with her brilliant round, Webb's lead over Mallon had
dropped to two strokes over the Natick, Mass., native when Webb
bogeyed the 17th hole and Mallon, in the group behind but three
holes in arrears, birdied the 15th hole.
</P>
<P>
   Mallon, though, chose the wrong time to hit what she called ``my
only bad drive of the day.'' The ball landed in the rough. ``When I
got to it, it looked like somebody stepped on it twice and then
threw some grass on it,'' she said. Mallon went rough-to-rough with
her shots, ending up with a double bogey. ``Now I have to come out
and be aggressive since I'm down four and not just down two,'' she
said of Sunday's play.
</P>
<P>
   No other golfers are within seven strokes of Webb. It's possible
Webb just may step away from this field as Woods has stepped away
from some men's fields. But, cautioned Webb, nobody should get
carried away with any comparisons to Woods, even if their birthdays
are nine days apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 25,'' she said with a laugh. ``I'm actually a year older
than Tiger. So, you know, I'm getting over the hill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
