<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOURDEFRANCE-LASTDAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL STAGE IS SET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROYES, France _ One day to go. After 20 races in 22 days, and
more than 3,500 miles around the country, the Tour de France is
almost over.
</P>
<P>
   And when the 128 remaining riders roll in Paris Sunday
afternoon, Lance Armstrong of Texas should take home the yellow
jersey for the second year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have to be careful,'' he said Saturday. ``It's still
a stage, it still counts, it's still official, and I'll still not
be convinced of victory until I finish the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even though Armstrong wouldn't jinx the win by assuming
it's all over, only a disaster on the ride around Paris Sunday
would cause him to stop pedaling and affect his six-minute lead
over German Jan Ullrich.
</P>
<P>
   As the riders made their way on the 158-mile, rolling course
that finished here in the Champagne region, none seemed inclined to
exert themselves more than necessary. It was the longest stage in
this year's Tour.
</P>
<P>
   French rider Francois Simon, who lives near the finish, went out
in front two-thirds of the way into the race and gained a
one-minute lead on the pack. But he was soon joined by two others,
and all three eventually were caught by the pack.
</P>
<P>
   With less than 2 miles to go, the cyclists came swarming into
town and jockeyed for position. Germany's Erik Zabel edged
Australian Robbie McEwen in the sprint finish with the rest of the
pack just behind them. It was only fitting for Zabel, who wears the
green jersey (worn by the rider with the most sprint points earned)
for the fifth straight year.
</P>
<P>
   Americans George Hincapie and Fred Rodriguez (who wears the
stars-and-stripes jersey as national champion) were in the final
sprint, but they and the first 100 riders were given ``same time''
as Zabel, and the overall standings didn't change.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong could only smile and shake his head when asked about
having one more day to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel really good, but I think everybody is relieved that
the race is almost over,'' he said. ``Three weeks is a long time to
race a sports event, whether you finish in first place or 101st
place. But it's nice to finish, and it's nice to finish hopefully
in yellow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
