<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-CROSHERE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROSHERE NOT A REAL NET GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There were more than a few shaking heads last week at the Shaw's
Pro Summer League when the topic came to the Celtics' pursuit of
Austin Croshere.
</P>
<P>
   Few could understand why the team was so infatuated with
Croshere _ more than one individual pointed to chairman of the
board Paul Gaston as the prime mover _ and fewer still could fathom
how the Celtics could pull it off, assuming it was even possible.
</P>
<P>
   You want Croshere? The same Croshere who averaged 10.3 points a
game in his ``breakout'' season after appearing in 53 games his
first two years? The same Croshere who has trouble defending
forwards? Then be prepared to say goodbye to Antoine Walker or Paul
Pierce. There's no other way he comes to Boston unless he pulls a
financial nutty and accepts the $2.25 million exception.
</P>
<P>
   The only other option is a sign-and-trade deal. Indiana is on
record as not wanting to do that, but, if it comes to that, who are
they going to take? Walter McCarty? Calbert Cheaney? Donnie Walsh's
mother didn't raise a stupid son.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers and Walsh have long held a fascination with Walker,
evidenced by last summer's discussion about a deal for Dale Davis.
One league executive said that if Walker is involved, the deal will
likely be expanded to include the likes of Davis or Travis Best,
names we've heard in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if you're Croshere, why would you want to go to a worse
situation made even more so by the departure of the team's best (or
second-best) player? Why would you leave a situation where you are
coming off a conference championship with some intriguing young
talent to add to the mix? Unless you detest new coach Isiah Thomas,
there's no logic in the move.
</P>
<P>
   It's all well and good that the Celtics have an interest in
Croshere. But you have to wonder what they're thinking considering
they have to know what it would take. Rick Pitino is on record as
not wanting to trade Walker, not wanting to break up the nucleus
and trying to win with what he has.
</P>
<P>
   The pursuit of Croshere tells us that he may have something very
different in mind. In this case, different might be better. But it
also may be worse. Not one executive I talked to would trade Walker
for Croshere and I wouldn't either. Others would have to be
included to make any such deal work, but those two would be the
keys.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics are in desperate need of tough defenders and no one
would classify Croshere in that category. Tariq Abdul-Wahad? Fine.
Bobby Jackson? Fine. Haywoode Workman? Fine. Throw a couple of
those guys into the existing mix and maybe you have a playoff
contender. Blow it all up _ again _ and, well, good luck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The future looks bright
</P>
<P>
   Orlando has been The Place for free agents so far and it will
definitely be The Place for future NBA stars for the next 10 days.
What's being called ``The Super Showcase'' is underway, featuring
32 elite AAU teams from across the land. Starting Tuesday, there
will be a six-day, Olympic-style tournament for national AAU teams
that have qualified (Leo Papile's BABC is one of them). What does
this mean? It means that every NBA team will have at least one
scout there and many, many eyes will be on three lads: Eddy Curry,
Tyson Chandler, and Kwame Brown. Curry is a flat-out monster from
Illinois who is being projected as a possible No. 1 pick in next
year's draft. Chandler, from California, has drawn comparisons to
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, although one scout likened him more to Richard
Washington, still not too shabby. Brown, who is from Georgia, is
another beast (6-10) who has committed verbally to the University
of Florida. ``This is probably going to be the last time these guys
will be seen in a challenging environment,'' said Papile. ``Once
high school starts, most of these guys are men against boys. The
games are blowouts and they're not challenged. This will be
different.'' Another high schooler to watch is Ousmane Cisse, a
Senegalese power forward/center who is playing for perennial
powerhouse Oak Hill in Virginia this season. Throw in some college
freshmen who could turn pro next year (Eddie Griffin, Gerald
Wallace, Alton Ford) and you could have a very young class next
season. One interesting tidbit: John Calipari has brought along
former Louisville/NBA player Milt Wagner to be his administrative
assistant at Memphis. Also coming to Memphis is Dajuan Wagner,
Milt's son, who is one of the most sought-after prep players in the
country. NBA people think the younger Wagner will spend, at most,
one season at Memphis . . . The Timberwolves think they have
assurances from Chauncey Billups that the ex-Celtics/Nuggets/Magic
guard will be in the Twin Cities next season. They see Billups as
more of a shooting guard than a point guard, although he should get
time at both positions. He's also hungry for a shot at the playoffs
after having had no luck in his first three years, the third one
lasting only a handful of games before shoulder surgery. Also,
impressive rookie Wally Szczerbiak had surgery on his right knee
last Wednesday to help secure his kneecap . . . Seattle is hoping
to retain Rashard Lewis, who is getting some serious attention from
Toronto. The capped-out Sonics are limited as to what they can pay,
but Lewis has said he would like to remain in Seattle. Coach Paul
Westphal seconds that emotion. ``He gets it,'' Westphal said of
Lewis. ``He's sensational as far as listening to coaches and being
respectful of the veterans. But he's also good enough to play. He
works on his game all the time. People say he came out of high
school. So what? He works on his game all the time.'' . . .
Speaking of Seattle, the Sonics may field the All-United Nations
team this season. In addition to holdovers Lazaro Borrell (Cuba)
and Vladimir Stepania (Georgia SSR), they've added two more
intriguing possibilities in Nigerian Olumide Oyedeji and
Argentinian Ruben Wolkowyski. Oyedeji was worked out extensively by
many teams before the draft, including Boston, and eventually went
to Seattle in the second round. Based on what we saw at
UMass-Boston, the kid can rebound and, well, not a lot else.
Wolkowyski is an interesting story. He speaks no English and,
according to Seattle general manager Wally Walker, has a chance to
make the squad. ``We plan to bring him in for our regular, veterans
camp,'' Walker said of the 6-10, 275-pound brute. Wolkowyski has
been a regular of Argentina's national teams for several years and
played this past season for A League champ Estudiantes de
Olivarria. Wolkowyski, 26, would be the first Argentinian to play
in the NBA . . . If you feel you're in need of some work on your
shooting, Celtics assistant coach Andy Enfield is holding a
one-week camp next month at Milton Academy. The camp is for boys
and girls, from grades 4-12, and is being held Aug. 7-11 from 8:30
a.m. to noon. For information, call 703-536-9026.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Too long a courtship
</P>
<P>
   The official courtship period for free agents still has eight
days to run. Most GMs polled last week think the league should cut
back the time to two weeks. ``It makes the summer long for
everyone,'' said Spurs coach Gregg Popovich. Added Nets general
manager John Nash, ``They could probably cut it back, although the
way they have it now, it eliminates all the talk about teams
contacting agents before the deadline.'' Celtics GM Chris Wallace
is wondering what's going to come of his summer. ``From the end of
the season until the end of June, you're consumed with the draft,''
he said. ``Then the month of July is for going after free agents
and having summer camps. And then you have August where you still
have to go after free agents and sign them.'' A period ending July
15 would make sense, provided, of course, that the league can go
through the books to get a salary cap figure for the upcoming
season . . . Agent Bill Duffy was on hand during the summer league
to witness a few of his clients, but one of them, Speedy Claxton,
was a no-show due to a hamstring injury. Duffy also represents free
agent point guard Anthony Carter and says he feels Carter will stay
with the Heat for the $1.2 million exception . . . The Celtics and
any other team with a rookie entering his third season have until
Oct. 31 to trigger a clause in the contract that will keep the
player signed through Year 4. In Pierce's case, he will
automatically get a 27.5 percent bump over his Year 3 salary ($1.6
million) that would put him at a still-underpaid $2.05 million in
2001-02. The same scenario holds true for Vince Carter, although he
gets a 26.5 percent raise. If a team does not exercise that right,
the player becomes a free agent . . . Here's a free agent guard no
one is talking about: J.R. Rider. And for good reason. ``This
summer, he could have made $50 million and I know because I would
have been the one who gave it to him,'' said Atlanta president Stan
Kasten. ``He was a borderline All-Star when he wanted to be and
when he was, we were a pretty good team.'' But that wasn't nearly
enough and, after umpteen transgressions, the Hawks finally
released him. ``Lenny Wilkens gave him more rope than anyone else
and he still managed to hang himself,'' Kasten said of Rider. ``It
says something that (Rider) couldn't get it done despite playing
for Lenny and (GM) Pete Babcock, the two most decent people to hold
their respective positions in the league.'' . . . Danny Fortson got
a nice reception in Golden State when he worked out there Thursday.
The Warriors are interested in him at the $2.25 million exception
and, not wanting to buck the trend, had a uniform and a locker
nameplate with Fortson's name on it. Fortson said he liked all the
attention, but with Antawn Jamison scheduled to go back to power
forward, the issue of minutes is bound to arise . . . The $2.25
million exception that so many teams have this summer will increase
next summer to around $4 million, or, ahem, 108 percent of the
average player's salary . . . New Washington coach Leonard Hamilton
was on the sidelines for the Wizards games at UMass-Boston. Most
coaches let assistants do the dirty work in summer league, but
Hamilton (and Lon Kruger of Atlanta) were on their respective
benches. Longtime coach Johnny Bach (as in 50 years of coaching) is
on Hamilton's staff and, in the space of a few weeks, sees some
similarities to Doug Collins in terms of intensity and energy.
``Everyone around this man sees that aura of drive, impatience,
seeking perfection after one day,'' Bach said. ``That can overcome
a lot of things that have been obstacles in the past. But the
reality side of the NBA is that it doesn't happen that fast. You
have to attack the citadels to reach the summit, but it takes time.
You can't wear your heart on your sleeve or it will get torn off.
You can teach, encourage, and motivate, but you also have to have
an understanding that in this job, you can exhaust yourself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
