<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISHOPEN-WOODS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS ROARS INTO SIX-SHOT LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ Having shot a tidy 6-under-par 66 in
Saturday's third round of the 129th British Open at St. Andrews,
David Duval said he welcomed the opportunity to play Sunday in the
final pairing with Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to look him in the eye,'' said Duval, who should have
added that it also affords him a front-row seat to witness golf
history.
</P>
<P>
   That is the drama Woods has added to the festivities here,
because he posted his third straight scorching round _ a 67_200 _
that pushed him to 16 under and into a six-shot lead over Duval and
Thomas Bjorn (68). If he holds on _ and we're discussing a player
who has won 17 of 19 times he has enjoyed a 54-hole lead and who
last month won the US Open by a record-shattering 15 shots _ Woods
would become the youngest (24) of five players who have won the
career grand slam (the Masters, the US Open, the British Open, and
the PGA Championship).
</P>
<P>
   Pretty daunting stuff set on a stage that sits in the long, cold
shadows cast by stone buildings that have stood for centuries, but
Woods rarely gets caught up in such hype. Nor does he get rattled
when the leaderboard starts to shake, which is what happened on yet
another brilliantly bright, but windless Scottish day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that's going to happen. That's part of playing this
golf course, especially under these conditions,'' said Woods, who
watched Duval and Bjorn lead the charge into deeper red numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But after sending the gallery into a state of shock with a
three-putt at the par-4 second _ his first bogey in major
championship action since the third round of last month's US Open,
an unprecedented stretch of 63 holes _ Woods promptly birdied the
third to prove that all was well.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, all was well with others, too, as birdies were
going up at a dizzying rate. First move went to David Toms, Woods's
playing partner who birdied the second to get to 9 under, just one
off the lead. But he bogeyed the fourth, fell three back, and would
never get any closer, closing with a 71_207 to tumble seven behind,
tied for fourth with Loren Roberts (70) and Darren Clarke (68).
</P>
<P>
   Heading downwind at ``the loop'' of Old Tom Morris's old
playground, birdies were available.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke, six behind to start, ripped two shots off par going out.
Bjorn went out in 34. Ernie Els, spotting five shots to Woods,
birdied Nos. 3, 5, 6, and when he made another at the par-4 ninth
he was out in 33. Steve Flesch, who trailed by just four shots
through 36 holes, birdied Nos. 5, 6, and 8 to entertain thoughts of
a charge.
</P>
<P>
   Good for them, said Woods, who patiently waited his turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get home in two on No. 5. You can drive (the par-4)
No. 10. You can drive (the par-4) No. 12, and get home (in two) on
14,'' said Woods. ``You're going to have to make some birdies.''
</P>
<P>
   So he did. At the 175-yard, par-3 eighth he stuffed a 6-iron to
inside of 2 feet, then nonchalantly hit his 9-iron approach to 15
feet at the par-4 ninth. Back-to-back birdies allowed him to turn
in 34, get to 13-under, and send a message to those ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the message shook them, because the charge quickly
stopped. Els, for instance, reached 10 under, very much in the
hunt, then slammed his drive into the gorse at the 312-yard par-4
12th. He took a drop, chipped poorly, three-putted, and came home
with nothing but pars to finish 70_208, tied for seventh with
Dennis Paulson (69), Tom Lehman (70), and Flesch, the lefthander
who got it to 10 under, only to fall back with a double bogey at
the par-4 13th.
</P>
<P>
   Of the pursuers, only Duval and Bjorn stayed steady. Duval, who
has not stepped into the winner's circle since March of 1999,
birdied the 18th to complete a backside 34 and arrive first at 10
under. Bjorn was next, his birdie at the 18th completing his third
straight sub-70 trip around this cherished layout. It's an
accomplishment that likely will go unrewarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second is the first guy that loses,'' said the Dane, ``and it
certainly looks like somebody out there is playing golf on a
different planet from the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Woods. He cast a casual eye on the leaderboard as
he went around the loop, saw that the pursuit had cooled, and felt
like adding some breathing room. He did so by nearly driving the
12th, pitching to 2 feet, and making his third straight birdie on
that hole. He also birdied the par-5 14th for the third consecutive
day, and in between made his first birdie of the week on the par-4
13th.
</P>
<P>
   It added up to 16 under and total command. Right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite, because at the par-4 17th Woods made a serious
gaffe. ``I tried to hit about a 1-yard draw,'' he said of his
approach, ``and I was able to do that, but it started about 2 yards
left of where I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Horrors, particularly when he three-putted for his second bogey
of the tournament. But again he answered a bogey with a birdie,
converting a 10-footer at the 18th to push his lead back to six.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can swing the golf club like I have the last few days and
putt like I have,'' said Duval, whose back has been sore all week,
``I can show him I've got a little game going right now, too.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no disputing that. It's just that the game Woods
possesses is near-flawless and on target with history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
