<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISHOPEN-WATSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON WATSON'S TO-DO LIST: WIN NO. 6 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ Tom Watson took part in the past
champions exhibition Wednesday, but there was nothing ceremonial
about his spot in the main event. He knows it's a longshot, but he
still thinks he has what it takes to win a sixth British Open,
which would tie Harry Vardon's record.
</P>
<P>
   He really thinks, at 50, he can be competitive with the young
crowd?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? ``I just do.''
</P>
<P>
   His fifth British Open title came 17 years ago but Watson has
returned every July since in search of No. 6. It won't come this
year because Watson made too many mistakes Saturday on a course he
should play better. On a day when he said the course played
``easy,'' Watson spoiled a five-birdie effort by making bogey at
both par-5s, landing in bunkers that are essential to avoid, and
stumbling home in 38 to shoot 72. He's at level par 216 through 54
holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not good, is it?'' he said. ``It was fun for a while, but it
got ugly real quickly. I made quite a few errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson is the last player to win the US Open and British Open
back-to-back, a feat that could be matched Sunday by Tiger Woods.
No, said Watson, there was no letdown in 1982 coming off the
stirring Pebble Beach dramatics over Jack Nicklaus in the US Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't difficult at all,'' he said. ``All you are doing is
playing each week like it's a new week. That's the way you play the
game. You obviously play with confidence when you are playing well,
and after winning the US Open I was playing with enough confidence
to see me through.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in 1982, I was given the tournament. I didn't win the
tournament, Nick (Price) lost it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0117 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-BUTKUS-B     07-22 2714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-BUTKUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
XFL SUITS THIS GRIZZLED BEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you think of football in Chicago, you think of lunch pails,
blue-collar players, blood and guts. It all fits. Dick Butkus _
tough-guy linebacker, and later actor, comedian, Miller Lite
pitchman _ is back in football, but not as a broadcaster or owner.
He's the head coach of Chicago's XFL franchise, which will make its
debut at Soldier Field in the dead of winter.
</P>
<P>
   If this is a sign of things to come for the XFL, league
mastermind Vince McMahon might have another empire on his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have come back to any other city,'' said Butkus, a
wealthy man with a long resume of movie and TV roles. ``There's a
team in LA and I live in Malibu so that would have been great,
except I wouldn't have coached anywhere but Chicago. To me, that's
football.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what McMahon thought, too. The World Wrestling
Federation's head honcho is trying to mold a new brand of football
out of the old brand, and who personifies that more than Butkus,
not only one of the best linebackers of all time, but also one of
the most entertaining?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the things in this league are similar to when I
played,'' said Butkus, who retired after only nine seasons because
of a bad knee but still made it to the Hall of Fame in Canton,
Ohio. ``They don't call `in the grasp,' so you can hit the
quarterback. You can clothesline a receiver over the middle like I
used to do. No fair catches. These are things that I'm familiar
with. This is the football that I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Butkus has never been a head coach. He did have a clause in his
Bears contract that said he would be a player-coach, but that never
materialized. He also was up for the head job at his alma mater,
the University of Illinois, but the alumni backed off, he said,
because he lacked experience. Some might say that at 57 he's too
old to be starting out.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring from the Bears in 1973, Butkus spent 10 years as
color commentator for the team's radio broadcasts. Then came the
national exposure of his Miller Lite ``Tastes Great-Less Filling''
TV commercials. Soon people in the entertainment business began
calling and he was so busy doing TV and movies he couldn't breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Now football is his focus again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I've just dropped down from Mars,'' said Butkus.
``I've followed football. I have friends in the game still. People
ask me how I can be a head coach and I tell them, `It's not that
hard.' I had a chance to get into coaching in the late '60s. I knew
Marty Schottenheimer, who was in Detroit, and he wanted to bring me
in. But then I heard he'd moved six or seven times in eight years,
and I didn't want that. I didn't want to move my family around. I
just did the games on radio and would come back to Chicago. Then,
after the Miller Lite stuff, I started going in a different
direction and my life took me away from (football).''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's back in the game he played so hard, the question
is, how will he coach? Can any of his players live up to Butkus's
desire for intensity and hard work?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are kids out there who still work hard,'' he
said. ``We do live in a society where people try to work the least
and make the most, but there are still players out there who work
hard. That's all I'll ever ask of them.''
</P>
<P>
   How about all the film work and 18-hour days coaches put in?
``What are you doing in 18 hours? Come on. I think some of these
guys say it just to justify what they do. No, I won't have people
sleeping overnight at the stadium,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he will assemble his staff. XFL teams are allowed six
coaches, including two coordinators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a set philosophy on offense and defense,'' Butkus
said. ``When I pick the guys, we'll work together toward putting
that together. We'll have fun and we'll be serious. I've always
thought football was serious.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing about his sideline demeanor: Butkus and the other XFL
coaches will wear microphones, so ``I'll have to learn how to clean
up my language.''
</P>
<P>
   Butkus enters the profession without what he calls ``coaching
baggage.'' In other words, he doesn't have cronies or people he's
promised jobs to. He said the league will give him a pool of
coaches to choose from and he'll go from there. But there are a lot
of things he'll have to get used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sang the national anthem during the seventh-inning (stretch)
at Wrigley the other day and it brought back a lot of memories of
when (George) Halas would bring us out near the lake to practice
and it was so cold you couldn't feel your body parts,'' said
Butkus. ``I remember near the Chicago Armory and stepping in horse
(excrement) from where they used to hold different events.
Nowadays, there are these elaborate practice complexes. It doesn't
mean you can't still work hard and have an edge.''
</P>
<P>
   When he visits Chicago, he stays with a lifelong friend who
recently informed him of a Sun-Times poll in which 96 percent
favored his return to football. ``That's why Chicago would be the
only place I'd come back to. The fans here are real football
fans,'' he said. ``I'll bet you that in the middle of February
there'll be 5,000 fans with their shirts off rooting for us. That's
if I win. If I don't, the honeymoon will be over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot to do in a short time, but I'm doing it
because I love the game. Football is football. I'll make sure we
play it right.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Raven-ous reconstruction
</P>
<P>
   You have to hand it to Ozzie Newsome, the Baltimore Ravens' vice
president of player personnel, for not believing the negative press
on former Patriot Ben Coates and finding out for himself that
Coates's conditioning was top flight and he's not the monster he's
been portrayed to be. Coach Brian Billick and his staff, including
East Coast supervisor Terry McDonough, have drafted and signed
excellent talent the past few years. They will go only as far as
quarterback Tony Banks takes them, but the addition of tight ends
Coates and Shannon Sharpe, the return of Pro Bowl linebacker Ray
Lewis (the best in the game before his murder trial), and the
drafting of running back Jamal Lewis and receiver Travis Taylor may
help the vastly improved Ravens steal a little thunder from the
Redskins in the Beltway . . . Patriots Football Weekly has
tabulated the results of its All-Patriots Team of the Century.
According to editor Bryan Mory, more than 25,000 votes were cast on
a newspaper ballot and on the team's Web site. The results: QB Drew
Bledsoe; RBs Sam Cunningham and Curtis Martin; WRs Gino Cappelletti
and Stanley Morgan; TE Ben Coates; OGs John Hannah and Sam Adams;
OTs Bruce Armstrong and Leon Gray; C Pete Brock; DEs Willie
McGinest and Julius Adams; DTs Houston Antwine and Jim Lee Hunt;
LBs Vincent Brown, Steve Nelson, Ted Johnson, and Andre Tippett;
DBs Mike Haynes, Ty Law, Lawyer Milloy, and Fred Marion; K
Cappelletti; P Rich Camarillo; coach Bill Parcells. Player of the
century: Hannah. Top-vote getter: Armstrong (23,518). Closest
races: Cappelletti nipped Irving Fryar at WR, and Martin edged Jim
Nance at RB . . . Pretty decent story developing in Chicago, where
former Boston College quarterback Mark Hartsell is making a
comeback after sitting out the past two years. Hartsell always had
the arm strength, but now he's more physically mature and it
appears he has a chance to stick under Gary Crowton, the Bears'
offensive coordinator who coached him at BC . . . Anyone who wishes
to use a golf cart at Patriots training camp at Bryant College in
Smithfield, R.I., must seek permission from coach Bill Belichick.
This long has been a subject of great debate among Patriot coaches.
The team even had to settle a lawsuit recently involving a teenage
girl struck by a cart last season. The Falcons also have had their
share of golf cart incidents at their Furman University site. Coach
Dan Reeves has forbid his players from tinkering with the carts to
speed them up after some Falcons engaged in races in years past . .
. Next Thursday's trek to the University of Massachusetts is now
being called a ``joint practice'' between the Patriots and New York
Giants, rather than a scrimmage. UMass is charging $5 for parking.
The practice runs from approximately noon to 2 p.m. The Patriots
will get a look at Giants quarterback Kerry Collins, who feels like
a new man and last week spoke of the Giants being a possible
championship team. ``I think I'm at a point in my career where I
can take it to a high level,'' said Collins, who had several
transgressions that squashed his star potential while with
Carolina. ``I've done it before as a young guy. I think I can be as
good as I've been in this league.'' . . . Former Patriots tight end
Russ Francis is making a congressional bid in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adding an old touch
</P>
<P>
   Mike Shanahan is at it again, bringing in another grizzled
veteran to help the Broncos get back to the Super Bowl. Former
Bills receiver Andre Reed, a future Hall of Famer, joined Denver in
a move Shanahan hopes will provide a spark similar to what Fryar
did for the Redskins last season. Speaking of Fryar, his agent,
Michael George, is experiencing deja vu regarding another client,
Coates. George pointed out that Fryar left the Patriots at 32 and
went on to four Pro Bowls. Coates left at 30, and George predicts
similar future success. Coates can earn up to $2.3 million if he
catches 70 passes. Coates will start the season as Sharpe's backup,
but he wouldn't have signed if he didn't expect to get the ball . .
. Sean Dawkins won't be going to Tennessee because the Titans don't
throw it downfield. Dawkins may return to Seattle, and recently
released Bengal Carl Pickens could hook on with the Titans or the
Jets, who are still looking for a No. 1 receiver . . . Carolina's
signing of Reggie White to a five-year deal Friday shows you the
state of defensive line play in the league. The Titans and Seahawks
(with his former coach, Mike Holmgren) were hoping to land the
38-year-old retiree. But the Panthers reportedly offered White $3
million-$4 million per year . . . The Jaguars are trying to scare
Tony Brackens back by flirting with free agent Eric Swann.
Brackens, however, isn't budging from his hopes of getting about $7
million per year . . . While teams are either in or getting ready
for training camp, expansion Houston is trying to position itself
for the 2002 season. Saints owner Tom Benson would like to see
Houston in an NFC Southern Division that also would include the
Saints, Falcons, and Buccaneers. Houston owner Bob McNair prefers
Houston stay where the old Houston Oilers were (AFC Central) to
take advantage of old city rivalries and a new one with Tennessee .
. . Geoff Hobson, formerly of the Portland (Maine) Press-Herald and
the Cincinnati Enquirer, is revolutionizing team Web sites. Hobson
is allowed to be critical of his employer, the Bengals. All team
president Mike Brown asks in return is for Hobson to be fair and
write both sides of the story. This is unique, because some teams
don't make their front-office personnel, executives, and owners
available to their own media outlets for comments on major issues .
. . Despite charging $10 for admission and $10 for parking at their
new practice facility, the Redskins don't believe they will turn a
profit since they estimate it will cost about $2 million to run the
camp. Their first day of camp produced 3,000 fans for one two-hour
practice. On Thursday, the Patriots drew a combined 4,000 fans for
their morning and afternoon sessions, and admission was free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Future is in sight
</P>
<P>
   Without question, the best thing about having the Patriots work
out at Foxboro Stadium was the opportunity to watch the erection of
the new stadium beyond the practice fields. Big Dig take note:
Those working on the stadium seemed to be making a lot of progress
during the course of the week. It appears a 2002 christening is
well within reach . . . Once signed, the Redskins plan to use LaVar
Arrington as a third-down pass rusher from outside linebacker,
according to coach Norv Turner, and once he grasps that role, the
Redskins will gradually make him a full-time player . . . An odd
story involving a draft pick is developing in Philadelphia, where
sixth-round selection John Frank, a defensive end from Utah, has
been missing from camp. Apparently Frank's parents know of his
whereabouts and say he's not in danger. Frank is evidently trying
to decide if football is what he wants to devote himself to . . .
Kurt Warner didn't have a contract when he reported to camp
Thursday, but he signed a one-year deal worth $358,000 Friday, the
league minimum for third-year players. Not wanting to hold out,
Warner agreed to the short-term solution so his representatives
could continue to work on a long-term deal with the Rams. ``My love
for the game and my responsibility to this team and my teammates
and coaches outweigh everything else. I definitely want to take
care of my family and do those types of things, but I realize why
I'm here and I felt it was something I had to do,'' Warner told the
St. Louis media . . . One of Kansas City coach Gunther Cunningham's
toughest tasks in camp is dealing with the death of Derrick Thomas.
Cunningham was very close to the linebacker, as the two often
conversed on the phone late at night. Other friends of Thomas, like
quarterback Elvis Grbac, also miss Thomas's presence. ``I give it
thought every day,'' said Cunningham. ``How are we going to handle
this? It's a delicate thing to handle.'' The Chiefs plan to pay
tribute to Thomas prior to their Sept. 3 opener against
Indianapolis, but getting there is the problem. ``There's a time
and place to talk about Derrick. There's a time and place to handle
his memory. I hope to do the right thing,'' said Cunningham . . .
Vincent Brisby has been taking snaps with the Patriots starters,
and the veteran receiver is not ready to give that up. ``I'll do
what I'm asked to do, but I want to start,'' he said. ``I think I
can help this team as a primary guy.'' The Patriots need a big
target over the middle with Coates gone, and it appears Brisby, who
isn't afraid of running routes in traffic, could be that guy.
Brisby would definitely be the winner of the Patriots'
``Survivor.'' He's escaped more salary-cap issues and had his
contract restructured more than any other player. If Brisby does
start and Bledsoe uses him as a main target, the receiver could
earn as much as $2.6 million this year. Brisby's deal was
restructured for a $750,000 salary and $650,000 signing bonus,
which cut the Patriots' salary cap hit from $2.15 million to about
$1.4 million. Brisby, one of the hardest workers in the offseason,
also will earn $50,000 for meeting his contractual workout demands
. . . Dimitrius Underwood is finally handling life in the NFL with
the Dallas Cowboys, but now he's got a few pounds to shed. Chosen
29th overall by Minnesota in the 1999 draft, Underwood hasn't
played in two years (he missed the '98 season at Michigan State
with an ankle injury) and reportedly weighs more than 300 pounds.
Last season he was released by the Vikings, signed by the Dolphins,
and tried to commit suicide after dislocating his shoulder during
an exhibition game. ``I believe I can play,'' Underwood told the
Dallas Morning News. ``I've got to do something. I can't sit around
and twiddle my thumbs all day. I want to play football.'' . . .
Interesting story in Chicago, where Bears public relations
executive Bryan Harlan resigned just days before it was reported he
was under investigation for placing bets on NFL games, including
his own team's. Former Bears executive Ken Valdiserri acknowledged
to the Sun-Times that he was subpoenaed two years ago in a federal
gambling probe regarding calls that were made to a bookmaker from
his phone. Valdiserri, now general manager of Chicago's XFL
franchise, denied he made the calls. ``Our phone was passed around
like it was a bottle of Coca-Cola,'' he said, adding that it was
impossible to determine who had called the bookie. If it was a
player or coach, that could lead to more serious ramifications.
</P>
</TEXT>
