</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GLENN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN IN FINE FORM FOR NEW SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ There are NFL players _ all of them great athletes
_ who can play a punishing, grueling sport with grace and agility.
And then there are a few who take it one step higher.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Patriots have one special, cut-above-the-rest
guy: Terry Glenn. He's the same guy the Patriots sometimes can't
live with, but know beyond a doubt they can't live without.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's amazing to watch sometimes,'' said former Brown star and
second-year Patriots receiver Sean Morey. ``I learn so much from
just watching the things he does and then try and go out there and
do them. He works so hard at being the best. That's what people
don't understand about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn understands how the mixed perception of him developed.
There was the ``she'' reference by Bill Parcells in his rookie
year. There were a few off-field problems, a one-game suspension by
then-coach Pete Carroll. Lots of injuries. Lost in the criticism is
the fact that few can match his level of athleticism. The extra
gear he shifts into when he needs to leaves defenders in the dust.
His great hands enable him to catch balls when he's double-covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's things that happened in the past and things that are said
about me,'' said Glenn. ``I'd like to prove all of those people
wrong, but I know I won't be able to do that unless the world comes
down to see the things I do. I work very hard when I'm out on that
field. I think the coaches and the players see that and they're the
ones that know it. I can't make everybody happy. I know what I'm
capable of and I know that when I'm practicing and playing, I give
everything I have.''
</P>
<P>
   At a March 15 team meeting called by coach Bill Belichick, Glenn
was pardoned for the fine Carroll levied last season when Glenn
broke a procedural rule when he was ill with a virus. When
Belichick heard Glenn's side and did his own research, he rescinded
the fine.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn asked for a new contract and was told he had to wait and
play out the season. Glenn never has balked at being rejected even
though Keyshawn Johnson and Marvin Harrison have received huge
deals.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn wanted to work out near his home in Columbus, Ohio, in the
offseason, but when Belichick asked him to be with the team, Glenn
left behind his 4-year-old son, Terry Jr., and his new house to
stay in Foxborough. He did not complete the full number of workouts
to earn a $50,000 bonus, and it appeared he rankled Belichick when
he left for Columbus three-quarters of the way through the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Bill didn't agree with it at first,'' said Glenn, ``but
when I told him what I was going to do, he put it in my hands. I'm
up here all alone and I have a son I need to be with in the
offseason. I went home and worked with my personal trainer and I
stayed in great shape. I think the bottom line is I came back here
in top shape. I didn't give anyone any reason to get on me about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson out of the division, Glenn, who made the Pro Bowl
last season for the first time with 69 catches, has a chance to be
the top receiver in the AFC East. Glenn has had a little battle
with Harrison, Johnson, and Eric Moulds, all taken in the first
round of the '96 draft. When Glenn caught 90 balls as a rookie, he
was clearly the best of the crop. Injuries have since played havoc,
though last year Glenn thought he was on his way to catching 120
balls. He and Drew Bledsoe were clicking as never before. Glenn was
the focal point of the Ernie Zampese offense, as he will be of
Charlie Weis's schemes.
</P>
<P>
   But soon the Zampese system stopped working. Glenn was seeing
double coverage all the time. Teams like Belichick's Jets designed
defenses to keep Glenn contained. He went from catching 43 passes
at midseason to 26 in the second half. He was shut out against
Miami. He missed the last two games, one with the flu and the other
because of his suspension.
</P>
<P>
   He caught 13 passes for 214 yards in a 19-7 win over Cleveland
early in the season. He had 32 catches after four games, leading
the league, and then didn't have another big splash until he had
nine receptions against Indianapolis Dec. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Since he landed in New England from Ohio State, the Patriots
have won 62.3 percent of the games in which Glenn has played
(30-18). They are 8-8 when he doesn't. They are 3-2 in the
postseason when he plays, 0-1 when he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth all-time leading receiver in Patriots history says his
success is linked to his health. He says he's careful about his
legs and his body because he knows his breaking point. If he backs
off workouts, it's because he doesn't think his body can take much
more.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Glenn feels great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling so good right now,'' he said. ``It usually doesn't
feel this good at this stage of training camp. I don't have any
bumps and bruises and I think the atmosphere Bill has created has
helped quite a bit. I love this setup we had here in Foxborough. As
a veteran player you can go home and sleep in your own bed and
relax and then come ready to practice the next day. I know we can't
stay here, but I think to start camp here was a good idea so now we
can go to Smithfield and work even harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the losses of players he liked and respected, Shawn
Jefferson and Ben Coates, Glenn thinks the Patriots will be fine
offensively.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said that Weis's offense resembles the offense the
Patriots had in '96, but added, ``there's more to it. It's been
expanded. Every year you have to add new things and Charlie has
added to what he had in place. I think Drew is comfortable. I think
we're all comfortable that we can get some things done and put some
points up.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn never has played a full season in the NFL because of
injuries, sickness, and the suspension. He achieved a lifelong
dream of being a Pro Bowler and he volunteered to return kicks in
that game. Although he would like to play all 16 games and then the
postseason, Glenn said his focus is not on personal goals anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about the team,'' said Glenn, who was involved in one
of the lighter moments of training camp when a police dog ran on
the field and stole the ball out of his hands. ``I think everybody
wants to win. We have a new coach and a new outlook. Everyone's
pretty excited. I know that some people don't think we'll be that
good, but when we get some of our offensive linemen back healthy
we'll be fine. It's best to be the underdog, anyway. I think it's
the best position to be in. It's nice to be able to prove people
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   That's something he's always had to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
