</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-SAMSONOV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS QUIET ABOUT SAMSONOV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Could you picture Sergei Samsonov in a uniform other than the
Bruins' next season? It's not as far-fetched as you might think.
Samsonov is a Group 2 free agent, and there's a perception that
because of the restrictive nature of that status, nobody in the
category changes teams. Well, truth be told, Samsonov and his
Boston-based attorney, Neil Abbott, are actively shopping the
market and even if clubs are reluctant to tender him an offer
sheet, there is the option of trading for him.
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov, like practically every one of his teammates, is coming
off a subpar season; for the last two seasons, in fact, he hasn't
exactly flourished. When asked if Samsonov is a good fit in Boston,
Abbott paused, then said, ``I have some questions. There are some
issues. If you look at the way it's all come down the last year or
so, you wonder. They have their opinion and I have mine, but you
certainly have to take a long look and see what's out there and see
where you do fit or you don't fit. I don't have any conclusions,
but certainly it's an issue we're looking at because you're looking
at a commitment for the next two, three, or four years of your
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott declined to say what those ``issues'' might be, but one
perception that has persisted is that coach Pat Burns isn't a big
fan of Samsonov's. Burns has denied it repeatedly, but the player's
east-west tendencies rather than skating north-south would cause
any coach to tear out his hair at times. There was a flap a couple
of years ago when Mike O'Connell questioned Burns's use of
Samsonov. Both the coach and assistant general manager felt the
issue was overblown, but the subject remains a sensitive one.
However, it's clear that if a team as offensively challenged as the
Bruins was to deal Samsonov, it would have to get back some
offensive talent.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Bruins sign or deal Samsonov remains to be seen. But
at this point, Abbott said, there is no dialogue _ zero, zilch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing going on,'' said Abbott. ``We're not in any
kind of active negotiating stage with the Bruins in any form and
we're not actively seeking that at this point. I've explained to
Sergei and every other Group 2 over the years that you only get to
the market two or three times in your career if you're lucky and
when you do, you owe it to yourself to take a look around and see
what might be out there. There's a perception sometimes that Group
2s never move, but if you look at the reality, they do move, most
often by trade _ but there have been some significant offers over
the years. Sometimes you fit better somewhere else and sometimes
somebody has a greater need for your services than the team that
has you. In the process of talking, you'll find all that out.''
</P>
<P>
   Anson Carter, also a restricted free agent, recently said
there's a giant gulf between how he views his worth and how the
Bruins view it. Abbott said he has no idea how the Bruins view
Samsonov's worth because it's never been discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made a qualifying offer, we rejected it, and that's where
we're at,'' he said. ``There are no discussions going on
whatsoever. That may develop, but there are a lot of issues to be
talked about before we even get that far, if and when we get there.
We have not had any discussion on his worth. They did their
obligatory CBA thing to qualify him, and that's normal. That's
where we're at. They know we won't sign that, and that's that. We
haven't had any discussions, and we haven't been seeking them.
Historically, not a lot of people get signed early in Boston. I'm
not expecting a lot of discussion in the short period here, and I'm
not looking for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Abbott said, he and his client are keeping an open mind
and fielding whatever offers may come down. ``Group 2s do move
through trades, free agency, or offers, it does happen,'' said
Abbott. ``It's not easy, it's not common, but it does occur. There
are a lot of players who started out in one place and ended up
somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he had a gut feeling on whether Samsonov would be
in Boston next season, Abbott said he didn't. ``It's too early to
say one way or the other,'' he said. ``We're going to take a look
around and talk to some people and see what's out there. We just
want to keep the field wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cheering with a twang
</P>
<P>
   Former NHL coach Terry Crisp says he's having the time of his
life in his current job as TV color commentator for the Nashville
Predators. Crisp is a passionate country music fan, and he said
many country singers have become hockey fans. ``Garth Brooks,
Barbara Mandrell, Amy Grant, Vince Gill, the Dixie Chicks _ you
name it, and they all come to our games,'' said Crisp. ``We've got
a thing called the Music Box, a private area where all the
celebrities can come at any time. But a lot of them have bought
season tickets and sit with the rest of the fans.'' Crisp said
Brooks, when he's touring, will sometimes call Predators coach
Barry Trotz for help booking ice time for pickup games . . .
Canadiens goalie Jeff Hackett, who is playing in his second
Original Six city (Chicago was the other), said feelings run high
in Montreal with the club being put up for sale and the loss of
Rocket Richard. ``Obviously, a lot of the past has been let go
recently what with the Forum (closing) and Mr. Richard,'' said
Hackett. ``It's a very emotional time for these people right now,
in some instances volatile. To any person growing up in Montreal,
there's so much passion involved with following the team. It's a
part of life there.'' There has been speculation the team could
move depending on who buys the franchise, a development that would
be unfathomable. ``It could be worrisome, especially when you see
what's going on in other cities,'' Hackett said. ``But maybe it's a
warning signal (about rising costs) more than anything else.'' . .
. Former Boston University and Catholic Memorial standout Chris
O'Sullivan has signed with the Anaheim Mighty Ducks. The
26-year-old defenseman, the Flames' second-round draft pick (No. 30
overall) in 1992, played most of his first three pro seasons in the
Calgary organization before being traded to the Rangers in March of
last year. He spent last season in the Vancouver organization,
appearing in 11 games with the Canucks and 59 with the AHL's
Syracuse Crunch, for whom he was the second-leading scorer with 65
points (18 goals).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A heady decision
</P>
<P>
   It's too soon to say what is going to happen with Philadelphia
center Eric Lindros. He has until Aug. 1 to decide whether to sign
the Flyers' qualifying offer of $8.5 million. Lindros, who suffered
four concussions in a little more than four months last season, is
scheduled to be checked by Chicago-based concussion expert Dr.
James Kelly just prior to the deadline . . . For a time, it
appeared Rob Ray would be looking for work outside of Buffalo. When
the Sabres declined to pick up the option on his deal, Ray figured
he would be playing elsewhere next season. But in a series of
meetings with management, Ray worked out a new deal and has been
assured by general manager Darcy Regier that he will have more
support than in the past. Ray, who averaged about four minutes a
game last season, will likely be used quite a bit more as the
Sabres try to increase their toughness. ``Part of our
responsibility to Rob is to make sure he's not isolated,'' said
Regier. ``Those are things we discussed as well. It's a two-way
street. (The responsibility) is not just Rob to the organization,
it's the organization to Rob as well.'' The Sabres felt as if they
were pushed around last season (sound familiar?) and want to
improve the club's physical presence. ``The fighting side, yes,
I've got to do it,'' said Ray. ``As a team on the whole, if you can
go out and play a physical game, it does just as much good as going
out and fighting. It's nice to have help, but you have to
understand that I'm the guy that has to do it. I've got to assume
that role.'' . . . Former Bruin Adam Oates of the Washington
Capitals has been in attendance at the British Open, where he is
offering some moral support to his friend, Mike Weir . . . Speaking
of golf (also known as hockey's offseason), Cummaquid, which is the
home club of Bruin forward Eric Nickulas, has a 7-point lead over
Thorny Lea after the first round of the Giardino Cup challenge. The
second and final round is Aug. 17. The Brockton group will have to
pick it up if they want to prevent the trophy, which has resided at
Thorny Lea the past two years, from heading back down Route 3 . . .
Forty-six days to training camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
