<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0120 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-22 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGACY OF PIONEER ALSO HIS STRENGTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ No one has seen his plaque yet, but you can
bet it will talk about catching more games and hitting more home
runs as a catcher than any player in baseball history. One might
reasonably assume it will also mention a certain home run in the
1975 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But if Carlton Fisk's Hall of Fame plaque is really
comprehensive, it might contain the following notation:
</P>
<P>
   Revolutionized baseball conditioning with an unprecedented
year-round regimen built around weightlifting, without which he
could never have caught as many games as he did. First player to
get through catching nine innings in a night game and then head
directly to the weight room.
</P>
<P>
   No one else has caught 2,000 games. Fisk caught 2,226 games. And
he caught them because he was capable. He caught them because his
managers believed he would do a good job, even at ages 40, 41, and
beyond. He caught them long past the age when most every other
quality catcher was either a) retired or b) playing another
position because he was no longer capable of both catching and
swinging an effective bat.
</P>
<P>
   More than any position player, a catcher can have a major
positive effect on his team, even while going 0 for 4. Batting is,
in fact, almost incidental to a catcher's primary task, as Fisk
himself made clear on the eve of his induction into the Baseball
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took great pride in what I did on the field, with my
contributions behind the plate,'' Fisk declared in response to a
query about ``special moments'' he had in the game. ``The
relationships with my pitching staffs were very special to me.
Catching guys like Luis Tiant, Tom Seaver, LaMarr Hoyt, Richard
Dotson, Jack McDowell, and Bobby Thigpen, that's where I had my
value to the team. Those were all special moments.''
</P>
<P>
   No other catcher in baseball history would have had a chance of
catching both Sonny Siebert and Thigpen. Carlton Fisk's longevity
at a position that is more physically demanding than, say, all
three outfield spots put together, is beyond comparison.
</P>
<P>
   It came about because in what would have been the November of
just about any other catcher's career he undertook a punishing
physical program. It's just that simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel I am somewhat of a pioneer,'' he said. ``I suppose
it all began when I had my knee destroyed in 1974 (a gruesome home
plate collision with Cleveland's Leron Lee). I know how hard I
worked to rehabilitate, and a year later I was playing in the World
Series when I was never supposed to squat again. So right there I
knew how important it was to keep your legs in shape, especially at
my position.''
</P>
<P>
   Move the clock forward nine years. Pudge Fisk has been injured
again, and this time he gets it in his head that there is no reason
why he must think about a rocking chair (or a first baseman's mitt)
just because he's 37.
</P>
<P>
   ``In baseball, the thinking was that you didn't lift weights
because they made you too tight and muscle-bound. They thought
you'd wind up looking like Arnold Schwarzenegger. But weight
lifting has redefined strength and conditioning in baseball. It's
so obvious, so commonsensical, that the stronger,
better-conditioned the athlete is, the better he will perform. That
year (1985), I went out and had one of my best years, with 37
homers, 107 runs batted in. And I caught 150-something games.''
</P>
<P>
   As the 1980s drifted into the '90s, Pudge Fisk became
increasingly buoyed by an intriguing phenomenon. ``There were a lot
of sons coming into baseball whose fathers I had played against,''
he said. ``I can't tell you how good a feeling it was to go onto
the field and play against people who were the same age as my own
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   It was all because his pioneering dedication to baseball
conditioning had permitted him to catch longer than any man in
history. ``I would not have played the last eight years of my
career without that strength and conditioning program,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than The Man Who Came To Dinner, he had become The Man
Who Came To Catch, as frustrated White Sox backup Ron Karkovice
knew better than anyone. By the time Fisk finally retired,
Karkovice was already 31. His career never really took off, and if
some day in the future you run into a stocky guy in a bar who tells
you that Pudge Fisk ruined his career, you won't even have to ask
his name. It will be Karkovice.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk has raised the bar ridiculously high. In order to
understand what 2,226 games caught means, consider the games-caught
totals of some other Hall of Fame catchers: Johnny Bench, 1,744;
Ray Schalk 1,726; Bill Dickey, 1,712; Yogi Berra, 1,696, and
Mickey Cochrane, 1,451. The only catcher within shouting distance
is Al Lopez with 1,918, and Al didn't bring one-10th the offense to
the table Pudge did.
</P>
<P>
   Was Fisk's best The Best? No. In our time Bench was surely
better, as was Gary Carter, at least in my opinion. Cochrane was
the consensus All-Time catcher before Bench came along, and I
suspect most people who watched Berra would prefer him to Fisk. But
Carlton Fisk is clearly among the great catchers of all time, and
absolutely no one else was able to maintain his excellence anywhere
as long as he did. If you want to put this in further perspective,
they're already talking about moving the great Ivan (Pudge)
Rodriguez to second base, a la Craig Biggio. And we all know that
Mike Piazza will not end his career as a catcher.
</P>
<P>
   The clear truth is that no catcher in history positively
affected more games than Carlton Fisk. The very real possibility is
that none ever will. How's that for your legacy?
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
