<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0273 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-G8-CLINTON23-1STLD-CO     07-22 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-G8-CLINTON23-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    G8 SUMMIT FOCUSES ON THIRD WORLD DISEASE, TECHNOLOGY GAP
 &HT;    Eds: Updates grafs 1-4, 23-24 with education initiative, Clinton
Mideast comment.
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAGO, Japan _ With most of their economies in decent shape,
leaders of the Group of Eight countries neared the end of their
annual summit Sunday focusing on helping poor countries wipe out
illiteracy, fight infectious diseases and get into cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   They announced a global initiative Sunday morning that includes
$300 million from the U.S. Department of Agriculture to provide
school meals for 9 million children a year in the poorest
countries, and another $1 billion in World Bank loans for basic
education.
</P>
<P>
   Serving breakfast and lunch at schools has been proven to entice
parents to send their children to school in developing countries,
said Gene Sperling, President Clinton's chief economic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a hopeless problem,'' he told reporters. ``This is
something that can be dealt with.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the G8 members announced a Digital Opportunity Task
Force, dubbed the ``dot force,'' charged with finding ways to
bridge the global digital divide. The group is to report to next
year's G8 summit in Italy on possible solutions for individual
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, officials said, is that technology will let poor
nations leapfrog obstacles to development, taking advantage of the
information age to improve education and health care.
</P>
<P>
   The G8 members _ the United States, Canada, Britain, Japan,
France, Germany, Italy and Russia _ also announced new programs and
funding to help prevent the spread of diseases such as AIDS,
tuberculosis and malaria.
</P>
<P>
   Several countries made financial pledges, including $3 billion
by Japan over the next five years. Clinton has requested $4 billion
in the 2001 budget for a vaccine program, research on HIV/AIDS and
international aid for various infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Lael Brainard, Clinton's deputy national economic adviser, said
that while past G8 summits have been more centered on the economic
problems of the member nations, Okinawa ``is shaping up to be the
development summit, with a focus on creating opportunity for the
least-developed.''
</P>
<P>
   However, about 50 non-governmental organizations who came to
Okinawa to monitor the summit were not impressed by either
initiative. They accused the G8 leaders of failing to address the
fundamental problems that cause poverty and disease, and instead
offering only superficial solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're quite angry,'' said Marlene Barrett, a spokesperson for
Jubilee 2000. ``This (digital divide effort) is an empty gesture
which will obviously benefit all of their industries. It's just to
distract attention away from the fact that they failed to cancel
the debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Jubilee 2000 burned a laptop computer on a beach here
in Okinawa to show their disappointment with G8's failure to
fulfill last year's promise to cancel up to $100 billion in Third
World debt.
</P>
<P>
   So far, just nine countries have qualified for debt relief of up
to $15 billion. Jubilee 2000 says debt relief is the first step to
ending the cycle of poverty, since poor countries are spending more
money to pay back debt than on basic needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't eat a laptop,'' said Barrett. ``It's a crisis, it's
an emergency, and it's something that they've failed to deal with
this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicins Sans Frontieres criticized the G8 program on infectious
diseases, saying that merely spending money to treat diseases does
not solve the core problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If part of this money is going to be used to buy expensive
brand-name drugs when we know there are cheaper, generic brands
available, that's public money going to private interests in the
West,'' said spokesperson Ellen 'T Hoen(cq).
</P>
<P>
   She said she was disappointed the G8 leaders did not address
patent issues that would allow, for example, local companies to
produce cheaper versions of pricey AIDS drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just saying, 'this is a serious issue and we're making money
available to deal with it' without giving clear direction on how to
do that is really a missed opportunity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on the digital divide, Clinton acknowledged that
technology is not the answer to all the problems of the developing
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet if we fail to ensure that all nations have the opportunity
to participate fully in the network economy and society, we run the
risk that the divide between nations will grow,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night, Clinton addressed U.S. troops and their
families on Okinawa. His speech was rescheduled from Sunday
afternoon to allow him to leave Japan several hours early in order
to return to the Mideast peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   He will arrive in Washington Sunday afternoon and head directly
to Camp David. In remarks to reporters Sunday morning, Clinton said
the talks continue to make progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I left ... there has been a lot more sort of systematic
effort in the groups on a lot of the issues,'' he said. ``So
whatever happens, I think they continue to make headway.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton gave an upbeat speech to troops lasting less than 10
minutes that did not
</P>
<P>
   directly address the issues that have led Okinawans to protest
the U.S. military
</P>
<P>
   presence on their island, which numbers about 26,000.
</P>
<P>
   Local residents have complained about instances of misbehavior
and crime, including killings, rapes and thefts. The presence of
about 4,000 children fathered out of wedlock by U.S. military
personnel has further strained relations.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton thanked the forces for their work and stated
the need to be good neighbors to their Okinawan hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each one of us has a personal obligation to do everything that
we can to strengthen our friendship and to do nothing to harm it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   For more information:www.g8kyushu-okinawa.go.jp
</P>
<P>
   Julie Chao's e-mail address is juliec(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
