<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0293 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ALNOTES-LADN     07-22 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S BEEN A `STORYBOOK' FOR GIAMBI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ The July 17 edition of Sports Illustrated features
Oakland A's first baseman Jason Giambi on the cover. He's holding a
bat in his hands and is wearing: A) a scowl; B) long greasy hair;
C) a T-shirt with the sleeves cut off, and D) a large tattoo of a
skull and flames on his left shoulder and upper arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new face of baseball,'' the magazine proclaims.
</P>
<P>
   For Giambi, who went to South Hills High in West Covina and Long
Beach State, the cover of SI simply added to what already has been
an incredible year for him.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Saturday's game, Giambi was hitting .334 with 23
homers and 85 RBI. But it's more than the numbers he's produced on
the field.
</P>
<P>
   His brother Jeremy was traded from the Royals to the A's and has
a locker next to Jason's in the A's clubhouse. The A's are in a
pennant race for the first time since Giambi has been with the
club.
</P>
<P>
   He not only was voted the starting first baseman for the
American League in the All-Star Game, but he was named by manager
Joe Torre as the A.L.'s cleanup hitter for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole year has been storybook,'' Giambi said Saturday.
``My brother's here, how well the team's doing. It's been
incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Giambi said he hasn't had too much time to reflect on all that's
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's one of those things that when I'm done with the
year it'll sink in,'' he said. ``It's blowing up. The cover of
Sports Illustrated, the All-Star Game, ... every time I turn around
it's something else. It's been unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Backin' Black: The Angels' young starters - Jarrod Washburn,
Scott Schoeneweis, Ramon Ortiz, Brian Cooper and Seth Etherton -
were drafted and developed by the previous management headed by
general manager Bill Bavasi and scouting director Bob Fontaine.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the new Angels regime has taken the baton and kept
it going. The five have combined to go 23-14, and a lot of credit
is going to new Angels pitching coach Bud Black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody here doesn't know what Buddy Black's meant to this
team,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said. ``Not only his insight
but his ability to communicate with them. Buddy has the ability to
break down and analyze each pitcher's strengths, and he doesn't try
to mold anyone to a particular path.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Black was a special assistant to Indians general
manager John Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Flirting with .400: Nomar Garciaparra was hitting .403 through
the Red Sox's game July 20. Since Ted Williams hit .406 in 1941,
the player who has gone the deepest into the season and still was
at .400 or better was John Olerud.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Olerud was hitting .400 through Aug. 2 with the Blue
Jays. He finished the season as the American League batting
champion with a .363 average.
</P>
<P>
   Interleague tally: Interleague play is over for 2000, and here
are the numbers - American League teams won 136 games to the
National League's 115. The Indians had the best record at 13-5, the
Padres had the worst at 5-10.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, Garciaparra had the highest batting average at
.468, Darin Erstad had the most hits with 37, Frank Thomas and
Sammy Sosa had the most homers with nine each, and Thomas had the
most RBI with 26.
</P>
<P>
   In the four seasons of interleague play, the A.L. leads the
series, 477-463.
</P>
<P>
   Short hops: The Indians want to re-sign free-agent-to-be Manny
Ramirez, but it doesn't look good because Ramirez wants as much as
$15 million a season. ``There's no question the Cleveland Indians
will make an offer,'' Indians GM John Hart told the Cleveland Plain
Dealer. ``I'm not optimistic. I don't think they're ready to sign
here. That's been my experience. I've been through quite a few of
these.'' ... In the ninth inning of Friday's 12-3 game in which the
home team A's were trailing the Angels, a chant of ``Let's go
A's!'' turned into ``Let's go home!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
