<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ATHLETICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE ZITO SILENCES ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Anaheim Angels pitcher Brian Cooper gave it the old
college try Saturday afternoon, given the chance to show a fellow
ex-Trojan how it's done in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   But Cooper, a veteran of all of 15 major-league starts, was
upstaged by Barry Zito, who made his big-league debut a memorable
one in the A's 10-3 victory before 20,111 at the Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper and Zito both attended USC but they were never teammates.
Cooper pitched for the Trojans in 1995, Zito in 1999. But Zito
looked more like the veteran, giving up only one run and two hits
in five innings. Cooper was gone after giving up seven runs and 10
hits in 3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   It was the shortest outing by an Angels starter since Ken Hill
lasted 1 innings on July 3. And it was the first time an Angels
starter failed to go at least six innings since Hill went 5 innings
on July 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though he's a Trojan, I wanted him to lose bad,'' Cooper
said of Zito. ``It's great for him to go out and keep this lineup
down. He did an excellent job by keeping the hitters off balance.
But even though he's a fellow Trojan, I didn't really feel for him.
I wanted to see us put up a 10-spot in the first inning.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was decided in the span of one inning - the bottom of
the fourth and the top of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the fourth, the A's unloaded on Cooper for five
hits and a walk, including a grand slam by Ben Grieve and a two-run
single by Terrence Long. The grand slam was the ninth by the A's
this season, setting a franchise record.
</P>
<P>
   The six runs gave the A's a 7-1 lead, but the Angels had an
opportunity to get back in it against Zito in the top of the fifth.
Adam Kennedy walked, Darin Erstad singled and Benji Gil walked to
load the bases with the heart of the Angels order coming up.
</P>
<P>
   But Zito responded by striking out Mo Vaughn (looking), Tim
Salmon (swinging) and Garret Anderson (swinging) to get out of the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went away from his fastball and threw his breaking ball for
strikes,'' Vaughn said of Zito's three key strikeouts. ``He showed
some poise right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Zito finished with six strikeouts, six walks and one hit batter
(Vaughn).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the A's were geared up for Cooper, who shut them out
on three hits in a 7-0 Angels win June 30 in Anaheim. After that
game, Cooper mentioned how he knew the A's hitters were a patient
bunch (they lead the league in walks), so he focused on throwing
strikes early in the count.
</P>
<P>
   A's manager Art Howe read his team Cooper's comments, they
adjusted and took a more aggressive approach Saturday. Cooper went
with the same approach and was hit hard despite feeling good about
the way he threw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back over the game, there's not one pitch I would take
back in the whole game,'' Cooper (4-4) said. ``Even the pitch to
Grieve. It was a sinker down and away, the perfect double-play ball
... If I had the choice I'd take that stuff, and the way I threw,
every game of the year. If I get beat every time, then I wouldn't
be long for the major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia had a little different view of
Cooper's outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Cooper struggled with his command,'' Scioscia said.
``He got behind a lot of hitters. He couldn't get the ball in the
location he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides working out of the fifth-inning jam, Zito got out of
potential trouble by picking off Erstad in the first inning. The
Angels scored their only run against him in the second inning on an
RBI single by Edgard Clemente.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you haven't seen a pitcher there's a slight advantage for
the pitcher,'' Scioscia said. ``But I don't think that was the case
today. When he had to, he made pitches to get out of jams. He
stepped up with the bases loaded. He has very good stuff, we knew
that. He kept his poise out there.''
</P>
<P>
   With the win the A's moved into a virtual tie with the Angels,
percentage points ahead in the wild-card race. Both teams are five
games behind AL West-leader Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
