<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS MIGHT BE NICE FIT FOR GWYNN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ No, it didn't work with Dave Parker, Eddie Murray or
Cecil Fielder. But this is different.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels have acquired talented hitters to be their
designated hitter in the past, only to learn the hard way they were
years beyond their prime. Way beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Gwynn is 40 years old and certainly beyond his prime. But
Gwynn has a message for those who might think his ailing knee and
his age have him thinking about retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have the fire in my belly to play,'' Gwynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn's bad left knee has limited him to 36 games this season.
He had surgery a month ago and is at least five weeks from
returning. He might not even make it back this season.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn is doing his rehab work with a passion every day. He says
even if he doesn't make it back this season, he'll be back in 2001
for his 20th season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes rehab easy,'' Gwynn said. ``Because I still
want to play. It's why you do what you gotta do. Whether or not I
make it back this year, I still want to play. I love what I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta put a lot of time and energy into (rehab). People
think it's a Caribbean vacation. But you work every day and don't
even get an opportunity to put a bat in your hands. You work every
day and you go home on crutches. No doubt it's a mental battle.''
</P>
<P>
   So Gwynn still wants to play. But isn't he still a Padre?
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the National League,'' Gwynn said. ``But if (the
Padres) don't want me and nobody in the National League wants me
and there's an opportunity to DH, I'm not going to be stupid. I'll
weigh my options, but that's way down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn said he has no idea which way the Padres are leaning. The
club has an option worth $6 million for next season. If they don't
want to keep him, they can buy him out for $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn has meant everything to the Padres. He's won eight batting
titles, has a .338 career average and 3,108 hits. But business is
business and Gwynn understands.
</P>
<P>
   If Gwynn's knee problem limits him from being productive as an
outfielder, there's no use for him in San Diego or on any National
League club. The DH spot offers a player like him an opportunity,
and Anaheim is as close to his San Diego home as he can get.
</P>
<P>
   It's also worth noting that this year's Angels team has no true
DH. They've used nine players as their DH this season, mostly Scott
Spiezio, who still wants to be an every-day player.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also have a hole in the No. 2 spot in the batting
order, where six players have been used this season.
</P>
<P>
   How about a batting order of 1) Darin Erstad; 2) Gwynn; 3) Mo
Vaughn; 4) Tim Salmon; 5) Garret Anderson; 6) Troy Glaus, etc.?
Angels manager Mike Scioscia refused comment. But he couldn't hide
a smile at the thought.
</P>
<P>
   Money is another big issue. Payroll is obviously a concern for
the Angels, but next season they will save $10.2 million in salary
that is going to Ken Hill and Tim Belcher this season. Take maybe
$3 million or $4 million of that to pay Gwynn, and the Angels are
still up $6-7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn, though, isn't simply looking for a paycheck. He doesn't
want to embarrass himself by playing one year too many. Gwynn
started slowly this season, but he got hot before his surgery and
is hitting .323.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hang around,'' he said. ``I'll only keep
playing if I can be productive. If I had my druthers, (San Diego)
is where I would finish playing. But with the situation here now, I
don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about (being a DH). It ain't hard to figure. If I
can swing a bat but have a bad knee and can't run, it's a natural.
If the opportunity presents itself, I'm willing to listen to
whatever anybody's willing to say.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is: Are the Angels listening?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
