<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-GIANTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE HOMERS PROVE COSTLY TO ROOKIE GAGNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers' next great pitching
prospect has evolved into their next great project.
</P>
<P>
   Capable of a dazzling performance one inning, and a stupefying
mistake the next, the education of Eric Gagne continued painfully
Saturday in a 5-2 loss to the Giants at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers look at the talented right-hander, watch him wobble
like the 24-year-old rookie he is, and scream patience.
</P>
<P>
   But after Gagne gave up three home runs to bottom of the Giants'
order on a muggy afternoon, he fell to 1-6 and his ERA swelled to
5.59.
</P>
<P>
   For a team trying to chase down the National League West leaders
and coming off a dramatic victory Friday, it made for a sobering
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way or another, we need him to get it going,'' Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne was just short of a sensation after a September call-up
last year from Double-A San Antonio, going 1-1 in five starts, with
30 strikeouts in as many innings.
</P>
<P>
   He was quickly dubbed the next great thing. Baseball Weekly
named him the top new impact pitcher for the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   But this season, he's had his moments, and too many of them bad.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne started Saturday looking like the hot prospect, retiring
the Giants' first five hitters, including a strikeout of Barry
Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throw the ball like he did in the first inning, and you get
excited,'' Dodgers catcher Chad Kreuter said. ``He's throwing the
ball 94 mph, had command, hitting my glove, strikes out one of the
best guys in the league, that's exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think you're going to continue to roll. Then you end up
having the guys in the bottom of the order beat you. And that's a
shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Gagne started his troubles by giving up a two-out solo home run
to shortstop Rich Aurilia. Armando Rios then doubled to bring up
catcher Bobby Estella, with right-hander Livan Hernandez on deck.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne got ahead of Estella 1-2 ... and threw a curveball over
the plate. Estella jumped on it for a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a crucial mistake to the catcher, with the pitcher
coming up,'' Kreuter said. ``That ball had no business being in the
strike zone. Once we have two strikes on him, you make him chase
something out of the zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to hit a ball a foot off the plate to get a base hit.
But a breaking ball basically down the middle of the plate, that's
a big mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Not the kind that Gagne hasn't made before. He's given up 18
home runs this season in just 75 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Patience, the Dodgers repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the starts he had last year were really good,'' Johnson
said. ``He's had a few little mechanical problems, been a little
too aggressive. But I still like him a whole lot, and he'll get it
right. Sometimes it just takes a little while.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a refrain even the young right-hander grows weary of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not used to losing,'' Gagne said. ``We have such a great
team, and we're so close. We need to win right now. I have to be
out there and win. I can't go out there and give up five runs in
five innings. It's real frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody says you have to go through all those things, but
you want to perform. You're a baseball player.''
</P>
<P>
   Gagne also gave up a two-out, two-run homer to Rios in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   A 5-0 lead was more than enough for Hernandez (9-7), who held
the Dodgers scoreless until Eric Karros' two-run homer in the
eighth. Robb Nen pitched a scoreless ninth for his 22nd save.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-22-00 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0253 </DOCNO>
