r s BC-RUN-TRACK-LADN     07-22 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-TRACK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWDOWN AWAITS JOHNSON, GREENE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 San Bernardino Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Michael Johnson felt an Achilles twinge.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Greene suffered a brain cramp.
</P>
<P>
   And now the greatest rivals in track and field could be matching
vapor trails twice in the span of two hours today in the U.S.
Olympic Trials at Sacramento State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt my Achilles through the curve, and then it went away,''
Johnson said moments after winning his 200-meter heat in a
day's-best time of 19.89 seconds. ``Hopefully, it will be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene, meanwhile, made an error in judgment in his 200 heat.
Running smoothly, and well out in front, Greene downshifted into
cruise mode 150 meters into the race, only to have to reignite the
afterburners when threatened by Ramon Clay and Darvis Patton.
</P>
<P>
   Greene barely won, in 20.29 seconds and, because he was only the
fourth-fastest qualifier, was seeded into Johnson's semifinal
today.
</P>
<P>
   The top four in each semi go to the final.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, the world 100-meter record holder, and Johnson, the 200
and 400 world-record holder, are in line to meet again in the 200
final. The top three go to the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Greene are 1-1 in their only head-to-head
encounters. Greene won the most recent meeting, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson refused to discuss his pending doubleheader with Greene.
``I'm not going to talk about that,'' Johnson said. ``It's silly.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene didn't speak at all, bolting Hornet Stadium within
seconds of watching Johnson's heat via TV in the athlete's
cool-down area.
</P>
<P>
   The two, who have waged a war of words for months, engaged in a
boxing-style staredown in the staging area before their heats.
</P>
<P>
   Competitor Brian Lewis said it ``kind of reminded me of a
heavyweight title fight. You know, when you got two guys in each
other's faces. Nobody said anything. They just stared at each
other, and then laughed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the women's 200, Marion Jones showed anew she is the person
to catch, striding to a 22.62-second mark, a full half-second
faster than reigning world champion (and putative arch-rival) Inger
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Like Greene, Miller was only the fourth-fastest qualifier (at
23.13),and sees Jones in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of all this, the trash-talk,'' Jones said after
running her first 200 of the year. ``If you're going to talk, put
up. If you're going to talk, come to the track and be ready to
race. That's all I'm asking.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Miller: ``I don't care how anybody else ran, just myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones needs only a top-three finish to take her dream of five
Olympic gold medals (100, 200, long jump, two relays) to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The dual 200 duels cap the busy final day of the trials today,
coming 12 minutes apart, with the women going first, at 5:36 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In other action Saturday before another capacity crowd of
23,000-plus at Hornet Stadium:
</P>
<P>
   --Rising star Angelo Taylor, 21, won the 400-meter hurdles in
47.62 seconds, fastest time in the world this year, but declined to
identify himself as the gold-medal favorite for the Sydney
Olympics. ``I just want to get to the final,'' he said. Eric Thomas
and James Carter also gained Sydney berths.
</P>
<P>
   --Nicole Gamble led an underwhelming field in the women's triple
jump with an effort of 45 feet, 9 inches. She is the only American
guaranteed a spot in the Olympics, because none of the jumpers
reached the Olympic standard of 46-5.
</P>
<P>
   --Former American-record holder Tim Seaman won the 20-kilometer
racewalk in 1 hour, 25 minutes, 41 seconds. Again, none of the
competitors reached the Olympic qualifying mark, so only Seaman
goes to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   --Mark Crear, ranked Nos. 1 or 2 every year since 1995, barely
survived the first round of the 100-meter hurdle prelims with a
13.77-second time. Defending Olympic gold medalist Allen Johnson
was sharper, at 13.42 seconds, but finished second in his heat to
Dominique Arnold, who ran a day's best of 13.36.
</P>
<P>
   --Gail Devers, denied a berth on the sprint squad, charged into
the women's 100-meter hurdles semis with a 12.57 clocking, not far
off her best-of-2000 time of 12.47. Devers is a three-time world
champion in the hurdles, but has never medaled in the event at the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   --World champion Anthony Washington led discus qualifying with a
throw of 219-7. John Godina, fourth in shot put qualifying, had the
second-best mark, at 216-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
