<SLUG> BC-RUN-LEBRETON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON-GREENE PART 1 SHOULD BE ALL MICHAEL'S
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ And so, at the end of weeks of hype and
hubbub, of disses and thats, we interrupt this Olympic Trials
yap-o-thon to bring you, of all things ... a race.
</P>
<P>
   In this corner, weighing in at 175 pounds, generously allowing
for contrived theatrics and accompanying run-on sentences, is the
reigning world champion at 200 meters, Maurice Greene.
</P>
<P>
   In the other corner, wearing many hats _ businessman, part-time
``USA Today'' columnist, millionaire sprinter, Nike show pony _ is
the 1996 gold medalist and the fastest human ever to cover 200
meters, Michael Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   There was a golden moment yesterday, eyewitnesses reported, when
the two sprint supernovas finally crossed orbital paths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, over in the warmup area,'' fellow 200 entrant Brian
Lewis recounted. ``Michael kinda walked by Maurice, and then
Maurice walked by Michael. It kinda reminded me of a heavyweight
title fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, nobody said anything. They just stared at each other, and
then they laughed.''
</P>
<P>
   Not unlike pro wrestling, in other words. Or maybe Mike and Mo
just heard that somebody was asking $1,500 for a ticket to today's
finals on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway. Somewhere near high noon yesterday here on the
California Ponderosa, Johnson eased into the starting blocks for
the first round of the 200 meters _ and nearly blew the whole
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Placed in lane five of heat No. 4, Johnson arrived at the apex
of the track's turn and _ gasp _ did not have his customary
six-boxcar lead. On the contrary, 21-year-old John Capel, a wide
receiver on the Florida Gators football team, was elbow-to-elbow
with His Goldenness, and they didn't appear to be chatting about
Maurice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt my Achilles cramp a little in the curve,'' Johnson
would say later.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed, perhaps, to be sensing someone's presence without
permission, Michael turned the radio down, accelerated and raced
young Capel to the finish line into the teeth of a mild headwind.
The electronic clock caught him in 19.89, which would have been
enough last year to win the world championships' 200 in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Greene? He had raced in the heat before Johnson's and had found
a similar adventure.
</P>
<P>
   First, understand the format that meet organizers devised for
entrants to advance. There were seven 200-meter heats. To reach
today's semifinals, a runner had to win his heat or have one of the
next nine best times.
</P>
<P>
   In short, there wasn't supposed to be any of the usual
chillin'-and-cruisin', looking-left-and-right,
only-wanted-to-qualify jogs to the tape seen in past trials. But
Greene must have missed the e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of the turn, he began to shut it down. Which is when
he noticed TCU's Darvis Patton and Tennessee native Ramon Clay
creeping gently to his right side. Greene accelerated, then Clay
accelerated, and then Greene had to accelerate again.
</P>
<P>
   Greene ended up winning the heat in 20.29, followed by Clay's
20.37 and Patton's 20.40.
</P>
<P>
   When they line up today for the first semifinal heat, Patton
will be in lane three, Greene in lane four and Johnson in lane
five. The top four in each semi will return one hour, 48 minutes
later to compete in the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the schedule won't be a problem, but I don't know right
now,'' said Johnson, who declined press interviews but spoke
through a USA Track and Field liaison.
</P>
<P>
   He explained the injury thusly: ``It went away on the straights.
Hopefully, it will be OK. I felt it through the curve, and then it
went away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what to say now. I was able to finish the race.''
</P>
<P>
   That's it. Nothing about tearing out and eating Maurice's heart.
Nothing blamed on any ``USA Today'' copy editors. Just a vague
medical prognosis by Johnson himself, and then an ominous ``I have
to go back and let my trainer look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Michael is hurt, of course, all bets and ebay bids are off.
Greene likes to chirp that he beat Johnson the last time that they
raced, but that was two years ago when the Olympic champion was
nursing a hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   As a man who should know said here yesterday, ``It's Maurice who
is going to have to run the exceptional race.''
</P>
<P>
   The man, Ato Boldon of Trinidad, finished third behind Johnson
and won the bronze medal at the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael knows a million ways to win a race like this,'' said
Boldon, who trains with Greene in Los Angeles. ``And I don't buy
Maurice's claim that if the race is close, Michael breaks down. I
always defer to the 400-meter sprinter.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it simple handicapping. Greene has never run faster than
19.86 in the 200. Johnson almost ran that yesterday _ with a cramp,
in a first-round heat.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming he's healthy, His Goldenness will get the last word,
indeed. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
