<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO SHOULD BE IN ANGELS' CENTER FIELD?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ One on, two outs, bottom of the seventh inning. The
A's lead, 9-3, when Jason Giambi hits a rope to the left-center
field gap.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim Angels center fielder Darin Erstad gets a good jump on
the ball, dives and makes a spectacular catch. Such plays have
become commonplace for Erstad, even in late in games when the
outcome essentially has already been decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things just happen,'' Erstad explained. ``I don't ever
think about diving. It just happens.''
</P>
<P>
   It also happens to stir conversation about who should be in
center field -- Erstad or Garret Anderson. Anderson was the DH for
the second game in a row Saturday because of a sore left Achilles
tendon.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no question Erstad is a better center fielder,
manager Mike Scioscia says the outfield as a whole is better with
Erstad in left and Anderson in center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about a lot of different scenarios,'' Scioscia
said. ``Darin obviously is an option in center field, but I feel we
line up well with Garret in center field. I think Garret's played
very good center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can talk about the couple of plays Garret has made (failing
to back up the right fielder) but Garret is getting good jumps on
the ball, his arm is accurate and he's shutting down runners from
going first to third. It's all part of the package why we think
he's a good major league center fielder.''
</P>
<P>
   About Erstad's catch, Scioscia said: ``Was I surprised? No.
That's Darin Erstad. That play right there is like Andre Dawson
used to play. Brett Butler for years played like that. Dusty Baker.
It does not matter what the score is. When they play, instincts
take over. Get the ball and get the out. I wouldn't expect anything
different from Darin.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it says it all. It's why I think he's the MVP of the
league so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad also had two hits Saturday, raising his major
league-leading total to 160. He's on pace to finish with 264 hits,
which would break George Sisler's 80-year-old major league mark of
257.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus' 29th: Third baseman Troy Glaus hit his 29th homer of the
season Saturday, tying his career-high set last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't witness what happened last year, but this year Troy
Glaus is making footprints as one of the best third baseman in the
league,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   Simulated game: Pitcher Kent Mercker, having recovered from a
cerebral hemorrhage suffered May 11, will throw a simulated game
Monday or Tuesday in Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
