<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK-TRIALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON IS NOW A MAYBE FOR RACE WITH GREENE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ After Maurice Greene sprinted the 200-meter
preliminaries in 20.28 seconds Saturday, he rolled his shoulders,
raised a finger in the air and motioned toward Michael Johnson as
if to say, ``Bring it on.''
</P>
<P>
   Running in the next heat, Johnson did exactly that, finishing in
19.89, within three-hundredths of a second of Greene's career best.
But Johnson felt his right thigh cramp in the middle of the turn,
and his status remained uncertain for Sunday's semifinal and final
rounds, which will be run two hours apart at the Olympic track and
field trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went away on the straights,'' Johnson said of the cramp
after having an ice wrap placed on his thigh. ``Hopefully it's
nothing. I hope the schedule won't be a problem, but I have no way
of knowing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   This 200 meters has become the most anticipated sprint since
Carl Lewis and Ben Johnson met at 100 meters in the final of the
1988 Summer Olympics in Seoul, South Korea. Greene is the world's
fastest man, holding the world record of 9.79 seconds at 100
meters. Johnson is the Olympic champion and world record-holder at
200 meters (19.32 seconds) and 400 meters (43.18 seconds). However,
Johnson has frequently injured himself when running fast. His body
is as fine-tuned as a dragster, fragile in its searing speed,
needing much tinkering between performances.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Greene have been placed in the same heat of Sunday's
semifinal, Greene in Lane 4 and Johnson outside in Lane 5. The
sprinters need only to finish among the top four to reach the
final, but they may feel a need to send each other a message, which
could lead to a fast time or could aggravate an injury. There are
no byes or free passes to the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney,
Australia. The only way to qualify for the 200 is to finish first,
second or third in Sunday's final.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the cramp was a temporary seizure, nothing more. Johnson
cooled down with no problem after Saturday's heat. But the risk is
that he could reinjure himself Sunday, fail to qualify in the 200,
threaten his chances to repeat as Olympic champion at 400 meters
and also jeopardize an opportunity to win a third gold in the
1,600-meter relay. Clyde Hart, Johnson's coach, said a decision
would be made after Johnson warms up for the semifinal round.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any doubt that he's not well, I'll recommend he
not run,'' Hart told the Dallas Morning News. ``There's no use
jeopardizing two gold medals to try to get more.''
</P>
<P>
   In track circles, Johnson has faced some skepticism about his
performances in big races, even though he possesses a combination
of speed and power that is unprecedented in the long sprints. He
pulled up with a strained left thigh during a 1997 match race
against Donovan Bailey of Canada, the reigning Olympic champion at
100 meters, leading Bailey to call him chicken and accuse him of
faking the injury. Johnson pulled a hamstring muscle while setting
his 200 world record at the Atlanta Olympics, then withdrew from
the 200 at the 1999 national championships with a strained right
hamstring. Greene has accused Johnson of ducking him. If Johnson
withdraws or pulls up again on Sunday, his motives will again draw
doubts in a sport that thrives on suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Michael sprints, he gets hurt,'' said Ato Boldon of
Trinidad, who finished third to Johnson in the 200 at the Atlanta
Olympics and who trains daily with Greene in Los Angeles. ``You
can't point to a time when Michael ran a really fast 200, and he
did not get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Boldon has picked Johnson to win Sunday's race because he is a
more experienced 200-meter runner than Greene. But, Boldon added:
``If for any reason Michael fails to show or does not finish, I
think it will conjure too many memories of Bailey-Johnson. He will
be seen as someone who can't handle the one-on-one thing. I don't
expect that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   On a practice track before Saturday's race, Johnson and Greene
engaged in a stare down, sprinter Brian Lewis said. ``That kind of
reminded me of a heavyweight title fight, when you've got two guys
in each other's faces,'' Lewis said. ``Nobody said anything. They
just stared at each other and then laughed.''
</P>
<P>
   The format of the trials may have contributed to Johnson's
injury, said John Chaplin, who will coach the American men in
Sydney. In previous years, the 200 has been contested over four
rounds. This time, there are only three, leaving more of the top
sprinters grouped in the same early heats. Saturday, only the
winner of each of the seven heats was guaranteed a spot in the
semifinals, so the sprinters had to run faster than they might have
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heats are overstacked,'' Chaplin said.
</P>
<P>
   Showing a lack of experience in his heat, Greene accelerated
through the curve, eased up then sped up again when his lead was
threatened. Such an immature performance could have led to injury.
After saying, ``I'm going to get Michael Johnson'' for the past
week, Greene decided not to speak to reporters Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the trash-talking has become so ostentatious that it did
not seem out of place that an Elvis impersonator showed up at the
track Saturday in a gold lame suit. Asked whom he favored, Elvis
said: ``I don't have any opinion on that. If I say so-and-so, the
other guy is going to come and beat me up. I'm pretty vulnerable.
I'm already dead. I can't take any more blows like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
