<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOMEN'S </SLUG>
 OPEN-TEX 
Bidding for title, Webb is a Tiger 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIBERTYVILLE, Ill. _ Karrie Webb smiled at the analogy, perhaps
for the zillionth time this season. But this time, she conceded,
there is some common ground between her and Tiger Woods heading
into today's final round at the U.S. Women's Open.
</P>
<P>
   Webb, with a 68 in yesterday's third round, reached 7-under par
for the tournament and opened a four-stroke advantage on the field
at the Merit Club. With only two players in red numbers, Webb has a
chance to finish as the lone player at the Open with a sub-par
total. As Woods did while winning last month at Pebble Beach Golf
Links.
</P>
<P>
   If Meg Mallon (3-under) falters, or if Webb goes on another
birdie barrage like she did on yesterday's front nine, the world's
top-ranked female golfer could stretch her victory margin to double
digits. As Woods did at the men's Open in June. Or as Webb did in
March while trouncing the field by 10 strokes at the Nabisco
Championship, the LPGA Tour's first major of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Like Webb, Woods also has a chance to record a landslide victory
today. The world's top-ranked male golfer leads the British Open by
six strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Woods hasn't coughed up a final-round lead at a PGA Tour event
since 1996. Webb has won seven consecutive LPGA Tour events when
she's held at least a two-stroke lead heading into the final round.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say, the smart money is on a Woods-Webb daily double
in today's dueling major championships. For both players, it would
mark their third triumph in the past four major championships
played on their respective tours.
</P>
<P>
   Karrie, can you say ``common ground?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty uncanny that it has been so similar,'' Webb said,
when asked about comparisons to Woods. ``I think about that all the
time. But that's as far as it goes. It's hard to compare two
players that don't play against one another.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also harder to count Webb's situation at the Merit Club as
a closed book. Mallon, after all, is a two-time major champion who
won the 1991 Open and held the 36-hole lead. Webb changed that with
four birdies in her first seven holes yesterday, eventually
stretching the lead to five by the time Mallon reached the 15th tee
box.
</P>
<P>
   Mallon responded with consecutive birdies, moving to 5-under,
and crept within two strokes when Webb bogeyed No. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, the 17th took its toll on Mallon as well. She
drove into the left rough, chipped back into the fairway, then
pushed her approach into the right rough. From there, Mallon
chipped to 30 feet and two-putted for double-bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made two mistakes on the same hole, and there's no excuse
for that,'' Mallon said, referring to the drive and approach that
found the rough. ``I can't go out and make the same mistakes and
expect to win the tournament. I have to play my smartest round of
golf and take advantage of every opportunity. That's the only way
that I can catch Karrie and beat her.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the field, for all practical purposes, considers
itself little more than window dressing unless Webb implodes. Laura
Davies heads a four-player group at even-par, seven strokes off the
pace, but conceded Mallon is the only person in position to put
heat on Webb, unless Webb suffers self-inflicted wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``To beat Karrie, you have to be better yourself,'' Davies said.
``You can't expect her to make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallon, for one, doesn't expect any free rides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of weird things happen at the Open,'' Mallon
said. ``But you don't expect them to happen to Karrie. She's got
the best head of anyone out here. I'm going to have to take some
chances and try to make some birdies early on.''
</P>
<P>
   This is precisely the game plan that propelled Webb into the
lead. During her first seven holes, Webb buried birdie putts of 15,
12, 10 and 10 feet. She added an 18-footer at No. 10 and a
20-footer at No. 15, which were offset by two bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all, I played pretty solidly,'' Webb said. ``If I can
do that again, and that means I get to hold the trophy, I'll be
very happy.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
