<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0305 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-DEVILRAYS     07-22 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVIL RAYS BEAT YANKEES, 12-4 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In desperate search of his second victory of the
year, David Cone has experimented with every kind of adjustment,
from tempo to grip to stance. Saturday he rolled his newest
concoction out of the lab: an Orlando Hernandez clone.
</P>
<P>
   Cone hiked his navy socks up high and adopted the El Duque high
leg kick, hoping to change his luck, break his string of futility
and recover his dignity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for something different,'' he said with
resignation. ``It was a semi-tribute to my idol.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone struck out the first two batters of the game, but he gave
up a home run to the third, Greg Vaughn, and it was as if nothing
had changed. Even so, he recovered and pitched effectively. He even
retired nine straight batters, in the third, fourth and fifth
innings. He gave up three runs and six hits, struck out five, and
left after spotting the Tampa Bay Devil Rays a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' bullpen proceeded to unravel. Jeff Nelson and Jason
Grimsley allowed five of the nine remaining runs, and the offense,
no matter how much it was pressing to win for Cone, could not
provide enough support to erase his loss.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay pounded the Yankees, 12-4, and Cone got the loss. His
record dropped to 1-9 _ he hasn't won since April 28 _ and the
Yankees have not won in his last 11 starts, a dismal franchise
record that is destroying his pride.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was much improved from his last outing, when he
gave up six runs in five innings, Cone took no comfort in Saturday.
``It's not good enough,'' he said. ``I lost.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused. ``Again.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter the tinkering, he has not found his answer. ``It's a
ball of confusion for me right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he was not alone Saturday. ``Cone definitely pitched better
than the end result,'' said Grimsley, who gave up Jose Canseco's
double and back-to-back walks on eight straight pitches to begin
the Devil Rays' seven-run eighth inning. ``We had a chance to win
the ballgame and I didn't do my job. I didn't throw strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Nelson, who came on in the seventh and allowed the Devil
Rays to widen their lead to 5-2 by giving up two runs on two walks
and a single. The Yankees had a chance to tie in the seventh
inning, when Derek Jeter and Paul O'Neill each had run-scoring
singles. With runners on first and third, Bernie Williams struck
out on a contested at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   On a 2-1 pitch by the Tampa Bay left-handed reliever Mark
Guthrie, Williams seemed to question Umpire Terry Craft's strike
call, as did Manager Joe Torre. When Williams struck out, ending
the inning, he turned to Craft and asked if he had fouled off the
pitch. Guthrie walked off the field, seemingly telling Williams to
keep quiet, and Williams mouthed that he was not addressing him.
Lee Mazzilli, the Yankees' first-base coach, rushed to restrain
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Einertson relieved Grimsley in the eighth. He gave up
two quick hits, and then Jeter's error on a force-out throw loaded
the bases. After Vaughn fouled out, Fred McGriff knocked a single
into center field. Williams ran slowly to the ball, assuming it
would be a two-run single, but that allowed another run to cross.
Bubba Trammell ended the scoring with a single that put the Devil
Rays ahead, 12-4.
</P>
<P>
   Cone did not see the score, only his mistakes. ``It's a broken
record,'' he said. ``We're not winning on days I pitch, regardless
of what my personal numbers are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have won just 5 of Cone's 18 starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Torre was encouraged. ``I thought he was a lot better,''
Torre said. ``He pitched out of jams and his fastball had life. It
was disappointing we let it get away.''
</P>
<P>
   The day began auspiciously for Cone. After his first two
strikeouts though, he threw a 3-1 fastball to Vaughn, who belted it
for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a microcosm of my season,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth straight game in which Cone had given up a
home run, and his ninth allowed in the last three games.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, Cone gave up a leadoff walk to Canseco.
After striking out Steve Cox, he gave up a ground-rule double to
John Flaherty. Miguel Cairo then fisted a singled past the left
side of the infield to give Tampa Bay a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees inched back into the game. David Justice,
playing left field again, singled in the second inning to extend
his hitting streak to 10 games. Tino Martinez followed with another
single and, after designated hitter Jorge Posada popped up to
second base, Chris Turner, who has turned into Cone's personal
catcher, helped his pitcher with a run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch tied the game at 2-2 when he led off the third
inning by cranking a 2-0 pitch from Tampa Bay starter Ryan Rupe
(2-4) for his fifth home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is enough for Cone right now. ``I've got no quit,'' Cone
said. ``I'm going to fight to the bitter end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
