<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0311 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GAS-SAFETY-REAL-NYT &LR;      07-22 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-SAFETY-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: PLAY IT SAFE WITH GAS IN THE HOME
</HEADLINE>
  By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  While accidents caused by gas leaks in homes are relatively rare,
when they do occur they can be devastating. Here are some tips for
dealing with gas appliances and equipment in and around your house
or apartment.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``When gas lines and gas appliances are installed and maintained
properly, they're not going to be a problem,'' said Ralph DiBiase,
the service manager of Public Service Electric and Gas, a utility
company based in Newark, N.J. ``But when you're dealing with gas,
you can never take anything for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   One way natural gas can pose a potential problem for a
homeowner, DiBiase said, is when there is a leak or break in the
gas pipe buried outside the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because gas is lighter than air, it seeks the path of least
resistance into the atmosphere,'' he said. ``That means that if
there is a leak in the gas line running from the street to the
house, and the gas is looking for the path of least resistance,
that path might be through a crack in the foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the chances of an exterior gas leak making its way into
the house through the foundation are unlikely under ordinary
circumstances, he said, the possibility increases in winter because
the frozen ground could prevent the leaking gas from rising out of
the ground and instead force it to migrate toward the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, DiBiase said, if underground gas lines are left
undisturbed, they are not likely to develop leaks. Unfortunately,
they are not always left undisturbed.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, a homeowner or worker digging outside the
house _ installing anything from a fence post to a swimming pool _
could strike and damage an underground utility pipe. While most
such pipes are buried at least three feet underground to be below
the frost line and protected from freeze-thaw cycles, a previous
owner could have changed the grading of the land or the pipe could
have been buried closer to the surface because of topographical
considerations or soil conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, DiBiase said, a homeowner or contractor digging
where pipes or power lines may be buried should call the utility
companies that service the house to determine exactly where the
utilities are located.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Yutkowitz, a spokesman for the Keyspan Corp., the Brooklyn,
N.Y., company that provides natural gas service to about 1.6
million homes in Brooklyn, Queens, Staten Island and Long Island,
said gas lines and appliances inside the house are also potential
problems. As a result, he said, all gas appliances should be kept
clean and well maintained and should be inspected regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Ovens should be checked to ensure that all pilot lights are lit
and stay lit and that all burners work properly, Yutkowitz said.
Flames on gas appliances should burn blue, not yellow or orange.
``Any color other than blue means that the gas is not burning
properly,'' he said, explaining that improper combustion in a gas
appliance can produce dangerous levels of carbon monoxide, a
colorless, odorless and potentially deadly gas.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners should also be careful when moving stoves and clothes
dryers because they are usually connected to the gas supply by what
is known as a flex connector. That connector, designed to bend
without kinking, can develop leaks if stretched too far or bent too
frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the flex hose is old or deteriorated, you might want to
have it replaced,'' Yutkowitz said, adding that Keyspan maintains
lists of contractors who can be hired to perform such services.
</P>
<P>
   Most homeowners, he said, first detect a gas leak by smelling
it. (While natural gas has no odor of its own, a chemical is added
to give it its distinct aroma.) Other things can also indicate a
potential gas problem.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no gas or the pressure is low (indicated by a low
flame) at all of a home's gas appliances, that could indicate a
leak in the line elsewhere in the house or outside. Another danger
sign would be the inability to shut off gas to an appliance or
heating unit.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, and whenever the smell of gas is detected in a
house, Yutkowitz said, the homeowner should immediately leave,
being careful not to smoke, light matches or operate any electrical
appliances or switches on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to, you can open doors and windows before you
leave, but just make sure you avoid doing anything that could
create a spark, including picking up the telephone,'' he said,
adding that once outside the house the homeowner should use a
public telephone or a neighbor's telephone to call 911 and the
local utility company. Homeowners should not use a cordless phone
to make the call, he said, since that would activate the base unit
inside the house.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Spear, director of education and safety for the National
Propane Gas Association, a trade organization based in Lisle, Ill.,
said similar cautions and procedures should be used with appliances
fueled by propane gas. ``Propane is widely used in areas where
natural gas is not available,'' she said, explaining that the fuel,
derived from natural gas and is stored in liquid form in metal
cylinders, also has an odor added to it so that it is recognizable
if it leaks.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike natural gas, however, propane is slightly heavier than
air and dissipates more slowly. As a result, Spear said, if propane
leaks from a tank or an appliance, it can accumulate on the floor
in combustible concentrations, even in a room that is ventilated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good idea to use propane above the first floor of a
building,'' she said, explaining that if a tank is dropped and the
valve is broken or leaks, the gas could escape and drift down
stairways to the floors below.
</P>
<P>
   Spear added that all propane tanks should be inspected regularly
for rust and corrosion and to ensure that their valves are
operating properly. Moreover, she said, propane tanks should never
be filled to more than 80 percent of their capacity and should
always be stored outside.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners should also make sure that appliances that are to be
used with propane or natural gas have the proper burners installed
for the type of fuel being used. For example, Spear said, a clothes
dryer or barbecue grill that is set up to be used with propane fuel
cannot simply be attached to a natural gas line without changing
the orifice size of the burner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the orifice size isn't correct, that can potentially lead
to high levels of carbon monoxide,'' she said, adding that the
conversion, as well as any work on gas lines or appliances, should
be done by a professional.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bellini, vice president of Varsity Plumbing and Heating
in Flushing, agreed. ``Homeowners think that if they can buy
something at Home Depot, they can legally install it,'' he said.
``But any time you are working on gas lines or installing new gas
equipment or appliances, you need a licensed plumber to do it and
he has to take out a permit.''
</P>
<P>
   And while it is legal for homeowners to replace existing gas
appliances themselves, Bellini said, it is not necessarily wise to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Messing around with gas lines is one thing you really don't
want a handyman to do,'' he said. ``Even when the handyman is
you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
