<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0323 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     07-22 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; HOME TOWN &LR; , by Tracy Kidder. (Washington Square/Pocket Books,
$14.95.) Through personal profiles and historical and demographic
digressions, the author takes the pulse of Northampton, Mass., a
city of 30,000 highly diverse people. Most of the natives leave
when they reach adulthood, and are replaced by newcomers. Kidder's
``smart and gently ironic writing is always good company,'' Ben
Yagoda wrote in The New York Times Book Review in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOUSE &LR; , by David Grand. (Harvest/Harcourt, $13.) This satirical
tale of a monstrous tycoon modeled on the aging Howard Hughes and
the loyal valet who tends to his boss's increasingly eccentric
demands mirrors the plight of workers in an era of job insecurity
and corporate brainwashing. The result is ``a delightfully eerie
and angry first novel,'' David Sacks wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TRUE ADVENTURES OF THE ROLLING STONES &LR; , by Stanley Booth.
(A Cappella, $16.95.) This backstage account of the band's 1969
tour and the author's own seduction by the group's dark allure is
also a personal vision of how the 1960s, from Vietnam to Altamont,
shaped an era. ``It is the only book about the Stones that I would
recommend both to the general reader and to the most devoted fan,''
Robert Palmer wrote in 1984. ``Both will find an epiphany on almost
every page.''
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; FAITHFULL: An Autobiography &LR; , by Marianne Faithfull with
David Dalton (Cooper Square, $16.95), the singer, '60s survivor and
serial Rolling Stone paramour recounts her many love affairs with
men, women and controlled substances. Her narrative is filled with
``spicy stories about Mick Jagger, Keith Richards and Bob Dylan,''
David Kelly wrote in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HUMMINGBIRD HOUSE &LR; , by Patricia Henley. (MacMurray &AMP; Beck,
$13.) This first novel is about a burned-out American midwife
working in Central America who seems to find her true cause in
fighting the Guatemalan government's persecution of the country's
indigenous Mayan people. ``Henley does a fine job of demonstrating
the cost of compassion,'' Jeannie Pyun wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SOPRANOS &LR; , by Alan Warner. (Harvest/Harcourt, $14.) This
tender novel follows a pack of choirgirls from rural Scotland as
they embark on an odyssey of carousing while in the big city for a
singing contest. ``It's refreshing to read a novel loaded down with
teen-age drinking, smoking, swearing and the urge for sex ... and
be spared the moralizing that usually goes along with these
activities,'' Charles Taylor wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TALES OF FISHING VIRGIN SEAS &LR; , by Zane Grey. (Derrydale,
$19.95.) The acclaimed writer of westerns was also an insatiable
angler and a passionate naturalist, as this illustrated account of
his sailing trips throughout the Pacific reveals. ``Anyone who
loves tales of adventure into far seas, unusual experiences,
accounts of exotic and almost intoxicating beauty, to say nothing
of those enthusiastic fishermen for whose perusal the book is
especially intended, will find it a fascinating volume,'' The New
York Times Book Review said in 1926.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOLLIE PEER: Or, The Underground Adventure of the Moosepath
League &LR; , by Van Reid. (Penguin, $12.95.) This sequel to ``Cordelia
Underwood: Or, The Marvelous Beginnings of the Moosepath League''
describes the continuing exploits of a Dickensian collection of
journalists, journeymen, smugglers, baseball players, barkeeps,
crooks and street urchins at loose in late 19th-century Maine. The
result is ``a thoroughly easygoing and entertaining'' novel, Betsy
Groban wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADDIE: A Memoir &LR; , by Mary Lee Settle. (Berkley, $13.) By
casting her autobiography as a memoir about her grandmother, whose
out-of-wedlock pregnancy scandalized turn-of-the-century West
Virginia, the novelist explores the way one understands truth by
indirection. ``Settle has preserved for us a moment in the South's
history palpable as the trumpet vines and rocking chairs of a
long-departed front-porch afternoon,'' Angeline Goreau wrote in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN THE DRINK &LR; , by Kate Christensen. (Anchor, $12.) Claudia
Steiner could be Bridget Jones' darker twin: struggling to pay the
rent on her studio apartment by toiling as a ghostwriter to an
insane New York socialite, she can't keep from crawling through
some of the city's meaner streets. Last year the reviewer Vanessa
Grigoriadis called this a ``breezy and confident first novel.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A SHORT HISTORY OF RUDENESS: Manners, Morals, and Misbehavior
in Modern America &LR; , by Mark Caldwell. (Picador USA, $13.) A
literary critic surveys social behavior, past and present, and
finds that while manners change over time, they are basically no
worse today than they used to be. Last year the reviewer Naomi
Bliven called this a ``modest, readable, intelligent and
companionable'' book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
