<DOCNO> NYT20000722.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ONLINE-LEASE-REAL-NYT     07-22 1392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-LEASE-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMERCIAL REAL ESTATE: CREATING AN ONLINE LEASE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Falus said he was feeling a lot like Chuck Yeager these
days. Just like the first man to break the sound barrier in
aviation, Falus is trying to push the envelope of real estate
transactions by helping develop a system for doing the
often-complex deals over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   His company, Cushman &AMP; Wakefield, one of the largest commercial
real estate brokerages in the country, recently signed a contract
with Zethus Inc. to conduct leasing transactions online starting
next year. Zethus, which is based in Houston, is backed by the
Goldman Sachs Group, the Wall Street investment banking firm, which
has extensive links to real estate. Zethus officials have said the
system will require an investment of $40 million to $50 million
before its launch.
</P>
<P>
   Although Zethus is one of hundreds of companies trying to adapt
Internet technology to the real estate market (a recent report by
Credit Suisse First Boston listed 214), Falus said he thought it
had the best chance of developing a Nasdaq-like market for leasing
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are following a long-term business strategy,'' said Falus,
who is president of Cushman &AMP; Wakefield's new ventures group. ``We
think we have partnered with the best and the brightest in the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Falus acknowledged that in order to trade real estate like
stocks or bonds, standards would have to be developed so that terms
and descriptions of available space in different locations would be
comparable. ``All parties can agree that a foot is 12 inches, rent
is rent, and so forth'' he said. He noted that real estate debt
documentation had been standardized sufficiently to permit the
development of the commercial mortgage-backed securities market.
</P>
<P>
   Describing how such a system would work, Falus said: ``We could
put a request for proposals out on the Internet to landlords who
have space available. We could say that Cushman &AMP; Wakefield
represents a Standard &AMP; Poors AA rated tenant in the financial
services field that needs X thousand square feet in these locations
on a 10-year lease. The bidding closes at 12 p.m. next Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees that it will be possible to simplify lease
transactions so they can trade like commodities. One doubter is
Julien J. Studley, chairman of the company bearing his name and the
dean of tenant brokers. He said there were too many twists and
turns in large commercial leases to trade office space like winter
wheat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to decide what it is you are buying,'' he said. One
example, he said, is the details attached to landlord allowances
for interior construction. ``If he gives you a certain amount of
money, the question is, how can you spend it? Do you have to use
his contractor? If you are free to use any contractor, do you have
to give back 20 percent? And how do you know that, after five
years, the guy next door has the right to take your space?''
</P>
<P>
   Studley said automated markets were most likely to develop for
very small spaces, where tenants have trouble attracting the
attention of brokers and value the speed of moving into a location
over the nuances of the lease.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew L. Farkas, the chairman of Insignia Financial Group,
which owns and manages commercial and residential properties and
supplies brokerage and other services, agreed that an automated
market might develop for smaller spaces, which he defined as
``15,000 square feet and south.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that, for the most part, ``the Internet will not
close transactions; people will close transactions over the
Internet.'' Nevertheless, he said, the perceived role of the broker
may change, and the commission structure may change to reflect
services, such as tax analysis, other than matching up buyers and
sellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value proposition has been seen as the place where supply
meets demand,'' he said. ``In fact that is the least important
aspect of sophisticated brokerage services.''
</P>
<P>
   James A. Hime, the chief executive of Zethus (the name comes
from a demigod in Greek mythology), said the system would be open
to all parties in commercial transactions and would be marketed to
the real estate officials of larger corporations. ``These companies
have hundreds and thousands of leases and corporate real estate
officers are beset by all this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The system, he said, would be programmed to notify these
officials of lease expirations well in advance of the need to make
a decision, and present them with alternative locations in the
market. Although the system will be capable of handling
transactions directly between a landlord and tenant without a
broker, he said, the expectation is that such deals will be
uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   ``After much thought and discussion with corporate real estate
officers, we were persuaded that, while the technology would permit
principal-to-principal transactions, they will be the exception
rather than the rule,'' Hime said. ``Even with the best data base,
only someone who is in the market every day really understands
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said real estate professionals were like lawyers and
investment bankers, whose skills in making a legal argument or
structuring a deal are as important as filing a suit or selling
securities. ``Brains are still valuable,'' he said. ``The place for
the expert is secure for the future, even as new technology makes
them more efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he expected some resistance to on-line transactions by
brokers accustomed to conventional approaches. But he likens it to
the way lawyers at his old firm of Baker &AMP; Botts reacted to the
installation of Lexus terminals giving access to legal data. ``At
first they were seen as a back-up to the books in the law
library,'' he said. ``Five years later it was reversed. I consulted
the Lexus terminal while I was on the telephone with clients.''
</P>
<P>
   The changing value of information and expertise led Cushman &AMP;
Wakefield earlier this year to sell its nationwide database on
properties, rental rates and vacancies to a company formerly known
as RELocate, now doing business as RealtyIQ.com.
</P>
<P>
   Falus said the sale was a recognition that the value of
gathering and storing information had diminished at a time when
information will be widely available commercially on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cushman &AMP; Wakefield wants to be positioned at the highest
value-added points in the real estate business,'' he said. ``In the
past we gathered and disseminated information. Once we realized
that there were going to be companies specializing in information,
we decided we did not have to do it ourselves. There are better
uses for our financial capital and our human capital.''
</P>
<P>
   He said this thinking was also behind the linkup with Goldman
Sachs and Zethus. ``We are consumers of technology, but we are not
a technology company. We have capital, but as a private company we
have to use it sparingly.''
</P>
<P>
   The search for an alliance with an entity that knew about
technology and had access to capital inevitably led to Wall Street,
Falus said. The search for one that also knew about real estate and
transactions led to Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet-dependent services due to hit the market shortly
are not as far-reaching as the Zethus plan. Farkas said Insignia,
which launched EdificeRex, a portal of Internet services, for its
residential tenants in February, would start rolling out RexOffice
for its commercial properties next month. He said the service would
offer e-mail, instant messaging, calendars, community announcements
and concierge functions, like reserving tickets to events.
</P>
<P>
   He said tenants too small to set up their own intranets for
employees could have what appeared to be their own Web pages. ``The
Widget Co.'s Web page will look like it is owned by the Widget
Co.,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Community buying services will also be possible, he said. As an
example, he gave tenants in a building who buy bottled water from
multiple vendors, each with it own delivery schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say you have 70 tenants in a building, each buying 50 to 70
gallons a month,'' he said. ``The system would accumulate all those
order and put out a request for proposals and buy all the water
from one vendor and one delivery. That is a more efficient way to
do things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
