<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0327 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-BRITISH-HNS &LR;      07-22 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Woods sets up British grand finale
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ Theoretically, it could go either way today
in the final round of the Millennium Open Championship.
</P>
<P>
   It might be the genesis of a rivalry. More likely, it will be
nothing more than another Sunday victory lap for Tiger Woods as he
goes for the Claret Jug-ular and the career Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval made a big charge Saturday with a superb 6-under-par
66 at the Old Course and finally finds himself paired with Tiger
Woods in the final round of a major championship.
</P>
<P>
   But if it is a rivalry being born, it will start as a
long-distance affair. There is an awful lot of air between the
world's two top-ranked players on the leader board.
</P>
<P>
   If Duval could see anything other than Woods' tail lights, it
might really be something special today. At the least, it will mark
the first time they have played together in the final round of any
tournament. That it will happen at historic St. Andrews in the
129th British Open seems apt.
</P>
<P>
   Duval sank a six-foot birdie putt on the 18th hole to get to 10
under par for the tournament. That shot wound up securing his spot
alongside Woods. The bad news is that he is six strokes behind
Woods, who shot 67 Saturday, yet saw his lead double in size as his
closest pursuers faltered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I had a very good chance of getting into
the last group at 9 under,'' Duval said. ``I most definitely wanted
to get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a circus. It'll be exciting. It'll be a slugfest.
Whatever you want to call it, I wanted to be sure I gave myself the
best chance to get there. To get in the last group of the oldest
tournament in the world with the player who is undoubtedly the best
in the world right now is an experience you want to have.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can swing the golf club like I have the last few days and
putt like I have, I can show him I've got a little game going right
now, too.''
</P>
<P>
   From Woods' perspective, the battle will be more with himself
than with Duval. He ensured that by calmly negating his first two
bogeys of the tournament with seven birdies. Woods survived three
three-putts, including one at the 17th, the Road Hole.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he is only a 69 away from beating Nick Faldo's St.
Andrews record of 18 under par set in 1990. Woods already owns the
scoring records at Augusta National (in 1997) and Pebble Beach
(this year). Shooting that number also would serve to shut out any
hope for Duval or Thomas Bjorn, who also is at 10 under par.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly looks like somebody out there is playing golf on
a different planet than the rest of us,'' Bjorn said. ``If you
shoot three rounds under 70 at St. Andrews (which Bjorn has done),
you're not doing so bad. Unfortunately for the rest of us, Tiger is
doing something that's just a different class.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt we're playing for second place. Unless some
of us go out there and make five or six birdies in the first six
holes well, St. Andrews has pulled off a lot of strange things in
the past.''
</P>
<P>
   This might be too much, however. Woods on Saturday briefly
showed his human side, making a bogey on the second hole when he
three-putted from 25 feet, botching a four-foot comebacker. But he
came back on the third hole with a birdie from 12 feet. Then he got
hit in the middle of the round after Ernie Els, Steve Flesch and
David Toms had gotten within close range of Woods.
</P>
<P>
   He slammed a 6-iron to within 18 inches on the par-3 eighth and
ran in a 15-footer on the ninth. He then birdied three in a row
starting on the 12th. Even when his lead slipped to five strokes
with the bogey at the 17th, he followed it with a birdie from 10
feet on the last hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a couple of mess-ups on the card, but overall it was a
good day,'' he said. ``It (his position) is not bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to enjoy it. David and I are great friends. I know
the public has always been wanting to have Nos. 1 and 2 playing
each other in the final round of a major. We have that opportunity.
We're going to enjoy each other's company and give it everything we
have to try to beat each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval's showing on Saturday was impressive on many fronts. He
has been fighting a back strain that has bugged him since the week
after the U.S. Open. Plus, staring at a seven-shot deficit at the
start of the day can take the starch out of anybody.
</P>
<P>
   But birdie putts from 20 feet on the eighth and 10 feet on the
ninth highlighted a 32 on the front nine. And he never came close
to making a bogey on the way in. His 66 tied Bob May and Bernhard
Langer for the low score of the day, as well as the lowest of the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was the best day I've felt all week,'' Duval said. ``For
the most part, I played pain-free. Oddly enough, coming in with a
back sprain, I really felt like I had regained my touch on the
greens. That's really important, as we all know. And it's something
that had been missing for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval knows that he has a difficult, if not impossible, task
ahead of him today. He could shoot another 66 and still not get
close to Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be trying to win my first major championship and
he's going to be going for the slam,'' Duval said. ``So there's
going to be some pressures on both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, probably not nearly as much on Woods. When you've got a
comfort zone the size of the Atlantic Ocean, it is easy to go out
swinging freely. Woods had a nine-shot lead at Augusta in 1997 and
was up by 10 last month at Pebble Beach after 54 holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had big leads before and I've been able to succeed
before,'' he said. ``But we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Others took that comment as only so much posturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only pressure that comes to him is from himself,'' Bjorn
said, ``because he's trying to win the Grand Slam of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
