<SLUG> BC-BB0-ROSE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rose rules Cooperstown, but not as Hall of Famer
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By RICHARD JUSTICE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ Pete Rose sits at a table, greeting a line of
fans that begins inside his covered tent and snakes along the wall
of one building and around the corner of another. Men, women and
children of all ages began gathering an hour before his scheduled
arrival, and by the time baseball's hit king stepped from a
Mercedes sedan, some had been standing in a steady rain for close
to 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone seems to mind. They've come from Columbus and
Boston and Macon and other places. They've come with kids for Rose
to be photographed with and for the chance to get Rose to sign
their bats, balls, pictures, game programs and scrapbooks. They've
come for the opportunity to share a memory in the 30 seconds or so
they get with him.
</P>
<P>
   Outside on Main Street, there's a carnival atmosphere as a guy
chants: ``Pete Rose signing autographs! Pete Rose signing
autographs!'' When fans approach, they are directed to a table
selling the tickets required to get in the line that leads to Rose.
Purchase a $35 ticket, and Rose will sign your baseball. For $45,
he'll autograph a batting helmet. And for $70, he'll add his
signature to your bat or lithograph.
</P>
<P>
   For three hours, Rose, wearing a red Nike T-shirt and rolls of
gold jewelry on both wrists, works methodically, signing hundreds
of autographs, trading small talk, smiling for pictures and mostly
just listening and smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete, how much would you charge me for a hug?'' asks Pat Smith
of York, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Rose grins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's got to be worth $75,'' he jokes while motioning
her to come around the table.
</P>
<P>
   As Smith wraps her arms around him, Rose playfully screams:
``Now watch where you put your hands!''
</P>
<P>
   Another fan shows off a ball Rose has just signed and jokes that
his hands are still shaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I paid $35 for his autograph,'' Jeff Morfolk of Columbus,
Ohio, says, ``and it was worth every penny of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Morfolk are among the thousands who've gathered in
this picturesque village in the rolling hills of upstate New York
for the Baseball Hall of Fame's annual induction ceremonies.
They've come to cheer as two more members of the Big Red Machine _
manager Sparky Anderson and first baseman Tony Perez _ are
enshrined today along with Red Sox/White Sox catcher Carlton Fisk
and two posthumous inductees, former Negro League star Turkey
Stearnes and 19th-century Reds player Bid McPhee.
</P>
<P>
   And the fans have also come to catch a glimpse of baseball's
most famous exile _ Peter Edward Rose.
</P>
<P>
   With Hall of Famers ranging from Willie Mays to Duke Snider to
Frank Robinson selling their autographs outside the book shops and
souvenir stores lining Main Street, it's Rose who draws the biggest
crowds. He arrived on Friday, and by the time he leaves Monday, he
will have signed thousands of autographs and pocketed thousands of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows?'' Rose asks. ``Maybe I wouldn't be so popular if I
were in the Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his popularity, Rose knows he will not in the Hall any
time soon. Commissioner Bud Selig has indicated he has no intention
of ever lifting Rose's lifetime ban because of what he sees as
overwhelming evidence that Rose bet on big-league games while he
was managing the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take the integrity of this game very seriously,'' Selig
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rose has vigorously denied ever betting on major-league games,
although he declined the opportunity to cross-examine any of the
witnesses or refute any of the evidence during baseball's 1989
investigation that led to his suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball had the goods on him, and he knows it,'' said chief
investigator John Dowd. ``You've got the betting records, where he
recorded the results of the games in his own handwriting. We had 10
separate witnesses who saw him betting on the Cincinnati Reds. We
had the betting records recovered from bookmakers. He told Bob
Costas he'd never seen the evidence. We spent two days in Dayton in
1989, and I showed Pete all the evidence. He simply couldn't handle
it. We made 113 witnesses available to him and his lawyers. They
never interviewed one of them. The report is uncontradicted.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Rose remains a compelling figure, especially
during a weekend like this one when he stations himself a few yards
from the stately building from which he is banned. Anderson and
Perez will join Joe Morgan and Johnny Bench as the third and fourth
members of the Big Red Machine to be inducted. Along with Rose,
they were the heart of a team that won six division titles, four
pennants and two World Series in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Long before he retired as a player in 1986, Rose had established
himself as one of the game's greatest players and fiercest
competitors. His 4,256 career hits are the most in history, and
they provide the footnote to almost every autograph he gives: Pete
Rose _ 4256.
</P>
<P>
   As for Rose, he seems in an upbeat mood this weekend even as he
adamantly refuses to admit he ever bet on a big-league game. He
does vaguely admit to ``mistakes,'' but insists that an 11-year ban
is enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, how long am I going to be punished?'' he asked. ``I've
lost millions; I've been to prison (for tax evasion); I've been
banned from baseball. I can't go to games. I think I've been
punished enough. Maybe you disagree. I know some people do.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bart Giamatti died eight days after suspending Rose
in 1989. Said Rose in a remark directed at Selig: ``If Bart were
alive, I think he'd have given me a second chance. He was a fair
man. We'll never know that, will we? Bud is afraid to make a move
because of his friendship with Bart. That's a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the hundreds of fans awaiting the chance to get his
autograph, Rose said: ``Public opinion has snowballed for me. Fans
realize I made mistakes. They know I've paid for my mistakes.
They're willing to turn the page. But I understand the situation. I
just hope I don't get in after I'm dead. That would be empty. It's
important, but it's going to be more important to my kids who never
saw me play. I know what kind of player I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose goes out of his way, however, to say how happy he is for
Anderson and Perez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously special to me,'' he said. ``They are dear
friends. Sparky was the best manager I ever played for. Dog
(Perez's nickname) was the best clutch hitter I ever played with.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose is already in the Hall of Fame in a sense, because his
uniform, batting helmet and jersey are hanging in a display case
honoring his Cincinnati teams.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, he has become something of a martyr despite the
evidence against him. He received the loudest ovation last fall
when he was introduced as a member of the All-Century team before
Game 1 of the World Series. And when baseball forbade him from
taking part in a 25th-anniversary celebration of the 1975 Reds, a
mention of Rose drew the longest and loudest cheers of the evening.
A drawing of Rose's jersey hung from the owner's box at Cinergy
Field, and Perez's wife Pituka wore a handmade button bearing
Rose's No. 14 and the inscription, ``For love and respect.''
Current Reds shortstop Barry Larkin provided the final punctuation
mark in the celebration by placing a rose at third base to
commemorate Rose's absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is whatever he did that was wrong, he did as a
manager,'' Anderson said. ``Nobody could ever find a single thing
he did when he was a player. Believe me, he was the hardest-playing
player I ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Perez: ``For Pete not to be here is something I don't
understand. I think he belongs here.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Bench and others have been harsh in their criticism of
Rose, saying he's now sleeping in a bed of his own making. Even
some of the 47 Hall of Famers back for this weekend's ceremony
wrestle with the issue of Rose and the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just on his credentials, he gets in,'' Fergie Jenkins said.
``The problem is he agreed to a lifetime ban. And Pete has never
apologized for what he did. I guess he's too proud. I think if he'd
done that, there's no doubt he'd be in the Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his presence this weekend might detract from Anderson
and Perez, Rose said: ``I won't bother them. Those guys know how I
feel about them. I won't steal their thunder. There are 50 Hall of
Famers here. Bench will be here. Morgan will be here. Those guys
know I won't steal their show. I'm me, and they're them. It would
be stealing their thunder if I went to the induction. Let me
explain something. If I got the feeling I wasn't wanted, I'd never
come back here. I get the warmest reception you can imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then, Rose is interrupted by a fan pointing toward the Hall
of Fame building and screaming: ``Pete! You should be down the
street!''
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean that Chinese restaurant?'' Rose shouts back. ``Yeah,
I'm going there tonight!''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
