</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CARDINALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros pummel Cards, give Miller first victory
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Baseball is indeed a funny game, although it hasn't put many smiles
on the Astros' faces this season.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours after being pummeled with their hottest
pitcher on the mound, the Astros served payback to the St. Louis
Cardinals on Saturday behind a breakout offensive performance and a
pitcher starting for just the fourth time in his big-league career.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros tied a season high with 17 hits, and rookie
righthander Wade Miller notched his first win in a 10-5 romp over
the National League Central leaders. It was a game that wasn't as
close as the score indicated.
</P>
<P>
   If the Astros played like this every day, they certainly
wouldn't have the worst record in the majors. They scored five runs
in the first inning and put the game on ice with four more in the
fourth, winning for just the fourth time in 10 games since the
All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   A man of Drayton McLane Jr.'s stature no doubt received more
valuable birthday presents Saturday. But there was perhaps none the
Astros owner could have used more than a victory by his struggling
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea,'' the 23-year-old Miller said when told the
significance of the day. ``Well, happy birthday, Drayton.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller also couldn't have had any idea he would be blessed with
so much run support one day after the Astros and Scott Elarton took
a 12-1 beating from the Cardinals. Nevertheless, Miller was the
beneficiary of a four-run lead before many in the fourth
consecutive sellout crowd at Enron Field had found their seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always good when the team goes out and gets a big lead
early like that,'' Miller said. ``When that happens, you can just
go right after the hitters. It seemed like we were scoring two or
three runs every inning. I just tried to stay focused and throw
strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't seem to be much of a problem. For most of the day,
Miller had his way with a dangerous lineup, perfectly spotting his
95 mph fastball and keeping the Cardinals off balance with a hard
slider and a big-breaking curveball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a lot of outs with my fastball,'' said Miller, who had
nine strikeouts. ``I guess I was just throwing it in the right
spots. I've waited a long time to win my first big-league game.
I've dreamed about this since I was a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   The game ball from Saturday's victory immediately went to the
top of the list of mementos Miller has collected throughout his
playing days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give it to my parents,'' Miller said of the
keepsake. ``I'm sure they'll figure out something to do with it.
Maybe they'll put it in their coffin.''
</P>
<P>
   After Fernando Vina led off the game with a double, Miller
retired 15 of the next 16 batters he faced, including 11 in a row
during one stretch. He didn't allow another hit until Jim Edmonds'
two-run homer in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the Astros already had put 10 runs on the board.
Edmonds' sacrifice fly gave the Cardinals an early lead in the
first, but the Astros quickly erased that with five runs in the
bottom of the inning. Jeff Bagwell, Richard Hidalgo and Chris Truby
each drove in a run in the uprising, and Mitch Meluskey added a
two-run homer off Cardinals starter Pat Hentgen (9-7).
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I faced Hentgen, he got me,'' Meluskey said.
``This time, I got him. He's a tough pitcher. It was one of those
lucky things. I just got a good swing on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The first inning looked like extended batting practice for the
Astros, who established a season high with seven hits in an inning.
The Astros' other 17-hit performance this year came in a 10-inning
game against the Dodgers on May 7.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell hit a solo homer in the second, and the game took on the
look of a blowout in the fourth when Daryle Ward and Julio Lugo hit
RBI singles and Truby drove home a run with a double. Meluskey
collected his third RBI when he was hit by a pitch with the bases
loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell finished 3-for-4 and came within a triple of the cycle,
which didn't exactly excite him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't care about the cycle,'' he said. ``The only
good thing about the cycle is it means you got at least four hits.
I would have rather had another home run than a triple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to feel a little better at the plate every day,
and that's a good thing,'' added Bagwell, who lifted his batting
average to .294. ``But every day is a battle. I don't know what's
going to come tomorrow, but I'm feeling better.
</P>
<P>
   ``After getting beat up like we did (Friday), we needed a game
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
